CHAPTER I.
<subhead>THE WIDOW AND HER CHILD.</subhead> <attbytes>29Kb</attbytes><reflink>000027</reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z400030618</ID><A1>Ainsworth, William Harrison, 1805&ndash;1882</A1><T1>Jack Sheppard. A Romance.</T1><PBL>Richard Bentley</PBL><Y1>1839</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd4>
<p><pp><smallcap>On</smallcap> the night of Friday, the 26th of November,
1703, and at the hour of eleven, the door
of a miserable habitation, situated in an obscure
quarter of the Borough of Southwark, known
as the Old Mint, was opened; and a man, with
a lantern in his hand, appeared at the threshold.
This person, whose age might be about forty,
was attired in a brown double&hyphen;breasted frieze
coat, with very wide skirts, and a very narrow
collar; a light drugget waistcoat, with pockets
reaching to the knees; black plush breeches; 
grey worsted hose; and shoes with round toes,
wooden heels, and high quarters, fastened by
small silver buckles. He wore a three&hyphen;cornered
hat, a sandy&hyphen;coloured scratch wig, and had a
thick woollen wrapper folded round his throat.</pp>
<pb n="2">
<pp>His clothes had evidently seen some service,
and were plentifully begrimed with the dust of
the workshop. Still he had a decent look, and
decidedly the air of one well&hyphen;to&hyphen;do in the world.
In stature, he was short and stumpy; in person,
corpulent; and in countenance, sleek,
snub&hyphen;nosed, and demure.</pp></p>
<p>Immediately behind this individual, came a
pale, poverty&hyphen;stricken woman, whose forlorn
aspect contrasted strongly with his plump and
comfortable physiognomy. She was dressed in
a tattered black stuff gown, discoloured by
various stains, and intended, it would seem,
from the remnants of rusty crape with which it
was here and there tricked out, to represent the
garb of widowhood, and held in her arms a
sleeping infant, swathed in the folds of a linsey&hyphen;woolsey
shawl.</p>
<p><pp>Notwithstanding her emaciation, her features
still retained something of a pleasing expression,
and might have been termed beautiful, had
it not been for that repulsive freshness of lip
denoting the habitual dram&hyphen;drinker; a freshness</pp>
<pb n="3">
<pp>in her case rendered the more shocking
from the almost livid hue of the rest of her
complexion. She could not be more than
twenty; and though want and other suffering
had done the work of time, had wasted her
frame, and robbed her cheek of its bloom and
roundness, they had not extinguished the lustre
of her eyes, nor thinned her raven hair. Checking
an ominous cough, that, ever and anon, convulsed
her lungs, the poor woman addressed a
few parting words to her companion, who lingered
at the doorway as if he had something on
his mind, which he did not very well know how
to communicate.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Well, good night, Mr. Wood,&rdquo; said she, in
the deep, hoarse accents of consumption; &ldquo;and
may God Almighty bless and reward you for
your kindness! You were always the best of
masters to my poor husband; and now you've
proved the best of friends to his widow and orphan
boy.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Poh! poh! say no more about it,&rdquo; rejoined
the man hastily. &ldquo;I've done no more than my</pp>
<pb n="4">
<pp>duty, Mrs. Sheppard, and neither deserve nor
desire your thanks. &lsquo;Whoso giveth to the
poor lendeth to the Lord;&rsquo; that's my comfort.
And such slight relief as I can afford should
have been offered earlier, if I'd known where
you'd taken refuge after your unfortunate
husband's&wblank;&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Execution, you would say, sir,&rdquo; added
Mrs. Sheppard, with a deep sigh, perceiving
that her benefactor hesitated to pronounce the
word. &ldquo;You show more consideration to the
feelings of a hempen widow, than there is any
need to show. I'm used to insult as I am to
misfortune, and am grown callous to both; but
I'm <it>not</it> used to compassion, and know not how
to take it. My heart would speak if it could,
for it is very full. There was a time, long,
long ago, when the tears would have rushed to
my eyes unbidden at the bare mention of generosity
like yours, Mr. Wood; but they never
come now. I have never wept since that day.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;And I trust you will never have occasion
to weep again, my poor soul,&rdquo; replied Wood,
setting down his lantern, and brushing a few</pp>
<pb n="5">
<pp>drops from his eyes, &ldquo;unless it be tears of joy.
Pshaw!&rdquo; added he, making an effort to subdue
his emotion, &ldquo;I can't leave you in this way. I
must stay a minute longer, if only to see you
smile.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>So saying, he re&hyphen;entered the house, closed
the door, and, followed by the widow, proceeded
to the fire&hyphen;place, where a handful of
chips, apparently just lighted, crackled within
the rusty grate.</p>
<p><pp>The room in which this interview took place
had a sordid and miserable look. Rotten, and
covered with a thick coat of dirt, the boards of
the floor presented a very insecure footing; the
bare walls were scored all over with grotesque
designs, the chief of which represented the
punishment of Nebuchadnezzar. The rest were
hieroglyphic characters, executed in red chalk
and charcoal. The ceiling had, in many places,
given way; the laths had been removed; and,
where any plaster remained, it was either
mapped and blistered with damps, or festooned
with dusty cobwebs. Over an old crazy bedstead
was thrown a squalid, patchwork counterpane;</pp>
<pb n="6">
<pp>and upon the counterpane lay a black
hood and scarf, a pair of bodice of the cumbrous
form in vogue at the beginning of the
last century, and some other articles of female
attire. On a small shelf near the foot of the
bed stood a couple of empty phials, a cracked
ewer and basin, a brown jug without a handle,
a small tin coffee&hyphen;pot without a spout, a saucer
of rouge, a fragment of looking&hyphen;glass, and a
flask, labelled &ldquo;<it>Rosa Solis.</it>&rdquo; Broken pipes
littered the floor, if that can be said to be littered,
which, in the first instance, was a mass of
squalor and filth.</pp></p>
<p><pp>Over the chimney&hyphen;piece was pasted a handbill,
purporting to be &ldquo;<it>The last Dying Speech
and Confession of</it> TOM SHEPPARD, <it>the
Notorious Housebreaker, who suffered at Tyburn
on the 25th of February</it>, 1703.&rdquo; This
placard was adorned with a rude wood&hyphen;cut,
representing the unhappy malefactor at the
place of execution. On one side of the handbill
a print of the reigning sovereign, Anne,
had been pinned over the portrait of William
the Third, whose aquiline nose, keen eyes,</pp>
<pb n="7">
<pp>and luxuriant wig, were just visible above
the diadem of the queen. On the other a
wretched engraving of the Chevalier de Saint
George, or, as he was styled in the label attached
to the portrait, James the Third, raised
a suspicion that the inmate of the house was
not altogether free from some tincture of
Jacobitism.</pp></p>
<p>Beneath these prints, a cluster of hobnails,
driven into the wall, formed certain letters,
which, if properly deciphered, produced the
words, &ldquo;<it>Paul Groves, cobler</it>;&rdquo; and under the
name, traced in charcoal, appeared the following
record of the poor fellow's fate, &ldquo;<it>Hung
himsel in this rum for luv off licker</it>;&rdquo; accompanied
by a graphic sketch of the unhappy
suicide dangling from a beam. A farthing
candle, stuck in a bottle neck, shed its feeble
light upon the table, which, owing to the provident
kindness of Mr. Wood, was much
better furnished with eatables than might
have been expected, and boasted a loaf, a
knuckle of ham, a meat&hyphen;pie, and a flask of
wine.</p>
<pb n="8">
<p>&ldquo;You've but a sorry lodging, Mrs. Sheppard,&rdquo; 
said Wood, glancing round the chamber,
as he expanded his palms before the
scanty flame.</p>
<p>&ldquo;It's wretched enough, indeed, sir,&rdquo; rejoined
the widow; &ldquo;but, poor as it is, it's
better than the cold stones and open streets.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Of course&mdash;of course,&rdquo; returned Wood,
hastily; &ldquo;anything's better than that. But
take a drop of wine,&rdquo; urged he, filling a drinking&hyphen;horn
and presenting it to her; &ldquo;it's choice
canary, and 'll do you good. And now, come
and sit by me, my dear, and let's have a little
quiet chat together. When things are at the
worst, they'll mend. Take my word for it,
your troubles are over.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I hope they are, sir,&rdquo; answered Mrs. Sheppard,
with a faint smile and a doubtful shake
of the head, as Wood drew her to a seat beside
him, &ldquo;for I've had my full share of misery.
But I don't look for peace on this side the
grave.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Nonsense!&rdquo; cried Wood; &ldquo;while there's
life there's hope. Never be down&hyphen;hearted.</pp>
<pb n="9">
<pp>Besides,&rdquo; added he, opening the shawl in
which the infant was wrapped, and throwing
the light of the candle full upon its sickly,
but placid features, &ldquo;it's sinful to repine
while you've a child like this to comfort you.
Lord help him! he's the very image of his
father. Like carpenter, like chips.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;That likeness is the chief cause of my misery,&rdquo; 
replied the widow, shuddering. &ldquo;Were
it not for that, he would indeed be a blessing
and a comfort to me. He never cries nor frets,
as children generally do, but lies at my bosom,
or on my knee, as quiet and as gentle as you
see him now. But, when I look upon his
innocent face, and see how like he is to his
father,&mdash;when I think of that father's shameful
ending, and recollect how free from guilt
<it>he</it> once was,&mdash;at such times, Mr. Wood, despair
will come over me; and, dear as this
babe is to me, far dearer than my own wretched
life, which I would lay down for him any
minute, I have prayed to Heaven to remove
him, rather than he should grow up to be a
man, and be exposed to his father's temptations</pp>
<pb n="10">
<pp>&mdash;rather than he should live as wickedly and
die as disgracefully as his father. And, when
I have seen him pining away before my eyes,
getting thinner and thinner every day, I have
sometimes thought my prayers were heard.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Marriage and hanging go by destiny,&rdquo; 
observed Wood, after a pause; &ldquo;but I trust
your child is reserved for a better fate than
either, Mrs. Sheppard.&rdquo;</p>
<p>The latter part of this speech was delivered
with so much significance of manner, that a
by&hyphen;stander might have inferred that Mr. Wood
was not particularly fortunate in his own matrimonial
connections.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Goodness only knows what he's reserved
for,&rdquo; rejoined the widow in a desponding tone; 
&ldquo;but if Mynheer Van Galgebrok, whom I
met last night at the Cross Shovels, spoke
the truth, little Jack will never die in his
bed.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Save us!&rdquo; exclaimed Wood. &ldquo;And who
is this Van Gal&mdash;Gal&mdash;what's his outlandish
name?&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Van Galgebrok,&rdquo; replied the widow.</pp>
<pb n="11">
<pp>&ldquo;He's the famous Dutch conjuror who foretold
King William's accident and death, last
February but one, a month before either event
happened, and gave out that another prince
over the water would soon enjoy his own
again; for which he was committed to Newgate,
and whipped at the cart's tail. He
went by another name then,&mdash;Rykhart Scherprechter
I think he called himself. His fellow&hyphen;prisoners
nicknamed him the gallows&hyphen;provider,
from a habit he had of picking out all
those who were destined to the gibbet. He
was never known to err, and was as much
dreaded as the gaol&hyphen;fever in consequence. He
singled out my poor husband from a crowd
of other felons; and you know how right he
was in that case, sir.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Ay, marry,&rdquo; replied Wood, with a look
that seemed to say that he did not think it
required any surprising skill in the art of
divination to predict the doom of the individual
in question; but whatever opinion he
might entertain, he contented himself with
inquiring into the grounds of the conjuror's</pp>
<pb n="12">
<pp>evil augury respecting the infant. &ldquo;What
did the old fellow judge from, eh, Joan?&rdquo; 
asked he.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;From a black mole under the child's right
ear, shaped like a coffin, which is a bad sign; 
and a deep line just above the middle of the
left thumb, meeting round about in the form of
a noose, which is a worse,&rdquo; replied Mrs. Sheppard.
&ldquo;To be sure, it's not surprising the poor
little think should be so marked; for, when I
lay in the women&hyphen;felons' ward in Newgate,
where he first saw the light, or at least such
light as ever finds entrance into that gloomy
place, I had nothing, whether sleeping or waking,
but halters, and gibbets, and coffins, and
such like horrible visions, for ever dancing
round me! And then, you know, sir&mdash;but,
perhaps, you don't know that little Jack was
born, a month before his time, on the very day
his poor father suffered.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Lord bless us!&rdquo; ejaculated Wood, &ldquo;how
shocking! No, I did <it>not</it> know that.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You may see the marks on the child yourself,
if you choose, sir,&rsquo; urged the widow.</p>
<pb n="13">
<p>&ldquo;See the devil!&mdash;not I,&rdquo; cried Wood impatiently.
&ldquo;I didn't think you'd been so
easily fooled, Joan.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Fooled or not,&rdquo; returned Mrs. Sheppard
mysteriously, &ldquo;old Van told me <it>one</it> thing
which has come true already.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;What's that?&rdquo; asked Wood with some
curiosity.</p>
<p>&ldquo;He said, by way of comfort, I suppose,
after the fright have gave me at first, that the
child would find a friend within twenty&hyphen;four
hours, who would stand by him through life.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;A friend is not so soon gained as lost,&rdquo; 
replied Wood; &ldquo;but how has the prediction
been fulfilled, Joan, eh?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I thought you would have guessed, sir,&rdquo; 
replied the widow, timidly. &ldquo;I'm sure little
Jack has but one friend beside myself, in the
world, and that's more than I would have ventured
to say for him yesterday. However,
I've not told you all; for old Van <it>did</it> say
something about the child saving his newfound
friend's life at the time of meeting; but
how that's to happen, I'm sure I can't guess.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="14">
<p>&ldquo;Nor any one else in his senses,&rdquo; rejoined
Wood, with a laugh. &ldquo;It's not very likely
that a babby of nine months old will save <it>my</it>
life, if I'm to be his friend, as you seem to
say, Mrs. Sheppard. But I've not promised
to stand by him yet; nor will I, unless he
turns out an honest lad,&mdash;mind that. Of all
crafts,&mdash;and it was the only craft his poor
father, who, to do him justice, was one of the
best workmen that ever handled a saw or drove
a nail, could never understand,&mdash;of all crafts, I
say, to be an honest man is the master&hyphen;craft.
As long as your son observes that precept I'll
befriend him, but no longer.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I don't desire it, sir,&rdquo; replied Mrs. Sheppard,
meekly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;There's an old proverb,&rdquo; continued Wood,
rising and walking towards the fire &ldquo;which
says,&mdash;&lsquo;Put another man's child in your
bosom, and he'll creep out at your elbow.&rsquo; 
But I don't value that, because I think it
applies to one who marries a widow with incumbrances; 
and that's not my case, you
know.&rdquo;</p>
<pb>
<edit>[Figure: <bytes>393Kb</bytes>]</edit><figure sys.id="N010102">
<pb n="15">
<p>&ldquo;Well, sir,&rdquo; gasped Mrs. Sheppard.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Well, my dear, I've a proposal to make
in regard to this babby of yours, which may,
or may not, be agreeable. All I can say is, it's
well meant; and I may add, I'd have made
it five minutes ago, if you'd given me the
opportunity.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Pray come to the point, sir,&rdquo; said Mrs.
Sheppard, somewhat alarmed by this preamble.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I <it>am</it> coming to the point, Joan. The
more haste, the worse speed&mdash;better the feet
slip than the tongue. However, to cut a long
matter short, my proposal's this:&mdash;I've taken
a fancy to your bantling, and, as I've no son
of my own, if it meets with your concurrence
and that of Mrs. Wood, (for I never do anything
without consulting my better half,) I'll
take the boy, educate him, and bring him up
to my own business of a carpenter.&rsquo;</p>
<p>The poor widow hung her head, and pressed
her child closer to her breast.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Well, Joan,&rdquo; said the benevolent mechanic,
after he had looked of her steadfastly for a</pp>
<pb n="16">
<pp>few moments, &ldquo;what say you?&mdash;silence gives
consent, eh?&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>Mrs. Sheppard made an effort to speak, but
her voice was choked by emotion.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Shall I take the babby home with me?&rdquo; 
persisted Wood, in a tone between jest and
earnest.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I cannot part with him,&rdquo; replied the widow,
bursting into tears; &ldquo;indeed, indeed, I cannot.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;So I've found out the way to move her,&rdquo; 
thought the carpenter; &ldquo;those tears will do
her some good, at all events. Not part with
him!&rdquo; added he aloud. &ldquo;Why, you wouldn't
stand in the way of his good fortune surely?
I'll be a second father to him, I tell you.
Remember what the conjuror said.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I <it>do</it> remember it, sir,&rdquo; replied Mrs. Sheppard,
&ldquo;and am most grateful for your offer.
But I dare not accept it.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Dear not!&rdquo; echoed the carpenter; &ldquo;I don't
understand you, Joan.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;I mean to say, sir,&rdquo; answered Mrs. Sheppard
in a troubled voice, &ldquo;that if I lost my</pp>
<pb n="17">
<pp>child, I should lose all I have left in the world.
I have neither father, mother, brother, sister,
nor husband&mdash;I have only <it>him.</it>&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;If I ask you to part with him, my good
woman, it's to better his condition. I suppose,
and't it?&rdquo; rejoined Wood angrily; for, though
he had no serious intention of carrying his
proposal into effect, he was rather offended at
having it declined. &ldquo;It's not an offer,&rdquo; continued
he, &ldquo;that I'm likely to make, or you're
likely to receive every day in the year.&rdquo;</p>
<p>And muttering some remarks, which we do
not care to repeat, reflecting upon the consistency
of the sex, he was preparing once
more to depart, when Mrs. Sheppard stopped
him.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Give me till to&hyphen;morrow,&rdquo; implored she,
&ldquo;and if I <it>can</it> bring myself to part with him,
you shall have him without another word.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Take time to consider of it,&rdquo; replied Wood
sulkily, &ldquo;there's no hurry.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Don't be angry with me, sir,&rdquo; cried the
widow, sobbing bitterly, &ldquo;pray don't. I know
I am undeserving of your bounty; but if I</pp>
<pb n="18">
<pp>were to tell you what hardships I have undergone&mdash;to
what frightful extremities I have
been reduced&mdash;and to what infamy I have submitted,
to earn a scanty subsistence for this
child's sake,&mdash;if you could feel what it is to
stand alone in the world as I do, bereft of
all who have ever loved me, and shunned by
all who have ever known me, except the
worthless and the wretched,&mdash;if you knew
(and Heaven grant you may be spared the
knowledge!) how much affliction sharpens
love, and how much more dear to me my
child has become for every sacrifice I have
made for him,&mdash;if you were told all this,
you would, I am sure, pity rather than reproach
me, because I cannot at once consent
to a separation, which I feel would break
my heart. But give me till to&hyphen;morrow&mdash;only
till to&hyphen;morrow&mdash;I may be able to part with
him then.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p><pp>The worthy carpenter was now far more
angry with himself than he had previously
been with Mrs. Sheppard; and, as soon as he
could command his feelings, which were considerably</pp>
<pb n="19">
<pp>excited by the mention of her distresses,
he squeezed her hand warmly, bestowed
a hearty execration upon his own inhumanity,
and swore he would neither separate
he from her child, nor suffer any one else
to separate them.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Plague on't!&rdquo; added he: &ldquo;I never meant
to take your babby from you. But I'd a
mind to try whether you really loved him as
much as you pretended. I was to blame to
carry the matter so far. However, confession
of a fault makes half amends for it. A time
<it>may</it> come when this little chap will need my
aid, and, depend upon it, he shall never want
a friend in Owen Wood.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>As he said this, the carpenter patted the
cheek of the little object of his benevolent
professions, and, in so doing, unintentionally
aroused him from his slumbers. Opening a
pair of large black eyes, the child fixed them
for an instant upon Wood, and then, alarmed
by the light, uttered a low and melancholy
cry, which, however, was speedily stilled by
the caresses of his mother, towards whom he</pp>
<pb n="20">
<pp>extended his tiny arms, as if imploring protection.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;I don't think he would leave me, even if
I could part with him,&rdquo; observed Mrs. Sheppard,
smiling through her tears.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I don't think he would,&rdquo; acquiesced the
carpenter. &ldquo;No friend like the mother, for
the babby knows no other.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;And that's true,&rdquo; rejoined Mrs. Sheppard; 
&ldquo;for if I had <it>not</it> been a mother, I would not
have survived the day on which I became a
widow.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You mustn't think of that, Mrs. Sheppard,&rdquo; 
said Wood in a soothing tone.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I can't help thinking of it, sir,&rdquo; answered
the widow. &ldquo;I can never get poor Tom's last
look out of my head, as he stood in the Stone&hyphen;Hall
at Newgate, after his irons had been
knocked off, unless I manage to stupify myself
somehow. The dismal tolling of St. Sepulchre's
bell is for ever ringing in my ears&mdash;oh!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;If that's she case,&rdquo; observed Wood, &ldquo;I'm
surprised you should like to have such a
frightful picture constantly in view as that
over the chimney&hyphen;piece.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="21">
<p>&ldquo;I'd good reasons for placing it there, sir; 
but don't question me about them now, or
you'll drive me mad,&rdquo; returned Mrs. Sheppard
wildly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Well, well, we'll say no more about, it,&rdquo; 
replied Wood; &ldquo;and, by way of changing
the subject, let me advise you on no account
to fly to strong waters for consolation, Joan.
One nail drives out another, it's true; but
the worst nail you an employ is a coffinnail.
Gin Lane's the nearest road to the
churchyard.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;It may be; but if it shortens the distance
and lightens the journey, I care not,&rdquo; retorted
the widow, who seemed by this reproach to
be roused into sudden eloquence. &ldquo;To those
who, like me, have never been able to get out
of the dark and dreary paths of life, the grave
is indeed a refuge, and the sooner they reach
it the better. The spirit I drink may be
poison,&mdash;it may kill me,&mdash;perhaps it <it>is</it> killing
me:&mdash;but so would hunger, cold, misery,
&mdash;so would my own thoughts. I should have
gone mad without it. Gin is the poor man's</pp>
<pb n="22">
<pp>friend,&mdash;his sole set&hyphen;off against the rich man's
luxury. It comforts him when he is most
forlorn. It may be treacherous, it may lay
up a store of future woe; but it insurers present
happiness, and that is sufficient. When
I have traversed the streets a houseless wanderer,
driven with curses from every door
where I have solicited alms, and with blows
from every gate&hyphen;way where I have sought
shelter,&mdash;when I have crept into some deserted
building, and stretched my wearied limbs
upon a bulk, in the vain hope of repose,&mdash; 
or, worse than all, when, frenzied with want,
I have yielded to horrible temptation, and
earned a meal in the only way I could earn
one,&mdash;when I have felt, at times like these,
my heart sink within me, I have drank of
this drink, and have at once forgotten my
cares, my poverty, my guilty. Old thoughts,
old feelings, old faces, and old scenes have
returned to me, and I have fancied myself
happy,&mdash;as happy as I am now.&rdquo; And she
burst into a wild hysterical laugh.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Poor creature!&rdquo; ejaculated Wood. &ldquo;Do
you call this frantic glee happiness?&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="23">
<p>&ldquo;It's all the happiness I have known for
years,&rdquo; returned the widow, becoming suddenly
calm, &ldquo;and it's short&hyphen;lived enough, as
you perceive. I tell you what, Mr. Wood,&rdquo; 
added she in a hollow voice, and with a ghastly
look, &ldquo;gin may bring ruin; but as long as
poverty, vice, and ill&hyphen;usage exist, it will be
drunk.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;God forbid!&rdquo; exclaimed Wood, fervently; 
and, as if afraid of prolonging the interview,
he added, with some precipitation, &ldquo;But
I must be going: I've stayed here too long
already. You shall hear from me to&hyphen;morrow.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Stay!&rdquo; said Mrs. Sheppard, again arresting
his departure. &ldquo;I've just recollected that my
husband left a key with me, which he charged
me to give you when I could find an opportunity.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;A key!&rdquo; exclaimed Wood eagerly. &ldquo;I
lost a very valuable one some time ago.
What's it like, Joan?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;It's a small key, with curiously&hyphen;fashioned
wards.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;It's mine, I'll be sworn,&rdquo; rejoined Wood.</pp>
<pb n="24">
<pp>&ldquo;Well, who'd have thought of finding it in
this unexpected way!&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Don't be too sure till you see it,&rdquo; said the
widow. &ldquo;Shall I fetch it for you, sir?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;By all means.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I must trouble you to hold the child, then,
for a minute, while I run up to the garret,
where I've hidden it for safety,&rdquo; said Mrs.
Sheppard, &lsquo;I think I <it>may</it> trust him with
you, sir,&rdquo; added she, taking up the candle.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Don't leave him, if you're at all fearful,
my dear,&rdquo; replied Wood, receiving the little
burthen with a laugh. &ldquo;Poor thing!&rdquo; muttered
he, as the widow departed on her errand,
&ldquo;she's seen better days and better circumstances
than she'll ever see again,&mdash;I'm sure.
Strange, I could never learn her history. Tom
Sheppard was always a close file, and would
never tell whom he married. Of this I'm certain,
however, she was much too good for him,
and was never meant to be a journeyman carpenter's
wife, still less what she is now. Her
heart's in the right place, at all events; and,
since that's the case, the rest may perhaps</pp>
<pb n="25">
<pp>come round,&mdash;that is, if she gets through her
present illness. A dry cough's the trumpeter
of death. If that's rule, she's not long for
this world. As to this little fellow, in spite of
the Dutchman, who, in my opinion, is more of
a Jacobite than a conjurer, and more of a knave
than either, he shall never mount a horse foaled
by an acorn, if I can help it.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p><pp>The course of the carpenter's meditations
was here interrupted by a loud note of lamentation
from the child, who, disturbed by the
transfer, and not receiving the gentle solace to
which he was ordinarily accustomed, raised his
voice to the utmost, and exerted his feeble
strength to escape. For a few moments Mr.
Wood dandled his little charge to and fro,
after the most approved nursery fashion, essaying
at the same time the soothing influence of
an infantine melody proper to the occasion; 
but, failing in his design, he soon lost all patience,
and being, as we have before hinted,
rather irritable, though extremely well&hyphen;meaning,
he lifted the unhappy bantling in the air,
and shook him with so much good will, that he</pp>
<pb n="26">
<pp>had well&hyphen;nigh silenced him most effectually. A
brief calm succeeded. But with returning
breath came returning vociferations; and the
carpenter, with a faint hope of lessening the
clamour by change of scene, took up his lantern,
opened the door, and walked out</pp></p></div4>
<pb n="27">
<div4>
<comhd4><idref>Z400030619</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
CHAPTER II.
<subhead>THE OLD MINT.</subhead> <attbytes>34Kb</attbytes><reflink>000027</reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z400030619</ID><A1>Ainsworth, William Harrison, 1805&ndash;1882</A1><T1>Jack Sheppard. A Romance.</T1><PBL>Richard Bentley</PBL><Y1>1839</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd4>
<p><pp><smallcap>Mrs. Sheppard's</smallcap> habitation terminated a row
of old ruinous buildings called Wheeler's
Rents; a dirty thoroughfare, part street, and
part lane, running from Mint Street, through
a variety of turnings, and along the brink of a
deep kennel, skirted by a number for petty and
neglected gardens in the direction of Saint
George's Fields. The neighbouring houses
were tenanted by the lowest order of insolvent
traders, thieves, mendicants, and other worthless
and nefarious characters, who fled thither
to escape from their creditors, or to avoid the
punishment due to their different offences; for
we may observe that the Old Mind, although it
had been divested for some of its privileges as a
sanctuary by a recent statute passed in the
reign of William the Third, still presented a</pp>
<pb n="28">
<pp>safe asylum to the debtor, and even continued
to do so until the middle of the reign of George
the First, when the crying nature of the evil
called loudly for a remedy, and another and
more sweeping enactment entirely took away
its immunities. In consequence of the encouragement
thus offered to dishonesty, and the
security afforded to crime, this quarter of the
Borough of Southwark was accounted (at the
period of our narrative) the grand receptacle
of the superfluous villany of the metropolis.
Infested by every description of vagabond and
miscreant, it was, perhaps, a few degrees worse
than the rookery near Saint Giles's and the
desperate neighbourhood of Saffron Hill in our
own time. And yet, on the very site of the sordid
tenements and squalid courts we have mentioned,
where the felon openly made his dwelling,
and the fraudulent debtor laughed the
object of his knavery to scorn&mdash;on this spot,
not two centuries ago, stood the princely residence
of Charles Brandon, the chivalrous Duke
of Suffolk, whose stout heart was a well of
honour, and whose memory breathes of loyalty</pp>
<pb n="29">
<pp>and valour. Suffolk House, as Brandon's
palace was denominated, was subsequently converted
into a mint by his royal brother&hyphen;in&hyphen;law,
Henry the Eighth; and, after its demolition,
and the removal of the place of coinage to the
Tower, the name was still continued to the
district in which it had been situated.</pp></p>
<p><pp>Old and dilapidated, the widow's domicile
looked the very picture of desolation and misery.
Nothing more forlorn could be conceived.
The roof was partially untiled; the
chimneys were tottering; the side&hyphen;walls bulged,
and were supported by a piece of timber
propped against the opposite house; the glass
in most of the windows was broken, and its
place supplied with paper; while, in some cases,
the very frames of the windows had been destroyed,
and the apertures were left free to the
airs of heaven. On the ground&hyphen;floor the shutters
were closed, or, to speak more correctly,
altogether nailed up, and presented a very singular
appearance, being patched all over with
the soles of old shoes, rusty hobnails, and bits
of iron hoops, the ingenious device of the former</pp>
<pb n="30">
<pp>occupant of the apartment, Paul Groves,
the cobbler, to whom we have before alluded.</pp></p>
<p>It was owing to the untimely end of this
poor fellow that Mrs. Sheppard was enabled to
take possession of the premises. In a fit of
despondency, superinduced by drunkenness, he
made away with himself; and when the body
was discovered, after a lapse of some months,
such was the impression produced by the spectacle
&mdash;such the alarm occasioned by the crazy
state of the building, and, above all, by the
terror inspired by strange and unearthly noises
heard during the night, which were, of course,
attributed to the spirit of the suicide, that the
place speedily enjoyed the reputation of being
haunted, and was, consequently, entirely abandoned.
In this state Mrs. Sheppard found it; 
and, as no one opposed her, she at once took
up her abode there; nor was she long in discovering
that the dreaded sounds proceeded
from the nocturnal gambols of a legion of rats.</p>
<p><pp>A narrow entry, formed by two low walls,
communicated with the main thoroughfare; 
and in this passage, under the cover of a penthouse,</pp>
<pb n="31">
<pp>stood Wood, with his little burthen, to
whom we shall now return.</pp></p>
<p>As Mrs. Sheppard did not make her appearance
quite so soon as he expected, the carpenter
became a litle fidgetty, and, having succeeded
in tranquillizing the child, he thought proper
to walk so far down the entry as would enable
him to reconnoitre the upper windows of the
house. A light was visible in the garret, feebly
struggling through the damp atmosphere, for
the night was raw and overcast. This light did
not remain stationary, but could be seen at
one moment glimmering through the rents in
the roof, and at another shining through the
cracks in the wall, or the broken panes of the
casement. Wood was unable to discover the
figure of the widow, but he recognised her dry,
hacking cough, and was about to call her down,
if she could not find the key, as he imagined
must be the case, when a loud noise was heard,
as though a chest, or some weighty substance,
had fallen upon the floor.</p>
<p><pp>Before Wood had time to inquire into the
cause of this sound, his attention was diverted</pp>
<pb n="32">
<pp>by a man, who rushed past the entry with the
swiftness of desperation. This individual apparently
met with some impediment to his further
progress; for he had not proceeded many
steps when he turned suddenly about, and
darted up the passage in which Wood stood.</pp></p>
<p>Uttering a few inarticulate ejaculations,&mdash; 
for he was completely out of breath,&mdash;the fugitive
placed a bundle in the arms of the carpenter,
and, regardless of the consternation he
excited in the breast of that personage, who
was almost stupified with astonishment, he
began to divest himself of a heavy horseman's
cloak, which he threw over Wood's shoulder,
and, drawing his sword, seemed to listen intently
for the approach of his pursuers.</p>
<p><pp>The appearance of the new&hyphen;comer was extremely
prepossessing; and, after his trepidation
had a little subsided, Wood began to
regard him with some degree of interest. Evidently
in the flower of his age, he was scarcely
less remarkable for symmetry of person than
for comeliness of feature; and, though his
attire was plain and unpretending, it was such</pp>
<pb n="33">
<pp>as could be worn only by one belonging to the
higher ranks of society. His figure was tall
and commanding, and the expression of his
countenance (though somewhat disturbed by
his recent exertion, was resolute and stern.</pp></p>
<p>At this juncture, a cry burst from the child,
who, nearly smothered by the weight imposed
upon him, only recovered the use of his lungs
as Wood altered the position of the bundle.
The stranger turned his head at the sound.</p>
<p>&ldquo;By Heaven!&rdquo; cried he in a tone of surprise,
&ldquo;you have an infant there!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;To be sure I have,&rdquo; replied Wood, angrily; 
for, finding that the intentions of the
stranger were pacific, so far as he was concerned,
he thought he might safely venture on
a slight display of spirit. &ldquo;It's very well
you haven't crushed the poor little thing to
death with this confounded clothes'&hyphen;bag. But
some people have no consideration.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;That child may be the means of saving
me,&rdquo; muttered the stranger, as if struck by a
new idea: &ldquo;I shall gain time by the expedient.
Do you live here?&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="34">
<p>&ldquo;Not exactly,&rdquo; answered the carpenter.</p>
<p>&ldquo;No matter. The door is open, so it is
needless to ask leave to enter. Ha!&rdquo; exclaimed
the stranger, as shouts and other vociferations
resounded at no great distance along the thoroughfare,
&ldquo;not a moment is to be lost. Give
me that precious charge,&rdquo; he added, snatching
the bundle from Wood. &ldquo;If I escape, I will
reward you. Your name?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Owen Wood,&rdquo; replied the carpenter; &ldquo;I've
no reason to be ashamed of it. And now, a
fair exchange, sir. Yours?&rdquo;</p>
<p>The stranger hesitated. The shouts drew
nearer, and lights were seen flashing ruddily
against the sides and gables of the neighbouring
houses.</p>
<p>&ldquo;My name is Darrell,&rdquo; said the fugitive
hastily. &ldquo;But, if you are discovered, answer
no questions, as you value your life. Wrap
yourself in my cloak, and keep it. Remember!
not a word!&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>So saying, he huddled the mantle over
Wood's shoulders, dashed the lantern to the
ground, and extinguished the light. A moment</pp>
<pb n="35">
<pp>afterwards, the door was closed and bolted,
and the carpenter found himself alone.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Mercy on us!&rdquo; cried he, as a thrill of
apprehension ran through his frame. &ldquo;The
Dutchman was right, after all.&rdquo;</p>
<p>This exclamation had scarcely escaped him,
when the discharge of a pistol was heard, and
a bullet whizzed past his ears.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I have him!&rdquo; cried a voice in triumph.</p>
<p>A man, then, rushed up the entry, and,
seizing the unlucky carpenter by the collar,
presented a drawn sword to his throat. This
person was speedily followed by half a dozen
others, some of whom carried flambeaux.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Mur&mdash;der!&rdquo; roared Wood, struggling to
free himself from his assailant, by whom he
was half strangled.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Damnation!&rdquo; exclaimed one of the leaders
of the party in a furious tone, snatching
a torch from an attendant, and throwing
its light full upon the face of the carpenter; 
&ldquo;this is not the villain, Sir Cecil.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;So I find, Rowland,&rdquo; replied the other,
in accents of deep disappointment, and at the</pp>
<pb n="36">
<pp>same time relinquishing his grasp. &ldquo;I could
have sworn I saw him enter this passage.
And how comes his cloak on this knave's
shoulders?&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;It <it>is</it> his cloak, of a surety,&rdquo; returned
Rowland. &ldquo;Harkye, sirrah,&rdquo; continued he,
haughtily interrogating Wood; &ldquo;where is the
person from whom you received this mantle?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Throttling a man isn't the way to make
him answer questions,&rdquo; replied the carpenter,
doggedly. &ldquo;You'll get nothing out of me, I
can promise you, unless you show a little more
civility.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;We waste time with this fellow,&rdquo; interposed
Sir Cecil, &ldquo;and may lose the object of
our quest, who, beyond doubt, has taken refuge
in this building. Let us search it.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Just then, the infant began to sob piteously.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Hist!&rdquo; cried Rowland, arresting his comrade.
&ldquo;Do you hear that? We are not
wholly at fault. The dog&hyphen;fox cannot be far
off, since the cub is found.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>With these words, he tore the mantle from
Wood's back, and, perceiving the child, endeavoured</pp>
<pb n="37">
<pp>to seize it. In this attempt he was,
however, foiled by the agility of the carpenter,
who managed to retreat to the door,
against which he placed his back, kicking the
boards vigorously with his heel.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Joan! Joan!&rdquo; vociferated he, &ldquo;open the
door, for God's sake, or I shall be murdered,
and so will your babby! Open the door
quickly, I say!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Knock him on the head,&rdquo; thundered Sir
Cecil, &ldquo;or we shall have the watch upon us.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;No fear of that,&rdquo; rejoined Rowland:
&ldquo;such vermin never dare to show themselves
in this privileged district. All we have to
apprehend is a rescue.&rdquo;</p>
<p>The hint was not lost upon Wood. He
tried to raise an outcry, but his throat was
again forcibly griped by Rowland.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Another such attempt,&rdquo; said the latter,
&ldquo;and you are a dead man. Yield up the
babe, and I pledge my word you shall remain
unmolested.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I will yield it to no one but its mother,&rdquo; 
answered Wood.</p>
<pb n="38">
<p>&ldquo;'Sdeath! do you trifle with me, sirrah?&rdquo; 
cried Rowland fiercely. &ldquo;Give me the child,
or&mdash;&rdquo; 
<lb>As he spoke the door was thrown open,
and Mrs. Sheppard staggered forward. She
looked paler than ever; but her countenance,
though bewildered, did not exhibit the alarm
which might naturally have been anticipated
from the strange and perplexing scene presented
to her view.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Take it,&rdquo; cried Wood, holding the infant
towards her; &ldquo;take it, and fly.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Mrs. Sheppard put out her arms mechanically.
But before the child could be committed
to her care, it was wrested from the
carpenter by Rowland.</p>
<p>&ldquo;These people are all in league with him,&rdquo; 
cried the latter. &ldquo;But don't wait for me, Sir
Cecil. Enter the house with your men. I'll
dispose of the brat.&rdquo;</p>
<p>This injunction was instantly obeyed. The
knight and his followers crossed the threshold,
leaving one of the torch&hyphen;bearers behind
them.</p>
<pb n="39">
<p>&ldquo;Davies,&rdquo; said Rowland, delivering the
babe, with a meaning look, to his attendant.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I understand, sir,&rdquo; replied Davies, drawing
a little aside. And, setting down the link,
he proceeded deliberately to untie his cravat.</p>
<p>&ldquo;My God! will you see your child strangled
before your eyes, and not so much as
scream for help?&rdquo; said Wood, staring at the
widow with a look of surprise and horror.
&ldquo;Woman, your wits are fled!&rdquo;</p>
<p>And so it seemed; for all the answer she
could make was to murmur distractedly, &ldquo;I
can't find the key.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Devil take the key!&rdquo; ejaculated Wood.
&ldquo;They're about to murder your child&mdash;<it>your</it>
child, I tell you! Do you comprehend what I
say, Joan?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I've hurt my head,&rdquo; replied Mrs. Sheppard,
pressing her hand to her temples.</p>
<p>And then, for the first time, Wood noticed a
small stream of blood coursing slowly down
her cheek.</p>
<p>At this moment, Davies, who had completed
his preparations, extinguished the torch.</p>
<pb n="40">
<p>&ldquo;It's all over,&rdquo; groaned Wood, &ldquo;and perhaps
it's as well her senses are gone. However,
I'll make a last effort to save the poor
little creature,) if it costs me my life.&rdquo;</p>
<p>And, with this generous resolve, he shouted
at the top of his voice, &ldquo;Arrest! arrest! help!
help!&rdquo; seconding the words with a shrill and
peculiar cry, well known at the time to the
inhabitants of the quarter in which it was
uttered.</p>
<p>In reply to this summons a horn was instantly
blown at the corner of the street.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Arrest!&rdquo; vociferated Wood. &ldquo;Mint!
Mint!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Death and hell!&rdquo; cried Rowland, making
a furious pass at the carpenter, who fortunately
avoided the thrust in the darkness; 
&ldquo;will nothing silence you?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Help!&rdquo; ejaculated Wood, renewing his
cries. &ldquo;Arrest!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Jigger closed!&rdquo; shouted a hoarse voice in
reply. &ldquo;All's bowman, my covey. Fear nothing.
We'll be upon the bandogs before
they can shake their trotters!&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="41">
<p>And the alarum was sounded more loudly
than ever.</p>
<p>Another horn now resounded from the further
extremity of the thoroughfare; this was
answered by a third; and presently a fourth,
and more remote blast, took up the note of
alarm. The whole neighbourhood was disturbed.
A garrison called to arms at dead of
night on the sudden approach of the enemy,
could not have been more expeditiously, or
effectually aroused. Rattles were sprung; 
lanterns lighted, and hoisted at the end of
poles; windows thrown open; doors unbarred; 
and, as if by magic, the street was instantaneously
filled with a crowd of persons of
both sexes, armed with such weapons as came
most readily to hand, and dressed in such
garments as could be most easily slipped on.
Hurrying in the direction of the supposed
arrest, they encouraged each other with shouts,
and threatened the offending parties with their
vengeance.</p>
<p><pp>Regardless as the gentry of the Mint usually
were (for, indeed, they had become habituated</pp>
<pb n="42">
<pp>from their frequent occurrence to such scenes,)
of any outrages committed in their streets; 
deaf, as they had been, to the recent scuffle
before Mrs. Sheppard's door, they were always
sufficiently on the alert to maintain their privileges,
and to assist each other against the
attacks of their common enemy&mdash;the sheriff's
officer. It was only by the adoption of such
a course (especially since the late act of suppression,
to which we have alluded,) that the
inviolability of the asylum could be preserved.
Incursions were often made upon its territories
by the functionaries of the law; sometimes
attended with success, but more frequently
with discomfiture; and it rarely happened,
unless by stratagem or bribery, that
(in the language of the gentlemen of the short
staff) an important caption could be effected.
In order to guard against accidents or surprises,
watchmen, or scouts, (as they were
styled,) were stationed at the three main outlets
of the sanctuary ready to give the signal
in the manner just described: bars were erected,
which, in case of emergency, could be</pp>
<pb n="43">
<pp>immediately stretched across the streets; doors
were attached to the alleys; and were never
opened without due precautions; gates were
affixed to the courts, wickets to the gates, and
bolts to the wickets. The back windows of
the houses (where any such existed) were
strongly barricaded, and kept constantly shut; 
and the fortress was, furthermore, defended by
high walls and deep ditches in those quarters
where it appeared most exposed. There was
also a Maze, (the name is still retained in the
district,) into which the debtor could run,
and through the intricacies of which it was
impossible for an officer to follow him, without
a clue. Whoever chose to incur the risk
of so doing might enter the Mint at any hour; 
but no one was suffered to depart without
giving a satisfactory account of himself, or
producing a pass from the Master. In short,
every contrivance that ingenuity could devise
was resorted to by this horde of reprobates to
secure themselves from danger or molestation.
Whitefriars had lost its privileges; Salisbury
Court and the Savoy no longer offered places</pp>
<pb n="44">
<pp>of refuge to the debtor; and it was, therefore,
doubly requisite that the Island of Bermuda
(as the Mint was termed by its occupants)
should uphold its rights, as long as it was
able to do so.</pp></p>
<p>Mr. Wood, meantime, had not remained
idle. Aware that not a moment was to be
lost, if he meant to render any effectual assistance
to the child, he ceased shouting, and
defending himself in the best way he could
from the attacks of Rowland, by whom he was
closely pressed, forced his way, in spite of all
opposition, to Davies, and dealt him a blow
on the head with such good will that, had it
not been for the intervention of the wall, the
ruffian must have been prostrated. Before he
could recover from the stunning effects of the
blow, Wood possessed himself of the child:
and, untying the noose which had been slipped
round its throat, had the satisfaction of
hearing it cry lustily.</p>
<p>At this juncture, Sir Cecil and his followers
appeared at the threshold.</p>
<pb n="45">
<p>&ldquo;He has escaped!&rdquo; exclaimed the knight; 
&ldquo;we have searched every corner of the house
without finding a trace of him.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Back!&rdquo; cried Rowland. &ldquo;Don't you hear
those shouts? Yon fellow's clamour has
brought the whole horde of jail&hyphen;birds and
cut&hyphen;throats that infest this place about our
ears. We shall be torn in pieces if we are
discovered. Davies!&rdquo; he added, calling to the
attendant, who was menacing Wood with a
severe retaliation, &ldquo;don't heed him; but, if
you value a whole skin, come into the house,
and bring that woman with you. She may
afford us some necessary information.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Davies reluctantly complied. And, dragging
Mrs. Sheppard, who made no resistance,
along with him, entered the house, the door
of which was instantly shut and barricaded.</p>
<p>A moment afterwards, the street was illumined
by a blaze of torchlight, and a tumultuous
uproar, mixed with the clashing of weapons,
and the braying of horns, announced the
arrival of the first detachment of Minters.</p>
<pb n="46">
<p>Mr. Wood rushed instantly to meet them.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Hurrah!&rdquo; shouted he, waving his hat
triumphantly over his head. &ldquo;Saved!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ay, ay, it's all bob, my covey! You're
safe enough, that's certain!&rdquo; responded the
Minters, baying, yelping, leaping, and howling
around him like a pack of hounds when the
huntsman is beating cover; &ldquo;but, where are
the lurchers?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Who?&rdquo; asked Wood.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The traps!&rdquo; responded a bystander.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The shoulder&hyphen;clappers!&rdquo; added a lady,
who, in her anxiety to join the party, had
unintentionally substituted her husband's nether
habiliments for her own petticoats.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The ban&hyphen;dogs!&rdquo; thundered a tall man,
whose stature and former avocations had procured
him the nickname of &ldquo;The long drover
of the Borough market.&rdquo; &ldquo;Where are they?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ay, where are they?&rdquo; chorussed the mob,
flourishing their various weapons, and flashing
their torches in the air; &ldquo;we'll sarve 'em
out.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>Mr. Wood trembled. He felt he had raised</pp>
<pb n="47">
<pp>a storm which it would be very difficult, if
not impossible, to allay. He knew not what
to say, or what to do; and his confusion was
increased by the threatening gestures and furious
looks of the ruffians in his immediate
vicinity.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;I don't understand you, gentlemen,&rdquo; stammered
he, at length.</p>
<p>&ldquo;What does he say?&rdquo; roared the long
drover.</p>
<p>&ldquo;He says he don't understand flash,&rdquo; replied
the lady in gentleman's attire.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Cease your confounded clutter!&rdquo; said a
young man, whose swarthy visage, seen in the
torchlight, struck Wood as being that of a
Mulatto. &ldquo;You frighten the cull out of his
senses. It's plain he don't understand our
lingo; as, how should he? Take pattern by
me;&rdquo; and as he said this he strode up to
the carpenter, and, slapping him on the shoulder,
propounded the following questions, accompanying
each interrogation with a formidable
contortion of countenance. &ldquo;Curse you!
Where are the bailiffs? Rot you! have you</pp>
<pb n="48">
<pp>lost your tongue? Devil seize you! you
could bawl loud enough a moment ago!&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Silence, Blueskin!&rdquo; interposed an authoritative
voice, immediately behind the ruffian.
&ldquo;Let me have a word with the cull!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ay! ay!&rdquo; cried several of the bystanders,
&ldquo;let Jonathan kimbaw the cove. He's got
the gift of the gab.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>The crowd accordingly drew aside, and the
individual, in whose behalf the movement had
been made, immediately stepped forward. He
was a young man of about two&hyphen;and&hyphen;twenty,
who, without having anything remarkable
either in dress or appearance, was yet a noticeable
person, if only for the indescribable
expression of cunning pervading his countenance.
His eyes were small and grey; as
far apart and as sly&hyphen;looking as those of a
fox. A physiognomist, indeed, would have
likened him to that crafty animal, and it must
be owned the general formation of his features
favoured such a comparison. The nose was
long and sharp, the chin pointed, the forehead
broad and flat, and connected, without any</pp>
<pb n="49">
<pp>intervening hollow, with the eyelid; the teeth
when displayed, seemed to reach from ear to
ear. Then his beard was of a reddish hue,
and his complexion warm and sanguine. Those
who had seen him slumbering, averred that
he slept with his eyes open. But this might
be merely a figurative mode of describing his
customary vigilance. Certain it was, that the
slightest sound aroused him. This astute personage
was somewhat under the middle size,
but fairly proportioned, inclining rather to
strength than symmetry, and abounding more
in muscle than in flesh.</pp></p>
<p>It would seem, from the attention which he
evidently bestowed upon the hidden and complex
machinery of the grand system of villainy
at work around him, that his chief object in
taking up his quarters in the Mint, must have
been to obtain some private information respecting
the habits and practices of its inhabitants,
to be turned to account hereafter.</p>
<p><pp>Advancing towards Wood, Jonathan fixed
his keen grey eyes upon him, and demanded,
in a stern tone, whether the persons who had</pp>
<pb n="50">
<pp>taken refuge in the adjoining house, were
bailiffs.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Not that I know of,&rdquo; replied the carpenter,
who had in some degree recovered his
confidence.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Then I presume you've not been arrested?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I have not,&rdquo; answered Wood firmly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I guessed as much. Perhaps you'll next
inform us why you have occasioned this disturbance.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Because this child's life was threatened
by the persons you have mentioned,&rdquo; rejoined
Wood.</p>
<p>&ldquo;An excellent reason, i' faith!&rdquo; exclaimed
Blueskin, with a roar of surprise and indignation,
which was echoed by the whole assemblage.
&ldquo;And so we're to be summoned from
our beds and snug firesides, because a kid
happens to squall, eh? By the soul of my
grandmother, but this is too good!&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Do you intend to claim the privileges
of the Mint?&rdquo; said Jonathan, calmly pursuing</pp>
<pb n="51">
<pp>his interrogations amid the uproar. &ldquo;Is your
person in danger?&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Not from my creditors,&rdquo; replied Wood,
significantly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Will he post the cole? Will he come
down with the dues? Ask him that?&rdquo; cried
Blueskin.</p>
<p>&ldquo;You hear,&rdquo; pursued Jonathan; &ldquo;my friend
desires to know if you are willing to pay your
footing as a member of the ancient and respectable
fraternity of debtors?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I owe no man a farthing, and my name
shall never appear in any such rascally list,&rdquo; 
replied Wood angrily. &ldquo;I don't see why I
should be obliged to pay for doing my duty.
I tell you this child would have been strangled.
The noose was at its throat when I called
for help. I knew it was in vain to cry &lsquo;murder!&rsquo; 
in the Mint, so I had recourse to stratagem.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Well, sir, I must say you deserve some
credit for your ingenuity, at all events,&rdquo; replied
Jonathan, repressing a smile; &ldquo;but, before you</pp>
<pb n="52">
<pp>put out your foot so far, it would have been
quite as prudent to consider how you were to
draw it back again. For my own part, I don't
see in what way it is to be accomplished, except
by the payment of our customary fees. Do
not imagine you can at one moment avail yourself
of our excellent regulations, (with which
you seem sufficiently well acquainted,) and the
next break them with impunity. If you assume
the character of a debtor for your own
convenience, you must be content to maintain
it for ours. If you have not been arrested,
we have been disturbed; and it is but just and
reasonable you should pay for occasioning such
disturbance. By your own showing you are
in easy circumstances,&mdash;for it is only natural
to presume that a man who owes nothing must
be in a condition to pay liberally,&mdash;and you
cannot therefore feel the loss of such a trifle
as ten guineas.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p><pp>However illogical and inconclusive these arguments
might appear to Mr. Wood, and however
he might dissent from the latter proposition,
he did not deem it expedient to make</pp>
<pb n="53">
<pp>any reply; and the orator proceeded with his
harangue amid the general applause of the
assemblage.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;I am perhaps exceeding my authority in
demanding so slight a sum,&rdquo; continued Jonathan,
modestly, &ldquo;and the Master of the Mint
may not be disposed to let you off so lightly.
He will be here in a moment or so, and you
will then learn his determination. In the mean
time, let me advise you as a friend not to
irritate him by a refusal, which would be
as useless as vexatious. He has a very summary
mode of dealing with refractory persons,
I assure you. My best endeavours shall
be used to bring you off, on the easy terms I
have mentioned.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Do you call ten guineas easy terms?&rdquo; cried
Wood, with a look of dismay. &ldquo;Why, I
should expect to purchase the entire freehold
of the Mint for less money.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Many a man has been glad to pay double
the amount to get his head from under the
mint pump,&rdquo; observed Blueskin, gruffly.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Let the gentleman take his own course,&rdquo;</pp>
<pb n="54">
<pp>said Jonathan, mildly. &ldquo;I should be sorry
to persuade him to do anything his calmer
judgment might disapprove.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Exactly my sentiments,&rdquo; rejoined Blueskin.
&ldquo;I wouldn't force him for the world; 
but if he don't tip the stivers, may I be cursed
if he don't get a taste of the <it>aqua pompaginis</it>.
Let's have a look at the kinchen that <it>ought</it>
to have been throttled,&rdquo; added he, snatching
the child from Wood. &ldquo;My stars! here's a
pretty lullaby&hyphen;cheat to make a fuss about&mdash; 
ho! ho!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Deal with me as you think proper, gentlemen,&rdquo; 
exclaimed Wood; &ldquo;but, for mercy's
sake don't harm the child! Let it be taken
to its mother.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;And who is its mother?&rdquo; asked Jonathan,
in an eager whisper. &ldquo;Tell me frankly, and
speak under your breath. Your own safety&mdash; 
the child's safety&mdash;depends upon your candour.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>While Mr. Wood underwent this examination,
Blueskin felt a small and trembling hand</pp>
<pb n="55">
<pp>placed upon his own, and, turning at the summons,
beheld a young female, whose features
were partially concealed by a loo, or half mask,
standing beside him. Coarse as were the ruffian's
notions of feminine beauty, he could not
be insensible to the surpassing loveliness of
the fair creature, who had thus solicited his
attention. Her figure was, in some measure,
hidden by a large scarf, and a deep hood
drawn over the head contributed to her disguise; 
still it was evident, from her lofty bearing,
that she had nothing in common, except
an interest in their proceedings, with the crew
by whom she was surrounded.</pp></p>
<p>Whence she came,&mdash;who she was,&mdash;and
what she wanted,&mdash;were questions which naturally
suggested themselves to Blueskin, and
he was about to seek for some explanation,
when his curiosity was checked by a gesture
of silence from the lady.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Hush!&rdquo; said she, in a low, but agitated
voice; &ldquo;would you earn this purse?&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;I've no objection,&rdquo; replied Blueskin, in</pp>
<pb n="56">
<pp>a tone intended to be gentle, but which sounded
like the murmuring whine of a playful
bear. &ldquo;How much is there in it?&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;It contains gold,&rdquo; replied the lady; &ldquo;but
I will add this ring.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;What am I to do to earn it?&rdquo; asked Blueskin,
with a disgusting leer,&mdash;&ldquo;cut a throat&mdash; 
or throw myself at your feet&mdash;eh, my dear?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Give me that child,&rdquo; returned the lady,
with difficulty overcoming the loathing inspired
by the ruffian's familiarity.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Oh! I see!&rdquo; replied Blueskin, winking
significantly. &ldquo;Come nearer, or they'll observe
us. Don't be afraid&mdash;I won't hurt you.
I'm always agreeable to the women, bless
their kind hearts! Now! slip the purse into
my hand. Bravo!&mdash;the best cly&hyphen;faker of 'em
all couldn't have done it better. And now for
the fawney&mdash;the ring I mean. I'm no great
judge of these articles, ma'am; but I trust
to your honour not to palm off paste upon
me.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;It is a diamond,&rdquo; said the lady, in an
agony of distress,&mdash;&ldquo;the child!&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="57">
<p>&ldquo;A diamond! Here, take the kid,&rdquo; cried
Blueskin, slipping the infant adroitly under
her scarf. &ldquo;And so this is a diamond,&rdquo; added
he, contemplating the brilliant from the hollow
of his hand: &ldquo;it does sparkle almost as brightly
as your ogles. By the by, my dear, I forgot
to ask your name&mdash;perhaps you'll oblige
me with it now? Hell and the devil!&mdash; 
gone!&rdquo;</p>
<p>He looked around in vain. The lady had
disappeared.</p></div4>
<pb n="58">
<div4>
<comhd4><idref>Z400030620</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
CHAPTER III.
<subhead>THE MASTER OF THE MINT.</subhead> <attbytes>13Kb</attbytes><reflink>000027</reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z400030620</ID><A1>Ainsworth, William Harrison, 1805&ndash;1882</A1><T1>Jack Sheppard. A Romance.</T1><PBL>Richard Bentley</PBL><Y1>1839</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd4>
<p><smallcap>Jonathan</smallcap>, meanwhile, having ascertained the
parentage of the child from Wood, proceeded
to question him, in an under tone, as to the
probable motives of the attempt upon its life; 
and, though he failed in obtaining any information
on this point, he had little difficulty
in eliciting such particulars of the mysterious
transaction as have already been recounted.
When the carpenter concluded his recital,
Jonathan was for a moment lost in reflection.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Devilish strange!&rdquo; thought he, chuckling
to himself; &ldquo;queer business! Capital trick
of the cull in the cloak to make another person's
brat stand the brunt for his own&mdash;capital!
ha! ha! Won't do, though. He must
be a sly fox to get out of the Mint without my</pp>
<pb n="59">
<pp>knowledge. I've a shrewd guess where he's
taken refuge; but I'll ferret him out. These
bloods will pay well for his capture; if not,
<it>he'll</it> pay well to get out of their hands; so
I'm safe either way&mdash;ha! ha! Blueskin,&rdquo; 
he added aloud, and motioning that worthy,
&ldquo;follow me.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>Upon which, he set off in the direction of
the entry. His progress, however, was checked
by loud acclamations, announcing the arrival
of the Master of the Mint and his train.</p>
<p><pp>Baptist Kettleby (for so was the Master
named) was a &ldquo;goodly portly man, and a corpulent,&rdquo; 
whose fair round paunch bespoke the
affection he entertained for good liquor and
good living. He had a quick, shrewd, merry
eye, and a look in which duplicity was agreeably
veiled by good humour. It was easy to
discover that he was a knave, but equally easy
to perceive that he was a pleasant fellow; a
combination of qualities by no means of rare
occurrence. So far as regards his attire, Baptist
was not seen to advantage. No great lover
of state or state costume at any time, he was</pp>
<pb n="60">
<pp>generally, towards the close of an evening,
completely in dishabille, and in this condition
he now presented himself to his subjects. His
shirt was unfastened, his vest unbuttoned, his
hose ungartered; his feet were stuck into a
pair of pantoufles, his arms into a greasy flannel
dressing&hyphen;gown, his head into a thrum&hyphen;cap,
the cap into a tie&hyphen;periwig, and the wig into
a gold&hyphen;edged hat. A white apron was tied
round his waist, and into the apron was thrust
a short thick truncheon, which looked very
much like a rolling&hyphen;pin.</pp></p>
<p><pp>The Master of the Mint was accompanied
by another gentleman almost as portly as himself,
and quite as deliberate in his movements.
The costume of this personage was somewhat
singular, and might have passed for a masquerading
habit, had not the imperturbable gravity
of his demeanour forbidden any such supposition.
It consisted of a close jerkin of
brown frieze, ornamented with a triple row
of brass buttons; loose Dutch slops, made
very wide in the seat and very tight at the
knees; red stockings with black clocks, and</pp>
<pb n="61">
<pp>a fur cap. The owner of this dress had a
broad weather&hyphen;beaten face, small twinkling
eyes, and a bushy, grizzled beard. Though
he walked by the side of the governor, he
seldom exchanged a word with him, but appeared
wholly absorbed in the contemplations
inspired by a broad&hyphen;bowled Dutch pipe.</pp></p>
<p>Behind the illustrious personages just described
marched a troop of stalwart fellows,
with white badges in their hats, quarter&hyphen;staves,
oaken cudgels, and links in their hands. These
were the Master's body&hyphen;guard.</p>
<p>Advancing towards the Master, and claiming
an audience, which was instantly granted, Jonathan,
without much circumlocution, related the
sum of the strange story he had just learnt
from Wood, omitting nothing except a few
trifling particulars, which he thought it politic
to keep back; and, with this view, he
said not a word of their being any probability
of capturing the fugitive, but, on the
contrary, roundly asserted that his informant
had witnessed that person's escape.</p>
<p><pp>The Master listened, with becoming attention,</pp>
<pb n="62">
<pp>to the narrative, and, at its conclusion,
shook his head gravely, applied his thumb
to the side of his nose, and, twirling his fingers
significantly, winked at his phlegmatic companion.
The gentleman appealed to shook
his head in reply, coughed as only a Dutchman
<it>can</it> cough, and raising his hand from
the bowl of his pipe, went through precisely
the same mysterious ceremonial as the Master.</pp></p>
<p>Putting his own construction upon this mute
interchange of opinions, Jonathan ventured to
observe, that it certainly was a very perplexing
case, but that he thought something <it>might</it>
be made of it, and, if left to him, he would
undertake to manage the matter to the Master's
entire satisfaction.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Ja, ja, Muntmeester,&rdquo; said the Dutchman,
removing the pipe from his mouth, and speaking
in a deep and guttural voice, &ldquo;leave the
affair to Johannes. He'll settle it brafely.
And let ush go back to our brandewyn, and
hollandsche genever. Dese ere not schouts,
as you faind, but jonkers on a vrolyk; and
if dey'd chanshed to keel de vrow Sheppard's</pp>
<pb n="63">
<pp>pet lamb, dey'd have done her a servish, by
shaving it from dat unpleasant complaint, de
hempen fever, with which its laatter days are
threatened, and of which its poor vader died.
Myn Got! haanging runs in some families,
Muntmeester. It's hereditary, like de jigt,
vat you call it&mdash;gout&mdash;haw! haw!&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;If the child <it>is</it> destined to the gibbet, Van
Galgebrok,&rdquo; replied the Master, joining in the
laugh, &ldquo;it'll never be choked by a footman's
cravat, that's certain; but, in regard to going
back empty&hyphen;handed,&rdquo; continued he, altering
his tone, and assuming a dignified air, &ldquo;it's
quite out of the question. With Baptist Kettleby,
to engage in a matter is to go through
with it. Besides, this is an affair which no
one but myself can settle. Common offences
may be decided upon by deputy; but outrages
perpetrated by men of rank, as these
appear to be, must be judged by the Master
of the Mint in person. These are the decrees
of the Island of Bermuda, and I will never
suffer its excellent laws to be violated. Gentlemen
of the Mint,&rdquo; added he, pointing with</pp>
<pb n="64">
<pp>his truncheon towards Mrs. Sheppard's house,
&ldquo;forward!&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Hurrah!&rdquo; shouted the mob, and the whole
phalanx was put in motion in that direction.
At the same moment a martial flourish, proceeding
from cows' horns, tin canisters filled
with stones, bladders and cat&hyphen;gut, with other
sprightly instruments, was struck up, and, enlivened
by this harmonious accompaniment,
the troop reached its destination in the best
possible spirits for an encounter.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Let us in,&rdquo; said the Master, rapping his
truncheon authoritatively against the boards,
&ldquo;or we'll force an entrance.&rdquo;</p>
<p>But as no answer was returned to the summons,
though it was again, and more peremptorily,
repeated, Baptist seized a mallet from a
bystander and burst open the door. Followed
by Van Galgebrok and others of his retinue,
he then rushed into the room, where Rowland,
Sir Cecil, and their attendants, stood with
drawn swords prepared to receive them.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Beat down their blades,&rdquo; cried the Master; 
&ldquo;no bloodshed.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="65">
<p>&ldquo;Beat out their brains, you mean,&rdquo; rejoined
Blueskin with a tremendous imprecation; 
&ldquo;no half measures now, Master.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Hadn't you better hold a moment's parley
with the gentlemen before proceeding to extremities?&rdquo; 
suggested Jonathan.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Agreed,&rdquo; responded the Master. &ldquo;Surely,&rdquo; 
he added, staring at Rowland, &ldquo;either I'm
greatly mistaken, or it is&mdash;&rdquo; 
<lb>&ldquo;You are not mistaken, Baptist,&rdquo; returned
Rowland with a gesture of silence; 
&ldquo;it is your old friend. I'm glad to recognise
you.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;And I'm glad your worship's recognition
doesn't come too late,&rdquo; observed the Master.
&ldquo;But why didn't you make yourself known at
once?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I'd forgotten the office you hold in the
Mint, Baptist,&rdquo; replied Rowland. &ldquo;But clear
the room of this rabble, if you have sufficient
authority over them. I would speak with
you.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;There's but one way of clearing it, your
worship,&rdquo; said the Master, archly.</p>
<pb n="66">
<p>&ldquo;I understand,&rdquo; replied Rowland. &ldquo;Give
them what you please. I'll repay you.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;It's all right, pals,&rdquo; cried Baptist, in a
loud tone; &ldquo;the gentlemen and I have settled
matters. No more scuffling.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;What's the meaning of all this?&rdquo; demanded
Sir Cecil. &ldquo;How have you contrived
to still these troubled waters?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I've chanced upon an old ally in the Master
of the Mint,&rdquo; answered Rowland. &ldquo;We
may trust him,&rdquo; he added in a whisper; &ldquo;he is
a staunch friend of the good cause.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Blueskin, clear the room,&rdquo; cried the Master; 
&ldquo;these gentlemen would be private.
They've <it>paid</it> for their lodging. Where's
Jonathan?&rdquo;</p>
<p>Inquiries were instantly made after that individual,
but he was nowhere to be found.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Strange!&rdquo; observed the Master; &ldquo;I thought
he'd been at my elbow all this time. But it
don't much matter&mdash;though he's a devilish
shrewd fellow, and might have helped me out
of a difficulty, had any occurred. Hark ye,
Blueskin,&rdquo; continued he, addressing that personage,</pp>
<pb n="67">
<pp>who, in obedience to his commands,
had, with great promptitude, driven out the
rabble, and again secured the door, &ldquo;a word
in your ear. What female entered the house
with us?&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Blood and thunder!&rdquo; exclaimed Blueskin,
afraid, if he admitted having seen the lady, of
being compelled to divide the plunder he had
obtained from her among his companions,
&ldquo;how should I know? D'ye suppose I'm
always thinking of the petticoats? I observed
no female; but if any one <it>did</it> join the assault,
it must have been either Amazonian Kate, or
Fighting Moll.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;The woman I mean did not join the assault,&rdquo; 
rejoined the Master, &ldquo;but rather
seemed to shun observation; and, from the
hasty glimpse I caught of her, she appeared to
have a child in her arms.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Then, most probably, it was the widow
Sheppard,&rdquo; answered Blueskin, sulkily.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Right,&rdquo; said the Master, &ldquo;I didn't
think of her. And now I've another job for
vou.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="68">
<p>&ldquo;Propose it,&rdquo; returned Blueskin, inclining
his head.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Square accounts with the rascal who got
up the sham arrest; and, if he don't tip the
cole without more ado, give him a taste of the
pump, that's all.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;He shall go through the whole course,&rdquo; 
replied Blueskin, with a ferocious grin, &ldquo;unless
he comes down to the last grig. We'll
lather him with mud, shave him with a rusty
razor, and drench him with <it>aqua pompaginis</it>.
Master, your humble servant.&mdash;Gentlemen,
your most obsequious trout.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Having effected his object, which was to get
rid of Blueskin, Baptist turned to Rowland
and Sir Cecil, who had watched his proceedings
with much impatience, and remarked, &ldquo;Now,
gentlemen, the coast's clear; we've nothing to
interrupt us. I'm entirely at your service.&rdquo;</p></div4>
<pb n="69">
<div4>
<comhd4><idref>Z400030621</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
CHAPTER IV.
<subhead>THE ROOF AND THE WINDOW.</subhead> <attbytes>20Kb</attbytes><reflink>000027</reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z400030621</ID><A1>Ainsworth, William Harrison, 1805&ndash;1882</A1><T1>Jack Sheppard. A Romance.</T1><PBL>Richard Bentley</PBL><Y1>1839</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd4>
<p><pp><smallcap>Leaving</smallcap> them to pursue their conference, we
shall follow the footsteps of Jonathan, who, as
the Master surmised, and, as we have intimated,
had unquestionably entered the house.
But at the beginning of the affray, when he
thought every one was too much occupied with
his own concerns to remark his absence, he
slipped out of the room, not for the purpose of
avoiding the engagement (for cowardice was
not one of his failings), but because he had
another object in view. Creeping stealthily up
stairs, unmasking a dark lantern, and glancing
into each room as he passed, he was startled
in one of them by the appearance of Mrs.
Sheppard, who seemed to be crouching upon
the floor. Satisfied, however, that she did not
notice him, Jonathan glided away as noiselessly</pp>
<pb n="70">
<pp>as he came, and ascended another short flight
of stairs leading to the garret. As he crossed
this chamber, his foot struck against something
on the floor, which nearly threw him down,
and stooping to examine the object, he found
it was a key. &ldquo;Never throw away a chance,&rdquo; 
thought Jonathan. &ldquo;Who knows but this
key may open a golden lock one of these
days?&rdquo; And, picking it up, he thrust it into
his pocket.</pp></p>
<p>Arrived beneath an aperture in the broken
roof, he was preparing to pass through it,
when he observed a little heap of tiles upon
the floor, which appeared to have been recently
dislodged. &ldquo;He <it>has</it> passed this way,&rdquo; cried
Jonathan, exultingly; &ldquo;I have him safe
enough.&rdquo; He then closed the lantern, mounted
without much difficulty upon the roof, and
proceeded cautiously along the tiles.</p>
<p><pp>The night was now profoundly dark. Jonathan
had to feel his way. A single false step
might have precipitated him into the street; or,
if he had trodden upon an unsound part of the
roof, he must have fallen through it. He had</pp>
<pb n="71">
<pp>nothing to guide him; for though the torches
were blazing ruddily below, their gleam fell
only on the side of the building. The venturous
climber gazed for a moment at the
assemblage beneath, to ascertain that he was
not discovered; and, having satisfied himself in
this particular, he stepped out more boldly.
On gaining a stack of chimneys at the back
of the house, he came to a pause, and again
unmasked his lantern. Nothing, however,
could be discerned, except the crumbling brickwork.
&ldquo;Confusion!&rdquo; ejaculated Jonathan; 
&ldquo;can he have escaped? No. The walls are
too high, and the windows too stoutly barricaded
in this quarter, to admit such a supposition.
He can't be far off. I shall find him
yet. Ah! I have it,&rdquo; he added, after a moment's
deliberation; &ldquo;he's there, I'll be
sworn.&rdquo; And, once more enveloping himself
in darkness, he pursued his course.</pp></p>
<p><pp>He had now reached the adjoining house,
and, scaling the roof, approached another building,
which seemed to be, at least, one story
loftier than its neighbours. Apparently, Jonathan</pp>
<pb n="72">
<pp>was well acquainted with the premises; 
for, feeling about in the dark, he speedily discovered
a ladder, up the steps of which he
hurried. Drawing a pistol, and unclosing his
lantern with the quickness of thought, he then
burst through an open trap&hyphen;door into a small
loft.</pp></p>
<p>The light fell upon the fugitive, who stood
before him in an attitude of defence, with the
child in his arms.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Aha!&rdquo; exclaimed Jonathan, acting upon
the information he had obtained from Wood; 
&ldquo;I have found you at last. Your servant,
Mr. Darrell.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Who are you?&rdquo; demanded the fugitive,
sternly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;A friend,&rdquo; replied Jonathan, uncocking the
pistol, and placing it in his pocket.</p>
<p>&ldquo;How do I know you are a friend?&rdquo; asked
Darrell.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;What should I do here alone if I were an
enemy? But, come, don't let us waste time in
bandying words, when we might employ it so
much more profitably. Your life, and that of</pp>
<pb>
<edit>[Figure: <bytes>280Kb</bytes>]</edit><figure sys.id="N010103">
<pb n="73">
<pp>your child, are in my power. What will you
give me to save you from your pursuers?&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;<it>Can</it> you do so?&rdquo; asked the other, doubtfully.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I can, and will. Now, the reward?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I have but an ill&hyphen;furnished purse. But if
I escape, my gratitude&wblank;&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Pshaw!&rdquo; interrupted Jonathan, scornfully.
&ldquo;Your gratitude will vanish with your danger.
Pay fools with promises. I must have something
in hand.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You shall have all I have about me,&rdquo; replied
Darrell.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Well&mdash;well,&rdquo; grumbled Jonathan, &ldquo;I suppose
I must be content. An ill&hyphen;lined purse is a
poor recompense for the risk I have run.
However, come along. I needn't tell you to
tread carefully. You know the danger of this
breakneck road as well as I do. The light
would betray us.&rdquo; So saying, he closed the
lantern.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Harkye, sir,&rdquo; rejoined Darrell; &ldquo;one word
before I move. I know not who you are; and,
as I cannot discern your face, I may be doing</pp>
<pb n="74">
<pp>you an injustice. But there is something in
your voice that makes me distrust you. If you
attempt to play the traitor, you will do so at
the hazard of your life.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;I have already hazarded my life in this attempt
to save you,&rdquo; returned Jonathan boldly,
and with apparent frankness; &ldquo;this ought to
be sufficient answer to your doubts. Your
pursuers are below. What was to hinder me,
if I had been so inclined, from directing them
to your retreat?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Enough,&rdquo; replied Darrell. &ldquo;Lead on!&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>Followed by Darrell, Jonathan retraced his
dangerous path. As he approached the gable
of Mrs. Sheppard's house, loud yells and vociferations
reached his ears; and, looking downwards,
he perceived a great stir amid the mob.
The cause of this uproar was soon manifest.
Blueskin and the Minters were dragging Wood
to the pump. The unfortunate carpenter struggled
violently, but ineffectually. His hat was
placed upon one pole, his wig on another. His
shouts for help were answered by roars of
mockery and laughter. He continued alternately</pp>
<pb n="75">
<pp>to be tossed in the air, or rolled in the
kennel until he was borne out of sight. The
spectacle seemed to afford as much amusement
to Jonathan as to the actors engaged in it. He
could not contain his satisfaction, but chuckled,
and rubbed his hands with delight.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;By Heaven!&rdquo; cried Darrell, &ldquo;it is the poor
fellow whom I placed in such jeopardy a short
time ago. I am the cause of his ill&hyphen;usage.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;To be sure you are,&rdquo; replied Jonathan,
laughing. &ldquo;But, what of that? It'll be a
lesson to him in future, and will show him the
folly of doing a good&hyphen;natured action!&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>But perceiving that his companion did not
relish his pleasantry, and fearing that his sympathy
for the carpenter's situation might betray
him into some act of imprudence, Jonathan,
without further remark, and by way of putting
an end to the discussion, let himself drop
through the roof. His example was followed
by Darrell. But, though the latter was somewhat
embarrassed by his burthen, he peremptorily
declined Jonathan's offer of assistance.
Both, however, having safely landed, they</pp>
<pb n="76">
<pp>cautiously crossed the room, and passed down
the first flight of steps in silence. At this moment,
a door was opened below; lights gleamed
on the walls; and the figures of Rowland and
Sir Cecil were distinguished at the foot of the
stairs.</pp></p>
<p>Darrell stopped, and drew his sword.</p>
<p>&ldquo;You have betrayed me,&rdquo; said he, in a deep
whisper, to his companion; &ldquo;but you shall reap
the reward of your treachery.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Be still!&rdquo; returned Jonathan, in the same
under tone, and with great self&hyphen;possession: &ldquo;I
can yet save you. And see!&rdquo; he added, as the
figures drew back, and the lights disappeared; 
&ldquo;it's a false alarm. They have retired. However,
not a moment is to be lost. Give me your
hand.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>He then hurried Darrell down another short
flight of steps, and entered a small chamber at
the back of the house. Closing the door, Jonathan
next produced his lantern, and, hastening
towards the window, undrew a bolt by which it
was fastened. A stout wooden shutter, opening
inwardly, being removed, disclosed a grating of</pp>
<pb n="77">
<pp>iron bars. This obstacle, which appeared to
preclude the possibility of egress in that quarter,
was speedily got rid of. Withdrawing
another bolt, and unhooking a chain suspended
from the top of the casement, Jonathan pushed
the iron framework outwards. The bars dropped
noiselessly and slowly down, till the chain
tightened at the staple.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;You are free,&rdquo; said he, &ldquo;that grating
forms a ladder, by which you may descend in
safety. I learnt the trick of the place from one
Paul Groves, who used to live here, and who
contrived the machine. He used to call it his
fire&hyphen;escape&mdash;ha! ha! I've often used the ladder
for my own convenience, but I never expected
to turn it to such good account. And
now, sir, have I kept faith with you?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You have,&rdquo; replied Darrell. &ldquo;Here is my
purse; and I trust you will let me know to
whom I am indebted for this important service.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;It matters not who I am,&rdquo; replied Jonathan,
taking the money. &ldquo;As I said before, I
have little reliance upon <it>professions</it> of
gratitude.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;I know not how it is,&rdquo; sighed Darrell, &ldquo;but</pp>
<pb n="78">
<pp>I feel an unaccountable misgiving at quitting
this place. Something tells me I am rushing
on greater danger.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;You know best,&rdquo; replied Jonathan, sneeringly; 
&ldquo;but if I were in your place I would
take the chance of a future and uncertain risk
to avoid a present and certain peril.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You are right,&rdquo; replied Darrell; &ldquo;the
weakness is past. Which is the nearest way to
the river?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Why, it's an awkward road to direct you,&rdquo; 
returned Jonathan. &ldquo;But if you turn to the
right when you reach the ground, and keep
close to the Mint wall, you'll speedily arrive
at White Cross Street; White Cross Street, if
you turn again to the right, will bring you into
Queen Street; Queen Street, bearing to the
left, will conduct you to Deadman's Place; 
and Deadman's Place to the water&hyphen;side, not
fifty yards from Saint Saviour's stairs, where
you're sure to get a boat.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;The very point I aim at,&rdquo; said Darrell as
he passed through the outlet.</p>
<pb n="79">
<p>&ldquo;Stay!&rdquo; said Jonathan, aiding his descent; 
&ldquo;you had better take my lantern. It may be
useful to you. Perhaps you'll give me in return
some token, by which I may remind you
of this occurrence, in case we meet again. Your
glove will suffice.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;There it is,&rdquo; replied the other, tossing him
the glove. &ldquo;Are you sure these bars touch
the ground?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;They come within a yard of it,&rdquo; answered
Jonathan.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Safe!&rdquo; shouted Darrell, as he effected a
secure landing. &ldquo;Good night!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;So,&rdquo; muttered Jonathan, &ldquo;having started
the hare, I'll now unleash the hounds.&rdquo;</p>
<p>With this praiseworthy determination, he
was hastening down stairs, with the utmost rapidity,
when he encountered a female, whom he
took, in the darkness, to be Mrs. Sheppard.
The person caught hold of his arm, and, in
spite of his efforts to disengage himself, detained
him.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Where is he?&rdquo; asked she, in an agitated</pp>
<pb n="80">
<pp>whisper. &ldquo;I heard his voice; but I saw them
on the stairs, and durst not approach him, for
fear of giving the alarm.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;If you mean the fugitive, Darrell, he has
escaped through the back window,&rdquo; replied
Jonathan.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Thank Heaven!&rdquo; she gasped.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Well, you women are forgiving creatures,
I must say,&rdquo; observed Jonathan, sarcastically.
&ldquo;You thank Heaven for the escape of the
man who did his best to get your child's neck
twisted.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;What do you mean?&rdquo; asked the female, in
astonishment.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I mean what I say,&rdquo; replied Jonathan.
&ldquo;Perhaps you don't know that this Darrell so
contrived matters, that your child should be
mistaken for his own; by which means it had
a narrow escape from a tight cravat, I can assure
you. However, the scheme answered well
enough, for Darrell has got off with his own
brat.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Then this is not my child?&rdquo; exclaimed
she, with increased astonishment.</p>
<pb n="81">
<p>&ldquo;If you have a child there, it certainly is
not,&rdquo; answered Jonathan, a little surprised; 
&ldquo;for I left your brat in the charge of Blueskin,
who is still among the crowd in the street,
unless, as is not unlikely, he's gone to see your
other friend disciplined at the pump.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Merciful Providence!&rdquo; exclaimed the female.
&ldquo;Whose child can this be?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;How the devil should I know?&rdquo; replied
Jonathan gruffly. &ldquo;I suppose it didn't drop
through the ceiling, did it? Are you quite
sure it's flesh and blood?&rdquo; asked he, playfully
pinching its arm till it cried out with
pain.</p>
<p>&ldquo;My child! my child!&rdquo; exclaimed Mrs.
Sheppard, rushing from the adjoining room.
&ldquo;Where is it?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Are you the mother of this child?&rdquo; inquired
the person who had first spoken, addressing
Mrs. Sheppard.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I am&mdash;I am!&rdquo; cried the widow, snatching
the babe, and pressing it to her breast with
rapturous delight. &ldquo;God be thanked, I have
found it!&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="82">
<p>&ldquo;We have both good reason to be grateful,&rdquo; 
added the lady, with great emotion.</p>
<p>&ldquo;'Sblood!&rdquo; cried Jonathan, who had listened
to the foregoing conversation with angry wonder,
&ldquo;I've been nicely done here. Fool that
I was to part with my lantern! But I'll soon
set myself straight. What ho! lights! lights!&rdquo;</p>
<p>And, shouting as he went, he flung himself
down stairs.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Where shall I fly?&rdquo; exclaimed the lady,
bewildered with terror. &ldquo;They will kill me, if
they find me, as they would have killed my
husband and child. Oh God! my limbs fail
me.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Make an effort, madam,&rdquo; cried Mrs. Sheppard,
as a storm of furious voices resounded
from below, and torches were seen mounting
the stairs; &ldquo;they are coming!&mdash;they are coming!
&mdash;fly!&mdash;to the roof! to the roof!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;No,&rdquo; cried the lady, &ldquo;this room&mdash;I recollect
&mdash;it has a back window.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;It is shut,&rdquo; said Mrs. Sheppard.</p>
<p>&ldquo;It is open,&rdquo; replied the lady, rushing towards
it, and springing through the outlet.</p>
<pb n="83">
<p>&ldquo;Where is she?&rdquo; thundered Jonathan, who
at this moment reached Mrs. Sheppard.</p>
<p>&ldquo;She has flown up stairs,&rdquo; replied the widow.</p>
<p>&ldquo;You lie, hussy!&rdquo; replied Jonathan, rudely
pushing her aside, as she vainly endeavoured to
oppose his entrance into the room; &ldquo;she is
here. Hist!&rdquo; cried he, as a scream was heard
from without. &ldquo;By G&wblank;! she has missed her
footing.&rdquo;</p>
<p>There was a momentary and terrible silence,
broken only by a few feeble groans.</p>
<p>Sir Cecil, who with Rowland and some
others had entered the room rushed to the
window with a torch.</p>
<p>He held down the light, and a moment afterwards
beckoned, with a blanched cheek, to
Rowland.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Your sister is dead,&rdquo; said he, in a deep
whisper.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Her blood be upon her own head, then,&rdquo; 
replied Rowland, sternly. &ldquo;Why came she
here?&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;She could not resist the hand of fate</pp>
<pb n="84">
<pp>which drew her hither,&rdquo; replied Sir Cecil,
mournfully.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Descend and take charge of the body,&rdquo; said
Rowland, conquering his emotion by a great
effort. &ldquo;I will join you in a moment. This accident
rather confirms than checks my purpose.
The stain upon our family is only half effaced:
I have sworn the death of the villain and his
bastard, and I will keep my oath. Now,
sir,&rdquo; he added, turning to Jonathan, as Sir
Cecil and his followers obeyed his injunctions,
&ldquo;you say you know the road which
the person whom we seek has taken?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I do,&rdquo; replied Jonathan. &ldquo;But I give
no information gratis!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Speak, then,&rdquo; said Rowland, placing money
in his hand.</p>
<p>&ldquo;You'll find him at St. Saviour's stairs,&rdquo; 
answered Jonathan. &ldquo;He's about to cross
the river. You'd better lose no time. He
has got five minutes' start of you. But I
sent him the longest way about.&rdquo;</p>
<p>The words were scarcely pronounced, when
Rowland disappeared.</p>
<pb n="85">
<p>&ldquo;And now to see the end of it,&rdquo; said Jonathan,
shortly afterwards passing through the
window. &ldquo;Good night, Master.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Three persons only were left in the room.
These were the Master of the Mint, Van Galgebrok,
and Mrs. Sheppard.</p>
<p>&ldquo;A bad business this, Van,&rdquo; observed Baptist,
with a prolonged shake of the head.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ja, ja, Muntmeester,&rdquo; said the Hollander,
shaking his head in reply;&mdash;&ldquo;very bad&mdash; 
very.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;But then they're staunch supporters of
our friend over the water,&rdquo; continued Baptist,
winking significantly; &ldquo;so we must e'en hush
it up in the best way we can.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ja,&rdquo; answered Van Galgebrok. &ldquo;But&mdash; 
sapperment!&mdash;I wish they hadn't broken my
pipe.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;<smallcap>Jonathan Wild</smallcap> promises well,&rdquo; observed
the Master, after a pause: &ldquo;he'll become a
great man. Mind, I, Baptist Kettleby, say
so.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;He'll be haanged nevertheless,&rdquo; replied the
Hollander, giving his collar an ugly jerk.</pp>
<pb n="86">
<pp>Mind, I, Rykhart Van Galgebrok predict it.
And now let's go back to the Shovels, and
finish our brandewyn and bier, Muntmeester.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Alas!&rdquo; cried Mrs. Sheppard, relieved by
their departure, and giving way to a passionate
flood of tears; &ldquo;were it not for my child,
I should wish to be in the place of that unfortunate
lady.&rdquo;</p></div4>
