CHAPTER V.
<subhead>THE DENUNCIATION.</subhead> <attbytes>19Kb</attbytes><reflink>000027</reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z400030622</ID><A1>Ainsworth, William Harrison, 1805&ndash;1882</A1><T1>Jack Sheppard. A Romance.</T1><PBL>Richard Bentley</PBL><Y1>1839</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd4>
<p><pp><smallcap>For</smallcap> a short space, Mrs. Sheppard remained
dissolved in tears. She then dried her eyes, and
laying her child gently upon the floor, knelt
down beside him. &ldquo;Open my heart, Father
of Mercy!&rdquo; she murmured, in a humble tone,
and with downcast looks, &ldquo;and make me sensible
of the error of my ways. I have sinned
deeply; but I have been sorely tried. Spare
me yet a little while, Father! not for my own
sake, but for the sake of this poor babe.&rdquo; Her
utterance was here choked by sobs. &ldquo;But if
it is thy will to take me from him,&rdquo; she continued,
as soon as her emotion permitted her,
&mdash;&ldquo;if he must be left an orphan amid strangers,
implant, I beseech thee, a mother's feelings
in some other bosom, and raise up a</pp>
<pb n="88">
<pp>friend, who shall be to him what I would
have been. Let him not bear the weight of
my punishment. Spare him!&mdash;pity me!&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>With this she arose, and, taking up the
infant, was about to proceed down stairs,
when she was alarmed by hearing the street&hyphen;door
opened, and the sound of heavy foot&hyphen;steps
entering the house.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Halloa, widow!&rdquo; shouted a rough voice
from below, &ldquo;where the devil are you?&rdquo;</p>
<p>Mrs. Sheppard returned no answer.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I've got something to say to you,&rdquo; continued
the speaker, rather less harshly; &ldquo;something
to your advantage; so come out o' your
hiding&hyphen;place, and let's have some supper, for
I'm infernally hungry.&mdash;D'ye hear?&rdquo;</p>
<p>Still the widow remained silent.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Well, if you won't come, I shall help myself,
and that's unsociable,&rdquo; pursued the
speaker, evidently, from the noise he made,
suiting the action to the word. &ldquo;Devilish
nice ham you've got here!&mdash;capital pie!&mdash; 
and, as I live, a flask of excellent canary.
You're in luck to&hyphen;night, widow. Here's your</pp>
<pb n="89">
<pp>health in a bumper, and wishing you a better
husband than your first. It'll be your own
fault if you don't soon get another and a
proper young man into the bargain. Here's
his health likewise. What! mum still. You're
the first widow I ever heard of who could withstand
that lure. I'll try the effect of a jolly
stave.&rdquo; And he struck up the following ballad:&mdash;</pp></p>
<caption>SAINT GILES'S BOWL. <edit>[Footnote: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="FFN00001">At the hospital of Saint Giles for
Lazars, the prisoners
conveyed from the City of London towards Tyburn, there
to be executed for treasons, felonies, or other trespasses,
were presented with a Bowl of Ale, thereof to drink, as
their last refreshing in this life.&mdash;<it>Strype's Stow</it>. Book ix.
ch. iii.</note></caption>
<caption>I.</caption>
<edit>[Figure: <bytes>56Kb</bytes>]</edit><figure sys.id="N010104"><edit>[Figure: <bytes>188Kb</bytes>]</edit><figure sys.id="N010133"><edit>[Figure: <bytes>37Kb</bytes>]</edit><figure sys.id="N010134">
<pb n="90">
<pb n="91">
<caption>II.</caption>
<lg><l>By many a highwayman many a draught</l>
<l>Of nutty&mdash;brown ale at Saint Giles's was quaft,</l>
<l>Until the old lazar&mdash;house chanced to fall down,</l>
<l>And the broad&mdash;bottom'd bowl was removed to the Crown.</l>
<l align="r"><it>Where the robber may cheer</it></l>
<l align="r"><it>His spirit with beer,</it></l>
<l><it>And drown in a sea of good liquor all fear!</it></l>
<l><it>For nothing the transit to Tyburn beguiles</it></l>
<l><it>So well as a draught from the Bowl of Saint Giles</it>!</l></lg>
<caption>III.</caption>
<p>There <smallcap>Mulsack</smallcap> and <smallcap>Swiftneck</smallcap>, both prigs from their
birth,</p>
<p><smallcap>Old Mob</smallcap> and <smallcap>Tom Cox</smallcap> took their last draught on earth:
There <smallcap>Randal</smallcap>, and <smallcap>Shorter</smallcap>, and <smallcap>Whitney</smallcap> pulled up,
And jolly <smallcap>Jack Joyce</smallcap> drank his finishing cup!</p>
<lb><lg><l align="r"><it>For a can of ale calms,</it></l>
<l align="r"><it>A highwayman's qualms,</it></l>
<l><it>And makes him sing blithely his dolorous psalms!</it></l>
<l><it>And nothing the transit to Tyburn beguiles</it></l>
<l><it>So well as a draught from the Bowl of Saint Giles</it>!</l></lg>
<lb><p><pp>&ldquo;Singing's dry work,&rdquo; observed the stranger,
pausing to take a pull at the bottle.</pp>
<pb n="92">
<pp>&ldquo;And now, widow,&rdquo; he continued, &ldquo;attend
to the next verse, for it consarns a friend o'
your's.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<caption>IV.</caption>
<lb><lg><l>When gallant <smallcap>Tom Sheppard</smallcap> to Tyburn was led,&mdash;</l>
<l>&ldquo;Stop the cart at the Crown&mdash;stop a moment,&rdquo; he said.</l>
<l>He was offered the Bowl, but he left it and smiled,</l>
<l>Crying, &ldquo;Keep it till call'd for by <smallcap>Jonathan Wild</smallcap>!</l>
<l align="r"><it>&ldquo;The rascal one day,</it></l>
<l align="r"><it>Will pass by this way,</it></l>
<l><it>And drink a full measure to moisten his clay!</it></l>
<l><it>And never will Bowl of Saint Giles have beguiled</it></l>
<l><it>Such a thorough&hyphen;paced scoundrel as</it> <smallcap>Jonathan Wild</smallcap>!&rdquo;</l></lg>
<lb><caption>V.</caption>
<lb><lg><l>Should it e'er be <it>my</it> lot to ride backwards that
way,</l>
<l>At the door of the Crown I will certainly stay;</l>
<l>I'll summon the landlord&mdash;I'll call for the Bowl,</l>
<l>And drink a deep draught to the health of my soul!</l>
<l align="r"><it>Whatever may hap,</it></l>
<l align="r"><it>I'll taste of the tap,</it></l>
<l><it>To keep up my spirits when brought to the crap!</it></l>
<l><it>For nothing the transit to Tyburn beguiles</it></l>
<l><it>So well as a draught from the Bowl of St. Giles</it>!</l></lg>
<lb><p><pp>&ldquo;Devil seize the woman!&rdquo; growled the
singer, as he brought his ditty to a close; 
&ldquo;will nothing tempt her out? Widow Sheppard,
I say,&rdquo; he added, rising, &ldquo;don't be</pp>
<pb n="93">
<pp>afraid. It's only a gentleman come to offer
you his hand. &lsquo;He that woos a maid,&rsquo;&mdash;folde&hyphen;rol
&mdash;(hiccupping.)&mdash;I'll soon find you
out.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>Mrs. Sheppard, whose distress at the consumption
of the provisions had been somewhat
allayed by the anticipation of the intruder's
departure after he had satisfied his
appetite, was now terrified in the extreme by
seeing a light approach, and hearing footsteps
on the stairs. Her first impulse was
to fly to the window; and she was about
to pass through it, at the risk of sharing
the fate of the unfortunate lady, when her
arm was grasped by some one in the act of
ascending the ladder from without. Uttering
a faint scream, she sank backwards, and would
have fallen, if it had not been for the interposition
of Blueskin, who, at that moment,
staggered into the room with a candle in one
hand, and the bottle in the other.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Oh, you're here, are you?&rdquo; said the
ruffian, with an exulting laugh: &ldquo;I've been
looking for you everywhere.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="94">
<p>&ldquo;Let me go,&rdquo; implored Mrs. Sheppard,&mdash; 
&ldquo;pray let me go. You hurt the child. Don't
you hear how you've made it cry?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Throttle the kid!&rdquo; rejoined Blueskin,
fiercely. &ldquo;If you don't stop its squalling,
I will. I hate children. And, if I'd my
own way, I'd drown 'em all like a litter o'
puppies.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Well knowing the savage temper of the
person she had to deal with, and how likely
he was to put his threat into execution, Mrs.
Sheppard did not dare to return any answer; 
but, disengaging herself from his embrace,
endeavoured meekly to comply with his request.</p>
<p>&ldquo;And now, widow,&rdquo; continued the ruffian,
setting down the candle, and applying his
lips to the bottle neck as he flung his heavy
frame upon a bench, &ldquo;I've a piece o' good
news for you.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Good news will be news to me. What
is it?&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Guess,&rdquo; rejoined Blueskin, attempting to</pp>
<pb n="95">
<pp>throw a gallant expression into his forbidding
countenance.</pp></p>
<p>Mrs. Sheppard trembled violently; and
though she understood his meaning too well,
she answered,&mdash;&ldquo;I can't guess.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Well, then,&rdquo; returned the ruffian, &ldquo;to
put you out o' suspense, as the topsman remarked
to poor Tom Sheppard, afore he
turned him off, I'm come to make you an
honourable proposal o' marriage. You won't
refuse me, I'm sure; so no more need be
said about the matter. To&hyphen;morrow, we'll go
to the Fleet and get spliced. Don't shake
so. What I said about your brat was all
stuff. I didn't mean it. It's my way when
I'm ruffled. I shall take to him as nat'ral
as if he were my own flesh and blood afore
long.&mdash;I'll give him the edication of a prig,&mdash; 
teach him the use of his forks betimes,&mdash;and
make him, in the end, as clever a cracksman
as his father.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Never!&rdquo; shrieked Mrs. Sheppard; &ldquo;never!
never!&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="96">
<p>&ldquo;Halloa! what's this?&rdquo; demanded Blueskin,
springing to his feet. &ldquo;Do you mean
to say that if I support your kid, I shan't
bring him up how I please&mdash;eh?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Don't question me, but leave me,&rdquo; replied
the widow wildly; &ldquo;you had better.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Leave you!&rdquo; echoed the ruffian, with a
contemptuous laugh; &ldquo;&mdash;not just yet.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I am not unprotected,&rdquo; rejoined the poor
woman; &ldquo;there's some one at the window.
Help! help!&rdquo;</p>
<p>But her cries were unheeded. And Blueskin,
who, for a moment, had looked round
distrustfully, concluding it was a feint, now
laughed louder than ever.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;It won't do, widow,&rdquo; said he, drawing
near her, while she shrank from his approach,
&ldquo;so you may spare your breath. Come, come,
be reasonable, and listen to me. Your kid
has already brought me good luck, and may
bring me still more if his edication's attended
to. This purse,&rdquo; he added, chinking it in
the air, &ldquo;and this ring, were given me for
him just now by the lady, who made a false</pp>
<pb n="97">
<pp>step on leaving your house. If I'd been in
the way, instead of Jonathan Wild, that accident
wouldn't have happened.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>As he said this, a slight noise was heard
without.</p>
<p>&ldquo;What's that?&rdquo; ejaculated the ruffian,
glancing uneasily towards the window. &ldquo;Who's
there?&mdash;Pshaw! it's only the wind.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;It's Jonathan Wild,&rdquo; returned the widow,
endeavouring to alarm him. &ldquo;I told you I
was not unprotected.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;<it>He</it> protect <it>you</it>,&rdquo; retorted Blueskin,
maliciously; 
<lb>&ldquo;you haven't a worse enemy on
the face of the earth than Jonathan Wild.
If you'd read your husband's dying speech,
you'd know that he laid his death at Jonathan's
door,&mdash;and with reason too, as I can
testify.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Man!&rdquo; screamed Mrs. Sheppard, with a
vehemence that shook even the hardened wretch
beside her, &ldquo;begone, and tempt me not.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;What should I tempt you to?&rdquo; asked
Blueskin, in surprise.</pp>
<pb n="98">
<pp>&ldquo;To&mdash;to&mdash;no matter what,&rdquo; returned the
widow distractedly. &ldquo;Go&mdash;go!&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;I see what you mean,&rdquo; rejoined Blueskin,
tossing a large case&hyphen;knife, which he took from
his pocket, in the air, and catching it dexterously
by the haft as it fell; &ldquo;you owe Jonathan
a grudge;&mdash;so do I. He hanged your
first husband. Just speak the word,&rdquo; he
added, drawing the knife significantly across
his throat, &ldquo;and I'll put it out of his power
to do the same by your second. But d&mdash;n
him! let's talk o' something more agreeable.
Look at this ring;&mdash;it's a diamond, and worth
a mint o' money. It shall be your wedding
ring. Look at it, I say. The lady's name's
engraved inside, but so small I can scarcely
read it. <smallcap>A&hyphen;l&hyphen;i&hyphen;v&hyphen;a</smallcap>&mdash;Aliva&mdash;<smallcap>T&hyphen;r&hyphen;e&hyphen;n</smallcap>&mdash;Trencher
&mdash;that's it. Aliva Trencher.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Aliva Trenchard!&rdquo; exclaimed Mrs. Sheppard,
hastily; &ldquo;is that the name?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ay, ay, now I look again it <it>is</it> Trenchard.
How came you to know it? Have you heard
the name before?&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;I think I have&mdash;long, long ago, when I</pp>
<pb n="99">
<pp>was a child,&rdquo; replied Mrs. Sheppard, passing
her hand across her brow; &ldquo;but my memory is
gone&mdash;quite gone. Where <it>can</it> I have heard
it!&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Devil knows,&rdquo; rejoined Blueskin. &ldquo;Let
it pass. The ring's yours, and you're mine.
Here, put it on your finger.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Mrs. Sheppard snatched back her hand from
his grasp, and exerted all her force to repel his
advances.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Set down the kid,&rdquo; roared Blueskin, savagely.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Mercy!&rdquo; screamed Mrs. Sheppard, struggling
to escape, and holding the infant at arm's
length; &ldquo;have mercy on this helpless innocent!&rdquo;</p>
<p>And the child, alarmed by the strife, added
its feeble cries to its mother's shrieks.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Set it down, I tell you,&rdquo; thundered Blueskin,
&ldquo;or I shall do it a mischief.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Never!&rdquo; cried Mrs. Sheppard.</p>
<p>Uttering a terrible imprecation, Blueskin
placed the knife between his teeth, and endeavoured
to seize the poor woman by the throat.</p>
<pb n="100">
<p>In the struggle her cap fell off. The ruffian
caught hold of her hair, and held her fast.
The chamber rang with her shrieks. But her
cries, instead of moving her assailant's compassion,
only added to his fury. Planting his
knee against her side, he pulled her towards
him with one hand, while with the other he
sought his knife. The child was now within
reach; and, in another moment, he would have
executed his deadly purpose, if an arm from
behind had not felled him to the ground.</p>
<p>When Mrs. Sheppard, who had been stricken
down by the blow that prostrated her assailant,
looked up, she perceived Jonathan
Wild kneeling beside the body of Blueskin.
He was holding the ring to the light, and
narrowly examining the inscription.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Trenchard,&rdquo; he muttered; &ldquo;Aliva Trenchard
&mdash;they were right, then, as to the name.
Well, if she survives the accident&mdash;as the
blood, who styles himself Sir Cecil, fancies she
may do&mdash;this ring will make my fortune by
leading to the discovery of the chief parties
concerned in this strange affair.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="101">
<p>&ldquo;Is the poor lady alive?&rdquo; asked Mrs. Sheppard,
eagerly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;'Sblood!&rdquo; exclaimed Jonathan, hastily
thrusting the ring into his vest, and taking
up a heavy horseman's pistol with which he
had felled Blueskin,&mdash;&ldquo;I thought you'd been
senseless.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Is she alive?&rdquo; repeated the widow.</p>
<p>&ldquo;What's that to you?&rdquo; demanded Jonathan,
gruffly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Oh, nothing&mdash;nothing,&rdquo; returned Mrs.
Sheppard. &ldquo;But pray tell me if her husband
has escaped?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Her husband!&rdquo; echoed Jonathan scornfully.
&ldquo;A <it>husband</it> has little to fear from his
wife's kinsfolk. Her <it>lover</it>, Darrell, has embarked
upon the Thames, where, if he's not
capsized by the squall, (for it's blowing like
the devil,) he stands a good chance of getting
his throat cut by his pursuers&mdash;ha! ha! I
tracked 'em to the banks of the river, and
should have followed to see it out, if the watermen
hadn't refused to take me. However, as
things have turned up, it's fortunate that I
came back.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="102">
<p>&ldquo;It is, indeed,&rdquo; replied Mrs. Sheppard; 
&ldquo;most fortunate for me.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;For <it>you</it>!&rdquo; exclaimed Jonathan &ldquo;don't
flatter yourself that I'm thinking of you.
Blueskin might have butchered you and your
brat before I'd have lifted a finger to prevent
him, if it hadn't suited my purposes to do so,
and <it>he</it> hadn't incurred my displeasure. I
never forgive an injury. Your husband could
have told you that.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;How had he offended you?&rdquo; inquired the
widow.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I'll tell you,&rdquo; answered Jonathan, sternly.
&ldquo;He thwarted my schemes twice. The first
time, I overlooked the offence; but the second
time, when I had planned to break open the
house of his master, the fellow who visited
you to&hyphen;night,&mdash;Wood, the carpenter of Wych
Street,&mdash;he betrayed me. I told him I would
bring him to the gallows, and I was as good
as my word.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You were so,&rdquo; replied Mrs. Sheppard; 
&ldquo;and for that wicked deed you will one day
be brought to the gallows yourself.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="103">
<p>&ldquo;Not before I have conducted your child
thither,&rdquo; retorted Jonathan, with a withering
look.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ah!&rdquo; ejaculated Mrs. Sheppard, paralysed
by the threat.</p>
<p>&ldquo;If that sickly brat lives to be a man,&rdquo; 
continued Jonathan, rising, &ldquo;I'll hang him
upon the same tree as his father.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Pity!&rdquo; shrieked the widow.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I'll be his evil genius!&rdquo; vociferated Jonathan,
who seemed to enjoy her torture.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Begone, wretch!&rdquo; cried the mother, stung
beyond endurance by his taunts; &ldquo;or I will
drive you hence with my curses.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Curse on, and welcome,&rdquo; jeered Wild.</p>
<p>Mrs. Sheppard raised her hand, and the malediction
trembled upon her tongue. But ere
the words could find utterance, her maternal
tenderness overcame her indignation; and,
sinking upon her knees, she extended her
arms over her child.</p>
<p>&ldquo;A mother's prayers&mdash;a mother's blessings,&rdquo; 
she cried, with the fervour almost of inspiration,
&ldquo;will avail against a fiend's malice.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="104">
<p>&ldquo;We shall see,&rdquo; rejoined Jonathan, turning
carelessly upon his heel.</p>
<p>And, as he quitted the room, the poor widow
fell with her face upon the floor.</p></div4>
<pb n="105">
<div4>
