CHAPTER I.
<subhead>THE IDLE APPRENTICE.</subhead> <attbytes>29Kb</attbytes><reflink>000027</reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z400030626</ID><A1>Ainsworth, William Harrison, 1805&ndash;1882</A1><T1>Jack Sheppard. A Romance.</T1><PBL>Richard Bentley</PBL><Y1>1839</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd4>
<p><smallcap>Twelve years</smallcap>! How many events have
occurred during that long interval! how many
changes have taken place! The whole aspect
of things is altered. The child has sprung
into a youth; the youth has become a man; 
the man has already begun to feel the advances
of age. Beauty has bloomed and
faded. Fresh flowers of loveliness have budded,
expanded, died. The fashions of the
day have become antiquated. New customs
have prevailed over the old. Parties, politics,
and popular opinions have changed. The
crown has passed from the brow of one monarch
to that of another. Habits and tastes
are no longer the same. We, ourselves, are
scarcely the same we were twelve years ago.</p>
<pb n="148">
<p>Twelve years ago! It is an awful retrospect.
Dare we look back upon the darkened
vista, and, in imagination, retrace the path
we have trod? With how many vain hopes
is it shaded! with how many good resolutions,
never fulfilled, is it paved! Where are the
dreams of ambition in which, twelve years
ago, we indulged? Where are the aspirations
that fired us&mdash;the passions that consumed
us then? Has our success in life been
commensurate with our own desires&mdash;with the
anticipations formed of us by others? Or,
are we not blighted in heart, as in ambition?
Has not the loved one been estranged by
doubt, or snatched from us by the cold hand
of death? Is not the goal, towards which
we pressed, further off than ever&mdash;the prospect
before us cheerless as the blank behind?
&mdash;Enough of this. Let us proceed with our
tale.</p>
<p><pp>Twelve years, then, have elapsed since the
date of occurrences detailed in the preceding
division of this history. At that time,
we were beneath the sway of Anne: we are</pp>
<pb n="149">
<pp>now at the commencement of the reign of
George the First. Passing at a glance over
the whole of the intervening period; leaving,
in the words of the poet,
<lb><lg><l align="r">&mdash;The growth untried</l>
<l>Of that wide gap&mdash;</l></lg>
<lb>we shall resume our narrative at the beginning
of June, 1715.</pp></p>
<p>One Friday afternoon, in this pleasant month,
it chanced that Mr. Wood, who had been absent
on business during the greater part of the
day, returned (perhaps not altogether undesignedly)
at an earlier hour than was expected.
to his dwelling in Wych Street, Drury Lane; 
and was about to enter his workshop, when, not
hearing any sound of labour issue from within,
he began to suspect that an apprentice, of whose
habits of industry he entertained some doubt,
was neglecting his employment. Impressed
with this idea, he paused for a moment to
listen. But finding all continue silent, he
cautiously lifted the latch, and crept into the
room, resolved to punish the offender in case
his suspicions should prove correct.</p>
<pb n="150">
<p><pp>The chamber, into which he stole, like all
carpenters' workshops, was crowded with the
implements and materials of that ancient and
honourable art. Saws, hammers, planes, axes,
augers, adzes, chisels, gimblets, and an endless
variety of tools were ranged, like a stand of
martial weapons at an armoury, in racks against
the walls. Over these hung levels, bevels,
squares, and other instruments of measurement.
Amid a litter of nails without heads,
screws without worms, and locks without wards,
lay a glue&hyphen;pot and an oilstone, two articles
which their owner was wont to term &ldquo;his
right hand and his left.&rdquo; On a shelf was
placed a row of paint&hyphen;jars; the contents of
which had been daubed in rainbow streaks
upon the adjacent closet and window sill.
Divers plans and figures were chalked upon
the walls; and the spaces between them were
filled up with an almanack for the year; a
godly ballad, adorned with a rude wood&hyphen;cut,
purporting to be &ldquo;<it>The History of Chaste
Susannah</it>;&rdquo; an old print of the Seven Golden
Candlesticks; an abstract of the various Acts</pp>
<pb n="151">
<pp>of Parliament against drinking, swearing, and
all manner of profaneness; and a view of the
interior of Doctor Daniel Burgess's Presbyterian
meeting&hyphen;house in Russell Court, with
portraits of the reverend gentleman and the
principal members of his flock. The floor
was thickly strewn with sawdust and shavings; 
and across the room ran a long and wide bench,
furnished at one end with a powerful vice; 
next to which three nails driven into the
boards served, it would appear from the lump
of unconsumed tallow left in their custody,
as a substitute for a candlestick. On the
bench was set a quartern measure of gin, a
crust of bread, and a slice of cheese. Attracted
by the odour of the latter dainty, a
hungry cat had contrived to scratch open the
paper in which it was wrapped, displaying
the following words in large characters:&mdash; 
&ldquo;<smallcap>The History of the Four Kings, or Child's
best Guide to the Gallows.</smallcap>&rdquo; And, as if to
make the moral more obvious, a dirty pack
of cards was scattered, underneath, upon the
sawdust. Near the door stood a pile of deal</pp>
<pb n="152">
<pp>planks, behind which the carpenter ensconced
himself, in order to reconnoitre, unobserved,
the proceedings of his idle apprentice.</pp></p>
<p>Standing on tiptoe, on a joint&hyphen;stool, placed
upon the bench, with his back to the door,
and a clasp&hyphen;knife in his hand, this youngster,
instead of executing his appointed task, was
occupied in carving his name upon a beam,
overhead. Boys, at the time of which we write,
were attired like men of their own day, or certain
charity&hyphen;children of ours; and the stripling
in question was dressed in black plush breeches,
and a grey drugget waistcoat, with immoderately
long pockets, both of which were evidently
the cast&hyphen;off clothes of some one considerably
his senior. Coat, on the present occasion,
he had none, it being more convenient, as well
as agreeable to him, to pursue his avocations in
his shirt&hyphen;sleeves; but, when fully equipped, he
wore a large cuffed, long&hyphen;skirted garment, which
had once been the property of his master.</p>
<p><pp>In concealing himself behind the timber, Mr.
Wood could not avoid making a slight shuffling
sound. The noise startled the apprentice, who</pp>
<pb>
<edit>[Figure: <bytes>345Kb</bytes>]</edit><figure sys.id="N010107">
<pb n="153">
<pp>instantly suspended his labour, and gazed
anxiously in the direction whence he supposed
it proceeded. His face was that of a quick, intelligent&hyphen; 
looking boy, with fine hazel eyes, and
a clear olive complexion. His figure was uncommonly
slim even for his age, which could
not be more than thirteen; and the looseness of
his garb made him appear thinner than he was
in reality. But if his frame was immature, his
looks were not so. He seemed to possess a
penetration and cunning beyond his years&mdash;to
hide a man's judgment under a boy's mask.
The glance, which he threw at the door, was
singularly expressive of his character: it was
a mixture of alarm, effrontery, and resolution.
In the end, resolution triumphed, as it was sure
to do, over the weaker emotions, and he laughed
at his fears. The only part of his otherwise&hyphen;interesting
countenance, to which one could decidedly
object, was the mouth; a feature that,
more than any other, is conceived to betray the
animal propensities of the possessor. If this is
true, it must be owned that the boy's mouth
showed a strong tendency on his part to coarse</pp>
<pb n="154">
<pp>indulgence. The eyes, too, though large and
bright, and shaded by long lashes, seemed to
betoken, as hazel eyes generally do in men, a
faithless and uncertain disposition. The cheekbone
were prominent: the nose slightly depressed,
with rather wide nostrils; the chin
narrow, but well&hyphen;formed; the forehead broad
and lofty; and he possessed such an extraordinary
flexibility of muscle in this region, that he
could elevate his eye&hyphen;brows at pleasure up to
the very verge of his sleek and shining black
hair, which, being closely cropped, to admit of
his occasionally wearing a wig, gave a singular
bullet&hyphen;shape to his head. Taken altogether, his
physiognomy resembled one of those vagabond
heads which Murillo delighted to paint, and for
which Guzman d'Alfarache, Lazarillo de Tormes,
or Estevanillo Gonzalez might have sat:&mdash; 
faces that almost make one in love with roguery,
they seem so full of vivacity and enjoyment.
There was all the knavery, and more than all
the drollery of a Spanish picaroon in the laughing
eyes of the English apprentice; and, with a
little more warmth and sunniness of skin on the</pp>
<pb n="155">
<pp>side of the latter, the resemblance between them
would have been complete.</pp></p>
<p>Satisfied, as he thought, that he had nothing
to apprehend, the boy resumed his task, chanting,
as he plied his knife with redoubled assiduity,
the following&mdash;not inappropriate
strains:&mdash; 
<lb><caption>THE NEWGATE STONE.</caption>
<lg><l><smallcap>When Claude du Val</smallcap> was in Newgate thrown,</l>
<l>He carved his name on the dungeon stone;</l>
<l>Quoth a dubsman, who gazed on the shattered wall,</l>
<l>&ldquo;You have carved your epitaph, <smallcap>Claude du Val</smallcap>,</l>
<l align="r"><it>With your chisel so fine, tra la</it>!&rdquo;</l></lg></p>
<lb><p>&ldquo;This S wants a little deepening,&rdquo; mused
the apprentice, retouching the letter in question; 
&ldquo;ay, that's better.&rdquo; 
<lb><lg><l><smallcap>Du Val</smallcap> was hang'd, and the next who came</l>
<l>On the selfsame stone inscribed his name:</l>
<l>&ldquo;Aha!&rdquo; quoth the dubsman, with devilish glee,</l>
<l>&ldquo;<smallcap>Tom Waters</smallcap>, <it>your</it> doom is the triple tree!</l>
<l align="r"><it>With your chisel so fine, tra la</it>!&rdquo;</l></lg></p>
<lb><p><pp>&ldquo;Tut, tut, tut,&rdquo; he cried, &ldquo;what a fool I
am to be sure! I ought to have cut John, not
Jack. However, it don't signify. Nobody ever
called me John, that I recollect. So I dare say</pp>
<pb n="156">
<pp>I was christened Jack. Deuce take it! I was
very near spelling my name with one P.
<lb><lg><l>Within that dungeon lay <smallcap>Captain Bew</smallcap>,</l>
<l><smallcap>Rumbold</smallcap> and <smallcap>Whitney</smallcap>&mdash;a jolly crew!</l>
<l>All carved their names on the stone, and all</l>
<l>Share the fate of the brave <smallcap>Du Val</smallcap>!</l>
<l align="r"><it>With their chisels so fine, tra la</it>!</l></lg></pp></p>
<lb><p>&ldquo;Save us!&rdquo; continued the apprentice, &ldquo;I
hope this beam doesn't resemble the Newgate
stone; or I may chance, like the great men the
song speaks of, to swing on the Tyburn tree for
my pains. No fear o' that.&mdash;Though if my
name should become as famous as theirs, it
wouldn't much matter. The prospect of the
gallows would never deter me from taking to
the road, if I were so inclined.</p>
<lb><lg><l>Full twenty highwaymen blithe and bold,</l>
<l>Rattled their chains in that dungeon old;</l>
<l>Of all that number there 'scaped not one</l>
<l>Who carved his name on the Newgate Stone,</l>
<l align="r"><it>With his chisel so fine, tra la</it>!</l></lg>
<lb><p>&ldquo;There!&rdquo; cried the boy, leaping from the
stool, and drawing back a few paces on the
bench to examine his performance,&mdash;&ldquo;that'll
do. Claude du Val, himself, couldn't have
carved it better&mdash;ha! ha!&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="157">
<p>The name inscribed upon the beam (of
which, as it has been carefully preserved by
the subsequent owners of Mr. Wood's habitation
in Wych Street, we are luckily enabled
to furnish a fac&hyphen;simile) was</p>
<edit>[Figure: <bytes>28Kb</bytes>]</edit><figure sys.id="N010108">
<p>&ldquo;I've half a mind to give old Wood the
slip, and turn highwayman,&rdquo; cried Jack, as he
closed the knife, and put it in his pocket.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The devil you have!&rdquo; thundered a voice
from behind, that filled the apprentice with
dismay. &ldquo;Come down, sirrah, and I'll teach
you how to deface my walls in future. Come
down, I say, instantly, or I'll make you.&rdquo; 
Upon which, Mr. Wood caught hold of Jack's
leg, and dragged him off the bench.</p>
<p>&ldquo;And so you'll turn highwayman, will
you, you young dog?&rdquo; continued the carpenter,
cuffing him soundly,&mdash;&ldquo;rob the mails,
like Jack Hall, I suppose.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="158">
<p>&ldquo;Yes, I will,&rdquo; replied Jack sullenly, &ldquo;if
you beat me in that way.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Amazed at the boy's assurance, Wood left
off boxing his ears for a moment, and, looking
at him steadfastly, said in a grave tone, &ldquo;Jack,
Jack, you'll come to be hanged!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Better be hanged than henpecked,&rdquo; retorted
the lad with a malicious grin.</p>
<p>&ldquo;What do you mean by that, sirrah?&rdquo; 
cried Wood, reddening with anger. &ldquo;Do you
dare to insinuate that Mrs. Wood governs
me?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;It's plain you can't govern yourself, at
all events,&rdquo; replied Jack coolly; &ldquo;but, be that
as it may, I won't be struck for nothing.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Nothing,&rdquo; echoed Wood furiously. &ldquo;Do
you call neglecting your work, and singing
flash songs nothing? Is your recent idle discourse,
and your present unblushing insolence
nothing? Zounds! you incorrigible rascal,
many a master would have taken you before
a magistrate, and prayed for your solitary
confinement in Bridewell for the least of these
offences. But I'll be more lenient, and content</pp>
<pb n="159">
<pp>myself with merely chastising you, on
condition&mdash;&rdquo; 
<lb>&ldquo;You may do as you please, master,&rdquo; interrupted
Jack, thrusting his hand into his
pocket, as if in search of the knife; &ldquo;but I
wouldn't advise you to lay hands on me again.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>Mr. Wood glanced at the hardy offender,
and not liking the expression of his countenance,
thought it advisable to post one the
execution of his threats to a more favourable
opportunity. So, by way of gaining time, he
resolved to question him further.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Where did you learn the song I heard just
now?&rdquo; he demanded, in an authoritative tone.</p>
<p>&ldquo;At the Black Lion in our street,&rdquo; replied
Jack, without hesitation.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The worst house in the neighbourhood&mdash; 
the constant haunt of reprobates and thieves,&rdquo; 
groaned Wood. &ldquo;And who taught it you&mdash; 
the landlord, Joe Hind?&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;No; one Blueskin, a fellow who frequents
the Lion,&rdquo; answered Jack, with a degree of
candour that astonished his master nearly as
much as his confidence. &ldquo;It was that song</pp>
<pb n="160">
<pp>that put it into my head to cut my name on
the beam.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;A white wall is a fool's paper, Jack,&mdash; 
remember that,&rdquo; rejoined Wood. &ldquo;Pretty
company for an apprentice to keep!&mdash;pretty
houses for an apprentice to frequent! Why,
the rascal you mention is a notorious housebreaker.
He was tried at the last Old Bailey
sessions; and only escaped the gallows by impeaching
his accomplices. Jonathan Wild
brought him off.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Do you happen to know Jonathan Wild,
master?&rdquo; inquired Jack, altering his tone, and
assuming a more respectful demeanour.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I've seen him some years ago, I believe,&rdquo; 
answered Wood; &ldquo;and, though he must be
much changed by this time, I dare say I
should know him again.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;A short man, isn't he, about your height,
sir,&mdash;with a yellow beard, and a face as sly as
a fox's?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Hem!&rdquo; replied Wood, coughing slightly
to conceal a smile; &ldquo;the description's not
amiss. But why do you ask?&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="161">
<p>&ldquo;Because&mdash;&rdquo; stammered the boy.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Speak out&mdash;don't be alarmed,&rdquo; said Wood,
in a kind and encouraging tone. &ldquo;If you've
done wrong, confess it, and I'll forgive you!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I don't deserve to be forgiven!&rdquo; returned
Jack, bursting into tears; &ldquo;for I'm afraid
I've done very wrong. Do you know this,
sir?&rdquo; he added, taking a key from his pocket.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Where did you find it!&rdquo; asked Wood.</p>
<p>&ldquo;It was given me by a man who was drinking
t'other night with Blueskin at the Lion!
and who, though he slouched his hat over his
eyes, and muffled his chin in a handkerchief,
must have been Jonathan Wild.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Where did <it>he</it> get it?&rdquo; inquired Wood, in
surprise.</p>
<p>&ldquo;That I can't say. But he promised to
give me a couple of guineas if I'd ascertain
whether it fitted your locks.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Zounds!&rdquo; exclaimed Wood; &ldquo;it's my
old master&hyphen;key. This key,&rdquo; he added, taking
it from the boy, &ldquo;was purloined from me
by your father, Jack. What he intended to
do with it is of little consequence now. But</pp>
<pb n="162">
<pp>before he suffered at Tyburn, he charged your
mother to restore it. She lost it in the Mint.
Jonathan Wild must have stolen it from her.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;He must,&rdquo; exclaimed Jack, hastily; &ldquo;but
only let me have it till to&hyphen;morrow, and if I
don't entrap him in a snare from which, with
all his cunning, he shall find it difficult to
escape, my name's not Jack Sheppard.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;I see through your design, Jack,&rdquo; returned
the carpenter, gravely; &ldquo;But I don't like under&hyphen;hand
work. Even when you've a knave
to deal with, let your actions be plain, and
above&hyphen;board. That's my maxim; and it's the
maxim of every honest man. It would be a
great matter, I must own, to bring Jonathan
Wild to justice. But I can't consent to the
course you would pursue&mdash;at least, not till
I've given it due consideration. In regard to
yourself, you've had a very narrow escape.
Wild's intention, doubtless, was to use you
as far as he found necessary, and then to sell
you. Let this be a caution to you in future&mdash; 
with whom, and about what you deal. We're
told, that &lsquo;Whoso is partner with a thief</pp>
<pb n="163">
<pp>hateth his own soul.&rsquo; Avoid taverns and bad
company, and you may yet do well. You
promise to become a first&hyphen;rate workman. But
you want one quality, without which all others
are valueless. You want industry&mdash;you want
steadiness. Idleness is the key of beggary,
Jack. If you don't conquer this disgraceful
propensity in time, you'll soon come to want; 
and then nothing can save you. Be warned by
your father's fate. As you brew so must you
drink. I've engaged to watch over you as
a son, and I <it>will</it> do so as far as I'm able; 
but if you neglect my advice, what chance
have I of benefitting you? On one point
I've made up my mind&mdash;you shall either obey
me, or leave me. Please yourself. Here are
your indentures, if you choose to seek another
master.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;I <it>will</it> obey you, master,&mdash;indeed I will!&rdquo; 
implored Jack, seriously alarmed at the carpenter's
calm displeasure.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;We shall see. Good words, without deeds,
are rushes and reeds. And now take away
those cards, and never let me see them again.</pp>
<pb n="164">
<pp>Drive away the cat; throw that measure of gin
through the window; and tell me why you've
not so much as touched the packing&hyphen;case for
Lady Trafford, which I particularly desired
you to complete against my return. It must
be sent home this evening. She leaves town
to&hyphen;morrow.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;It shall be ready in two hours,&rdquo; answered
Jack, seizing a piece of wood and a plane; &ldquo;it
isn't more than four o'clock. I'll engage to
get the job done by six. I didn't expect
you home before that hour, sir.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ah, Jack,&rdquo; said Wood, shaking his head,
&ldquo;where there's a will there's a way. You
can do anything you please. I wish I could
get you to imitate Thames Darrell.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I'm sure I understand the business of a
carpenter much better than he does,&rdquo; replied
Jack, adroitly adjusting the board, and using
the plane with the greatest rapidity.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Perhaps,&rdquo; replied Wood, doubtfully.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Thames was always your favourite,&rdquo; observed
Jack, as he fastened another piece of
wood on the teeth of the iron stopper.</p>
<pb n="165">
<p>&ldquo;I've made no distinction between you,
hitherto,&rdquo; answered Wood; &ldquo;nor shall I do
so, unless I'm compelled.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I've had the hard work to do, at all
events,&rdquo; rejoined Jack. &ldquo;But I won't complain.
I'd do anything for Thames Darrell.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;And Thames Darrell would do anything
for you, Jack,&rdquo; replied a blithe voice. &ldquo;What's
the matter, father?&rdquo; continued the new&hyphen;comer,
addressing Wood. &ldquo;Has Jack displeased you?
If so, overlook his fault this once. I'm sure he'll
do his best to content you. Won't you, Jack?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;That I will,&rdquo; answered Sheppard, eagerly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;When it thunders, the thief becomes
honest,&rdquo; muttered Wood.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Can I help you, Jack?&rdquo; asked Thames,
taking up a plane.</p>
<p>&ldquo;No, no, let him alone,&rdquo; interposed Wood.
&ldquo;He has undertaken to finish this job by six
o'clock, and I wish to see whether he'll be
as good as his word.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;He'll have hard work to do it by that
time, father,&rdquo; remonstrated Thames; &ldquo;you'd
better let me help him.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="166">
<p>&ldquo;On no account,&rdquo; rejoined Wood peremptorily.
&ldquo;A little extra exertion will teach him
the advantage of diligence at the proper season.
Lost ground must be regained. I need scarcely
ask whether you've executed your appointed
task, my dear? You're never behindhand.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Thames turned away at the question, which
he felt might be construed into a reproach.
But Sheppard answered for him.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Darrell's job was done early this morning,&rdquo; 
he said; &ldquo;and if I'd attended to his advice,
the packing&hyphen;case would have been finished at
the same time.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You trusted too much to your own skill,
Jack,&rdquo; rejoined Thames. &ldquo;If I could work
as fast as you, I might afford to be as idle.
See how he gets on, father,&rdquo; he added, appealing
to Wood: &ldquo;the box seems to grow under
his hands.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You're a noble&hyphen;hearted little fellow,
Thames,&rdquo; rejoined Wood, casting a look of
pride and affection at his adopted son, whose
head he gently patted; &ldquo;and give promise of
a glorious manhood.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="167">
<p><pp>Thames Darrell was, indeed, a youth of
whom a person of far greater wordly consequence
than the worthy carpenter might have
been justly proud. Though a few&hyphen;months
younger than his companion Jack Sheppard,
he was half a head taller, and much more
robustly formed. The two friends contrasted
strikingly with each other. In Darrell's open
features, frankness and honour were written
in legible characters; while, in Jack's physiognomy,
cunning and knavery were as
strongly imprinted. In all other respects
they differed as materially. Jack could hardly
be accounted good&hyphen;looking: Thames, on
the contrary, was one of the handsomest boys
possible. Jack's complexion was that of a
gipsy; Darrell's as fresh and bright as a rose.
Jack's mouth was coarse and large; Darrell's
small and exquisitely carved, with the short,
proud upper lip, which belongs to the highest
order of beauty. Jack's nose was broad and
flat; Darrell's straight and fine as that of
Antinous. The expression pervading the
countenance of the one was vulgarity; of the</pp>
<pb n="168">
<pp>other, that which is rarely found, except in
persons of high birth. Darrell's eyes were
of that clear grey which it is difficult to distinguish
from blue by day and black at night; 
and his rich brown hair, which he could not
consent to part with, even on the promise of
a new and modish peruke from his adoptive
father, fell in thick glossy ringlets upon his
shoulders; whereas Jack's close black crop
imparted the peculiar bullet&hyphen;shape we have
noticed, to his head.</pp></p>
<p>While Thames modestly expressed a hope
that he might not belie the carpenter's favourable
prediction, Jack Sheppard thought fit to
mount a small ladder placed against the wall,
and, springing with the agility of an ape upon
a sort of frame, contrived to sustain short spars
and blocks of timber, began to search about for
a piece of wood required in the work on which
he was engaged. Being in a great hurry, he
took little heed where he set his feet; and a
board giving way, he must have fallen, if he
had not grasped a large plank laid upon the
transverse beam immediately over his head.</p>
<pb n="169">
<p>&ldquo;Take care, Jack,&rdquo; shouted Thames, who
witnessed the occurrence; &ldquo;that plank isn't
properly balanced. You'll have it down.&rdquo;</p>
<p>But the caution came too late. Sheppard's
weight had destroyed the equilibrium of the
plank: it swerved, and slowly descended.
Losing his presence of mind, Jack quitted
his hold, and dropped upon the frame. The
plank hung over his head. A moment more
and he would have been crushed beneath the
ponderous board, when a slight but strong arm
arrested its descent.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Get from under it, Jack!&rdquo; vociferated
Thames. &ldquo;I can't hold it much longer&mdash;it'll
break my wrist. Down we come!&rdquo; he exclaimed,
letting go the plank, which fell with a
crash, and leaping after Sheppard, who had
rolled off the frame.</p>
<p>All this was the work of a minute.</p>
<p>&ldquo;No bones broken, I hope,&rdquo; said Thames,
laughing at Jack, who limped towards the
bench, rubbing his shins as he went.</p>
<p>&ldquo;All right,&rdquo; replied Sheppard, with affected
indifference.</p>
<pb n="170">
<p>&ldquo;It's a mercy you both escaped!&rdquo; ejaculated
Wood, only just finding his tongue. &ldquo;I declare
I'm all in a cold sweat. How came you,
sir,&rdquo; he continued, addressing Sheppard, &ldquo;to
venture upon that frame. I always told you
some accident would happen.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Don't scold him, father,&rdquo; interposed
Thames; &ldquo;he's been frightened enough already.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Well, well, since you desire it, I'll say no
more,&rdquo; returned Wood. &ldquo;You hav'n't hurt
your arm, I trust, my dear?&rdquo; he added, anxiously.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Only sprained it a little, that's all,&rdquo; answered
Thames; &ldquo;the pain will go off presently.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Then you <it>are</it> hurt,&rdquo; cried the carpenter in
alarm. &ldquo;Come down stairs directly, and let
your mother look at your wrist. She has an
excellent remedy for a sprain. And do you,
Jack, attend to your work, and mind you don't
get into further mischief.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Hadn't Jack better go with us?&rdquo; said
Thames. &ldquo;His shin may need rubbing.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;By no means,&rdquo; rejoined Wood, hastily.</pp>
<pb n="171">
<pp>&ldquo;A little suffering will do him good. I meant
to give him a drubbing. That bruise will answer
the same purpose.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Thames,&rdquo; said Sheppard in a low voice, as
he threw a vindictive glance at the carpenter,
&ldquo;I shan't forget this. You've saved my life.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Pshaw! you'd do as much for me any
day, and think no more about it. It'll be your
turn to save mine next.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;True, and I shan't be easy till my turn arrives.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I tell you what, Jack,&rdquo; whispered Thames,
who had noticed Sheppard's menacing glance,
and dreaded some further indiscretion on his
part, &ldquo;if you really wish to oblige me, you'll
get that packing&hyphen;case finished by six o'clock.
You <it>can</it> do it, if you will.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;And I <it>will</it>, if I can, depend upon it,&rdquo; answered
Sheppard, with a laugh.</p>
<p>So saying, he manfully resumed his work; 
while Wood and Thames quitted the room, and
went down stairs.</p></div4>
<pb n="172">
<div4>
<comhd4><idref>Z400030627</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
CHAPTER II.
<subhead>THAMES DARRELL.</subhead> <attbytes>18Kb</attbytes><reflink>000027</reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z400030627</ID><A1>Ainsworth, William Harrison, 1805&ndash;1882</A1><T1>Jack Sheppard. A Romance.</T1><PBL>Richard Bentley</PBL><Y1>1839</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd4>
<p><smallcap>Thames Darrell's</smallcap> arm having been submitted
to the scrutiny of Mrs. Wood, was pronounced
by that lady to be very much sprained; 
and she, forthwith, proceeded to bathe it
with a reddish&hyphen;coloured lotion. During this
operation, the carpenter underwent a severe
catechism as to the cause of the accident; and,
on learning that the mischance originated with
Jack Sheppard, the indignation of his helpmate
knew no bounds; and she was with difficulty
prevented from flying to the workshop to inflict
summary punishment on the offender.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;I knew how it would be,&rdquo; she cried, in the
shrill voice peculiar to a shrew, &ldquo;when you
brought that worthless hussy's worthless brat
into the house. I told you no good would</pp>
<pb n="173">
<pp>come of it. And every day's experience proves
that I was right. But, like all your overbearing
sex, you must have your own way.
You'll never be guided by me&mdash;never!&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Indeed, my love, you're entirely mistaken,&rdquo; 
returned the carpenter, endeavouring to deprecate
his wife's rising resentment by the softest
looks, and the meekest deportment.</p>
<p>So far, however, was this submission from
producing the desired effect, that it seemed
only to lend additional fuel to her displeasure.
Forgetting her occupation in her anger, she
left off bathing Darrell's wrist; and, squeezing
his arm so tightly that the boy winced with
pain, she clapped her right hand upon her hip,
and turned, with flashing eyes and an inflamed
countenance, towards her crest&hyphen;fallen spouse.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;What!&rdquo; she exclaimed, almost choked
with passion,&mdash;&ldquo;<it>I</it> advised you to burthen yourself
with that idle and good&hyphen;for&hyphen;nothing pauper,
whom you ought rather to send to the workhouse
than maintain at your own expense, did
I? <it>I</it> advised you to take him as an apprentice; 
and, so far from getting the regular fee</pp>
<pb n="174">
<pp>with him, to give him a salary? <it>I</it> advised
you to feed him, and clothe him, and treat him
like his betters; to put up with his insolence,
and wink at his faults? <it>I</it> counselled all this,
I suppose. You'll tell me next, I dare say,
that I recommended you to go and visit his
mother so frequently under the plea of charity; 
to give her wine, and provisions, and money; 
to remove her from the only fit quarters for
such people&mdash;the Mint; and to place her in a
cottage at Willesden, of which you must needs
pay the rent? Marry, come up! charity should
begin at home. A discreet husband would
leave the dispensation of his bounty, where
women are concerned, to his wife. And for my
part, if I were inclined to exercise my benevolence
at all, it should be in favour of some
more deserving object than that whining, hypocritical
Magdalene.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;It was the knowledge of this feeling on
your part, my love, that made me act without
your express sanction. I did all for the best,
I'm sure. Mrs. Sheppard is&mdash;&rdquo; 
<lb>&ldquo;I know what Mrs. Sheppard is, without</pp>
<pb n="175">
<pp>your information, sir. I haven't forgotten her
previous history. You've your own reasons,
no doubt, for bringing up her son&mdash;perhaps, I
ought rather to say <it>your</it> son, Mr. Wood.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Really, my love, these accusations are
most groundless&mdash;this violence is most unnecessary.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I can't endure the odious baggage. I
hope I may never come near her.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I hope you never may, my love,&rdquo; humbly
acquiesced the carpenter.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Is my house to be made a receptacle for all
your natural children, sir? Answer me that.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Winny,&rdquo; said Thames, whose glowing
cheek attested the effect produced upon him by
the insinuation; &ldquo;Winny,&rdquo; said he, addressing
a pretty little damsel of some twelve years of
age, who stood by his side holding the bottle
of embrocation, &ldquo;help me on with my coat,
please. This is no place for me.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Sit down, my dear, sit down,&rdquo; interposed
Mrs. Wood, softening her asperity. &ldquo;What
I said about natural children doesn't apply to
<it>you</it>. Don't suppose,&rdquo; she added, with a scornful</pp>
<pb n="176">
<pp>glance at her helpmate, &ldquo;that I would pay
him the compliment of thinking he could possibly
be the father of such a boy as you.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>Mr. Wood lifted up his hands in mute despair.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Owen, Owen,&rdquo; pursued Mrs. Wood, sinking
into a chair, and fanning herself violently,
&mdash;&ldquo;what a fluster you have put me into with
your violence, to be sure! And at the very
time, too, when you know I'm expecting a
visit from Mr. Kneebone, on his return from
Manchester. I wouldn't have him see me in
this state for the world. He'd never forgive you.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Poh, poh, my dear! Mr. Kneebone invariably
takes part with me, when any trifling
misunderstanding arises between us. I only
wish he was not a Papist and a Jacobite.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Jacobite!&rdquo; echoed Mrs. Wood. &ldquo;Marry,
come up! Mightn't he just as reasonably
complain of your being a Hanoverian and a
Presbyterian? It's all matter of opinion. And
now, my love,&rdquo; she added, with a relenting
look, &ldquo;I'm content to make up our quarrel.</pp>
<pb n="177">
<pp>But you must promise me not to go near that
abandoned hussy at Willesden. One can't
help being jealous, you know, even of an unworthy
object.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>Glad to make peace on any terms, Mr. Wood
gave the required promise, though he could
not help thinking that if either of them had
cause to be jealous he was the party.</p>
<p><pp>And here, we may be permitted to offer an
observation upon the peculiar and unaccountable
influence which ladies of a shrewish turn
so frequently exercise over&mdash;we can scarcely,
in this case, say&mdash;their lords and masters; an
influence which seems not merely to extend to
the will of the husband, but even to his inclinations.
We do not remember to have met
with a single individual, reported to be under
petticoat government, who was not content with
his lot,&mdash;nay, who so far from repining, did
not exult in his servitude; and we see no way
of accounting for this apparently inexplicable
conduct&mdash;for which, among other phenomena
of married life, various reasons have been
assigned, though none entirely satisfactory to</pp>
<pb n="178">
<pp>us&mdash;except upon the ground that these domineering
dames possess some charm sufficiently
strong to counteract the irritating effect of
their tempers; some secret and attractive quality
of which the world at large is in ignorance,
and with which their husbands alone can be
supposed to be acquainted. An influence of
this description appeared to be exerted on the
present occasion. The worthy carpenter was
restored to instant good humour by a glance
from his helpmate; and, notwithstanding the
infliction he had just endured, he would have
quarrelled with any one who had endeavoured
to persuade him that he was not the happiest
of men, and Mrs. Wood the best of wives.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Women must have their wills while they
live, since they can make none when they die,&rdquo; 
observed Wood, as he imprinted a kiss of
reconciliation on the plump hand of his consort; 
&mdash;a sentiment to the correctness of which
the party chiefly interested graciously vouchsafed
her assent.</p>
<p><pp>Lest the carpenter should be taxed with too
much uxoriousness, it behoves us to ascertain</pp>
<pb n="179">
<pp>whether the personal attractions of his helpmate
would, in any degree, justify the devotion
he displayed. In the first place, Mrs.
Wood had the advantage of her husband in
point of years, being on the sunny side of
forty,&mdash;a period pronounced by competent
judges to be the most fascinating, and, at the
same time, most critical epoch of woman's
existence,&mdash;whereas, he was on the shady side
of fifty,&mdash;a term of life not generally conceived
to have any special recommendation in
female eyes. In the next place, she really
had some pretensions to beauty. Accounted
extremely pretty in her youth, her features
and person expanded as she grew older, without
much detriment to their original comeliness.
Hers was beauty on a large scale no
doubt; but it was beauty, nevertheless: and
the carpenter thought her eyes as bright, her
complexion as blooming, and her figure (if a
little more buxom) quite as captivating as
when he led her to the altar some twenty
years ago.</pp></p>
<p><pp>On the present occasion, in anticipation of</pp>
<pb n="180">
<pp>Mr. Kneebone's visit, Mrs. Wood was dressed
with more than ordinary care, and in more
than ordinary finery. A dove&hyphen;coloured kincob
gown, embroidered with large trees, and made
very low in front, displayed to the greatest
possible advantage, the rounded proportions
of her figure; while a high&hyphen;heeled, red&hyphen;leather
shoe did not detract from the symmetry
of a very neat ankle, and a very small foot.
A stomacher, fastened by imitation&hyphen;diamond
buckles, girded that part of her person, which
should have been a waist; a coral necklace
encircled her throat, and a few black patches,
or mouches, as they were termed, served as
a foil to the bloom of her cheek and chin.
Upon a table, where they had been hastily
deposited, on the intelligence of Darrell's accident,
lay a pair of pink kid gloves, bordered
with lace, and an enormous fan; the latter,
when opened, represented the metamorphosis
and death of Act&aelig;on. From her stomacher,
to which it was attached by a multitude of
glittering steel chains, depended an immense
turnip&hyphen;shaped watch, in a pinchbeck case.</pp>
<pb n="181">
<pp>Her hair was gathered up behind, in a sort
of pad, according to the then&hyphen;prevailing mode; 
and she wore a muslin cap, and pinners, with
crow&hyphen;foot edging. A black silk furbelowed
scarf covered her shoulders; and over the
kincob gown hung a yellow satin apron, trimmed
with white Persian.</pp></p>
<p>But, in spite of her attractions, we shall
address ourselves to the younger, and more
interesting couple.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I could almost find in my heart to quarrel
with Jack Sheppard for occasioning you so
much pain,&rdquo; observed little Winifred Wood,
as, having completed her ministration to the
best of her ability, she helped Thames on
with his coat.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I don't think you could find in your heart
to quarrel with any one, Winny; much less
with a person whom I like so much as Jack
Sheppard. My arm's nearly well again. And
I've already told you the accident was not
Jack's fault. So, let's think no more about
it.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;It's strange you should like Jack so much</pp>
<pb n="182">
<pp>dear Thames. He doesn't resemble you at
all.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;The very reason why I like him, Winny.
If he <it>did</it> resemble me, I shouldn't care about
him. And, whatever you may think, I assure
you, Jack's a downright good&hyphen;natured
fellow.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Goodnatured fellows are always especial favourites
with boys. And, in applying the
term to his friend, Thames meant to pay him
a high compliment. And so Winifred understood
him.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Well,&rdquo; she said, in reply, &ldquo;I may have
done Jack an injustice. I'll try to think better
of him in future.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;And, if you want an additional inducement
to do so, I can tell you there's no one&mdash; 
not even his mother&mdash;whom he loves so well
as you.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Loves!&rdquo; echoed Winifred, slightly colouring.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Yes, loves, Winny. Poor fellow! he sometimes
indulges the hope of marrying you, when
he grows old enough.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="183">
<p>&ldquo;Thames!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Have I said anything to offend you?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Oh! no. But if you wouldn't have me
positively dislike Jack Sheppard, you'll never
mention such a subject again. Besides,&rdquo; she
added, blushing yet more deeply, &ldquo;it isn't a
proper one to talk upon.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Well then, to change it,&rdquo; replied Thames,
gravely, &ldquo;suppose I should be obliged to leave
you.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Winifred looked as if she could not indulge
such a supposition for a single moment.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Surely,&rdquo; she said, after a pause, &ldquo;you
don't attach any importance to what my mother
has just said. <it>She</it> has already forgotten it.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;But <it>I</it> never can forget it, Winny. I will
no longer be a burthen to those upon whom I
have no claim, but compassion.&rdquo;</p>
<p>As he said this, in a low and mournful, but
firm voice, the tears gathered thickly in Winifred's
dark eyelashes.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;If you are in earnest, Thames,&rdquo; she replied,
with a look of gentle reproach, &ldquo;you are very
foolish; and, if in jest, very cruel. My mother,</pp>
<pb n="184">
<pp>I'm sure, didn't intend to hurt your feelings.
She loves you too well for that. And I'll answer
for it, she'll never say a syllable to annoy
you again.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>Thames tried to answer her, but his voice
failed him.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Come! I see the storm has blown over,&rdquo; 
cried Winifred, brightening up.</p>
<p>&ldquo;You're mistaken, Winny. Nothing can
alter my determination. I shall quit this roof
to&hyphen;morrow.&rdquo;</p>
<p>The little girl's countenance fell.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Do nothing without consulting my father&mdash; 
<it>your</it> father, Thames,&rdquo; she implored. &ldquo;Promise
me that.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Willingly. And what's more, I promise
to abide by his decision.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Then, I'm quite easy,&rdquo; cried Winifred,
joyfully.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I'm sure he won't attempt to prevent me,&rdquo; 
rejoined Thames.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The slight smile that played upon Winifred's
lips seemed to say that <it>she</it> was not quite
so sure. But she made no answer.</p>
<pb n="185">
<p>&ldquo;In case he should consent&mdash;&rdquo; 
<lb>&ldquo;He never will,&rdquo; interrupted Winifred.</p>
<p>&ldquo;In case he <it>should</it>, I say,&rdquo; continued
Thames, &ldquo;will <it>you</it> promise to let Jack Sheppard
take my place in your affections, Winny?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Never!&rdquo; replied the little damsel. &ldquo;I can
never love any one so much as you.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Excepting your father.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Winifred was going to say &ldquo;No,&rdquo; but she
checked herself; and, with cheeks mantling
with blushes, murmured, &ldquo;I wish you wouldn't
teaze me about Jack Sheppard.&rdquo;</p>
<p>The foregoing conversation, having been conducted
throughout in a low tone, and apart,
had not reached the ears of Mr. and Mrs.
Wood, who were, furthermore, engaged in a
little conjugal <it>t&ecirc;te&hyphen;&agrave;&hyphen;t&ecirc;te</it> of their own. The last
observation, however, caught the attention of
the carpenter's wife.</p>
<p>&ldquo;What's that you're saying about Jack
Sheppard?&rdquo; she cried.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Thames was just observing&mdash;&rdquo; 
<lb>&ldquo;Thames!&rdquo; echoed Mrs. Wood, glancing
angrily at her husband. &ldquo;There's another instance</pp>
<pb n="186">
<pp>of your wilfulness and want of taste.
Who but <it>you</it> would have dreamed of giving
the boy such a name? Why, it's the name of
a river, not a Christian. No gentleman was
ever called Thames, and Darrell <it>is</it> a gentleman,
unless the whole story of his being found in the
river is a fabrication!&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;My dear, you forget&mdash;&rdquo; 
<lb>&ldquo;No, Mr. Wood, I forget nothing. I've an
excellent memory, thank God! And I perfectly
remember that everybody was drowned
upon that occasion&mdash;except yourself and the
child!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;My love, you're beside yourself&mdash;&rdquo; 
<lb>&ldquo;I <it>was</it> beside myself to take charge of
your&mdash;&rdquo; 
<lb>&ldquo;Mother!&rdquo; interposed Winifred.</p>
<p>&ldquo;It's of no use,&rdquo; observed Thames quietly,
but with a look that chilled the little damsel's
heart;&mdash;&ldquo;my resolution is taken.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You at least appear to forget that Mr.
Kneebone is coming, my dear,&rdquo; ventured Mr.
Wood.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Good gracious! so I do,&rdquo; exclaimed his</pp>
<pb n="187">
<pp>amiable consort. &ldquo;But you <it>do</it> agitate me so
much. Come into the parlour, Winifred, and
dry your eyes directly, or I'll send you to bed.
Mr. Wood, I desire you'll put on your best
things, and join us as soon as possible. Thames,
you needn't tidy yourself, as you've hurt your
arm. Mr. Kneebone will excuse you. Dear
me! if there isn't his knock. Oh! I'm in such
a fluster!&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>Upon which, she snatched up her fan, cast a
look into the glass, smoothed down her scarf,
threw a soft expression into her features, and
led the way into the next room, whither she
was followed by her daughter and Thames
Darrell.</p></div4>
<pb n="188">
<div4>
<comhd4><idref>Z400030628</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
CHAPTER III.
<subhead>THE JACOBITE.</subhead> <attbytes>8Kb</attbytes><reflink>000027</reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z400030628</ID><A1>Ainsworth, William Harrison, 1805&ndash;1882</A1><T1>Jack Sheppard. A Romance.</T1><PBL>Richard Bentley</PBL><Y1>1839</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd4>
<p><smallcap>Mr. William Kneebone</smallcap> was a woollen&hyphen;draper
of &ldquo;credit and renown,&rdquo; whose place of
business was held at the sign of the Angel (for,
in those days, every shop had its sign), opposite
Saint Clement's church in the Strand. A
native of Manchester, he was the son of Kenelm
Kneebone, a staunch catholic, and a sergeant
of dragoons, who lost his legs and his life while
fighting for James the Second at the battle of
the Boyne, and who had little to bequeath his
son except his laurels and his loyalty to the
house of Stuart.</p>
<p><pp>The gallant woolen&hyphen;draper was now in his
thirty&hyphen;sixth year. He had a handsome, jolly&hyphen;looking
face; stood six feet two in his stockings; 
and measured more than a cloth&hyphen;yard</pp>
<pb n="189">
<pp>shaft across the shoulders&mdash;athletic proportions
derived from his father the dragoon. And, if
it had not been for a taste for plotting, which
was continually getting him into scrapes, he
might have been accounted a respectable member
of society.</pp></p>
<p><pp>Of late, however, his plotting had assumed a
more dark and dangerous complexion. The
times were such that, with the opinions he entertained,
he could not remain idle. The spirit
of disaffection was busy throughout the kingdom.
It was on the eve of that memorable rebellion
which broke forth, two months later, in
Scotland. Since the accession of George the
First to the throne in the preceding year, every
effort had been made by the partisans of the
Stuarts to shake the credit of the existing government,
and to gain supporters to their cause.
Disappointed in their hopes of the restoration
of the fallen dynasty after the death of Anne,
the adherents of the Chevalier de Saint George
endeavoured, by sowing the seeds of dissension
far and wide, to produce a general insurrection
in his favour. No means were neglected to accomplish</pp>
<pb n="190">
<pp>this end. Agents were dispersed in all
directions&mdash;offers the most tempting held out
to induce the wavering to join the Chevalier's
standard. Plots were hatched in the provinces,
where many of the old and wealthy Catholic
families resided, whose zeal for the martyr of
their religion (as the Chevalier was esteemed),
sharpened by the persecutions they themselves
endured, rendered them hearty and efficient allies.
Arms, horses, and accoutrements were
secretly purchased and distributed; and it is
not improbable that, if the unfortunate prince,
in whose behalf these exertions were made, and
who was not deficient in courage, as he proved
at the battle of Malplaquet, had boldly placed
himself at the head of his party at an earlier
period, he might have regained the crown of his
ancestors. But the indecision, which had been
fatal to his race, was fatal to him. He delayed
the blow till the fortunate conjuncture was past.
And when, at length, it <it>was</it> struck, he wanted
energy to pursue his advantages.</pp></p>
<p><pp>But we must not anticipate the course of
events. At the precise period of this history,</pp>
<pb n="191">
<pp>the Jacobite party was full of hope and confidence.
Louis the Fourteenth yet lived, and
expectations were, therefore, indulged of assistance
from France. The disgrace of the
leaders of the late Tory administration had
strengthened, rather than injured, their cause.
Mobs were gathered together on the slightest
possible pretext; and these tumultuous assemblages,
while committing the most outrageous
excesses, loudly proclaimed their hatred to the
house of Hanover, and their determination to
cut off the Protestant succession. The proceedings
of this faction were narrowly watched
by a vigilant and sagacious administration.
The government was not deceived (indeed,
every opportunity was sought by the Jacobites
of parading their numbers,) as to the force of
its enemies; and precautionary measures were
taken to defeat their designs. On the very
day of which we write, namely, the 10th of
June 1715, Bolingbroke and Oxford were impeached
of high treason. The Committee of
Secrecy&mdash;that English Council of Ten&mdash;were
sitting, with Walpole at their head; and the</pp>
<pb n="192">
<pp>most extraordinary discoveries were reported
to be made. On the same day, moreover,
which, by a curious coincidence, was the birthday
of the Chevalier de Saint George, mobs
were collected together in the streets, and the
health of that prince was publicly drunk under
the title of James the Third; while, in many
country towns, the bells were rung, and rejoicings
held, as if for a reigning monarch:&mdash; 
the cry of the populace almost universally
being, &ldquo;No King George, but a Stuart!&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p><pp>The adherents of the Chevalier de Saint
George, we have said, were lavish in promises
to their proselytes. Posts were offered to all
who chose to accept them. Blank commissions,
signed by the prince, to be filled up by
the name of the person, who could raise a
troop for his service, were liberally bestowed.
Amongst others, Mr. Kneebone, whose interest
was not inconsiderable with the leaders of his
faction, obtained an appointment as captain in
a regiment of infantry, on the conditions above
specified. With a view to raise recruits for
his corps, the warlike woollen&hyphen;draper started</pp>
<pb n="193">
<pp>for Lancashire, under the colour of a journey
on business. He was pretty successful in
Manchester,&mdash;a town which may be said to
have been the head&hyphen;quarters of the disaffected.
On his return to London, he found that applications
had been made from a somewhat doubtful
quarter by two individuals, for the posts of
subordinate officers in his troop. Mr. Kneebone,
or, as he would have preferred being
styled, Captain Kneebone, was not perfectly
satisfied with the recommendations forwarded
by the applicants. But this was not a season
in which to be needlessly scrupulous. He resolved
to judge for himself. Accordingly, he
was introduced to the two military aspirants at
the Cross Shovels in the Mint, by our old acquaintance,
Baptist Kettleby. The Master of
the Mint, with whom the Jacobite captain had
often had transactions before, vouched for their
being men of honour and loyalty; and Kneebone
was so well satisfied with his representations,
that he at once closed the matter by
administering to the applicants the oath of
allegiance and fidelity to King James the</pp>
<pb n="194">
<pp>Third, and several other oaths besides, all of
which those gentlemen took with as little hesitation
as the sum of money, afterwards tendered,
to make the compact binding. The
party, then, sat down to a bowl of punch; 
and, at its conclusion, Captain Kneebone regretted
that an engagement to spend the evening
with Mrs. Wood, would preclude the possibility
of his remaining with his new friends
as long as his inclinations prompted. At this
piece of information, the two subordinate officers
were observed to exchange glances; and,
after a little agreeable raillery on their captain's
gallantry, they begged permission to
accompany him in his visit. Kneebone, who
had drained his glass to the restoration of the
house of Stuart, and the downfall of the house
of Hanover, more frequently than was consistent
with prudence, consented; and the trio
set out for Wych Street, where they arrived in
the jolliest humour possible.</pp></p></div4>
<pb n="195">
<div4>
<comhd4><idref>Z400030629</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
CHAPTER IV.
<subhead>MR. KNEEBONE AND HIS FRIENDS.</subhead> <attbytes>9Kb</attbytes><reflink>000027</reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z400030629</ID><A1>Ainsworth, William Harrison, 1805&ndash;1882</A1><T1>Jack Sheppard. A Romance.</T1><PBL>Richard Bentley</PBL><Y1>1839</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd4>
<p><pp><smallcap>Mrs. Wood</smallcap> was scarcely seated before Mr.
Kneebone made his appearance. To her great
surprise and mortification he was not alone; 
but brought with him a couple of friends,
whom he begged to introduce as Mr. Jeremiah
Jackson, and Mr. Solomon Smith, chapmen,
(or what in modern vulgar parlance would be
termed bagmen) travelling to procure orders
for the house of an eminent cloth manufacturer
in Manchester. Neither the manners,
the looks, nor the attire of these gentlemen
prepossessed Mrs. Wood in their favour.
Accordingly, on their presentation, Mr. Jeremiah
Jackson and Mr. Solomon Smith received
something very like a rebuff. Luckily, they</pp>
<pb n="196">
<pp>were not easily discomposed. Two persons
possessing a more comfortable stock of assurance
could not be readily found. Imitating
the example of Mr. Kneebone, who did not
appear in the slightest degree disconcerted by
his cool reception, each sank carelessly into
a chair, and made himself at home in a moment.
Both had very singular faces; very
odd wigs, very much pulled over their brows; 
and very large cravats, very much raised above
their chins. Besides this, each had a large
black patch over his right eye, and a very
queer twist at the left side of his mouth, so
that if their object had been disguise, they
could not have adopted better precautions.
Mrs. Wood thought them both remarkably
plain, but Mr. Smith decidedly the plainest of
the two. His complexion was as blue as a
sailor's jacket, and though Mr. Jackson had
one of the ugliest countenances imaginable, he
had a very fine set of teeth. That was something
in his favour. One peculiarity she did
not fail to notice. They were both dressed in
every respect alike. In fact, Mr. Solomon</pp>
<pb n="197">
<pp>Smith seemed to be Mr. Jeremiah Jackson's
double. He talked in the same style, and
pretty nearly in the same language; laughed
in the same manner, and coughed, or sneezed
at the same time. If Mr. Jackson took an
accurate survey of the room with his one eye,
Mr. Smith's solitary orb followed in the same
direction. When Jeremiah admired the Compasses
in the arms of the Carpenter's Company
over the chimney&hyphen;piece, or the portraits of the
two eminent masters of the rule and plane,
William Portington, and John Scott, Esquires,
on either side of it, Solomon was lost in wonder.
When Mr. Jackson noticed a fine service
of old blue china in an open japan closet, Mr.
Smith had never seen anything like it. And
finally, when Jeremiah, having bestowed upon
Mrs. Wood a very free&hyphen;and&hyphen;easy sort of stare,
winked at Mr. Kneebone, his impertinence was
copied to the letter by Solomon. All three,
then, burst into an immoderate fit of laughter.
Mrs. Wood's astonishment and displeasure
momentarily increased. Such freedoms from
such people were not to be endured. Her</pp>
<pb n="198">
<pp>patience was waning fast. Still, in spite of
her glances and gestures, Mr. Kneebone made
no effort to check the unreasonable merriment
of his companions, but rather seemed to encourage
it. So Mrs. Wood went on fuming,
and the trio went on laughing for some minutes,
nobody knew why or wherefore, until
the party was increased by Mr. Wood, in his
Sunday habiliments and Sunday buckle. Without
stopping to inquire into the cause of their
mirth, or even to ask the names of his guests,
the worthy carpenter shook hands with the
one&hyphen;eyed chapmen, slapped Mr. Kneebone
cordially on the shoulder, and began to laugh
as heartily as any of them.</pp></p>
<p>Mrs. Wood could stand it no longer.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I think you're all bewitched,&rdquo; she cried.</p>
<p>&ldquo;So we are, ma'am, by your charms,&rdquo; returned
Mr. Jackson, gallantly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Quite captivated, ma'am,&rdquo; added Mr.
Smith, placing his hand on his breast.</p>
<p>Mr. Kneebone and Mr. Wood laughed
louder than ever.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Mr. Wood,&rdquo; said the lady, bridling up,</pp>
<pb n="199">
<pp>&ldquo;my request may, perhaps, have some weight
with <it>you</it>. I desire, sir, you'll recollect yourself.
Mr. Kneebone,&rdquo; she added, with a glance
at that gentleman, which was meant to speak
daggers, &ldquo;will do as he pleases.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>Here the chapmen set up another boisterous
peal.</p>
<p>&ldquo;No offence, I hope, my dear Mrs. W.&rdquo; 
said Mr. Kneebone in a conciliatory tone.</p>
<p>&ldquo;My friends, Mr. Jackson and Mr. Smith,
may have rather odd ways with them; but&mdash;&rdquo; 
<lb>&ldquo;They <it>have</it> very odd ways,&rdquo; interrupted
Mrs. Wood, disdainfully.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Our worthy friend was going to observe,
ma'am, that we never fail in our devotion to
the fair sex,&rdquo; said Mr. Jackson.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Never, ma'am!&rdquo; echoed Mr. Smith, &ldquo;upon
my conscience.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;My dear,&rdquo;said the hospitable carpenter,</p>
<p>&ldquo;I dare say Mr. Kneebone and his friends
would be glad of a little refreshment.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;They shall have it, then,&rdquo; replied his better
half, rising. &ldquo;You base ingrate,&rdquo; she
added, in a whisper, as she flounced past Mr.</pp>
<pb n="200">
<pp>Kneebone on her way to the door, &ldquo;how could
you bring such creatures with you, especially
on an occasion like this, when we haven't
met for a fortnight!&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Couldn't help it, my life,&rdquo; returned the
gentleman addressed, in the same tone; &ldquo;but
you little know who those individuals are.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Lord bless us! you alarm me. Who are
they.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Mr. Kneebone assumed a mysterious air; 
and bringing his lips close to Mrs. Wood's ear,
whispered, &ldquo;Secret agents from France&mdash;you
understand&mdash;friends to the good cause&mdash; 
hem!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I see,&mdash;persons of rank?&rdquo;</p>
<p>Mr. Kneebone nodded.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Noblemen.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Mr. Kneebone smiled assent.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Mercy on us! Well, I thought their
manners quite out o' the common. And so,
the invasion really is to take place after all; 
and the Chevalier de Saint George is to land at
the Tower with fifty thousand Frenchmen; 
and the Hanoverian usurper's to be beheaded;</pp>
<pb n="201">
<pp>and Doctor Sacheverel's to be made a bishop,
and we're all to be&wblank;eh?&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;All in good time,&rdquo; returned Kneebone,
putting his finger to his lips; &ldquo;don't let your
imagination run away with you, my charmer.
That boy,&rdquo; he added, looking at Thames,
&ldquo;has his eye upon us.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Mrs. Wood, however, was too much excited
to attend to the caution.</p>
<p>&ldquo;O, lud!&rdquo; she cried; &ldquo;French noblemen in
disguise! and so rude as I was! I shall never
recover it!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;A good supper will set all to rights,&rdquo; insinuated
Kneebone. &ldquo;But be prudent, my
angel.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Never fear,&rdquo; replied the lady. &ldquo;I'm prudence
personified. You might trust me with
the Chevalier himself,&mdash;I'd never betray him.
But why didn't you let me know they were
coming. I'd have got something nice. As
it is, we've only a couple of ducks&mdash;and they
were intended for you. Winny, my love, come
with me. I shall want you.&mdash;Sorry to quit
your lord&mdash;worships, I mean,&mdash;I don't know</pp>
<pb n="202">
<pp>what I mean,&rdquo; she added, a little confused, and
dropping a profound curtsey to the disguised
noblemen, each of whom replied by a bow,
worthy, in her opinion, of a prince of the
blood at the least,&mdash;&ldquo;but I've a few necessary
orders to give below.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Don't mind us, ma'am,&rdquo; said Mr. Jackson:
&ldquo;ha! ha!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Not in the least, ma'am,&rdquo; echoed Mr.
Smith: &ldquo;ho! ho!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;How condescending!&rdquo; thought Mrs. Wood.
&ldquo;Not proud in the least, I declare. Well,
I'd no idea,&rdquo; she continued, pursuing her ruminations
as she left the room, &ldquo;that people
of quality laughed so. But it's French manners,
I suppose.&rdquo;</p></div4>
<pb n="203">
<div4>
<comhd4><idref>Z400030630</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
CHAPTER V.
<subhead>HAWK AND BUZZARD.</subhead> <attbytes>38Kb</attbytes><reflink>000027</reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z400030630</ID><A1>Ainsworth, William Harrison, 1805&ndash;1882</A1><T1>Jack Sheppard. A Romance.</T1><PBL>Richard Bentley</PBL><Y1>1839</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd4>
<p><pp><smallcap>Mrs. Wood's</smallcap> anxiety to please her distinguished
guests speedily displayed itself in a
very plentiful, if not very dainty repast. To
the duckling, peas, and other delicacies, intended
for Mr. Kneebone's special consumption,
she added a few impromptu dishes,
tossed off in her best style; such as lamb
chops, broiled kidneys, fried ham and eggs,
and toasted cheese. Side by side with the
cheese, (its never&hyphen;failing accompaniment, in
all seasons, at the carpenter's board) came a
tankard of swig, and a toast. Besides these
there was a warm gooseberry&hyphen;tart, and a cold
pigeon pie&mdash;the latter capacious enough, even
allowing for its due complement of steak, to</pp>
<pb n="204">
<pp>contain the whole produce of a dovecot; a
couple of lobsters and the best part of a salmon
swimming in a sea of vinegar, and shaded by
a forest of fennel. While the cloth was laid,
the host and Thames descended to the cellar,
whence they returned, laden with a number
of flasks of the same form, and apparently destined
to the same use as those depicted in
Hogarth's delectable print&mdash;the Modern Midnight
Conversation.</pp></p>
<p><pp>Mrs. Wood now re&hyphen;appeared with a very red
face; and, followed by Winifred, took her seat
at the table. Operations then commenced.
Mr. Wood carved the ducks; Mr. Kneebone
helped to the pigeon&hyphen;pie; while Thames unwired
and uncorked a bottle of stout Carnarvonshire
ale. The woollen&hyphen;draper was no despicable
trencherman in a general way; but
his feats with the knife and fork were child's
sport compared with those of Mr. Smith.
The leg and wing of a duck were disposed
of by this gentleman in a twinkling; a brace
of pigeons and a pound of steak followed with
equal celerity; and he had just begun to make</pp>
<pb n="205">
<pp>a fierce assault upon the eggs and ham. His
appetite was perfectly Gargantuan. Nor, must
it be imagined, that while he thus exercised
his teeth, he neglected the flagon. On the
contrary, his glass was never idle, and finding
it not filled quite so frequently as he desired,
he applied himself, notwithstanding the expressive
looks and muttered remonstrances of
Mr. Jackson, to the swig. The latter gentleman
did full justice to the good things before
him; but he drank sparingly, and was visibly
annoyed by his companion's intemperance. As
to Mr. Kneebone, what with flirting with Mrs.
Wood, carving for his friends, and pledging
the carpenter, he had his hands full. At this
juncture, and just as a cuckoo&hyphen;clock in the
corner struck six, Jack Sheppard walked into
the room, with the packing&hyphen;case under his arm.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;I was in the right, you see, father,&rdquo; observed
Thames, smiling; &ldquo;Jack <it>has</it> done his
task.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;So I perceive,&rdquo; replied Wood.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Where am I to take it to?&rdquo; asked Sheppard.</p>
<pb n="206">
<p>&ldquo;I told you that before,&rdquo; rejoined Wood,
testily. &ldquo;You must take it to Sir Rowland
Trenchard's in Southampton Fields. And,
mind, it's for his sister, Lady Trafford.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Very well, sir,&rdquo; replied Sheppard.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Wet your whistle before you start, Jack,&rdquo; 
said Kneebone, pouring out a glass of ale.
&ldquo;What's that you're taking to Sir Rowland
Trenchard's?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Only a box, sir,&rdquo; answered Sheppard,
emptying the glass.</p>
<p>&ldquo;It's an odd&hyphen;shaped one,&rdquo; rejoined Kneebone,
examining it attentively. &ldquo;But I can
guess what it's for. Sir Rowland is one of
<it>us</it>,&rdquo; he added, winking at his companions,
&ldquo;and so was his brother&hyphen;in&hyphen;law, Sir Cecil
Trafford. Old Lancashire families both. Strict
Catholics, and loyal to the backbone. Fine
woman, Lady Trafford&mdash;a little on the wane
though.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ah! you're so very particular,&rdquo; sighed
Mrs. Wood.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Not in the least,&rdquo; returned Kneebone,
slily; &ldquo;not in the least. Another glass, Jack.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="207">
<p>&ldquo;Thank'ee, sir,&rdquo; grinned Sheppard.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Off with it to the health of King James
the Third, and confusion to his enemies?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Hold!&rdquo; interposed Wood; &ldquo;that is treason.
I'll have no such toast drunk at my
table!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;It's the king's birthday,&rdquo; urged the woollen&hyphen;draper.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Not <it>my</it> king's&rdquo; returned Wood. &ldquo;I
quarrel with no man's political opinions, but
I will have my own respected!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Eh day!&rdquo; exclaimed Mrs. Wood; &ldquo;here's
a pretty&hyphen;to&hyphen;do about nothing. Marry, come
up! I'll see who's to be obeyed. Drink the
toast, Jack.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;At your peril, sirrah!&rdquo; cried Wood.</p>
<p>&ldquo;He was hanged that left his drink behind,
you know, master,&rdquo; rejoined Sheppard.
&ldquo;Here's King James the Third, and confusion
to his enemies!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Very well,&rdquo; said the carpenter, sitting
down amid the laughter of the company.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Jack!&rdquo; cried Thames, in a loud voice,
&ldquo;you deserve to be hanged for a rebel as you</pp>
<pb n="208">
<pp>are to your lawful king and your lawful master.
But since we must have toasts,&rdquo; he
added, snatching up a glass, &ldquo;listen to mine:
Here's King George the First! a long reign
to him! and confusion to the Popish Pretender
and his adherents!&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Bravely done!&rdquo; said Wood, with tears in
his eyes.</p>
<p>&ldquo;That's the kinchin as was to try the dub
for us, ain't it?&rdquo; muttered Smith to his companion
as he stole a glance at Jack Sheppard.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Silence!&rdquo; returned Jackson, in a deep
whisper; &ldquo;and don't muddle your brains with
any more of that Pharaoh. You'll need all
your strength to grab him.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;What's the matter?&rdquo; remarked Kneebone,
addressing Sheppard, who, as he caught
the single but piercing eye of Jackson fixed
upon him, started and trembled.</p>
<p>&ldquo;What's the matter?&rdquo; repeated Mrs. Wood,
in a sharp tone.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ay, what's the matter, boy?&rdquo; reiterated
Jackson sternly. &ldquo;Did you never see two
gentlemen with only a couple of peepers between
them before?&rdquo;</p>
<pb>
<edit>[Figure: <bytes>340Kb</bytes>]</edit><figure sys.id="N010109">
<pb n="209">
<p>&ldquo;Never, I'll be sworn!&rdquo; said Smith, taking
the opportunity of filling his glass while
his comrade's back was turned; &ldquo;we're a
nat'ral cur'osity.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Can I have a word with you, master?&rdquo; 
said Sheppard, approaching Wood.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Not a syllable!&rdquo; answered the carpenter,
angrily. &ldquo;Get about your business!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Thames!&rdquo; cried Jack, beckoning to his
friend.</p>
<p>But Darrell averted his head.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Mistress!&rdquo; said the apprentice, making a
final appeal to Mrs. Wood.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Leave the room instantly, sirrah!&rdquo; rejoined
the lady, bouncing up, and giving him a
slap on the cheek that made his eyes flash fire.</p>
<p>&ldquo;May I be cursed,&rdquo; muttered Sheppard,
as he slunk away with (as the woollen&hyphen;draper
pleasantly observed) &lsquo;a couple of boxes in
charge,&rsquo; &ldquo;if ever I try to be honest again!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Take a little toasted cheese with the swig,
Mr. Smith,&rdquo; observed Wood. &ldquo;That's an incorrigible
rascal,&rdquo; he added, as Sheppard closed
the door; &ldquo;it's only to&hyphen;day that I discovered&mdash;&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="210">
<p>&ldquo;What?&rdquo; asked Jackson, pricking up his
ears.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Don't speak ill of him behind his back,
father,&rdquo; interposed Thames.</p>
<p>&ldquo;If <it>I</it> were your father, young gentleman,&rdquo; 
returned Jackson, enraged at the interruption,
&ldquo;I'd teach <it>you</it> not to speak till you were
spoken to.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Thames was about to reply, but a glance
from Wood checked him.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The rebuke is just,&rdquo; said the carpenter; 
&ldquo;at the same time, I'm not sorry to find
you're a friend to fair play, which, as you
seem to know, is a jewel. Open that bottle
with a blue seal, my dear. Gentlemen! a glass
of brandy will be no bad finish to our meal.&rdquo;</p>
<p>This proposal giving general satisfaction,
the bottle circulated swiftly; and Smith found
the liquor so much to his taste, that he made it
pay double toll on its passage.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Your son is a lad of spirit, Mr. Wood,&rdquo; 
observed Jackson, in a slightly&hyphen;sarcastic tone.</p>
<p>&ldquo;He's not my son,&rdquo; rejoined the carpenter.</p>
<p>&ldquo;How, sir?&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="211">
<p>&ldquo;Except by adoption. Thames Darrell
is&mdash;&rdquo; 
<lb>&ldquo;My husband nicknames him Thames,&rdquo; interrupted
Mrs. Wood, &ldquo;because he found him
in the river!&mdash;ha! ha!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ha! ha!&rdquo; echoed Smith, taking another
bumper of brandy; &ldquo;he'll set the Thames on
fire one of these days, I'll warrant him!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;That's more than you'll ever do, you
drunken fool!&rdquo; growled Jackson, in an under
tone: &ldquo;be cautious, or you'll spoil all!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Suppose we send for a bowl of punch,&rdquo; 
said Kneebone.</p>
<p>&ldquo;With all my heart!&rdquo; replied Wood. And,
turning to his daughter, he gave the necessary
directions in a low tone.</p>
<p><pp>Winifred, accordingly, left the room, and a
servant being despatched to the nearest tavern,
soon afterwards returned with a crown bowl of
the ambrosian fluid. The tables were then
cleared. Bottles and glasses usurped the place
of dishes and plates. Pipes were lighted; and
Mr. Kneebone began to dispense the fragrant
fluid; begging Mrs. Wood, in a whisper, as</pp>
<pb n="212">
<pp>he filled a rummer to the brim, not to forget
the health of the Chevalier de Saint George&mdash; 
a proposition to which the lady immediately
responded by drinking the toast aloud.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;The Chevalier shall hear of this,&rdquo; whispered
the woollen&hyphen;draper.</p>
<p>&ldquo;You don't say so!&rdquo; replied Mrs. Wood,
delighted at the idea.</p>
<p>Mr. Kneebone assured her that he <it>did</it> say
so; and, as a further proof of his sincerity,
squeezed her hand very warmly under the table.</p>
<p><pp>Mr. Smith, now, being more than half&hyphen;seas
over, became very uproarious, and, claiming
the attention of the table, volunteered the following
<caption>DRINKING SONG.</caption>
<caption>I.</caption>
<lb><lg><l>Jolly nose! the bright rubies that garnish thy tip</l>
<l>Are dug from the mines of canary;</l>
<l>And to keep up their lustre I moisten my lip</l>
<l>With hogsheads of claret and sherry.</l></lg>
<lb><caption>II.</caption>
<lg><l>Jolly nose! he who sees thee across a broad glas</l>
<l>Beholds thee in all thy perfection;</l>
<l>And to the pale snout of a temperate ass</l>
<l>Entertains the profoundest objection.</l></lg></pp>
<pb n="213">
<pp><caption>III.</caption>
<lb><lg><l>For a big&hyphen;bellied glass is the palette I use,</l>
<l>And the choicest of wine is my colour;</l>
<l>And I find that my nose takes the mellowest hues</l>
<l>The fuller I fill it&mdash;the fuller!</l></lg>
<lb><caption>IV.</caption>
<lb><lg><l>Jolly nose! there are fools who say drink hurts the sight;</l>
<l>Such dullards know nothing about it.</l>
<l>'Tis better, with wine, to extinguish the light,</l>
<l>Than live always, in darkness, without it!</l></lg></pp></p>
<lb><p>&ldquo;How long may it be since that boy was
found in the way Mrs. Wood mentions?&rdquo; inquired
Jackson, as soon as the clatter that
succeeded Mr. Smith's melody had subsided.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Let me see,&rdquo; replied Wood; &ldquo;exactly
twelve years ago last November.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Why, that must be about the time of the
Great Storm,&rdquo; rejoined Jackson.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Egad!&rdquo; exclaimed Wood, &ldquo;you've hit
the right nail on the head, anyhow. It <it>was</it>
on the night of the Great Storm that I found
him.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;I should like to hear all particulars of the</pp>
<pb n="214">
<pp>affair,&rdquo; said Jackson, &ldquo;if it wouldn't be troubling
you too much.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>Mr. Wood required little pressing. He took
a sip of punch and commenced his relation.
Though meant to produce a totally different
effect, the narrative seemed to excite the risible
propensities rather than the commiseration of
his auditor; and when Mr. Wood wound it up
by a description of the drenching he had undergone
at the Mint pump, the other could
hold out no longer, but, leaning back in his
chair, gave free scope to his merriment.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I beg your pardon,&rdquo; he cried; &ldquo;but
really&mdash;ha! ha!&mdash;you must excuse me!&mdash;that
is so uncommonly diverting&mdash;ha! ha! Do let
me hear it again?&mdash;ha! ha! ha!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Upon my word,&rdquo; rejoined Wood, &ldquo;you
seem vastly entertained by my misfortunes.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;To be sure! Nothing entertains me so
much. People always rejoice at the misfortunes
of others&mdash;never at their own! The
droll dogs! how <it>they</it> must have enjoyed it!&mdash; 
ha! ha!&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;I dare say they did. But <it>I</it> found it no</pp>
<pb n="215">
<pp>laughing matter, I can assure you. And,
though it's a long time ago, I feel as sore on
the subject as ever.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Quite natural! Never forgive an injury!
&mdash;<it>I</it> never do!&mdash;ha! ha!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Really, Mr. Jackson, I could almost fancy
we had met before. Your laugh reminds me
of&mdash;of&mdash;&rdquo; 
<lb>&ldquo;Whose, sir?&rdquo; demanded Jackson, becoming
suddenly grave.</p>
<p>&ldquo;You'll not be offended, I hope,&rdquo; returned
Wood, drily, &ldquo;if I say that your voice, your
manner, and, above all, your very extraordinary
way of laughing, put me strangely in
mind of one of the &lsquo;droll dogs,&rsquo; (as you term
them,) who helped to perpetrate the outrage
I've just described.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Whom do you mean?&rdquo; demanded Jackson.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I allude to an individual, who has since
acquired an infamous notoriety as a thieftaker; 
but who, in those days, was himself
the associate of thieves.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Well, sir, his name?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Jonathan Wild.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="216">
<p>&ldquo;'Sblood!&rdquo; cried Jackson, rising, &ldquo;I can't
sit still and hear Mr. Wild, whom I believe to
be as honest a gentleman as any in the kingdom,
calumniated!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Fire and fury!&rdquo; exclaimed Smith, getting
up with the brandy&hyphen;bottle in his grasp; &ldquo;no
man shall abuse Mr. Wild in my presence!
He's the right&hyphen;hand of the community! We
could do nothing without him!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;<it>We</it>!&rdquo; repeated Wood, significantly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Every honest man, sir! He helps us to
our own again.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Humph!&rdquo; ejaculated the carpenter.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Surely,&rdquo; observed Thames, laughing, &ldquo;to
one who entertains so high an opinion of
Jonathan Wild, as Mr. Jackson appears to do,
it can't be very offensive to be told, that he's
like him.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;I don't object to the likeness, if any such
exists, young sir,&rdquo; returned Jackson, darting
an angry glance at Thames; &ldquo;indeed I'm
rather flattered by being thought to resemble
a gentleman of Mr. Wild's figure. But I
can't submit to hear the well&hyphen;earned reputation</pp>
<pb n="217">
<pp>of my friend termed an &lsquo;infamous notoriety.&rdquo;&rsquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;No, we can't stand that,&rdquo; hiccupped Smith,
scarcely able to keep his legs.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Well, gentlemen,&rdquo; rejoined Wood, mildly; 
since Mr. Wild is a friend of yours, I'm sorry
for what I said. I've no doubt he's as honest
as either of you.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Enough,&rdquo; returned Jackson, extending his
hand; &ldquo;and if I've expressed myself warmly,
I'm sorry for it likewise. But you must allow
me to observe, my good sir, that you're wholly
in the wrong respecting my friend. Mr. Wild
never was the associate of thieves.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Never,&rdquo; echoed Smith, emphatically, &ldquo;upon
my honour.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I'm satisfied with your assurance,&rdquo; replied
the carpenter, drily.</p>
<p>&ldquo;It's more than I am,&rdquo; muttered Thames.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I was not aware that Jonathan Wild was
an acquaintance of yours, Mr. Jackson,&rdquo; said
Kneebone, whose assiduity to Mrs. Wood had
prevented him from paying much attention to
the previous scene.</p>
<pb n="218">
<p>&ldquo;I've known him all my life,&rdquo; replied the
other.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The devil you have! Then, perhaps, you
can tell me when he intends to put his threat
into execution?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;What threat?&rdquo; asked Jackson.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Why, of hanging the fellow who acts as
his jackal; one Blake, or Blueskin, I think
he's called.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You've been misinformed, sir,&rdquo; interposed
Smith. &ldquo;Mr. Wild is incapable of such baseness.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Bah!&rdquo; returned the woollen&hyphen;draper. &ldquo;I
see you don't know him as well as you pretend.
Jonathan is capable of anything. He has
hanged twelve of his associates already. The
moment they cease to be serviceable, or become
dangerous, he lodges an information,
and the matter's settled. He has always
plenty of evidence in reserve. Blueskin is
booked. As sure as you're sitting there,
Mr. Smith, he'll swing after next Old Bailey
sessions. I wouldn't be in his skin for a
trifle!&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="219">
<p>&ldquo;But he may peach,&rdquo; said Smith, casting
an oblique glance at Jackson.</p>
<p>&ldquo;It would avail him little if he did,&rdquo; replied
Kneebone. &ldquo;Jonathan does what he pleases
in the courts.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Very true,&rdquo; chuckled Jackson; &ldquo;very
true.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Blueskin's only chance would be to carry
<it>his</it> threat into effect,&rdquo; pursued the woolen&hyphen;draper.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Aha!&rdquo; exclaimed Jackson. &ldquo;<it>He</it> threatens,
does he?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;More than that,&rdquo; replied Kneebone; &ldquo;I
understand he drew a knife upon Jonathan, in
a quarrel between them lately. And, since
then, he has openly avowed his determination
of cutting his master's throat on the slightest
inkling of treachery. But, perhaps Mr. Smith
will tell you I'm misinformed, also, on that
point.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;On the contrary,&rdquo; rejoined Smith, looking
askance at his companion, &ldquo;I happen to <it>know</it>
you're in the right.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Well, sir, I'm obliged to you,&rdquo; said Jackson;</pp>
<pb n="220">
<pp>&ldquo;I shall take care to put Mr. Wild on
his guard against an assassin.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;And I shall put Blueskin on the alert
against the designs of a traitor,&rdquo; rejoined
Smith, in a tone that sounded like a menace.</p>
<p>&ldquo;In my opinion,&rdquo; remarked Kneebone, &ldquo;it
doesn't matter how soon society is rid of two
such scoundrels; and if Blueskin dies by the
rope, and Jonathan by the hand of violence,
they'll meet the fate they merit. Wild was
formerly an agent to the Jacobite party, but,
on the offer of a bribe from the opposite
faction, he unhesitatingly deserted and betrayed
his old employers. Of late, he has become the
instrument of Walpole, and does all the dirty
work for the Secret Committee. Several arrests
of importance have been intrusted to him; 
but, forewarned, forearmed, we have constantly
baffled his schemes;&mdash;ha! ha! Jonathan's a
devilish clever fellow. But he can't have his
eyes always about him, or he'd have been with
us this morning at the Mint, eh, Mr. Jackson!&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="221">
<p>&ldquo;So he would,&rdquo; replied the latter; &ldquo;so he
would.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;With all his cunning, he may meet with
his match,&rdquo; continued Kneebone, laughing.
&ldquo;I've set a trap for him.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Take care you don't fall into it yourself,&rdquo; 
returned Jackson, with a slight sneer.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Were I in your place,&rdquo; said Smith, &ldquo;I
should be apprehensive of Wild, because he's
a declared enemy.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;And were I in <it>yours</it>,&rdquo; rejoined the woollen&hyphen; 
draper, &ldquo;I should be doubly apprehensive,
because he's a professed friend. But we're
neglecting the punch all this time. A bumper
round, gentlemen. Success to our enterprise!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Success to our enterprise!&rdquo; echoed the
others, significantly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;May I ask whether you made any further
inquiries into the mysterious affair about which
we were speaking just now?&rdquo; observed Jackson,
turning to the carpenter.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;I can't say I did,&rdquo; replied Wood, somewhat
reluctantly; &ldquo;what with the confusion
incident to the storm, and the subsequent press</pp>
<pb n="222">
<pp>of business, I put it off till it was too late.
I've often regretted that I didn't investigate
the matter. However, it doesn't much signify.
All concerned in the dark transaction must
have perished.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Are you sure of that,&rdquo; inquired Jackson.</p>
<p>&ldquo;As sure as one reasonably can be. I saw
their boat swept away, and heard the roar of
the fall beneath the bridge; and no one, who
was present, could doubt the result. If the
principal instigator of the crime, whom I afterwards
encountered on the platform, and who
was dashed into the raging flood by the shower
of bricks, escaped, his preservation must have
been indeed miraculous.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Your own was equally so,&rdquo; said Jackson
ironically. &ldquo;What if he <it>did</it> escape?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;My utmost efforts should be used to bring
him to justice.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Hum!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Have you any reason to suppose he survived
the accident?&rdquo; inquired Thames eagerly.</p>
<p>Jackson smiled and put on the air of a man
who knows more than he cares to tell.</p>
<pb n="223">
<p>&ldquo;I merely asked the question,&rdquo; he said,
after he had enjoyed the boy's suspense for a
moment.</p>
<p>The hope that had been suddenly kindled
in the youth's bosom was as suddenly extinguished.</p>
<p>&ldquo;If I thought he lived&mdash;&rdquo; observed
Wood.</p>
<p>&ldquo;<it>If</it>,&rdquo; interrupted Jackson, changing his
tone: &ldquo;he <it>does</it> live. And it has been well
for you that he imagines the child was
drowned.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Who is he?&rdquo; asked Thames impatiently.</p>
<p>&ldquo;You're inquisitive, young gentleman,&rdquo; 
replied Jackson, coldly. &ldquo;When you're
older, you'll know that secrets of importance
are not disclosed gratuitously. Your adoptive
father understands mankind better.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I'd give half I'm worth to hang the villain,
and restore this boy to his rights,&rdquo; said
Mr. Wood.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;How do you know he <it>has</it> any rights to be
restored to?&rdquo; returned Jackson, with a grin.
&ldquo;Judging from what you tell me, I've no</pp>
<pb n="224">
<pp>doubt he's the illegitimate offspring of some
handsome, but lowborn profligate; in which
case, he'll neither have name, nor wealth for
his inheritance. The assassination, as you call
it, was, obviously, the vengeance of a kinsman
of the injured lady, who no doubt was of
good family, upon her seducer. The less said,
therefore, on this point the better; because, as
nothing is to be gained by it, it would only be
trouble thrown away. But, if you have any
particular fancy for hanging the gentleman,
who chose to take the law into his own hands
&mdash;and I think your motive extremely disinterested
and praiseworthy&mdash;why, it's just possible,
if you make it worth my while, that your
desires may be gratified.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;I don't see how this is to be effected, unless
you yourself were present at the time,&rdquo; 
said Wood, glancing suspiciously at the
speaker.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I had no hand in the affair,&rdquo; replied Jackson,
bluntly; &ldquo;but I know those who had; 
and could bring forward evidence, if you require
it.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="225">
<p>&ldquo;The best evidence would be afforded by
an accomplice of the assassin,&rdquo; rejoined Thames,
who was greatly offended by the insinuation as
to his parentage.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Perhaps you could point out such a party,
Mr. Jackson?&rdquo; said Wood, significantly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;<it>I</it> could,&rdquo; replied Thames.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Then you need no further information from
me,&rdquo; rejoined Jackson, sternly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Stay!&rdquo; cried Wood, &ldquo;this is a most perplexing
business&mdash;if you really are privy to
the affair&mdash;&rdquo; 
<lb>&ldquo;We'll talk of it to&hyphen;morrow, sir,&rdquo; returned
Jackson, cutting him short. &ldquo;In the mean
time, with your permission, I'll just make a
few minutes of our conversation.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;As many as you please,&rdquo; replied Wood,
walking towards the chimney&hyphen;piece, and taking
down a constable's staff, which hung upon a nail.</p>
<p><pp>Jackson, mean time, produced a pocket book; 
and, after deliberately sharpening the
point of a pencil, began to write on a blank
leaf. While he was thus occupied, Thames,
prompted by an unaccountable feeling of</pp>
<pb n="226">
<pp>curiosity, took up the penknife which the
other had just used, and examined the haft.
What he there noticed occasioned a marked
change in his demeanour. He laid down the
knife, and fixed a searching and distrustful
gaze upon the writer, who continued his task,
unconscious of anything having happened.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;There,&rdquo; cried Jackson, closing the book
and rising, &ldquo;that'll do. To&hyphen;morrow at twelve
I'll be with you, Mr. Wood. Make up your
mind as to the terms, and I'll engage to find
the man.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Hold!&rdquo; exclaimed the carpenter, in an
authoritative voice: &ldquo;we can't part thus.
Thames, lock the door.&rdquo; (An order which was
promptly obeyed.) &ldquo;Now, sir, I must insist
upon a full explanation of your mysterious
hints, or, as I am headborough of the district,
I shall at once take you into custody.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Jackson treated this menace with a loud
laugh of derision.</p>
<p>&ldquo;What ho!&rdquo; he cried, slapping Smith, who
had fallen asleep with the brandy&hyphen;bottle in his
grasp, upon the shoulder. &ldquo;It is time!&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="227">
<p>&ldquo;For what?&rdquo; grumbled the latter, rubbing
his eyes.</p>
<p>&ldquo;For the caption!&rdquo; replied Jackson, coolly
drawing a brace of pistols from his pockets.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ready!&rdquo; answered Smith, shaking himself,
and producing a similar pair of weapons.</p>
<p>&ldquo;In Heaven's name! what's all this?&rdquo; cried
Wood.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Be still, and you'll receive no injury,&rdquo; 
returned Jackson. &ldquo;We're merely about to
discharge our duty by apprehending a rebel.
Captain Kneebone! we must trouble you to
accompany us.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I've no intention of stirring,&rdquo; replied the
woollen&hyphen;draper, who was thus unceremoniously
disturbed: &ldquo;and I beg you'll sit down, Mr.
Jackson.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Come, sir!&rdquo; thundered the latter, &ldquo;no
trifling! Perhaps,&rdquo; he added, opening a warrant,
&ldquo;you'll obey this mandate?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;A warrant!&rdquo; ejaculated Kneebone, starting
to his feet.</p>
<p><pp>&lsquo;Ay, sir, from the Secretary of State, for</pp>
<pb n="228">
<pp><it>your</it> arrest! You're charged with high&hyphen;treason.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;By those who've conspired with me?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;No! by those who've entrapped you!
You've long eluded our vigilance; but we've
caught you at last!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Damnation!&rdquo; exclaimed the woollen&hyphen;draper; 
&ldquo;that I should be the dupe of such a
miserable artifice!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;It's no use lamenting now, Captain! You
ought rather to be obliged to us for allowing
you to pay this visit. We could have secured
you when you left the Mint. But we wished
to ascertain whether Mrs. Wood's charms
equalled your description.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Wretches!&rdquo; screamed the lady; &ldquo;don't
dare to breathe your vile insinuations against
me! Oh! Mr. Kneebone, are these your
French noblemen?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Don't upbraid me!&rdquo; rejoined the woollen&hyphen;draper.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Bring him along, Joe!&rdquo; said Jackson, in
a whisper to his comrade.</p>
<p><pp>Smith obeyed. But he had scarcely advanced</pp>
<pb n="229">
<pp>a step, when he was felled to the
ground by a blow from the powerful arm of
Kneebone, who, instantly possessing himself
of a pistol, levelled it at Jackson's head.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Begone! or I fire!&rdquo; he cried.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Mr. Wood,&rdquo; returned Jackson, with the
utmost composure; &ldquo;you're a headborough,
and a loyal subject of King George. I call
upon you to assist me in the apprehension of
this person. You'll be answerable for his
escape.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Mr. Wood, I command you not to stir,&rdquo; 
vociferated the carpenter's better&hyphen;half; &ldquo;recollect
you'll be answerable to me.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I declare I don't know what to do,&rdquo; said
Wood, torn by conflicting emotions. &ldquo;Mr.
Kneebone! you would greatly oblige me by
surrendering yourself.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Never!&rdquo; replied the woolen&hyphen;draper; &ldquo;and
if that treacherous rascal, by your side, doesn't
make himself scarce quickly, I'll send a bullet
through his brain.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;My death will lie at your door,&rdquo; remarked
Jackson to the carpenter.</p>
<pb n="230">
<p>&ldquo;Show me your warrant!&rdquo; said Wood, almost
driven to his wit's&hyphen;end; &ldquo;perhaps it isn't
regular?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ask him who he is?&rdquo; suggested Thames.</p>
<p>&ldquo;A good idea!&rdquo; exclaimed the carpenter.
&ldquo;May I beg to know whom I've the pleasure
of addressing? Jackson, I conclude, is merely
an assumed name.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;What does it signify?&rdquo; returned the latter,
angrily.</p>
<p>&ldquo;A great deal!&rdquo; replied Thames. &ldquo;If you
won't disclose your name, I will for you!
You are Jonathan Wild!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Further concealment is needless,&rdquo; answered
the other, pulling off his wig and black
patch, and resuming his natural tone of voice; 
&ldquo;I <it>am</it> Jonathan Wild!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Say you so!&rdquo; rejoined Kneebone; &ldquo;then
be this your passport to eternity.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Upon which he drew the trigger of the
pistol, which, luckily for the individual against
whom it was aimed, flashed in the pan.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;I might now send you on a similar journey!&rdquo; 
replied Jonathan, with a bitter smile,</pp>
<pb n="231">
<pp>and preserving the unmoved demeanour he
had maintained throughout; &ldquo;but I prefer
conveying you, in the first instance, to Newgate.
The Jacobite daws want a scarecrow.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>So saying, he sprang, with a bound like that
of a tiger&hyphen;cat, against the throat of the woollen&hyphen;draper.
And so sudden and well&hyphen;directed
was the assault, that he completely overthrew
his gigantic antagonist.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Lend a hand with the ruffles, Blueskin!&rdquo; 
he shouted, as that personage, who had just
recovered from the stunning effects of the
blow, contrived to pick himself up. &ldquo;Look
quick, d&wblank;&hyphen;n you, or we shall never master
him!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Murder!&rdquo; shrieked Mrs. Wood, at the top
of her voice.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Here's a pistol!&rdquo; cried Thames, darting
towards the undischarged weapon dropped by
Blueskin in the scuffle, and pointing it at Jonathan.
&ldquo;Shall I shoot him!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Yes! yes! put it to his ear!&rdquo; cried Mrs.
Wood; &ldquo;that's the surest way!&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;No! no! give it me!&rdquo; vociferated Wood,</pp>
<pb n="232">
<pp>snatching the pistol, and rushing to the door,
against which he placed his back.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;I'll soon settle this business. Jonathan
Wild!&rdquo; he added, in a loud voice, &ldquo;I command
you to release your prisoner.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;So I will,&rdquo; replied Jonathan, who, with
Blueskin's aid, had succeeded in slipping a
pair of handcuffs over the woolen&hyphen;draper's
wrists, &ldquo;when I've Mr. Walpole's order to
that effect&mdash;but not before.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You'll take the consequences, then?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Willingly.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;In that case I arrest you, and your confederate,
Joseph Blake, alias Blueskin, on a
charge of felony,&rdquo; returned Wood, brandishing
his staff; &ldquo;resist my authority, if you dare.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;A clever device,&rdquo; replied Jonathan; &ldquo;but
it won't serve your turn. Let us pass, sir.
Strike the gag, Blueskin.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You shall not stir a footstep. Open the
window, Thames, and call for assistance.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Stop!&rdquo; cried Jonathan, who did not care to
push matters too far, &ldquo;let me have a word
with you, Mr. Wood.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="233">
<p>&ldquo;I'll have no explanations whatever,&rdquo; replied
the carpenter, disdainfully, &ldquo;except before
a magistrate.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;At least state your charge. It is a serious
accusation.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;It <it>is</it>,&rdquo; answered Wood. &ldquo;Do you recollect
this key? Do you recollect to whom you
gave it, and for what purpose? or shall I refresh
your memory?&rdquo;</p>
<p>Wild appeared confounded.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Release your prisoner,&rdquo; continued Wood,
&ldquo;or the window is opened.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Mr. Wood,&rdquo; said Jonathan, advancing towards
him, and speaking in a low tone, &ldquo;the
secret of your adopted son's birth is known to
me. The name of his father's murderer is also
known to me. I can help you to both,&mdash;nay,
I <it>will</it> help you to both, if you do not interfere
with my plans. The arrest of this person is of
consequence to me. Do not oppose it, and I
will serve you. Thwart me, and I become
your mortal enemy. I have but to give a hint
of that boy's existence in the proper quarter,
and his life will not be worth a day's purchase.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="234">
<p>&ldquo;Don't listen to him, father,&rdquo; cried Thames,
unconscious of what was passing; &ldquo;there are
plenty of people outside.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Make your choice,&rdquo; said Jonathan.</p>
<p>&ldquo;If you don't decide quickly, I'll scream,&rdquo; 
cried Mrs. Wood, popping her head through
the window.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Set your prisoner free!&rdquo; returned Wood.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Take off the ruffles, Blueskin,&rdquo; rejoined
Wild. &ldquo;You know my fixed determination,&rdquo; 
he added in a low tone, as he passed the carpenter.
&ldquo;Before to&hyphen;morrow night that boy
shall join his father.&rdquo;</p>
<p>So saying, he unlocked the door, and strode
out of the room.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Here are some letters, which will let you
see what a snake you've cherished in your
bosom, you uxorious old dotard,&rdquo; said Blueskin,
tossing a packet of papers to Wood, as he
followed his leader.</p>
<p>&ldquo;'Odd's&hyphen;my&hyphen;life! what's this?&rdquo; exclaimed
the carpenter, looking at the superscription of
one of them. &ldquo;Why, this is your writing,
Dolly, and addressed to Mr. Kneebone.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="235">
<p>&ldquo;My writing! no such thing!&rdquo; ejaculated
the lady, casting a look of alarm at the woollen&hyphen;draper.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Confusion! the rascal must have picked
my pocket of your letters,&rdquo; whispered Kneebone.
&ldquo;What's to be done?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;What's to be done! Why, I'm undone!
How imprudent in you not to burn them. But
men <it>are</it> so careless, there's no trusting anything
to them! However, I must try to brazen
it out.&mdash;Give me the letters, my love,&rdquo; she
added aloud, and in her most winning accents; 
&ldquo;they're some wicked forgeries.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Excuse me, madam,&rdquo; replied the carpenter,
turning his back upon her, and sinking
into a chair: &ldquo;Thames, my love, bring me my
spectacles. My heart misgives me. Fool that
I was to marry for beauty! I ought to have
remembered that a fair woman and a slashed
gown always find some nail in the way.&rdquo;</p></div4>
<pb n="236">
<div4>
<comhd4><idref>Z400030631</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
CHAPTER VI.
<subhead>THE FIRST STEP TOWARDS THE LADDER.</subhead> <attbytes>27Kb</attbytes><reflink>000027</reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z400030631</ID><A1>Ainsworth, William Harrison, 1805&ndash;1882</A1><T1>Jack Sheppard. A Romance.</T1><PBL>Richard Bentley</PBL><Y1>1839</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd4>
<p><smallcap>If</smallcap> there is one thing on earth, more lovely
than another, it is a fair girl of the tender age
of Winifred Wood! Her beauty awakens no
feeling beyond that of admiration. The charm
of innocence breathes around her, as fragrance
is diffused by the flower, sanctifying her lightest
thought and action, and shielding her, like
a spell, from the approach of evil. Beautiful
is the girl of twelve,&mdash;who is neither child nor
woman, but something between both, something
more exquisite than either!</p>
<p>Such was the fairy creature presented to
Thames Darrell, under the following circumstances.</p>
<p><pp>Glad to escape from the scene of recrimination
that ensued between his adopted parents,</pp>
<pb n="237">
<pp>Thames seized the earliest opportunity of retiring,
and took his way to a small chamber in
the upper part of the house, where he and Jack
were accustomed to spend most of their leisure
in the amusements, or pursuits, proper to their
years. He found the door ajar, and, to his
surprise, perceived little Winifred seated at a
table, busily engaged in tracing some design
upon a sheet of paper. She did not hear his
approach, but continued her occupation without
raising her head.</pp></p>
<p><pp>It was a charming sight to watch the motions
of her tiny fingers as she pursued her task; 
and though the posture she adopted was not
the most favourable that might have been chosen
for the display of her sylphlike figure, there
was something in her attitude, and the glow of
her countenance, lighted up by the mellow radiance
of the setting sun falling upon her
through the panes of the little dormar window,
that seemed to the youth inexpressibly
beautiful. Winifred's features would have been
pretty, for they were regular and delicately
formed, if they had not been slightly marked.</pp>
<pb n="238">
<pp>by the small&hyphen;pox;&mdash;a disorder, that sometimes
spares more than it destroys, and imparts an
expression to be sought for in vain in the
smoothest complexion. We have seen pitted
cheeks, which we would not exchange for dimples
and a satin skin. Winifred's face had a
thoroughly amiable look. Her mouth was worthy
of her face; with small, pearly&hyphen;white teeth; 
lips glossy, rosy, and pouting; and the sweetest
smile imaginable, playing constantly about
them. Her eyes were soft and blue, arched
over by dark brows, and fringed by long silken
lashes. Her hair was of the darkest brown,
and finest texture; and, when unloosed, hung
down to her heels. She was dressed in a little
white frock, with a very long body, and very
short sleeves, which looked (from a certain fullness
about the hips,) as if it was intended to be
worn with a hoop. Her slender throat was encircled
by a black riband, with a small locket
attached to it; and upon the top of her head
rested a diminutive lace cap.</pp></p>
<p><pp>The room in which she sat was a portion of
the garret, assigned, as we have just stated, by</pp>
<pb n="239">
<pp>Mr. Wood as a playroom to the two boys; 
and, like most boy's playrooms, it exhibited a
total absence of order, or neatness. Things
were thrown here and there, to be taken up, or
again cast aside, as the whim arose; while the
broken&hyphen;backed chairs and crazy table bore the
marks of many a conflict. The characters of
the youthful occupants of the room might be
detected in every article it contained. Darrell's
peculiar bent of mind was exemplified in a
rusty broadsword, a tall grenadier's cap, a
musket without lock or ramrod, a belt and
cartouch&hyphen;box, with other matters, evincing a
decided military taste. Among his books, Plutarch's
Lives, and the Histories of Great Commanders,
appeared to have been frequently consulted; 
but the dust had gathered thickly upon
the Carpenter's Manual, and a Treatise on Trigonometry
and Geometry. Beneath the shelf,
containing these books, hung the fine old ballad
of &lsquo;<it>St. George for England</it>,&rsquo;and a loyal
ditty, then much in vogue, called &lsquo;<it>True Protestant
Gratitude, or Britain's Thanksgiving
for the First of August, Being the Day of His</it></pp>
<pb n="240">
<pp><it>Majesty's Happy Accession to the Throne.</it>&rsquo; 
Jack Sheppard's library consisted of a few ragged
and well&hyphen;thumbed volumes abstracted from
the tremendous chronicles bequeathed to the
world by those Froissarts and Holinsheds of
crime&mdash;the Ordinaries of Newgate. His vocal
collection comprised a couple of flash songs
pasted against the wall, entitled &lsquo;<it>The Thief&hyphen;Catcher's
Prophecy</it>,&rsquo;and the &lsquo;<it>Life and Death
of the Darkman's Budge</it>;&rsquo;while his extraordinary
mechanical skill was displayed in what he
termed (Jack had a supreme contempt for orthography,)
a &lsquo;<it>Moddle of his Ma<sup>s</sup>. Jale off
Newgate</it>;&rsquo;another model of the pillory at
Fleet Bridge; and a third of the permanent
gibbet at Tyburn. The latter specimen of his
workmanship was adorned with a little scarecrow
figure, intended to represent a housebreaking
chimney&hyphen;sweeper of the time, described
in Sheppard's own hand&hyphen;writing, as
&lsquo;<it>Jack Hall a&hyphen;hanging.</it>&rsquo; We must not omit
to mention that a family group from the
pencil of little Winifred, representing Mr.
and Mrs. Wood in very characteristic attitudes,</pp>
<pb n="241">
<pp>occupied a prominent place on the
walls.</pp></p>
<p>For a few moments, Thames regarded the
little girl through the half&hyphen;opened door in silence.
On a sudden, a change came over her
countenance, which, up to this moment, had
worn a smiling and satisfied expression. Throwing
down the pencil, she snatched up a piece of
Indian&hyphen;rubber, and exclaiming,&mdash;&ldquo;It isn't at
all like him! it isn't half handsome enough!&rdquo; 
was about to efface the sketch, when Thames
darted into the room.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Who isn't it like?&rdquo; he asked, endeavouring
to gain possession of the drawing, which, at
the sound of his footstep, she crushed between
her fingers.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I can't tell you!&rdquo; she replied, blushing
deeply, and clinching her little hand as tightly
as possible; &ldquo;it's a secret!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I'll soon find it out, then,&rdquo; he returned,
playfully forcing the paper from her
grasp.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Don't look at it, I entreat,&rdquo; she cried.</p>
<p><pp>But her request was unheeded. Thames unfolded</pp>
<pb n="242">
<pp>the drawing, smoothed out its creases,
and beheld a portrait of himself.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;I've a good mind not to speak to you
again, sir!&rdquo; cried Winifred, with difficulty
repressing a tear of vexation; &ldquo;you've acted
unfairly.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I feel I have, dear Winny!&rdquo; replied
Thames, abashed at his own rudeness; &ldquo;my
conduct is inexcusable.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I'll excuse it, nevertheless,&rdquo; returned the
little damsel, affectionately extending her hand
to him.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Why were you afraid to show me this
picture, Winny?&rdquo; asked the youth.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Because it's not like you,&rdquo; was her answer.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Well, like or not, I'm greatly pleased
with it, and must beg it from you as a memorial&mdash;&rdquo; 
<lb>&ldquo;Of what?&rdquo; she interrupted, startled by his
change of manner.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Of yourself,&rdquo; he replied, in a mournful
tone. &ldquo;I shall value it highly, and will promise
never to part with it. Winny, this is the</pp>
<pb n="243">
<pp>last night I shall pass beneath your father's
roof.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Have you told him so?&rdquo; she inquired,
reproachfully.</p>
<p>&ldquo;No; but I shall, before he retires to rest.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Then you <it>will</it> stay!&rdquo; she cried, clapping
her hands joyfully; &ldquo;for I'm sure he won't
part with you. Oh! thank you&mdash;thank you!
I'm so happy!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Stop, Winny!&rdquo; he answered, gravely; &ldquo;I
haven't promised yet.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;But you will,&mdash;won't you?&rdquo; she rejoined,
looking him coaxingly in the face.</p>
<p>Unable to withstand this appeal, Thames
gave the required promise, adding,&mdash;&ldquo;Oh!
Winny, I wish Mr. Wood had been my father,
as well as yours.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;So do I!&rdquo; she cried; &ldquo;for then you would
have been <it>really</it> my brother. No, I don't,
either; because&wblank;&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Well, Winny?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I don't know what I was going to say,&rdquo; 
she added, in some confusion; &ldquo;only I'm
sorry you were born a gentleman.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="244">
<p>&ldquo;Perhaps, I wasn't,&rdquo; returned Thames,
gloomily, as the remembrance of Jonathan
Wild's foul insinuation crossed him. &ldquo;But
never mind who, or what I am. Give me this
picture. I'll keep it for your sake.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I'll give you something better worth keeping,&rdquo; 
she answered, detaching the ornament
from her neck, and presenting it to him; &ldquo;this
contains a lock of my hair, and may remind
you sometimes of your little sister. As to the
picture, I'll keep it myself; though, if you
<it>do</it> go I shall need no memorial of <it>you</it>.
I'd a good many things to say to you, besides
&mdash;but you've put them all out of my
head.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>With this, she burst into tears, and sank
with her face upon his shoulder. Thames did
not try to cheer her. His own heart was too
full of melancholy foreboding. He felt that
he might soon be separated&mdash;perhaps, for ever
&mdash;from the fond little creature he held in his
arms, whom he had always regarded with the
warmest fraternal affection, and the thought of
how much she would suffer from the separation</pp>
<pb n="245">
<pp>so sensibly affected him, that he could not
help joining in her grief.</pp></p>
<p>From this sorrowful state he was aroused by
a loud derisive whistle, followed by a still
louder laugh; and, looking up, he beheld the
impudent countenance of Jack Sheppard immediately
before him.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Aha!&rdquo; exclaimed Jack, with a roguish
wink, &ldquo;I've caught you,&mdash;have I?
<lb><lg><l>The carpenter's daughter was fair and free&mdash;</l>
<l>Fair, and fickle, and false, was she!</l>
<l>She slighted the journeyman, (meaning <it>me</it>!)</l>
<l>And smiled on a gallant of high degree.</l>
<l align="r">Degree! degree!</l>
<l>She smiled on a gallant of high degree.</l></lg>
<lb>Ha! ha! ha!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Jack!&rdquo; exclaimed Thames, angrily.</p>
<p>But Sheppard was not to be silenced. He
went on with his song, accompanying it with
the most ridiculous grimaces:
<lb><lg><l>&ldquo;When years were gone by, she began to rue</l>
<l>Her love for the gentleman, (meaning<it>you</it>!)</l>
<l>&lsquo;I slighted the journeyman fond,&rsquo;quoth she,</l>
<l>&lsquo;But where is my gallant of high degree?</l>
<l align="r">&lsquo;Where! where!</l>
<l>&lsquo;Oh! where is my gallant of high degree?&rsquo;</l></lg>
<lb>Ho! ho! ho!&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="246">
<p>&ldquo;What are you doing here?&rdquo; demanded
Thames.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Oh! nothing at all,&rdquo; answered Jack, sneeringly,
&ldquo;though this room's as much mine as
yours, for that matter. But I don't desire to
spoil sport,&mdash;not I. And, if you'll give me
such a smack of your sweet lips, Miss, as
you've just given Thames, I'll take myself
off in less than no time.&rdquo;</p>
<p>The answer to this request was a &ldquo;smack&rdquo; 
of a very different description, bestowed upon
Sheppard's outstretched face by the little damsel,
as she ran out of the room.</p>
<p>&ldquo;&lsquo;Odd's! bodikins!&rdquo; cried Jack, rubbing his
cheek, &ldquo;I'm in luck to&hyphen;day. However, I'd
rather have a blow from the daughter than the
mother. I know who hits hardest. I tell you
what, Thames,&rdquo; he added, flinging himself carelessly
into a chair, &ldquo;I'd give my right hand,
&mdash;and that's no light offer for a carpenter's
&rsquo;prentice,&mdash;if that little minx were half as fond
of me as she is of you.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;That's not likely to be the case, if you go
on in this way,&rdquo; replied Thames, sharply.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Why, what the devil would you have had</pp>
<pb n="247">
<pp>me do!&mdash;make myself scarce, eh? You should
have tipped me the wink.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;No more of this,&rdquo; rejoined Thames, &ldquo;or
we shall quarrel.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Who cares if we do?&rdquo; retorted Sheppard,
with a look of defiance.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Jack,&rdquo; said the other, sternly; &ldquo;don't
provoke me further, or I'll give you a thrashing.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Two can play at that game, my blood,&rdquo; 
replied Sheppard, rising, and putting himself
into a posture of defence.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Take care of yourself, then,&rdquo; rejoined
Thames, doubling his fists, and advancing towards
him; &ldquo;though my right arm's stiff, I
can use it, as you'll find.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Sheppard was no match for his opponent, for,
though he possessed more science, he was deficient
in weight and strength; and, after a short
round, in which he had decidedly the worst of
it, a well&hyphen;directed hit on the <it>nob</it> stretched him
at full length on the floor.</p>
<p>&ldquo;That'll teach you to keep a civil tongue in
your head for the future,&rdquo; observed Thames, as
he helped Jack to his feet.</p>
<pb n="248">
<p>&ldquo;I didn't mean to give offence,&rdquo; replied
Sheppard, sulkily. &ldquo;But, let me tell you, it's
not a pleasant sight to see the girl one likes in
the arms of another.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You want another drubbing, I perceive,&rdquo; 
said Thames, frowning.</p>
<p>&ldquo;No, I don't. Enough's as good as a feast
of the dainties you provide. I'll think no more
about her. Save us!&rdquo; he cried, as his glance
accidentally alighted on the drawing, which
Winifred had dropped in her agitation. &ldquo;Is
this <it>her</it> work?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;It is,&rdquo; answered Thames. &ldquo;Do you see
any likeness?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Don't I,&rdquo; returned Jack, bitterly.
&ldquo;Strange!&rdquo; he continued, as if talking to himself.
&ldquo;How very like it is!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Not so strange, surely,&rdquo; laughed Thames,
&ldquo;that a picture should resemble the person for
whom it's intended.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ay, but it <it>is</it> strange how much it resembles
somebody for whom it's <it>not</it> intended. It's exactly
like a miniature I have in my pocket.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;A miniature! Of whom?&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="249">
<p>&ldquo;That I can't say,&rdquo; replied Jack, mysteriously.
&ldquo;But, I half suspect, of your father.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;My father!&rdquo; exclaimed Thames, in the utmost
astonishment; &ldquo;let me see it!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Here it is,&rdquo; returned Jack, producing a
small picture in a case set with brilliants.</p>
<p>Thames took it, and beheld the portrait of
a young man, apparently&mdash;judging from his attire
&mdash;of high rank, whose proud and patrician
features certainly presented a very striking resemblance
to his own.</p>
<p>&ldquo;You're right Jack,&rdquo; he said, after a pause,
during which he contemplated the picture with
the most fixed attention: &ldquo;this must have been
my father!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;No doubt of it,&rdquo; answered Sheppard; 
&ldquo;only compare it with Winny's drawing, and
you'll find they're as like as two peas in a pod.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Where did you get it?&rdquo; inquired Thames.</p>
<p>&ldquo;From Lady Trafford's, where I took the
box.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Surely, you haven't stolen it?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Stolen's an awkward word. But, as you
perceive, I brought it away with me.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="250">
<p>&ldquo;It must be restored instantly,&mdash;be the consequences
what they may.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You're not going to betray me!&rdquo; cried
Jack, in alarm.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I am not,&rdquo; replied Thames; &ldquo;but I insist
upon your taking it back at once.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Take it back yourself,&rdquo; retorted Jack, sullenly.
&ldquo;I shall do no such thing.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Very well,&rdquo; replied Thames, about to depart.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Stop!&rdquo; exclaimed Jack, planting himself
before the door; &ldquo;do you want to get me sent
across the water?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I want to save you from disgrace and ruin,&rdquo; 
returned Thames.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Bah!&rdquo; cried Jack, contemptuously; &ldquo;nobody's
disgraced and ruined unless he's found
out. I'm safe enough if you hold your tongue.
Give me that picture, or I'll make you!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Hear me,&rdquo; said Thames, calmly; &ldquo;you
well know you're no match for me.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Not at fisticuffs, perhaps,&rdquo; interrupted Jack,
fiercely; &ldquo;but I've my knife.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You daren't use it.&rdquo;</p>
<pb>
<edit>[Figure: <bytes>358Kb</bytes>]</edit><figure sys.id="N010110">
<pb n="251">
<p>&ldquo;Try to leave the room, and see whether I
daren't,&rdquo; returned Jack, opening the blade.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I didn't expect this from you,&rdquo; rejoined
Thames, resolutely. &ldquo;But your threats won't
prevent my leaving the room when I please,
and as I please. Now, will you stand aside?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I won't,&rdquo; answered Jack, obstinately.</p>
<p>Thames said not another word, but marched
boldly towards him, and seized him by the
collar.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Leave go!&rdquo; cried Jack, struggling violently,
and raising his hand, &ldquo;or I'll maul you for
life.&rdquo;</p>
<p>But Thames was not to be deterred from his
purpose; and the strife might have terminated
seriously, if a peace&hyphen;maker had not appeared
in the shape of little Winifred, who,
alarmed by the noise, rushed suddenly into the
room.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ah!&rdquo; she screamed, seeing the uplifted
weapon in Sheppard's hand, &ldquo;don't hurt
Thames&mdash;don't, dear Jack! If you want to
kill somebody, kill me, not him.&rdquo;</p>
<p>And she flung herself between them.</p>
<pb n="252">
<p>Jack dropped the knife, and walked sullenly
aside.</p>
<p>&ldquo;What has caused this quarrel, Thames?&rdquo; 
asked the little girl, anxiously.</p>
<p>&ldquo;You,&rdquo; answered Jack, abruptly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;No such thing,&rdquo; rejoined Thames. &ldquo;I'll
tell you all about it presently. But you must
leave us now, dear Winny, Jack and I have
something to settle between ourselves. Don't
be afraid. Our quarrel's quite over.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Are you sure of that?&rdquo; returned Winifred,
looking uneasily at Jack.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ay, ay,&rdquo; rejoined Sheppard; &ldquo;he may do
what he pleases,&mdash;hang me, if he thinks proper,
&mdash;if <it>you</it> wish it.&rdquo;</p>
<p>With this assurance, and at the reiterated
request of Thames, the little girl reluctantly
withdrew.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Come, come, Jack,&rdquo; said Thames, walking
up to Sheppard, and taking his hand, &ldquo;have
done with this. I tell you once more, I'll
say and do nothing to get you into trouble.
Rest assured of that. But I'm resolved to
see Lady Trafford. Perhaps, she may tell me
whose picture this is.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="253">
<p>&ldquo;So she may,&rdquo; returned Jack, brightening
up; &ldquo;it's a good idea. I'll go with you.
But you must see her alone; and that'll be
no easy matter to manage, for she's a great
invalid, and has generally somebody with her.
Above all, beware of Sir Rowland Trenchard.
He's as savage and suspicious as the devil
himself. I should never have noticed the miniature
at all, if it hadn't been for him. He
was standing by, rating her ladyship,&mdash;who
can scarcely stir from the sofa,&mdash;while I was
packing up her jewels in the case, and I observed
that she tried to hide a small casket
from him. His back was no sooner turned,
than she slipped this casket into the box.
The next minute, I contrived, without either
of 'em perceiving me, to convey it into my
own pocket. I was sorry for what I did afterwards; 
for, I don't know why, but, poor
lady! with her pale face, and black eyes, she
reminded me of my mother.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;That, alone, ought to have prevented you
from acting as you did, Jack,&rdquo; returned
Thames, gravely.</p>
<pb n="254">
<p>&ldquo;I should never have acted as I did,&rdquo; rejoined
Sheppard, bitterly; &ldquo;if Mrs. Wood
hadn't struck me. That blow made me a
thief. And, if ever I'm brought to the gallows,
I shall lay my death at her door.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Well, think no more about it,&rdquo; returned
Thames. &ldquo;Do better in future.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I will, when I've had my revenge,&rdquo; muttered
Jack. &ldquo;But, take my advice, and keep
out of Sir Rowland's way, or you'll get the
poor lady into trouble as well as me.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Never fear,&rdquo; replied Thames, taking up
his hat. &ldquo;Come, let's be off.&rdquo;</p>
<p>The two boys, then, emerged upon the landing,
and were about to descend the stairs, when
the voices of Mr. and Mrs. Wood resounded
from below. The storm appeared to have
blown over, for they were conversing in a very
amicable manner with Mr. Kneebone, who was
on the point of departing.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Quite sorry, my good friend, there should
have been any misunderstanding between us,&rdquo; 
observed the woollen&hyphen;draper.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Don't mention it,&rdquo; returned Wood, in the</pp>
<pb n="255">
<pp>conciliatory tone of one who admits he has
been in the wrong; &ldquo;your explanation is perfectly
satisfactory.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;We shall expect you to&hyphen;morrow,&rdquo; insinuated
Mrs. Wood; &ldquo;and pray, don't bring
anybody with you,&mdash;especially Jonathan Wild.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;No fear of that,&rdquo; laughed Kneebone.&mdash; 
&ldquo;Oh! about that boy, Thames Darrell. His
safety must be looked to. Jonathan's threats
are not to be sneezed at. The rascal will be at
work before the morning. Keep your eye upon
the lad. And mind he doesn't stir out of your
sight, on any pretence whatever, till I call.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You hear that,&rdquo; whispered Jack.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I do,&rdquo; replied Thames, in the same tone; 
&ldquo;we haven't a moment to lose.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Take care of yourself,&rdquo; said Mr. Wood,
&ldquo;and I'll take care of Thames. It's never a
bad day that has a good ending. Good night!
God bless you!&rdquo;</p>
<p>Upon this, there was a great shaking of
hands, with renewed apologies and protestations
of friendship on both sides; after which
Mr. Kneebone took his leave.</p>
<pb n="256">
<p>&ldquo;And so, you really suspected me?&rdquo; murmured
Mrs. Wood, reproachfully, as they returned
to the parlour. &ldquo;Oh! you men!
you men! Once get a thing into your head,
and nothing will beat it out.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Why, my love,&rdquo; rejoined her husband,
&ldquo;appearances, you must allow, were a little
against you. But, since you assure me <it>you</it>
didn't write the letters, and Mr. Kneebone assures
me <it>he</it> didn't receive them, I can't do
otherwise than believe you. And I've made
up my mind that a husband ought to believe
only half that he hears, and nothing that
he sees.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;An excellent maxim!&rdquo; replied his wife,
approvingly; &ldquo;the best I ever heard you
utter.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I must now go and look after Thames,&rdquo; 
observed the carpenter.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Oh! never mind him: he'll take no harm!
Come with me into the parlour. I can't spare
you at present. Heigho!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Now for it!&rdquo; cried Jack, as the couple
entered the room: &ldquo;the coast's clear.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="257">
<p>Thames was about to follow, when he felt a
gentle grasp upon his arm. He turned, and
beheld Winifred.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Where are you going?&rdquo; she asked.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I shall be back presently,&rdquo; replied Thames,
evasively.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Don't go, I beg of you!&rdquo; she implored.
&ldquo;You're in danger. I overheard what Mr.
Kneebone said, just now.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Death and the devil! what a cursed interruption!&rdquo; 
cried Jack, impatiently. &ldquo;If you
loiter in this way, old Wood will catch us.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;If you stir, I'll call him!&rdquo; rejoined Winifred.
&ldquo;It's you, Jack, who are persuading
my brother to do wrong. Thames,&rdquo; she urged,
&ldquo;the errand, on which you're going, can't be
for any good, or you wouldn't be afraid of
mentioning it to my father.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;He's coming!&rdquo; cried Jack, stamping his
foot, with vexation. &ldquo;Another moment, and
it'll be too late.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Winny, I <it>must</it> go!&rdquo; said Thames, breaking
from her.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Stay, dear Thames!&mdash;stay!&rdquo; cried the</pp>
<pb n="258">
<pp>little girl. &ldquo;He hears me not! he's gone!&rdquo; 
she added, as the door was opened and shut
with violence; &ldquo;something tells me I shall
never see him again!&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>When her father, a moment afterwards,
issued from the parlour to ascertain the cause
of the noise, he found her seated on the stairs,
in an agony of grief.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Where's Thames?&rdquo; he hastily inquired.</p>
<p>Winifred pointed to the door. She could
not speak.</p>
<p>&ldquo;And Jack?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Gone too,&rdquo; sobbed his daughter.</p>
<p>Mr. Wood uttered something like an imprecation.</p>
<p>&ldquo;God forgive me for using such a word!&rdquo; 
he cried, in a troubled tone; &ldquo;if I hadn't
yielded to my wife's silly request, this wouldn't
have happened!&rdquo;</p></div4>
<pb n="259">
<div4>
<comhd4><idref>Z400030632</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
CHAPTER VII.
<subhead>BROTHER AND SISTER.</subhead> <attbytes>11Kb</attbytes><reflink>000027</reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z400030632</ID><A1>Ainsworth, William Harrison, 1805&ndash;1882</A1><T1>Jack Sheppard. A Romance.</T1><PBL>Richard Bentley</PBL><Y1>1839</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd4>
<p><pp><smallcap>On</smallcap> the same evening, in a stately chamber of
a noble old mansion of Elizabeth's time, situated
in Southampton Fields, two persons were
seated. One of these, a lady, evidently a confirmed
invalid, and attired in deep mourning,
reclined upon a sort of couch, or easy chair,
set on wheels, with her head supported by
cushions, and her feet resting upon a velvet
footstool. A crutch, with a silver handle,
stood by her side, proving the state of extreme
debility to which she was reduced. It was no
easy matter to determine her age, for, though
she still retained a certain youthfulness of appearance,
she had many marks in her countenance,
usually indicating the decline of life,
but which in her case were, no doubt, the result</pp>
<pb n="260">
<pp>of constant and severe indisposition. Her
complexion was wan and faded, except where
it was tinged by a slight hectic flush, that made
the want of colour more palpable; her eyes
were large and black, but heavy and lustreless; 
her cheeks sunken; her frame emaciated; 
her dark hair thickly scattered with grey.
When younger, and in better health, she must
have been eminently lovely; and there were
still the remains of great beauty about her.
The expression, however, which would chiefly
have interested a beholder, was that of settled
and profound melancholy.</pp></p>
<p><pp>Her companion was a person of no inferior
condition. Indeed it was apparent, from the
likeness between them, that they were nearly
related. He had the same dark eyes, though
lighted by a fierce flame; the same sallow complexion; 
the same tall, thin figure, and majestic
demeanour; the same proud cast of features.
But here the resemblance stopped. The
expression was wholly different. He looked
melancholy enough, it is true. But his gloom
appeared to be occasioned by remorse, rather</pp>
<pb n="261">
<pp>than sorrow. No sterner head was ever beheld
beneath the cowl of a monk, or the bonnet
of an inquisitor. He seemed inexorable, and
inscrutable as fate itself.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Well, Lady Trafford,&rdquo; he said, fixing a
severe look upon her. &ldquo;You depart for Lancashire
to&hyphen;morrow. Have I your final answer?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You have, Sir Rowland,&rdquo; she answered,
in a feeble tone, but firmly. &ldquo;You shall have
the sum you require, but&wblank;&rdquo;</p>
<p>But what, madam?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Do not misunderstand me,&rdquo; she proceeded.
&ldquo;I give it to King James&mdash;not to you: for
the furtherance of a great and holy cause,
not for the prosecution of wild and unprofitable
schemes.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Sir Rowland bit his lips to repress the
answer that rose to them.</p>
<p>&ldquo;And the will?&rdquo; he said, with forced calmness.
&ldquo;Do you still refuse to make one?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I <it>have</it> made one,&rdquo; replied Lady Trafford.</p>
<p>&ldquo;How?&rdquo; cried her brother, starting.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Rowland,&rdquo; she rejoined, &ldquo;you strive in
vain to terrify me into compliance with your</pp>
<pb n="262">
<pp>wishes. Nothing shall induce me to act contrary
to the dictates of my conscience. My
will is executed, and placed in safe custody.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;In whose favour is it made?&rdquo; he inquired,
sternly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;In favour of my son.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You have no son,&rdquo; rejoined Sir Rowland,
moodily.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I <it>had</it> one,&rdquo; answered his sister, in a mournful
voice; &ldquo;and, perhaps, I have one still.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;If I thought so&wblank;&rdquo; cried the knight,
fiercely; &ldquo;but this is idle,&rdquo; he added, suddenly
checking himself. &ldquo;Aliva, your child
perished with its father.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;And by whom were they both destroyed?&rdquo; 
demanded his sister, raising herself by a painful
effort, and regarding him with a searching
glance.</p>
<p>&ldquo;By the avenger of his family's dishonour&mdash; 
by your brother,&rdquo; he replied, coolly.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Brother,&rdquo; cried Lady Trenchard, her eye
blazing with unnatural light, and her cheek
suffused with a crimson stain: &ldquo;Brother,&rdquo; she
cried, lifting her thin fingers towards heaven,</pp>
<pb n="263">
<pp>&ldquo;as God shall judge me, I was wedded to that
murdered man!&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;A lie!&rdquo; ejaculated Sir Rowland, furiously; 
&ldquo;a black, and damning lie!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;It is the truth,&rdquo; replied his sister, falling
backwards upon the couch. &ldquo;I will swear it
upon the cross!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;His name, then?&rdquo; demanded the knight.
&ldquo;Tell me that, and I will believe you.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Not now&mdash;not now!&rdquo; she returned, with a
shudder. &ldquo;When I am dead you will learn it.
Do not disquiet yourself. You will not have
to wait long for the information. Rowland,&rdquo; 
she added, in an altered tone, &ldquo;I am certain
I shall not live many days. And, if you
treat me in this way, you will have my
death to answer for, as well as the deaths of
my husband and child. Let us part in peace.
We shall take an eternal farewell of each
other.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Be it so!&rdquo; rejoined Sir Rowland, with concentrated
fury; &ldquo;but before we <it>do</it> part, I am
resolved to know the name of your pretended
husband!&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="264">
<p>&ldquo;Torture shall not wrest it from me,&rdquo; answered
his sister, firmly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;What motive have you for concealment?&rdquo; 
he demanded.</p>
<p>&ldquo;A vow,&rdquo; she answered,&mdash;&ldquo;a vow to my
dead husband.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Sir Rowland looked at her for a moment, as
if he meditated some terrible reply. He then
arose, and, taking a few turns in the chamber,
stopped suddenly before her.</p>
<p>&ldquo;What has put it into your head that your
son yet lives?&rdquo; he asked.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I have dreamed that I shall see him before
I die,&rdquo; she rejoined.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Dreamed!&rdquo; echoed the knight, with a
ghastly smile. &ldquo;Is that all? Then learn from
me that your hopes are visionary as their foundation.
Unless he can arise from the bottom
of the Thames, where he and his abhorred father
lie buried, you will never behold him
again in this world.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Heaven have compassion on you, Rowland!&rdquo; 
murmured his sister, crossing her
hands, and looking upwards; &ldquo;you have none
on me.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="265">
<p>&ldquo;I <it>will</it> have none till I have forced the
villain's name from you!&rdquo; he cried, stamping
the floor with rage.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Rowland, your violence is killing me,&rdquo; she
returned, in a plaintive tone.</p>
<p>&ldquo;His name, I say!&mdash;his name!&rdquo; thundered
the knight.</p>
<p>And he unsheathed his sword.</p>
<p>Lady Trafford uttered a prolonged scream,
and fainted. When she came to herself,
she found that her brother had quitted
the room, leaving her to the care of a female
attendant. Her first orders were to summon
the rest of her servants to make immediate
preparations for her departure for Lancashire.</p>
<p>&ldquo;To&hyphen;night, your ladyship?&rdquo; ventured an
elderly domestic.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Instantly, Hobson,&rdquo; returned Lady Trafford; 
&ldquo;as soon as the carriage can be brought
round.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;It shall be at the door in ten minutes.
Has your ladyship any further commands?&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;None whatever. Yet, stay! There is</pp>
<pb n="266">
<pp>one thing I wish you to do. Take that box,
and put it into the carriage yourself. Where
is Sir Rowland?&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;In the library, your ladyship. He has
given orders that no one is to disturb him.
But there's a person in the hall&mdash;a very odd
sort of man&mdash;waiting to see him, who won't
be sent away.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Very well. Lose not a moment, Hobson.&rdquo;</p>
<p>The elderly domestic bowed, took up the
case, and retired.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Your ladyship is far too unwell to travel,&rdquo; 
remarked the female attendant, assisting her to
rise; &ldquo;you'll never be able to reach Manchester.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;It matters not, Norris,&rdquo; replied Lady
Trafford: &ldquo;I would rather die on the road,
than be exposed to another such scene as I
have just encountered.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Dear me!&rdquo; sympathised Mrs. Norris. &ldquo;I
was afraid from the scream I heard, that
something dreadful had happened, Sir Rowland
has a terrible temper indeed&mdash;a shocking</pp>
<pb n="267">
<pp>temper! I declare he frightens me out
of my senses.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Sir Rowland is my brother,&rdquo; resumed Lady
Trafford coldly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Well that's no reason why he should treat
your ladyship so shamefully, I'm sure. Ah!
how I wish poor dear Sir Cecil were alive!
he'd keep him in order.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Lady Trafford sighed deeply.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Your ladyship has never been well since
you married Sir Cecil,&rdquo; rejoined Mrs. Norris.
&ldquo;For my part, I don't think you ever quite
got over the accident you met with on the
night of the Great Storm.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Norris!&rdquo; gasped Lady Trafford, trembling
violently.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Mercy on us! what have I said?&rdquo; cried the
attendant, greatly alarmed by the agitation of
her mistress; &ldquo;do sit down, your ladyship,
while I run for the ratifia and rosa solis.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;It is past,&rdquo; rejoined Lady Trafford, recovering
herself by a powerful effort; &ldquo;but never
allude to the circumstance again. Go and prepare
for our departure.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="268">
<p>In less time than Hobson had mentioned, the
carriage was announced. And Lady Trafford
having been carried down stairs, and placed
within it, the postboys drove off, at a rapid
pace for Barnet.</p></div4>
<pb n="269">
<div4>
<comhd4><idref>Z400030633</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
CHAPTER VIII.
<subhead>MICHING MALLECHO.</subhead> <attbytes>28Kb</attbytes><reflink>000027</reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z400030633</ID><A1>Ainsworth, William Harrison, 1805&ndash;1882</A1><T1>Jack Sheppard. A Romance.</T1><PBL>Richard Bentley</PBL><Y1>1839</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd4>
<p><pp><smallcap>Sir rowland</smallcap>, meantime, paced his chamber
with a quick and agitated step. He was ill at
ease, though he would not have confessed his
disquietude even to himself. Not conceiving
that his sister&mdash;feeble as she was, and yielding
as she had ever shown herself to his wishes,
whether expressed or implied&mdash;would depart
without consulting him, he was equally surprised
and enraged to hear the servants busied
in transporting her to the carriage. His pride,
however, would not suffer him to interfere with
their proceedings; much less could he bring
himself to acknowledge that he had been in the
wrong, and entreat Lady Trafford to remain,
though he was well aware that her life might
be endangered if she travelled by night. But,</pp>
<pb n="270">
<pp>when the sound of the carriage&hyphen;wheels died
away, and he felt that she was actually gone,
his resolution failed him, and he rang the bell
violently.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;My horses, Charcam,&rdquo; he said, as a servant
appeared.</p>
<p>The man lingered.</p>
<p>&ldquo;'Sdeath! why am I not obeyed?&rdquo; exclaimed
the knight, angrily. &ldquo;I wish to overtake
Lady Trafford. Use despatch!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Her ladyship will not travel beyond Saint
Alban's to&hyphen;night, Sir Rowland, so Mrs. Norris
informed me,&rdquo; returned Charcam, respectfully; 
&ldquo;and there's a person without, anxious for an
audience, whom, with submission, I think your
honour would desire to see.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ah!&rdquo; exclaimed Sir Rowland, glancing
significantly at Charcam, who was a confidant
in his Jacobite schemes; &ldquo;is it the messenger
from Orchard&hyphen;Windham, from Sir William?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;No, Sir Rowland.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;From Mr. Corbet Kynaston, then? Sir
John Packington's courier was here yesterday.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;No, Sir Rowland.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="271">
<p>&ldquo;Perhaps he is from Lord Derwentwater, or
Mr. Forster? News <it>is</it> expected from
Northumberland.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I can't exactly say, Sir Rowland. The
gentleman didn't communicate his business to
me. But I'm sure it's important.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Charcam said this, not because he knew anything
about the matter; but, having received a
couple of guineas to deliver the message, he,
naturally enough, estimated its importance by
the amount of the gratuity.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Well, I will see him,&rdquo; replied the knight,
after a moment's pause; &ldquo;he may be from the
Earl of Mar. But let the horses be in readiness.
I shall ride to St. Alban's to&hyphen;night.&rdquo;</p>
<p>So saying, he threw himself into a chair.
And Charcam, fearful of another change in
his master's present uncertain mood, disappeared.</p>
<p><pp>The person, shortly afterwards ushered into
the room, seemed by the imperfect light,&mdash;for
the evening was advancing, and the chamber
darkened by heavy drapery,&mdash;to be a middle&hyphen;sized,
middle&hyphen;aged man, of rather vulgar appearance,</pp>
<pb n="272">
<pp>but with a very shrewd aspect. He
was plainly attired in a riding&hyphen;dress and boots
of the period, and wore a hanger by his side.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Your servant, Sir Rowland,&rdquo; said the
stranger, ducking his head, as he advanced.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Your business, sir?&rdquo; returned the other,
stiffly.</p>
<p>The new&hyphen;comer looked at Charcam. Sir
Rowland waved his hand, and the attendant
withdrew.</p>
<p>&ldquo;You don't recollect me, I presume?&rdquo; premised
the stranger, taking a seat.</p>
<p>The knight, who could ill brook this familiarity,
instantly arose.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Don't disturb yourself,&rdquo; continued the
other, nowise disconcerted by the rebuke. &ldquo;I
never stand upon ceremony where I know
I shall be welcome. We <it>have</it> met before.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Indeed!&rdquo; rejoined Sir Rowland, haughtily; 
&ldquo;perhaps, you will refresh my memory as to
the time, and place.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Let me see. The time was the 26th of
November, 1703: the place, the Mint in Southwark.</pp>
<pb n="273">
<pp>I have a good memory, you perceive,
Sir Rowland.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>The knight staggered as if struck by a mortal
wound. Speedily recovering himself, however,
he rejoined, with forced calmness, &ldquo;You
are mistaken, sir. I was in Lancashire, at our
family seat, at the time you mention.&rdquo;</p>
<p>The stranger smiled incredulously.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Well, Sir Rowland,&rdquo; he said, after a brief
pause, during which the knight regarded him
with a searching glance, as if endeavouring to recal
his features; &ldquo;I will not gainsay your words.
You are in the right to be cautious, till you
know with whom you have to deal; and, even
then, you can't be too wary. &lsquo;Avow nothing,
believe nothing, give nothing for nothing,&rsquo; is
my own motto. And it's a maxim of universal
application; or, at least, of universal practice.
I am not come here to play the part of your
father&hyphen;confessor. I am come to serve you.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;In what way, sir?&rdquo; demanded Trenchard,
in astonishment.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;You will learn anon. You refuse me your
confidence. I applaud your prudence: it is,</pp>
<pb n="274">
<pp>however, needless. Your history, your actions,
nay, your very thoughts are better known to
me than to your spiritual adviser.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Make good your assertions,&rdquo; cried Trenchard,
furiously, &ldquo;or&wblank;&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;To the proof,&rdquo; interrupted the stranger,
calmly. &ldquo;You are the son of Sir Montacute
Trenchard, of Ashton&hyphen;Hall, near Manchester.
Sir Montacute had three children&mdash;two daughters
and yourself. The eldest, Constance, was
lost, by the carelessness of a servant, during her
infancy, and has never since been heard of: the
youngest, Aliva, is the present Lady Trafford.
I merely mention these circumstances to show
the accuracy of my information.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;If this is the extent of it, sir,&rdquo; returned
the knight, ironically, &ldquo;you may spare yourself
further trouble. These particulars are
familiar to all, who have any title to the knowledge.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Perhaps so,&rdquo; rejoined the stranger; &ldquo;but
I have others in reserve, not so generally
known. With your permission, I will go on
in my own way. Where I am in error, you</pp>
<pb n="275">
<pp>can set me right.&mdash;Your father, Sir Montacute
Trenchard, who had been a loyal subject of
King James the Second, and borne arms in his
service, on the abdication of that monarch,
turned his back upon the Stuarts, and would
never afterwards recognise their claims to the
crown. It was said, that he received an affront
from James, in the shape of a public reprimand,
which his pride could not forgive. Be
this as it may, though a Catholic, he died a
friend to the Protestant succession.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;So far you are correct,&rdquo; observed Trenchard; 
&ldquo;still, this is no secret.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Suffer me to proceed,&rdquo; replied the stranger.
&ldquo;The opinions, entertained by the old knight,
naturally induced him to view with displeasure
the conduct of his son, who warmly espoused
the cause he had deserted. Finding remonstrances
of no avail, he had recourse to threats; 
and when threats failed, he adopted more decided
measures.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ha!&rdquo; ejaculated Trenchard.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;As yet,&rdquo; pursued the stranger, &ldquo;Sir Montacute
had placed no limit to his son's expenditure.</pp>
<pb n="276">
<pp>He did not quarrel with Rowland's
profusion, for his own revenues were ample; 
but he <it>did</it> object to the large sums lavished by
him in the service of a faction he was resolved
not to support. Accordingly, the old knight
reduced his son's allowance to a third of its
previous amount; and, upon further provocation,
he even went so far as to alter his will in
favour of his daughter, Aliva, who was then
betrothed to her cousin, Sir Cecil Trafford.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Proceed, sir,&rdquo; said Trenchard, breathing
hard.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Under these circumstances, Rowland did
what any other sensible person would do.
Aware of his father's inflexibility of purpose,
he set his wits to work to defeat the design.
He contrived to break off his sister's match; 
and this he accomplished so cleverly, that he
maintained the strictest friendship with Sir
Cecil. For two years he thought himself secure; 
and, secretly engaged in the Jacobite
schemes of the time, in which, also, Sir Cecil
was deeply involved, he began to relax in his
watchfulness over Aliva. About this time,</pp>
<pb n="277">
<pp>&mdash;namely, in November, 1703&mdash;while young
Trenchard was in Lancashire, and his sister in
London, on a visit, he received a certain communication
from his confidential servant, Davies,
which, at once, destroyed his hopes. He learnt
that his sister was privately married&mdash;the name
or rank of her husband could not be ascertained
&mdash;and living in retirement in an obscure dwelling
in the Borough, where she had given birth
to a son. Rowland's plans were quickly formed,
and as quickly executed. Accompanied by
Sir Cecil, who still continued passionately enamoured
of his sister, and to whom he represented
that she had fallen a victim to the arts
of a seducer, he set off, at fiery speed, for the
metropolis. Arrived there, their first object
was to seek out Davies, by whom they were
conducted to the lady's retreat,&mdash;a lone habitation,
situated on the outskirts of Saint George's
Fields in Southwark. Refused admittance,
they broke open the door. Aliva's husband,
who passed by the name of Darrell, confronted
them sword in hand. For a few minutes he
kept them at bay. But, urged by his wife's</pp>
<pb n="278">
<pp>cries, who was more anxious for the preservation
of her child's life than her own, he
snatched up the infant, and made his escape
from the back of the premises. Rowland and
his companions instantly started in pursuit,
leaving the lady to recover as she might. They
tracked the fugitive to the Mint; but, like
hounds at fault, they here lost all scent of their
prey. Meantime, the lady had overtaken
them; but, terrified by the menaces of her
vindictive kinsmen, she did not dare to reveal
herself to her husband, of whose concealment
on the roof of the very house the party were
searching she was aware. Aided by an individual,
who was acquainted with a secret outlet
from the tenement, Darrell escaped. Before
his departure, he gave his assistant a glove.
That glove is still preserved. In her endeavour
to follow him, Aliva met with a severe fall,
and was conveyed away, in a state of insensibility,
by Sir Cecil. She was supposed to be
lifeless; but she survived the accident, though
she never regained her strength. Directed by
the same individual, who had helped Darrell to</pp>
<pb n="279">
<pp>steal a march upon him, Rowland, with Davies,
and another attendant, continued the pursuit.
Both the fugitive and his chasers embarked
on the Thames. The elements were wrathful
as their passions. The storm burst upon
them in its fury. Unmindful of the terrors
of the night, unscared by the danger
that threatened him, Rowland consigned his
sister's husband and his sister's child to the
waves.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Bring your story to an end, sir,&rdquo; said
Trenchard, who had listened to the recital with
mingled emotions of rage and fear.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;I have nearly done,&rdquo; replied the stranger.
&mdash;&ldquo;As Rowland's whole crew perished in the
tempest, and he only escaped by miracle, he
fancied himself free from detection. And for
twelve years he has been so; until his long
security, well&hyphen;nigh obliterating remembrance of
the deed, has bred almost a sense of innocence
within his breast. During this period Sir
Montacute has been gathered to his fathers.
His title has descended to Rowland: his estates
to Aliva. The latter has, since, been induced to</pp>
<pb n="280">
<pp>unite herself to Sir Cecil, on terms originating
with her brother, and which, however strange
and unprecedented, were acquiesced in by the
suitor.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>Sir Rowland looked bewildered with surprise.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The marriage was never consummated,&rdquo; 
continued the imperturbable stranger. &ldquo;Sir
Cecil is no more. Lady Trafford, supposed to
be childless, broken in health and spirits, frail
both in mind and body, is not likely to make
another marriage. The estates must, ere long,
revert to Sir Rowland.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Are you man, or fiend?&rdquo; exclaimed Trenchard,
staring at the stranger, as he concluded his
narration.</p>
<p>&ldquo;You are complimentary, Sir Rowland,&rdquo; returned
the other, with a grim smile.</p>
<p>&ldquo;If you <it>are</it> human,&rdquo; rejoined Trenchard,
with stern emphasis, &ldquo;I insist upon knowing
whence you derived your information?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I might refuse to answer the question, Sir
Rowland. But I am not indisposed to gratify
you. Partly, from your confessor; partly,
from other sources.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="281">
<p>&ldquo;My confessor!&rdquo; ejaculated the knight, in
the extremity of surprise; &ldquo;has <it>he</it> betrayed
his sacred trust?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;He has,&rdquo; replied the other, grinning; &ldquo;and
this will be a caution to you in future, how you
confide a secret of consequence to a priest. I
should as soon think of trusting a woman.
Tickle the ears of their reverences with any
idle nonsense you please: but tell them nothing
you care to have repeated. I was once
a disciple of Saint Peter myself, and speak from
experience.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Who are you?&rdquo; ejaculated Trenchard,
scarcely able to credit his senses.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I'm surprised you've not asked that question
before, Sir Rowland. It would have
saved me much circumlocution, and you some
suspense. My name is Wild&mdash;Jonathan Wild.&rdquo;</p>
<p>And the great thief&hyphen;taker indulged himself in
a chuckle at the effect produced by this announcement.
He was accustomed to such surprises,
and enjoyed them.</p>
<p>Sir Rowland laid his hand upon his sword.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Mr. Wild,&rdquo; he said, in a sarcastic tone, but</pp>
<pb n="282">
<pp>with great firmness; &ldquo;a person of your well&hyphen;known
sagacity must be aware that some secrets
are dangerous to the possessor.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;I am fully aware of it, Sir Rowland,&rdquo; replied
Jonathan, coolly; &ldquo;but I have nothing
to fear; because, in the first place, it will be to
your advantage not to molest me; and, in the
second, I am provided against all contingencies.
I never hunt the human tiger without being
armed. My janizaries are without. One of
them is furnished with a packet containing the
heads of the statement I have just related,
which, if I don't return at a certain time, will
be laid before the proper authorities. I have
calculated my chances, you perceive.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You have forgotten that you are in my
power,&rdquo; returned the knight, sternly; &ldquo;and
that all your allies cannot save you from my
resentment.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;I can, at least, protect myself,&rdquo; replied
Wild, with provoking calmness. &ldquo;I am accounted
a fair shot, as well as a tolerable
swordsman, and I will give proof of my skill in
both lines, should occasion require it. I have</pp>
<pb n="283">
<pp>had a good many desperate engagements in my
time, and have generally come off victorious. I
bear the marks of some of them about me still,&rdquo; 
he continued, taking off his wig, and laying
bare a bald skull, covered with cicatrices and
plates of silver. &ldquo;This gash,&rdquo; he added,
pointing to one of the larger scars, &ldquo;was a wipe
from the hanger of Tom Thurland, whom I apprehended
for the murder of Mrs. Knap. This
wedge of silver,&rdquo; pointing to another, &ldquo;which
would mend a coffee&hyphen;pot, serves to stop up
a breach made by Will Colthurst, who robbed
Mr. Hearl on Hounslow&hyphen;Heath. I secured the
dog after he had wounded me. This fracture
was the handiwork of Jack Parrot (otherwise
called Jack the Grinder), who broke into the palace
of the Bishop of Norwich. Jack was a comical
scoundrel, and made a little too free with his
grace's best burgundy, as well as his grace's
favourite housekeeper. The Bishop, however,
to show him the danger of meddling with the
church, gave him a dance at Tyburn for his
pains. Not a scar but has its history. The
only inconvenience I feel from my shattered</pp>
<pb n="284">
<pp>noddle is an incapacity to drink. But that's
an infirmity shared by a great many sounder
heads than mine. The hardest bout I ever had
was with a woman&mdash;Sally Wells, who was
afterwards lagged for shoplifting. She attacked
me with a carving&hyphen;knife, and, when I had disarmed
her, the jade bit off a couple of fingers
from my left hand. Thus, you see, I've never
hesitated, and never <it>shall</it> hesitate to expose my
life where anything is to be gained. My profession
has hardened me.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>And, with this, he coolly re&hyphen;adjusted his peruke.</p>
<p>&ldquo;What do you expect to gain from this interview,
Mr. Wild?&rdquo; demanded Trenchard, as
if he had formed a sudden resolution.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ah! now we come to business,&rdquo; returned
Jonathan, rubbing his hands, gleefully. &ldquo;These
are my terms, Sir Rowland,&rdquo; he added, taking
a sheet of paper from his pocket, and pushing
it towards the knight.</p>
<p>Trenchard glanced at the document.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;A thousand pounds,&rdquo; he observed, gloomily,
&ldquo;is a heavy price to pay for doubtful</pp>
<pb n="285">
<pp>secrecy, when <it>certain silence</it> might be so
cheaply procured.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;You would purchase it at the price of your
head,&rdquo; replied Jonathan, knitting his brows.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Sir Rowland,&rdquo; he added, savagely, and with
somewhat of the look of a bull&hyphen;dog before he
flies at his foe, &ldquo;if it were my pleasure to do
so, I could crush you with a breath. You are
wholly in my power. Your name, with the
fatal epithet of &lsquo;dangerous&rsquo; attached to it,
stands foremost on the list of Disaffected now
before the Secret Committee. I hold a warrant
from Mr. Walpole for your apprehension.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Arrested!&rdquo; exclaimed Trenchard, drawing
his sword.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Put up your blade, Sir Rowland,&rdquo; rejoined
Jonathan, resuming his former calm demeanour,
&ldquo;King James the Third will need it. I have
no intention of arresting you. I have a different
game to play; and it'll be your own fault,
if you don't come off the winner. I offer you
my assistance on certain terms. The proposal
is so far from being exorbitant, that it should
be trebled if I had not a fellow&hyphen;feeling in the</pp>
<pb n="286">
<pp>cause. To be frank with you, I have an affront
to requite, which can be settled at the
same time, and in the same way with your
affair. That's worth something to me; for
I don't mind paying for revenge. After all
a thousand pounds is a trifle to rid you of
an upstart, who may chance to deprive you
of tens of thousands.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Did I hear you aright?&rdquo; asked Trenchard,
with startling eagerness.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Certainly,&rdquo; replied Jonathan, with the most
perfect <it>sangfroid</it>, &ldquo;I'll undertake to free you
from the boy. That's part of the bargain.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Is he alive?&rdquo; vociferated Trenchard.</p>
<p>&ldquo;To be sure,&rdquo; returned Wild; &ldquo;he's not
only alive, but likely for life, if we don't clip
the thread.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Sir Rowland caught at a chair for support,
and passed his hand across his brow, on which
the damp had gathered thickly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The intelligence seems new to you. I
thought I'd been sufficiently explicit,&rdquo; continued
Jonathan. &ldquo;Most persons would have
guessed my meaning.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="287">
<p>Then it was <it>not</it> a dream!&rdquo; ejaculated Sir
Rowland in a hollow voice, and as if speaking
to himself. &ldquo;I <it>did</it> see them on the platform
of the bridge&mdash;the child and his preserver!
They were <it>not</it> struck by the fallen ruin, nor
whelmed in the roaring flood,&mdash;or, if they <it>were</it>,
they escaped as I escaped. God! I have cheated
myself into a belief that the boy perished!
And now my worst fears are realized&mdash;he
lives!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;As yet,&rdquo; returned Jonathan, with fearful
emphasis.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I cannot&mdash;dare not injure him,&rdquo; rejoined
Trenchard, with a haggard look, and sinking,
as if paralysed, into a chair.</p>
<p>Jonathan laughed scornfully.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Leave him to me,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;He shan't
trouble you further.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;No,&rdquo; replied Sir Rowland, who appeared
completely prostrated. &ldquo;I will struggle no
longer with destiny. Too much blood has been
shed already.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;This comes of fine feelings!&rdquo; muttered
Jonathan, contemptuously. &ldquo;Give me your</pp>
<pb n="288">
<pp>thoroughpaced villain. But I shan't let him
off thus. I'll try a strong dose.&mdash;Am I to understand
that you intend to plead guilty, Sir
Rowland?&rdquo; he added. &ldquo;If so, I may as well
execute my warrant.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Stand off, sir!&rdquo; exclaimed Trenchard, starting
suddenly backwards.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I knew that would bring him to,&rdquo; thought
Wild.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Where is the boy?&rdquo; demanded Sir Rowland.</p>
<p>&ldquo;At present, under the care of his preserver
&mdash;one Owen Wood, a carpenter, by whom he
was brought up.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Wood!&rdquo; exclaimed Trenchard,&mdash;&ldquo;of
Wych Street?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;The same.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;A boy from his shop was here a short time
ago. Could it be him you mean?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;No. That boy was the carpenter's apprentice,
Jack Sheppard. I've just left your nephew.&rdquo;</p>
<p>At this moment Charcam entered the room.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Beg pardon, Sir Rowland,&rdquo; said the attendant;</pp>
<pb n="289">
<pp>&ldquo;but there's a boy from Mr. Wood,
with a message for Lady Trafford.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;From whom?&rdquo; vociferated Trenchard.</p>
<p>&ldquo;From Mr. Wood the carpenter.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;The same who was here just now?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;No, Sir Rowland, a much finer boy.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;'Tis he, by heaven!&rdquo; cried Jonathan; &ldquo;this
is lucky. Sir Rowland,&rdquo; he added, in a deep
whisper, &ldquo;do you agree to my terms?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I do,&rdquo; answered Trenchard, in the same
tone.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Enough!&rdquo; rejoined Wild; &ldquo;he shall not
return.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Have you acquainted him with Lady Trafford's
departure?&rdquo; said the knight, addressing
Charcam, with as much composure as he could
assume.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;No, Sir Rowland,&rdquo; replied the attendant,
&ldquo;as you proposed to ride to Saint Albans tonight,
I thought you might choose to see him
yourself. Besides, there's something odd
about the boy; for, though I questioned him
pretty closely concerning his business, he declined
answering my questions, and said he</pp>
<pb n="290">
<pp>could only deliver his message to her ladyship.
I thought it better not to send him
away till I'd mentioned the circumstance to
you.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;You did right,&rdquo; returned Trenchard.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Where is he?&rdquo; asked Jonathan.</p>
<p>&ldquo;In the hall,&rdquo; replied Charcam.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Alone?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Not exactly sir. There's another lad at
the gate waiting for him&mdash;the same who was
here just now, that Sir Rowland was speaking
of, who fastened up the jewel&hyphen;case for her ladyship.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;A jewel&hyphen;case!&rdquo; exclaimed Jonathan. &ldquo;Ah,
I see it all!&rdquo; he cried, with a quick glance.
&ldquo;Jack Sheppard's fingers are lime&hyphen;twigs. Was
anything missed after the lad's departure, Sir
Rowland?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Not that I'm aware of,&rdquo; said the knight.
&mdash;&ldquo;Stay! something occurs to me.&rdquo; And he
conferred apart with Jonathan.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;That's it!&rdquo; cried Wild when Trenchard
concluded. &ldquo;This young fool is come to restore
the article&mdash;whatever it may be&mdash;which</pp>
<pb n="291">
<pp>Lady Trafford was anxious to conceal, and
which his companion purloined. It's precisely
what such a simpleton would do. We have
him as safe as a linnet in a cage; and could
wring his neck round as easily. Oblige me
by acting under my guidance in the matter,
Sir Rowland. I'm an old hand at such
things. Harkee,&rdquo; he added, &ldquo;Mr. What's&hyphen;your&hyphen;name!&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Charcam,&rdquo; replied the attendant, bowing.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Very well, Mr.Charcoal, you may bring
in the boy. But not a word to him of Lady
Trafford's absence&mdash;mind that. A robbery has
been committed, and your master suspects this
lad as an accessory to the offence. He, therefore,
desires to interrogate him. It will be necessary
to secure his companion; and as you
say he is not in the house, some caution must
be used in approaching him, or he may chance
to take to his heels, for he's a slippery little
rascal. When you've seized him, cough thrice
thus,&mdash;and two rough&hyphen;looking gentlemen will
make their appearance. Don't be alarmed by
their manners, Mr. Charcoal. They're apt to be</pp>
<pb n="292">
<pp>surly to strangers, but it soon wears off. The
gentlemen with the red beard will relieve you
of your prisoner. The other must call a coach
as quickly as he can.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;For whom, sir?&rdquo; inquired Charcam.</p>
<p>&ldquo;For me&mdash;his master, Mr. Jonathan Wild.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Are <it>you</it> Mr. Jonathan Wild?&rdquo; asked the
attendant, in great trepidation.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I <it>am</it>, Charcoal. But don't let my name
frighten you. Though,&rdquo; said the thief&hyphen;taker,
with a complacent smile, &ldquo;all the world seems
to tremble at it. Obey my orders, and you've
nothing to fear. About them quickly. Lead
the lad to suppose that he'll be introduced to
Lady Trafford. You understand me, Charcoal.&rdquo;</p>
<p>The attendant did <it>not</it> understand him. He
was confounded by the presence in which he
found himself. But, not daring to confess his
want to comprehension, he made a profound
reverence, and retired.</p></div4>
<pb n="293">
<div4>
<comhd4><idref>Z400030634</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
CHAPTER IX.
<subhead>CONSEQUENCES OF THE THEFT.</subhead> <attbytes>16Kb</attbytes><reflink>000027</reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z400030634</ID><A1>Ainsworth, William Harrison, 1805&ndash;1882</A1><T1>Jack Sheppard. A Romance.</T1><PBL>Richard Bentley</PBL><Y1>1839</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd4>
<p>&ldquo;<smallcap>How</smallcap> do you mean to act, sir?&rdquo; inquired
Trenchard, as soon as they were left alone.</p>
<p>&ldquo;As circumstances shall dictate, Sir Rowland,&rdquo; 
returned Jonathan. &ldquo;Something is sure
to arise in the course of the investigation, of
which I can take advantage. If not, I'll convey
him to St. Giles's roundhouse on my own
responsibility.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Is this your notable scheme?&rdquo; asked the
knight, scornfully.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Once there,&rdquo; proceeded Wild, without noticing
the interruption, &ldquo;he's as good as in his
grave. The constable, Sharples, is in my pay.
I can remove the prisoner at any hour of the
night I think fit: and I <it>will</it> remove him. You
must know, Sir Rowland&mdash;for I've no secrets</pp>
<pb n="294">
<pp>from you&mdash;that, in the course of my business
I've found it convenient to become the owner
of a small Dutch sloop; by means of which I
can transmit any light ware,&mdash;such as gold
watches, rings, and plate, as well as occasionally
a bank or goldsmith's note, which has been
<it>spoken with</it> by way of the mail,&mdash;you understand
me?&mdash;to Holland or Flanders, and obtain
a secure and ready market for them. This
vessel is now in the river, off Wapping. Her
cargo is nearly shipped. She will sail, at early
dawn to&hyphen;morrow, for Rotterdam. Her commander,
Rykhart Van Galgebrok, is devoted to
my interests. As soon as he gets into blue
water, he'll think no more of pitching the boy
overboard than of lighting his pipe. This will
be safer than cutting his throat on shore. I've
tried the plan, and found it answer. The
Northern Ocean keeps a secret better than the
Thames, Sir Rowland. Before midnight, your
nephew shall be safe beneath the hatches of the
Zeeslang.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Poor child!&rdquo; muttered Trenchard, abstractedly; 
&ldquo;the whole scene upon the river is</pp>
<pb n="295">
<pp>passing before me. I hear the splash in the
water&mdash;I see the white object floating like a
sea&hyphen;bird on the tide&mdash;it will not sink!&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;'Sblood!&rdquo; exclaimed Jonathan, in a tone of
ill&hyphen;disguised contempt; &ldquo;it won't do to indulge
these fancies now. Be seated, and calm yourself.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I have often conjured up some frightful
vision of the dead,&rdquo; murmured the knight,
&ldquo;but I never dreamed of an interview with the
living.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;It'll be over in a few minutes,&rdquo; rejoined
Jonathan, impatiently; in fact, it'll be over
too soon for me. I like such interviews. But
we waste time. Have the goodness to affix
your name to that memorandum, Sir Rowland.
I require nothing, you see, till my share
of the contract is fulfilled.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Trenchard took up a pen.</p>
<p>&ldquo;It's the boy's death&hyphen;warrant,&rdquo; observed
Jonathan, with a sinister smile.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I cannot sign it,&rdquo; returned Trenchard.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Damnation!&rdquo; exclaimed Wild with a snarl,
that displayed his glistening fangs to the farthest</pp>
<pb n="296">
<pp>extremity of his mouth, &ldquo;I'm not to be
trifled with thus. That paper <it>must</it> be signed,
or I take my departure.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Go, sir,&rdquo; rejoined the knight, haughtily.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ay, ay, I'll go, fast enough!&rdquo; returned
Jonathan, putting his hands into his pockets,
&ldquo;but not alone, Sir Rowland.&rdquo;</p>
<p>At this juncture, the door was flung open,
and Charcam entered, dragging in Thames,
whom he held by the collar, and who struggled
in vain to free himself from the grasp imposed
upon him.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Here's one of the thieves, Sir Rowland!&rdquo; 
cried the attendant. &ldquo;I was only just in time.
The young rascal had learnt from some of the
women&hyphen;servants that Lady Trafford was from
home, and was in the very act of making off
when I got down stairs. Come along, my
Newgate bird!&rdquo; he continued, shaking him
with great violence.</p>
<p>Jonathan gave utterance to a low whistle.</p>
<p>&ldquo;If things had gone smoothly,&rdquo; he thought,
&ldquo;I should have cursed the fellow's stupidity.
As it is, I'm not sorry for the blunder.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="297">
<p>Trenchard, meanwhile, whose gaze was fixed
upon the boy, became livid as death, but he
moved not a muscle.</p>
<p>&ldquo;'Tis he!&rdquo; he mentally ejaculated.</p>
<p>&ldquo;What do you think of your nephew, Sir
Rowland?&rdquo; whispered Jonathan, who sat with
his back towards Thames, so that his features
were concealed from the youth's view. It
would be a thousand pities, wouldn't it, to
put so promising a lad out of the way?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Devil!&rdquo; exclaimed the knight fiercely
&ldquo;Give me the paper.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Jonathan hastily picked up the pen, and
presented it to Trenchard, who attached his
signature to the document.</p>
<p>&ldquo;If I <it>am</it> the devil,&rdquo; observed Wild, &ldquo;as
some folks assert, and I myself am not unwilling
to believe, you'll find that I differ from
the generally&hyphen;received notions of the arch&hyphen;fiend,
and faithfully execute the commands of those
who confide their souls to my custody.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Take hence this boy, then,&rdquo; rejoined
Trenchard; &ldquo;his looks unman me.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Of what am I accused?&rdquo; asked Thames</pp>
<pb n="298">
<pp>who though a good deal alarmed at first, had
now regained his courage.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Of robbery!&rdquo; replied Jonathan in a thundering
voice, and suddenly confronting him.
&ldquo;You're charged with assisting your comrade,
Jack Sheppard, to purloin certain articles of
value from a jewel&hyphen;case belonging to Lady
Trafford. Aha!&rdquo; he continued, producing a
short silver staff, which he carried constantly
about with him, and uttering a terrible imprecation,
&ldquo;I see you're confounded. Down on
your marrow&hyphen;bones, sirrah! Confess your
guilt, and Sir Rowland may yet save you from
the gallows.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I've nothing to confess,&rdquo; replied Thames,
boldly; &ldquo;I've done no wrong. Are <it>you</it> my
accuser?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I am,&rdquo; replied Wild; &ldquo;have you anything
to allege to the contrary?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Only this,&rdquo; returned Thames: &ldquo;that the
charge is false, and malicious, and that <it>you</it>
know it to be so.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Is that all?&rdquo; retorted Jonathan. &ldquo;Come,
I must search you, my youngster!&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="299">
<p>&ldquo;You shan't touch me,&rdquo; rejoined Thames; 
and, suddenly bursting from Charcam, he threw
himself at the feet of Trenchard. &ldquo;Hear me,
Sir Rowland!&rdquo; he cried. &ldquo;I am innocent. I
have stolen nothing. This person&mdash;this Jonathan
Wild, whom I beheld for the first time,
scarcely an hour ago, in Wych Street, is&mdash;I
know not why&mdash;my enemy. He has sworn
that he'll take away my life!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Bah!&rdquo; interrupted Jonathan. &ldquo;You won't
listen to this nonsense, Sir Rowland!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;If you <it>are</it> innocent, boy,&rdquo; said the knight,
controlling his emotion; &ldquo;you have nothing to
apprehend. But, what brought you here?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Excuse me, Sir Rowland. I cannot answer
that question. My business is with Lady
Trafford.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Are you aware that I am her ladyship's
brother?&rdquo; returned the knight. &ldquo;She has no
secrets from me.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Possibly not,&rdquo; replied Thames, in some
confusion; &ldquo;but I am not at liberty to speak.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Your hesitation is not in your favour,&rdquo; observed
Trenchard, sternly.</p>
<pb n="300">
<p>&ldquo;Will he consent to be searched?&rdquo; inquired
Jonathan.</p>
<p>&ldquo;No,&rdquo; rejoined Thames, &ldquo;I won't be treated
like a common felon, if I can help it.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You shall be treated according to your
deserts, then,&rdquo; said Jonathan, maliciously.
And, in spite of the boy's resistance, he plunged
his hands into his pockets, and drew forth
the miniature.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Where did you get this from?&rdquo; asked
Wild, greatly surprised at the result of his
investigation.</p>
<p>Thames returned no answer.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I thought as much,&rdquo; continued Jonathan.
&ldquo;But we'll find a way to make you open
your lips presently. Bring in his comrade,&rdquo; 
he added, in a whisper to Charcam; &ldquo;I'll
take care of him. And don't neglect my instructions
this time.&rdquo; Upon which, with an
assurance that he would not do so, the attendant
departed.</p>
<p>&ldquo;You can, of course, identify this picture
as Lady Trafford's property?&rdquo; pursued Jonathan,
with a meaning glance, as he handed it
to the knight.</p>
<pb n="301">
<p>&ldquo;I can,&rdquo; replied Trenchard. &ldquo;Ha!&rdquo; he
exclaimed, with a sudden start, as his glance
fell upon the portrait; &ldquo;how came this into
your possession, boy?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Why don't you answer, sirrah?&rdquo; cried
Wild, in a savage tone, and striking him with
the silver staff. &ldquo;Can't you speak?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I don't choose,&rdquo; replied Thames, sturdily; 
&ldquo;and your brutality shan't make me.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;We'll see that,&rdquo; replied Jonathan, dealing
him another and more violent blow.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Let him alone,&rdquo; said Trenchard authoritatively.
&ldquo;I have another question to propose.
Do you know whose portrait this is?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I do not,&rdquo; replied Thames, repressing his
tears, &ldquo;but I believe it to be the portrait of
my father.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Indeed!&rdquo; exclaimed the knight, in astonishment.
&ldquo;Is your father alive?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;No,&rdquo; returned Thames; &ldquo;he was assassinated
while I was an infant.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Who told you this is his portrait?&rdquo; demanded
Trenchard.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;My heart,&rdquo; rejoined Thames, firmly;</pp>
<pb n="302">
<pp>&ldquo;which now tells me I am in the presence of
his murderer.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;That's me,&rdquo; interposed Jonathan; &ldquo;a
thief&hyphen;taker is always a murderer in the eyes of
a thief. I'm almost sorry your suspicions are
unfounded, if your father in any way resembled
you, my youngster. But I can tell you
who'll have the pleasure of hanging your father's
son; and that's a person not a hundred
miles distant from you at this moment&mdash;ha!
ha!&rdquo;</p>
<p>As he said this, the door was opened,
and Charcam entered, accompanied by a
dwarfish, shabby&hyphen;looking man, in a brown
serge frock, with coarse Jewish features, and
a long red beard. Between the Jew and the
attendant came Jack Sheppard; while a crowd
of servants, attracted by the news, that the
investigation of a robbery was going forward,
lingered at the doorway in hopes of catching
something of the proceedings.</p>
<p><pp>When Jack was brought in, he cast a rapid
glance around him, and perceiving Thames in
the custody of Jonathan, instantly divined how</pp>
<pb n="303">
<pp>matters stood. As he looked in this direction,
Wild gave him a significant wink, the meaning
of which he was not slow to comprehend.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Get it over quickly,&rdquo; said Trenchard, in a
whisper to the thief&hyphen;taker.</p>
<p>Jonathan nodded assent.</p>
<p>&ldquo;What's your name?&rdquo; he said, addressing
the audacious lad, who was looking about
him as coolly as if nothing material was
going on.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Jack Sheppard,&rdquo; returned the boy, fixing
his eyes upon a portrait of the Earl of Mar.
&ldquo;Who's that queer cove in the full&hyphen;bottomed
wig?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Attend to me, sirrah,&rdquo; rejoined Wild,
sternly. &ldquo;Do you know this picture?&rdquo; he
added, with another significant look, and pointing
to the miniature.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I do,&rdquo; replied Jack, carelessly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;That's well. Can you inform us whence
it came?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I should think so.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;State the facts, then.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;It came from Lady Trafford's jewel&hyphen;box.'</p>
<pb n="304">
<p>Here a murmur of amazement arose from
the assemblage outside.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Close the door!&rdquo; commanded Trenchard,
impatiently.</p>
<p>&ldquo;In my opinion, Sir Rowland,&rdquo; suggested
Jonathan; &ldquo;you'd better allow the court to
remain open.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Be it so,&rdquo; replied the knight, who saw the
force of this reasoning. &ldquo;Continue the proceedings.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You say that the miniature was abstracted
from Lady Trafford's jewel&hyphen;box,&rdquo; said Jonathan,
in a loud voice. &ldquo;Who took it thence?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Thames Darrell; the boy at your side.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Jack!&rdquo; cried Thames, in indignant surprise.</p>
<p>But Sheppard took no notice of the exclamation.</p>
<p>A loud buzz of curiosity circulated among
the domestics; some of whom&mdash;especially the
females&mdash;leaned forward to obtain a peep at
the culprit.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Si&mdash;lence!&rdquo; vociferated Charcam, laying
great emphasis on the last syllable.</p>
<pb>
<edit>[Figure: <bytes>388Kb</bytes>]</edit><figure sys.id="N010111">
<pb n="305">
<p>&ldquo;Were you present at the time of the robbery?&rdquo; 
pursued Jonathan.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I was,&rdquo; answered Sheppard.</p>
<p>&ldquo;And will swear to it?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I will.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Liar!&rdquo; ejaculated Thames.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Enough!&rdquo; exclaimed Wild, triumphantly.
&ldquo;Close the court, Mr. Charcoal. They've
heard quite enough for my purpose,&rdquo; he muttered,
as his orders were obeyed, and the domestics
excluded. &ldquo;It's too late to carry
'em before a magistrate now, Sir Rowland; 
so, with your permission, I'll give 'em a
night's lodging in Saint Giles's roundhouse.
You, Jack Sheppard, have nothing to fear,
as you've become evidence against your accomplice.
To&hyphen;morrow, I shall carry you before
Justice Walters, who'll take your information; 
and I've no doubt but Thames Darrell
will be fully committed. Now, for the
cage, my pretty canary&hyphen;bird. Before we start,
I'll accommodate you with a pair of ruffles.&rdquo; 
And he proceeded to handcuff his captive.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Hear me!&rdquo; cried Thames, bursting into</pp>
<pb n="306">
<pp>tears. &ldquo;I am innocent. I could not have
committed this robbery. I have only just left
Wych Street. Send for Mr. Wood, and you'll
find that I've spoken the truth.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;You'd better hold your peace, my lad,&rdquo; 
observed Jonathan, in a menacing tone.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Lady Trafford would not have thus condemned
me!&rdquo; cried Thames.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Away with him!&rdquo; exclaimed Sir Rowland,
impatiently.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Take the prisoners below, Nab,&rdquo; said Jonathan,
addressing the dwarfish Jew; &ldquo;I'll
join you in an instant.&rdquo;</p>
<p>The bearded miscreant seized Jack by the
waist, and Thames by the nape of the neck,
and marched off, like the ogre in the fairy
tale, with a boy under each arm, while Charcam
brought up the rear.</p></div4>
<pb n="307">
<div4>
<comhd4><idref>Z400030635</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
CHAPTER X.
<subhead>MOTHER AND SON.</subhead> <attbytes>13Kb</attbytes><reflink>000027</reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z400030635</ID><A1>Ainsworth, William Harrison, 1805&ndash;1882</A1><T1>Jack Sheppard. A Romance.</T1><PBL>Richard Bentley</PBL><Y1>1839</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd4>
<p><smallcap>They</smallcap> had scarcely been gone a moment,
when a confused noise was heard without,
and Charcam re&hyphen;entered the room, with a
countenance of the utmost bewilderment and
alarm.</p>
<p>&ldquo;What's the matter with the man?&rdquo; demanded
Wild.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Her ladyship&wblank;&rdquo; faltered the attendant.</p>
<p>&ldquo;What of her?&rdquo; cried the knight. &ldquo;Is she
returned?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Y&mdash;e&mdash;s, Sir Rowland,&rdquo; stammered Charcam.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The devil!&rdquo; ejaculated Jonathan. &ldquo;Here's
a cross&hyphen;bite.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;But that's not all, your honour,&rdquo; continued
Charcam; &ldquo;Mrs. Norris says she's dying.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="308">
<p>&ldquo;Dying!&rdquo; echoed the knight.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Dying, Sir Rowland. She was taken dreadfully
ill on the road, with spasms and short
breath, and swoonings,&mdash;worse than ever she
was before. And Mrs. Norris was so frightened
that she ordered the postboys to drive back as
fast as they could. She never expected to get
her ladyship home alive.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;My God!&rdquo; cried Trenchard, stunned by
the intelligence, &ldquo;I have killed her.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;No doubt,&rdquo; rejoined Wild, with a sneer; 
&ldquo;but don't let all the world know it.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;They're lifting her out of the carriage,&rdquo; 
interposed Charcam; &ldquo;will it please your
honour to send for some advice and the chaplain?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Fly for both,&rdquo; returned Sir Rowland, in a
tone of bitter anguish.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Stay!&rdquo; interposed Jonathan. &ldquo;Where are
the boys?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;In the hall.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Her ladyship will pass through it?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Of course; there's no other way.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Then, bring them into this room, the first</pp>
<pb n="309">
<pp>thing&mdash;quick! They must not meet, Sir Rowland,&rdquo; 
he added, as Charcam hastened to obey
his instructions.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Heaven has decreed it otherwise,&rdquo; replied
the knight, dejectedly. &ldquo;I yield to fate.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Yield to nothing,&rdquo; returned Wild, trying
to re&hyphen;assure him; &ldquo;above all, when your designs
prosper. Man's fate is in his own hands.
You are your nephew's executioner, or he is
yours. Cast off this weakness. The next hour
makes, or mars you for ever. Go to your sister,
and do not quit her till all is over. Leave the
rest to me.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Sir Rowland moved irresolutely towards the
door, but recoiled before a sad spectacle. This
was his sister, evidently in the last extremity.
Borne in the arms of a couple of assistants, and
preceded by Mrs. Norris, wringing her hands
and weeping, the unfortunate lady was placed
upon a couch. At the same time, Charcam,
who seemed perfectly distracted by the recent
occurrences, dragged in Thames, leaving Jack
Sheppard outside in the custody of the dwarfish
Jew.</p>
<pb n="310">
<p>&ldquo;Hell's curses!&rdquo; muttered Jonathan between
his teeth; &ldquo;that fool will ruin all. Take him
away,&rdquo; he added, striding up to Charcam.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Let him remain,&rdquo; interposed Trenchard.</p>
<p>&ldquo;As you please, Sir Rowland,&rdquo; returned
Jonathan, with affected indifference; &ldquo;but I'm
not going to hunt the deer for another to eat
the ven'son, depend on't.&rdquo;</p>
<p>But seeing that no notice was taken of the
retort, he drew a little aside, and folded his
arms, muttering, &ldquo;The whim will soon be over.
She can't last long. I can pull the strings of
this stiff&hyphen;necked puppet as I please.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Sir Rowland, meantime, threw himself on
his knees beside his sister, and, clasping her
chilly fingers within his own, besought her forgiveness
in the most passionate terms. For a
few minutes, she appeared scarcely sensible of
his presence. But, after some restoratives had
been administered by Mrs. Norris, she revived
a little.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Rowland,&rdquo; she said, in a faint voice, &ldquo;I
have not many minutes to live. Where is
Father Spencer? I must have absolution. I</pp>
<pb n="311">
<pp>have something that weighs heavily upon my
mind.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>Sir Rowland's brow darkened.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I have sent for him, Aliva,&rdquo; he answered; 
&ldquo;he will be here directly, with your medical
advisers.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;They are useless,&rdquo; she returned. &ldquo;Medicine
cannot save me now.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Dear sister&mdash;&rdquo; 
<lb>&ldquo;I should die happy, if I could behold my
child.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Comfort yourself, then, Aliva. You <it>shall</it>
behold him.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You are mocking me, Rowland. Jests are
not for seasons like this.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I am not, by heaven,&rdquo; returned the knight,
solemnly. &ldquo;Leave us, Mrs. Norris, and do not
return till Father Spencer arrives.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Your ladyship&mdash;&rdquo; hesitated Norris.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Go!&rdquo; said Lady Trafford; &ldquo;it is my last
request.&rdquo;</p>
<p>And her faithful attendant, drowned in tears,
withdrew, followed by the two assistants.</p>
<p>Jonathan stepped behind a curtain.</p>
<pb n="312">
<p>&ldquo;Rowland,&rdquo; said Lady Trafford, regarding
him with a look of indescribable anxiety, &ldquo;you
have assured me that I shall behold my son.
Where is he?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Within this room,&rdquo; replied the knight.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Here!&rdquo; shrieked Lady Trafford.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Here,&rdquo; repeated her brother. &ldquo;But calm
yourself, dear sister, or the interview will be too
much for you.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I <it>am</it> calm&mdash;quite calm, Rowland,&rdquo; she answered,
with lips whose agitation belied her
words. &ldquo;Then, the story of his death was
false. I knew it. I was sure you could not
have the heart to slay a child&mdash;an innocent
child. God forgive you!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;May He, indeed, forgive me!&rdquo; returned
Trenchard, crossing himself devoutly; &ldquo;but
my guilt is not the less heavy, because your
child escaped. This hand consigned him to
destruction, but another was stretched forth to
save him. The infant was rescued from a
watery&hyphen;grave by an honest mechanic, who has
since brought him up as his own son.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Blessings upon him!&rdquo; cried Lady Trafford,</pp>
<pb n="313">
<pp>fervently. &ldquo;But trifle with me no
longer. Moments are ages now. Let me see
my child, if he is really here?&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Behold him!&rdquo; returned Trenchard, taking
Thames (who had been a mute, but deeply&hyphen;interested,
witness of the scene) by the hand,
and leading him towards her.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ah!&rdquo; exclaimed Lady Trafford, exerting
all her strength. &ldquo;My sight is failing me.
Let me have more light, that I may behold
him. Yes!&rdquo; she screamed, &ldquo;these are his
father's features! It is&mdash;it is my son!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Mother!&rdquo; cried Thames; &ldquo;are you, indeed,
my mother?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I am, indeed&mdash;my own sweet boy!&rdquo; she
sobbed, pressing him tenderly to her breast.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Oh!&mdash;to see you thus!&rdquo; cried Thames, in
an agony of affliction.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Don't weep, my love,&rdquo; replied the lady,
straining him still more closely to her. &ldquo;I am
happy&mdash;quite happy now.&rdquo;</p>
<p>During this touching interview, a change
had come over Sir Rowland, and he half repented
of what he had done.</p>
<pb n="314">
<p>&ldquo;You can no longer refuse to tell me the
name of this youth's father, Aliva,&rdquo; he said.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I dare not, Rowland,&rdquo; she answered. &ldquo;I
cannot break my vow. I will confide it to
Father Spencer, who will acquaint you with it
when I am no more. Undraw the curtain,
love,&rdquo; she added to Thames, &ldquo;that I may look
at you.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ha!&rdquo; exclaimed her son, starting back, as
he obeyed her, and disclosed Jonathan Wild.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Be silent,&rdquo; said Jonathan, in a menacing
whisper.</p>
<p>&ldquo;What have you seen?&rdquo; inquired Lady
Trafford.</p>
<p>&ldquo;My enemy,&rdquo; replied her son.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Your enemy!&rdquo; she returned, imperfectly
comprehending him. &ldquo;Sir Rowland is your
uncle&mdash;he will be your guardian&mdash;he will
protect you. Will you not, brother?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Promise,&rdquo; said a deep voice in Trenchard's
ear.</p>
<p>&ldquo;He will kill me,&rdquo; cried Thames. &ldquo;There
is a man in this room who seeks my life.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Impossible!&rdquo; rejoined his mother.</p>
<pb n="315">
<p>&ldquo;Look at these fetters,&rdquo; returned Thames,
holding up his manacled wrists; &ldquo;they were
put on by my uncle's command.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ah!&rdquo; shrieked Lady Trafford.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Not a moment is to be lost,&rdquo; whispered
Jonathan to Trenchard. &ldquo;His life&mdash;or yours?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;No one shall harm you more, my dear,&rdquo; 
cried Lady Trafford. &ldquo;Your uncle <it>must</it> protect
you. It will be his interest to do so. He
will be dependent on you.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Do what you please with him,&rdquo; muttered
Trenchard to Wild.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Take off these chains, Rowland,&rdquo; said Lady
Trafford, &ldquo;instantly,&mdash;I command you.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;<it>I</it> will,&rdquo; replied Jonathan, advancing, and
rudely seizing Thames.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Mother!&rdquo; cried the son, &ldquo;help!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;What is this?&rdquo; shrieked Lady Trafford,
raising herself on the couch, and extending
her hands towards him. &ldquo;Oh, God! would
you take him from me?&mdash;would you murder
him?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;His father's name?&mdash;and he is free,&rdquo; rejoined
Rowland, holding her arms.</p>
<pb n="316">
<p>&ldquo;Release him first&mdash;and I will disclose it!&rdquo; 
cried Lady Trafford; &ldquo;on my soul, I will!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Speak then!&rdquo; returned Rowland.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Too late!&rdquo; shrieked the lady, falling heavily
backwards,&mdash;&ldquo;too late!&mdash;oh!&rdquo;</p>
<p>Heedless of her cries, Jonathan passed a
handkerchief tightly over her son's mouth, and
forced him out of the room.</p>
<p>When he returned, a moment or so afterwards,
he found Sir Rowland standing by the
lifeless body of his sister. His countenance
was almost as white and rigid as that of the
corpse by his side.</p>
<p>&ldquo;This is your work,&rdquo; said the knight,
sternly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Not entirely,&rdquo; replied Jonathan, calmly; 
&ldquo;though I shouldn't be ashamed of it if it
were. After all, you failed in obtaining the secret
from her, Sir Rowland. Women are hypocrites
to the last&mdash;true only to themselves.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Peace!&rdquo; cried the knight, fiercely.</p>
<p>&ldquo;No offence,&rdquo; returned Jonathan. &ldquo;I was
merely about to observe that <it>I</it> am in possession
of her secret.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="317">
<p>&ldquo;You!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Didn't I tell you that the fugitive Darrell
gave me a glove? But we'll speak of this
hereafter. You can <it>purchase</it> the information
from me whenever you're so disposed. I
shan't drive a hard bargain. To the point,
however. I came back to say, that I've placed
your nephew in a coach; and, if you'll be at
my lock in the Old Bailey an hour after midnight,
you shall hear the last tidings of him.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I will be there,&rdquo; answered Trenchard,
gloomily.</p>
<p>&ldquo;You'll not forget the thousand, Sir Rowland
&mdash;short accounts, you know.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Fear nothing. You shall have your reward.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Thank'ee,&mdash;thank'ee. My house is the
next door to the Cooper's Arms, in the Old
Bailey, opposite Newgate. You'll find me at
supper.&rdquo;</p>
<p>So saying, he bowed and departed.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;That man should have been an Italian
bravo,&rdquo; murmured the knight, sinking into a
chair: &ldquo;he has neither fear nor compunction.</pp>
<pb n="318">
<pp>Would I could purchase his apathy as easily as
I can procure his assistance.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>Soon after this Mrs. Norris entered the
room, followed by Father Spencer. On approaching
the couch, they found Sir Rowland
senseless, and extended over the dead body of
his unfortunate sister.</p></div4>
<pb n="319">
<div4>
<comhd4><idref>Z400030636</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
CHAPTER XI.
<subhead>THE MOHOCKS.</subhead> <attbytes>18Kb</attbytes><reflink>000027</reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z400030636</ID><A1>Ainsworth, William Harrison, 1805&ndash;1882</A1><T1>Jack Sheppard. A Romance.</T1><PBL>Richard Bentley</PBL><Y1>1839</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd4>
<p><pp><smallcap>Jonathan Wild</smallcap>, meanwhile, had quitted the
house. He found a coach at the door, with the
blinds carefully drawn up, and ascertained from
a tall, ill&hyphen;looking, though tawdrily&hyphen;dressed fellow,
who held his horse by the bridle, and
whom he addressed as Quilt Arnold, that the
two boys were safe inside, in the custody of
Abraham Mendez, the dwarfish Jew. As soon
as he had delivered his instructions to Quilt,
who, with Abraham, constituted his bodyguard,
or janizaries, as he termed them, Jonathan
mounted his steed, and rode off at a gallop.
Quilt was not long in following his example.
Springing upon the box, he told the coachman
to make the best of his way to Saint Giles's.
Stimulated by the promise of something handsome</pp>
<pb n="320">
<pp>to drink, the man acquitted himself to admiration
in the management of his lazy cattle.
Crack went the whip, and away floundered the
heavy vehicle through the deep ruts of the
ill&hyphen;kept road, or rather lane, (for it was little
better,) which, then, led across Southampton
Fields. Skirting the noble gardens of Montague
House, (now, we need scarcely say, the
British Museum,) the party speedily reached
Great Russell Sreet,&mdash;a quarter described by
Strype, in his edition of old Stow's famous <it>Survey</it>,
&ldquo;as being graced with the best buildings
in all Bloomsbury, and the best inhabited by the
nobility and gentry, especially the north side,
as having gardens behind the houses, and the
prospect of the pleasant fields up to Hampstead
and Highgate; insomuch that this place,
by physicians, is esteemed the most healthful
of any in London.&rdquo; Neither of the parties
outside bestowed much attention upon these
stately and salubriously&hyphen;situated mansions; indeed,
as it was now not far from ten o'clock,
and quite dark, they could scarcely discern
them. But, in spite of his general insensibility</pp>
<pb n="321">
<pp>to such matters, Quilt could not help commenting
upon the delicious perfume wafted
from the numerous flower&hyphen;beds past which
they were driving. The coachman answered
by a surly grunt, and, plying his whip with
redoubled zeal, shaped his course down Dyot
Street; traversed that part of Holborn, which
is now called Broad Street, and where two ancient
alms&hyphen;houses were, then, standing in the
middle of that great thoroughfare, exactly opposite
the opening of Compton Street; and,
diving under a wide gateway on the left, soon
reached a more open space, surrounded by
mean habitations, coach&hyphen;houses and stables,
called Kendrick Yard, at the further end of
which Saint Giles's roundhouse was situated.</pp></p>
<p><pp>No sooner did the vehicle turn the corner of
this yard, than Quilt became aware, from the
tumultuous sounds that reached his ears, as
well as from the flashing of various lanterns at
the door of the roundhouse, that some disturbance
was going on; and, apprehensive of a
rescue, if he drew up in the midst of the mob,
he thought it prudent to come to a halt. Accordingly,</pp>
<pb n="322">
<pp>he stopped the coach, dismounted,
and hastened towards the assemblage, which,
he was glad to find, consisted chiefly of a posse
of watchmen and other guardians of the night.
Quilt, who was an ardent lover of mischief,
could not help laughing most heartily at the
rueful appearance of these personages. Not
one of them but bore the marks of having
been engaged in a recent and severe conflict.
Quarter&hyphen;staves, bludgeons, brown&hyphen;bills, lanterns,
swords, and sconces were alike shivered; 
and, to judge from the sullied state of their
habiliments, the claret must have been tapped
pretty freely. Never was heard such a bawling
as these unfortunate wights kept up. Oaths
exploded like shells from a battery in full fire,
accompanied by threats of direst vengeance
against the individuals who had maltreated
them. Here, might be seen a poor fellow
whose teeth were knocked down his throat,
spluttering out the most tremendous menaces,
and gesticulating like a madman: there, another,
whose nose was partially slit, vented imprecations
and lamentations in the same breath.</pp>
<pb n="323">
<pp>On the right, stood a bulky figure, with a
broken rattle hanging out of his great&hyphen;coat
pocket, who held up a lantern to his battered
countenance to prove to the spectators that
both his orbs of vision were darkened: on the
left, a meagre constable had divested himself of
his shirt, to bind up with greater convenience a
gaping cut in the arm.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;So, the Mohocks have been at work, I perceive,&rdquo; 
remarked Quilt, as he drew near the
group.</p>
<p>&ldquo;'Faith, an' you may say that,&rdquo; returned a
watchman, who was wiping a ruddy stream
from his brow; &ldquo;they've broken the paice,
and our pates into the bargain. But shure<it>ly</it>
I'd know that vice,&rdquo; he added, turning his lantern
towards the janizary. &ldquo;Ah! Quilt Arnold,
my man, is it you? By the powers! I'm
glad to see you. The sight o' your 'andsome
phiz allys does me good.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I wish I could return the compliment,
Terry. But your cracked skull is by no means
a pleasing spectacle. How came you by the
hurt, eh?&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="324">
<p>&ldquo;How did I come by it?&mdash;that's a nate
question. Why, honestly enough. It was lent
me by a countryman o' mine; but I paid him
back in his own coin&mdash;ha! ha!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;A countryman of yours, Terry?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ay, and a noble one, too, Quilt&mdash;more's
the pity! You've heard of the Marquis of
Slaughterford, belike?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Of course; who has not? He's the leader
of the Mohocks, the general of the Scourers,
the prince of rakes, the friend of the surgeons
and glaziers, the terror of your tribe, and the
idol of the girls!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;That's him to a hair!&rdquo; cried Terence,
rapturously. &ldquo;Och! he's a broth of a boy!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Why, I thought he'd broken your head,
Terry?&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Phooh! that's nothing'! A piece o' plaster'll
set all to rights; and Terry O'Flaherty
's not the boy to care for the stroke of a
supple&hyphen;jack. Besides, didn't I tell you that
I giv'him as good as he brought&mdash;and better!
I jist touched him with my &lsquo;Evenin&rsquo; Star,&rsquo; 
as I call this shillelah,&rdquo; said the watchman,</pp>
<pb n="325">
<pp>flourishing an immense bludgeon, the knob
of which appeared to be loaded with lead,
&ldquo;and, by Saint Patrick! down he cum'd like
a bullock.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Zounds!&rdquo; exclaimed Quilt, &ldquo;did you kill
him?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Not quite,&rdquo; replied Terence, laughing; 
&ldquo;but I brought him to his senses.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;By depriving him of 'em, eh? But I'm
sorry you hurt his lordship, Terry. Young
noblemen ought to be indulged in their frolics.
If they <it>do</it>, now and then, run away with a
knocker, paint a sign, beat the watch, or huff a
magistrate, they <it>pay</it> for their pastime, and
that's sufficient. What more could any reasonable
man&mdash;especially a watchman&mdash;desire?
Besides, the Marquis, is a devilish fine fellow,
and a particular friend of mine. There's not
his peer among the peerage.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Och! if he's a friend o' yours, my dear
joy, there's no more to be said; and right
sorry am I, I struck him. But, blood&hyphen;an'&hyphen;'ouns!
man,&hyphen;if ould Nick himself were to hit
me a blow, I'd be afther givin'him another.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="326">
<p>&ldquo;Well, well&mdash;wait a while,&rdquo; returned Quilt; 
&ldquo;his lordship won't forget you. He's as
generous as he's frolicsome.&rdquo;</p>
<p>As he spoke, the door of the roundhouse
was opened, and a stout man, with a lantern
in his hand, presented himself at the threshold.</p>
<p>&ldquo;There's Sharples,&rdquo; cried Quilt.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Whist!&rdquo; exclaimed Terence; &ldquo;he elevates
his glim. By Jasus! he's about to spake
to us.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Gem'men o' the votch!&rdquo; cried Sharples,
as loudly as a wheezy cough would permit
him, &ldquo;my noble pris'ner&mdash;ough! ough;&mdash;the
Markis o' Slaughterford&mdash;&rdquo; 
<lb>Further speech was cut short by a volley
of execrations from the angry guardians of
the night.</p>
<p>&ldquo;No Mohocks! No Scourers!&rdquo; cried the
mob.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Hear! hear!&rdquo; vociferated Quilt.</p>
<p>&ldquo;His lordship desires me to say&mdash;ough!
ough!&rdquo;</p>
<p>Fresh groans and hisses.</p>
<pb n="327">
<p>&ldquo;Von't you hear me?&mdash;ough! ough!&rdquo; demanded
Sharples, after a pause.</p>
<p>&ldquo;By all means,&rdquo; rejoined Quilt.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Raise your vice, and lave off coughin',&rdquo; 
added Terence.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The long and the short o' the matter's
this then,&rdquo; returned Sharples with dignity,
&ldquo;the Markis begs your acceptance o' ten guineas
to drink his health.</p>
<p>The hooting was instantaneously changed to
cheers.</p>
<p>&ldquo;And his lordship, furthermore, requests
me to state,&rdquo; proceeded Sharples, in a hoarse
tone, &ldquo;that he'll be responsible for the doctors'
bills of all such gem'men as have received
broken pates, or been other<it>wise</it> damaged in the
fray&mdash;ough! ough!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Hurrah!&rdquo; shouted the mob.</p>
<p>&ldquo;We're all damaged&mdash;we've all got broken
pates,&rdquo; cried a dozen voices.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ay, good luck to him! so we have,&rdquo; rejoined
Terence; &ldquo;but we've no objection to
take out the dochter's bill in drink.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;None whatever,&rdquo; replied the mob.</p>
<pb n="328">
<p>&ldquo;Your answer, gem'men?&rdquo; demanded Sharples.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Long life to the Markis, and we accept his
honourable proposal,&rdquo; responded the mob.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Long life to the Marquis!&rdquo; reiterated
Terence; &ldquo;he's an honour to ould Ireland!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Didn't I tell you how it would be?&rdquo; remarked
Quilt.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Troth, and so did you,&rdquo; returned the watchman; 
&ldquo;but I couldn't belave it. In futur', I'll
keep the &lsquo;Evenin&rsquo; Star&rsquo; for his lordship's
enemies.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You'd better,&rdquo; replied Quilt. &ldquo;But bring
your glim this way. I've a couple of kinchens
in yonder rattler, whom I wish to place under
old Sharple's care.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Be handy, then,&rdquo; rejoined Terence, &ldquo;or
I'll lose my share of the smart money.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>With the assistance of Terence, and a link&hyphen;boy
who volunteered his services, Quilt soon
removed the prisoners from the coach, and
leaving Sheppard to the custody of Abraham,
proceeded to drag Thames towards the roundhouse.</pp>
<pb n="329">
<pp>Not a word had been exchanged between
the two boys on the road. Whenever
Jack attempted to speak, he was checked by
an angry growl from Abraham; and Thames,
though his heart was full almost to bursting,
felt no inclination to break the silence. His
thoughts, indeed, were too painful for utterance,
and so acute were his feelings, that, for
some time, they quite overcame him. But his
grief was of short duration. The elastic spirits
of youth resumed their sway; and, before the
coach stopped, his tears had ceased to flow. As
to Jack Sheppard, he appeared utterly reckless
and insensible, and did nothing but whistle and
sing the whole way.</pp></p>
<p><pp>While he was dragged along in the manner
just described, Thames looked around to ascertain,
if possible, where he was; for he did not
put entire faith in Jonathan's threat of sending
him to the roundhouse, and was apprehensive
of something even worse than imprisonment.
The aspect of the place, so far as he could
discern through the gloom, was strange to
him; but chancing to raise his eyes above</pp>
<pb n="330">
<pp>the level of the surrounding habitations, he
beheld, relieved against the sombre sky, the
tall steeple of Saint Giles's church, the precursor
of the present structure, which was not
erected till some fifteen years later. He recognised
this object at once. Jonathan had
not deceived him.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;What's this here kinchen <it>in</it> for?&rdquo; asked
Terence, as he and Quilt strode along, with
Thames between them.</p>
<p>&ldquo;What for?&rdquo; rejoined Quilt, evasively.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Oh! nothin' partickler&mdash;mere curossity,&rdquo; 
replied Terence. &ldquo;By the powers!&rdquo; he added,
turning his lantern full upon the face of the
captive, &ldquo;he's a nice gennteel&hyphen;lookin' kiddy,
I must say. Pity he's ta'en to bad ways so
airly.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You may spare me your compassion,
friend,&rdquo; observed Thames; &ldquo;I am falsely detained.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Of course,&rdquo; rejoined Quilt, maliciously; 
&ldquo;every thief is so. If we were to wait till a
prig was rightfully nabbed, we might tarry
till doomsday. We never supposed you helped</pp>
<pb n="331">
<pp>yourself to a picture set with diamonds&mdash; 
&mdash;not we!&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Is the guv'ner consarned in this job?&rdquo; 
asked Terence, in a whisper.</p>
<p>&ldquo;He is,&rdquo; returned Quilt, significantly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Zounds! what's that!&rdquo; he cried, as the
noise of a scuffle was heard behind them.
&ldquo;The other kid's given my partner the slip.
Here, take this youngster, Terry; my legs
are lighter than old Nab's.&rdquo; And, committing
Thames to the care of the watchman, he darted
after the fugitive.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Do you wish to earn a rich reward, my
good friend?&rdquo; said Thames to the watchman,
as soon as they were left alone.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Is it by lettin' you go, my darlin', that
I'm to airn it?&rdquo; inquired Terence. &ldquo;If so,
it won't pay. You're Misther Wild's pris'ner,
and worse luck to it!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I don't ask you to liberate me,&rdquo; urged
Thames; &ldquo;but will you convey a message for
me?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Where to, honey?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;To Mr. Wood's, the carpenter in Wych
Street. He lives near the Black Lion.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="332">
<p>&ldquo;The Black Lion!&rdquo; echoed Terence. &ldquo;I
know the house well; by the same token that
it's a flash crib. Och! many a mug o'bubb
have I drained wi' the landlord, Joe Hind.
And so Misther Wudd lives near the Black
Lion, eh?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;He does,&rdquo; replied Thames. &ldquo;Tell him
that I&mdash;his adopted son, Thames Darrell&mdash; 
am detained here by Jonathan Wild.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Thames Ditton&mdash;is that your name?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;No,&rdquo; replied the boy, impatiently; &ldquo;Darrell
&mdash;Thames Darrell.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I'll not forget it. It's a mighty quare'un,
though. I never yet heard of a Christian as
was named after the Shannon or the Liffy; 
and the Thames is no better than a dhurty
puddle, compared wi' them two noble strames.
But then you're an adopted son, and that
makes all the difference. People do call their
unlawful children strange names. Are you
quite shure you haven't another alyas, Masther
Thames Ditton?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Darrell, I tell you. Will you go? You'll
be paid handsomely for your trouble.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="333">
<p>&ldquo;I don't mind the throuble,&rdquo; hesitated Terence,
who was really a good&hyphen;hearted fellow at
the bottom; &ldquo;and I'd like to sarve you if I
could, for you look like a gentleman's son, and
that goes a great way wi' me. But if Misther
Wild were to find out that I thwarted his
schames&mdash;&rdquo; 
<lb>&ldquo;I'd not be in your skin for a trifle,&rdquo; interrupted
Quilt, who having secured Sheppard,
and delivered him to Abraham, now approached
them unawares; &ldquo;and it shan't be my fault
if he don't hear of it.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;'Ouns!&rdquo; ejaculated Terence, in alarm,
&ldquo;would you turn snitch on your old pal,
Quilt?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ay, if he plays a&hyphen;cross,&rdquo; returned Quilt.
&ldquo;Come along, my sly shaver. With all your
cunning, we're more than a match for you.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;But not for me,&rdquo; growled Terence, in an
under tone.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Remember!&rdquo; cried Quilt, as he forced the
captive along.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Remember the devil!&rdquo; retorted Terence,
who had recovered his natural audacity. &ldquo;Do</pp>
<pb n="334">
<pp>you think I'm afeard of a beggarly thief&hyphen;taker
and his myrmidons? Not I. Masther Thames
Ditton, I'll do your biddin'; and you, Misther
Quilt Arnold, may do your worst, I defy
you.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Dog!&rdquo; exclaimed Quilt, turning fiercely
upon him, &ldquo;do you threaten?&rdquo;</p>
<p>But the watchman eluded his grasp, and,
mingling with the crowd, disappeared.</p></div4>
<pb n="335">
<div4>
<comhd4><idref>Z400030637</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
CHAPTER XII.
<subhead>SAINT GILES'S ROUNDHOUSE.</subhead> <attbytes>22Kb</attbytes><reflink>000027</reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z400030637</ID><A1>Ainsworth, William Harrison, 1805&ndash;1882</A1><T1>Jack Sheppard. A Romance.</T1><PBL>Richard Bentley</PBL><Y1>1839</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd4>
<p><pp><smallcap>Saint Giles's Roundhouse</smallcap> was an old detached
fabric, standing in an angle of Kendrick
Yard. Originally built, as its name
imports, in a cylindrical form, like a modern
Martello tower, it had undergone, from time to
time, so many alterations, that its symmetry
was, in a great measure, destroyed. Bulging
out more in the middle than at the two extremities,
it resembled an enormous cask set on
its end,&mdash;a sort of Heidelberg tun on a large
scale,&mdash;and this resemblance was increased by
the small circular aperture&mdash;it hardly deserved
to be called a door&mdash;pierced, like the
bung&hyphen;hole of a barrel, through the side of the
structure, at some distance from the ground,
and approached by a flight of wooden steps.
The prison was two stories high, with a flat</pp>
<pb n="336">
<pp>roof, surmounted by a gilt vane fashioned like
a key; and, possessing considerable internal
accommodation, it had, in its day, lodged some
thousands of disorderly personages. The windows
were small, and strongly grated, looking,
in front, on Kendrick Yard, and, at the back,
upon the spacious burial&hyphen;ground of Saint
Giles's Church. Lights gleamed from the lower
rooms, and, on a nearer approach to the building,
the sound of revelry might be heard from
within.</pp></p>
<p><pp>Warned of the approach of the prisoners by
the increased clamour, Sharples, who was busied
in distributing the Marquis's donation,
affected to throw the remainder of the money
among the crowd, though, in reality, he kept
back a couple of guineas, which he slipped into
his sleeve, and running hastily up the steps,
unlocked the door. He was followed, more
leisurely, by the prisoners; and, during their
ascent, Jack Sheppard made a second attempt
to escape by ducking suddenly down, and endeavouring
to pass under his conductor's legs.
The dress of the dwarfish Jew was not, however,</pp>
<pb n="337">
<pp>favourable to this expedient. Jack was
caught, as in a trap, by the pendant tails of
Abraham's long frock; and, instead of obtaining
his release by his ingenuity, he only got a
sound thrashing.</pp></p>
<p>Sharples received them at the threshold, and
holding his lantern towards the prisoners to acquaint
himself with their features, nodded to
Quilt, between whom and himself some secret
understanding seemed to subsist, and then
closed and barred the door.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Vell,&rdquo; he growled, addressing Quilt, &ldquo;you
know who's here, I suppose?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;To be sure I do,&rdquo; replied Quilt; &ldquo;my
noble friend, the Marquis of Slaughterford.
What of that?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Vot'o that!&rdquo; echoed Sharples, peevishly:
&ldquo;Everythin'. Vot am I to do vith these young
imps, eh?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;What you generally do with your prisoners,
Mr. Sharples,&rdquo; replied Quilt; &ldquo;lock 'em
up.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;That's easily said. But, suppose I've no
place to lock 'em up in, how then?&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="338">
<p>Quilt looked a little perplexed. He passed
his arm under that of the constable, and drew
him aside.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Vell, vell,&rdquo; growled Sharples, after he had
listened to the other's remonstrances, &ldquo;it shall
be done. But it's confounded inconwenient.
One don't often get sich a vindfal as the Markis&mdash;&rdquo; 
<lb>&ldquo;Or such a customer as Mr. Wild,&rdquo; edged
in Quilt.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Now, then, Saint Giles!&rdquo; interposed
Sheppard, &ldquo;are we to be kept here all night?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Eh day!&rdquo; exclaimed Sharples: &ldquo;wot newfledged
bantam's this?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;One that wants to go to roost,&rdquo; replied
Sheppard. &ldquo;So, stir your stumps, Saint
Giles; and, if you mean to lock us up, use
despatch.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Comin'! comin'!&rdquo; returned the constable,
shuffling towards him.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Coming!&mdash;so is midnight&mdash;so is Jonathan
Wild,&rdquo; retorted Jack, with a significant look at
Thames.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Have you never an out&hyphen;o'&hyphen;the&hyphen;vay corner,</pp>
<pb n="339">
<pp>into vich you could shtow these troublesome
warmint?&rdquo; observed Abraham. &ldquo;The guv'ner
'll be here afore midnight.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>Darrell's attention was drawn to the latter
part of this speech by a slight pressure on his
foot. And, turning at the touch, he perceived
Sheppard's glance fixed meaningly upon him.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Stow it, Nab!&rdquo; exclaimed Quilt, angrily; 
&ldquo;the kinchen's awake.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Awake!&mdash;to be sure I am, my flash cove,&rdquo; 
replied Sheppard; &ldquo;I'm down as a hammer.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I've just bethought me of a crib as'll serve
their turn,&rdquo; interposed Sharples; &ldquo;at any rate,
they'll be out o' the vay, and as safe as two
chicks in a coop.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Lead the way to it then, Saint Giles,&rdquo; said
Jack, in a tone of mock authority.</p>
<p><pp>The place, in which they stood, was a small
entrance&hyphen;chamber, cut off, like the segment of a
circle, from the main apartment, (of which it is
needless to say it originally constituted a portion,)
by a stout wooden partition. A door led
to the inner room; and it was evident, from
the peals of merriment, and other noises, that,</pp>
<pb n="340">
<pp>ever and anon, resounded from within, that this
chamber was occupied by the Marquis and his
friends. Against the walls hung an assortment
of staves, brown&hyphen;bills, (weapons then borne by
the watch,) muskets, handcuffs, great&hyphen;coats,
and lanterns. In one angle of the room stood
a disused fire&hyphen;place, with a rusty grate and
broken chimney&hyphen;piece; in the other there was
a sort of box, contrived between the wall and
the boards, that looked like an apology for a
cupboard. Towards this box Sharples directed
his steps, and, unlocking a hatch in the door,
disclosed a recess scarcely as large, and certainly
not as clean, as a dog&hyphen;kennel.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Vill this do?&rdquo; demanded the constable,
taking the candle from the lantern, the better
to display the narrow limits of the hole. &ldquo;I
call this ere crib the Little&hyphen;Ease, arter the
runaway prentices' cells in Guildhall. I <it>have</it>
squeezed three kids into it afore now. To be
sure,&rdquo; he added, lowering his tone, &ldquo;they
wos little 'uns, and one on 'em was smothered
&mdash;ough! ough!&mdash;how this cough chokes
me!&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="341">
<p>Sheppard, mean while, whose hands were at
liberty, managed to possess himself, unperceived,
of the spike of a halbert, which was
lying, apart from the pole, upon a bench near
him. Having secured this implement, he burst
from his conductor, and, leaping into the hatch,
as clowns generally spring into the clock&hyphen;faces,
when in pursuit of harlequin in the pantomime,
&mdash;that is, back foremost,&mdash;broke into a fit of
loud and derisive laughter, kicking his heels
merrily all the time against the boards. His
mirth, however, received an unpleasant check; 
for Abraham, greatly incensed by his previous
conduct, caught him by the legs, and pushed
him with such violence into the hole that the
point of the spike, which he had placed in his
pocket, found its way through his clothes to
the flesh, inflicting a slight, but painful wound.
Jack, who had something of the Spartan in his
composition, endured his martyrdom without
flinching; and carried his stoical indifference
so far, as even to make a mocking grimace in
Sharples's face, while that amiable functionary
thrust Thames into the recess beside him.</p>
<pb n="342">
<p>&ldquo;How do you like your quarters, saucebox?&rdquo; 
asked Sharples, in a jeering tone.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Better than your company, Saint Giles,&rdquo; 
replied Sheppard; &ldquo;so, shut the door, and
make yourself scarce.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;That boy'll never rest till he finds his vay
to Bridewell,&rdquo; observed Sharples.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Or the street,&rdquo; returned Jack: &ldquo;mind my
words, the prison's not built that can keep me.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;We'll see that, young hempseed,&rdquo; replied
Sharples, shutting the hatch furiously in his face,
and locking it. &ldquo;If you get out o' that cage,
I'll forgive you. Now, come along, gem'men,
and I'll show you some precious sport.&rdquo;</p>
<p>The two janizaries followed him as far as
the entrance to the inner room, when Abraham,
raising his finger to his lips, and glancing
significantly in the direction of the boys, to
explain his intention to his companions, closed
the door after them, and stole softly back
again, planting himself near the recess.</p>
<p>For a few minutes all was silent. At length
Jack Sheppard observed:&mdash;&ldquo;The coast's clear.
They're gone into the next room.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="343">
<p>Darrell returned no answer.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Don't be angry with me, Thames,&rdquo; continued
Sheppard, in a tone calculated, as he
thought, to appease his companion's indignation.
&ldquo;I did all for the best, as I'll explain.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I won't reproach you, Jack,&rdquo; said the
other, sternly. &ldquo;I've done with you.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Not quite, I hope,&rdquo; rejoined Sheppard.
&ldquo;At all events, I've not done with you. If
you owe your confinement to me, you shall owe
your liberation to me, also.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I'd rather lie here for ever, than be indebted
to <it>you</it> for my freedom,&rdquo; returned
Thames.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I've done nothing to offend you,&rdquo; persisted Jack.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Nothing!&rdquo; echoed the other, scornfully.
&ldquo;You've perjured yourself.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;That's my own concern,&rdquo; rejoined Sheppard.
&ldquo;An oath weighs little with me, compared
with your safety.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;No more of this,&rdquo; interrupted Thames,
&ldquo;you make the matter worse by these excuses.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Quarrel with me as much as you please,
Thames, but hear me,&rdquo; returned Sheppard.
&ldquo;I took the course I pursued to serve you.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="344">
<p>&ldquo;Tush!&rdquo; cried Thames; &ldquo;you accused me
to skreen yourself.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;On my soul, Thames, you wrong me!&rdquo; replied
Jack, passionately. &ldquo;I'd lay down my
life for yours.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;And you expect me to believe you after
what has passed?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I do; and, more than that, I expect you
to thank me.&rdquo;</p>
<lb><lg><l>&ldquo;For procuring my imprisonment?&rdquo;</l>
<l>&ldquo;For saving your life.&rdquo;</l>
<l>&ldquo;How?&rdquo;</l></lg>
<lb><p>&ldquo;Listen to me, Thames. You're in a more
serious scrape than you imagine. I overheard
Jonathan Wild's instructions to Quilt Arnold,
and though he spoke in slang, and in an under
tone, my quick ears, and acquaintance with the
thieves' lingo, enabled me to make out every
word he uttered. Jonathan is in league with
Sir Rowland to make away with you. You are
brought here that their designs may be carried
into effect with greater security. Before morning,
unless we can effect an escape, you'll be
kidnapped, or murdered, and your disappearance
attributed to the negligence of the constable.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="345">
<p>&ldquo;Are you sure of this?&rdquo; asked Thames,
who, though as brave a lad as need be, could
not repress a shudder at the intelligence.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Certain. The moment I entered the room,
and found you a prisoner in the hands of Jonathan
Wild, I guessed how matters stood, and
acted accordingly. Things haven't gone quite
as smoothly as I anticipated; but they might
have been worse. I <it>can</it> save you, and <it>will</it>.
But, say we're friends.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You're not deceiving me!&rdquo; said Thames,
doubtfully.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I am not, by heaven!&rdquo; replied Sheppard,
firmly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Don't swear, Jack, or I shall distrust you.
I can't give you my hand; but you may
take it.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Thank you! thank you!&rdquo; faltered Jack,
in a voice full of emotion. &ldquo;I'll soon free you
from these bracelets.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You needn't trouble yourself,&rdquo; replied
Thames. &ldquo;Mr. Wood will be here presently.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Mr. Wood!&rdquo; exclaimed Jack, in surprise.
&ldquo;How have you managed to communicate with
him?&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>Abraham, who had listened attentively to</pp>
<pb n="346">
<pp>the foregoing conversation,&mdash;not a word of
which escaped him,&mdash;now drew in his breath,
and brought his ear closer to the boards.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;By means of the watchman who had the
charge of me,&rdquo; replied Thames.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Curse him!&rdquo; muttered Abraham.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Hist!&rdquo; exclaimed Jack. &ldquo;I thought I
heard a noise. Speak lower. Somebody may
be on the watch&mdash;perhaps, that old gingerhackled
Jew.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I don't care if he is,&rdquo; rejoined Thames,
boldly. &ldquo;He'll learn that his plans will be
defeated.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;He may learn how to defeat yours,&rdquo; replied
Jack.</p>
<p>&ldquo;So he may,&rdquo; rejoined Abraham, aloud, &ldquo;so
he may.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Death and fiends!&rdquo; exclaimed Jack; &ldquo;the
old thief <it>is</it> there. I knew it. You've betrayed
yourself, Thames.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Vot o' that?&rdquo; chuckled Abraham. &ldquo;<it>You</it>
can shave him, you know.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I <it>can</it>,&rdquo; rejoined Jack; &ldquo;and you, too, old
Aaron, if I'd a razor.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;How soon do you expect Mishter Vudd?&rdquo; 
inquired the janizary, tauntingly.</p>
<pb n="347">
<p>&ldquo;What's that to you?&rdquo; retorted Jack, surlily.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Because I shouldn't like to be out o'
the vay ven he arrives,&rdquo; returned Abraham,
in a jeering tone; &ldquo;it vouldn't be vell bred.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Vouldn't it!&rdquo; replied Jack, mimicking his
snuffling voice; &ldquo;then shtay vere you are, and
be cursed to you.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;It's all up,&rdquo; muttered Thames. &ldquo;Mr.
Wood will be intercepted. I've destroyed my
only chance.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Not your <it>only</it> chance, Thames,&rdquo; returned
Jack, in the same undertone; &ldquo;but your best.
Never mind. We'll turn the tables upon 'em
yet. Do you think we could manage that old
clothesman between us, if we got out of this
box?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I'd manage him myself, if my arms were
free,&rdquo; replied Thames, boldly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Shpeak up, vill you?&rdquo; cried Abraham, rapping
his knuckles against the hatch. &ldquo;I likes
to hear vot you says. You <it>can</it> have no shecrets
from me.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Vy don't you talk to your partner, or
Saint Giles, if you vant conversation, Aaron?&rdquo; 
asked Jack, slily.</p>
<pb n="348">
<p>&ldquo;Because they're in the next room, and the
door's shut; that's vy, my jack&hyphen;a&hyphen;dandy!&rdquo; 
replied Abraham, unsuspiciously.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Oh! they are&mdash;are they?&rdquo; muttered Jack,
triumphantly; &ldquo;that'll do. Now for it,
Thames! Make as great a row as you can to
divert his attention.&rdquo;</p>
<p>With this, he drew the spike from his
pocket; and, drowning the sound of the
operation by whistling, singing, shuffling, and
other noises, contrived, in a few minutes, to
liberate his companion from the handcuffs.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Now, Jack,&rdquo; cried Thames, warmly grasping
Sheppard's hand, &ldquo;you are my friend
again. I freely forgive you.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Sheppard cordially returned the pressure; 
and, cautioning Thames, &ldquo;not to let the ruffles
drop, or they might tell a tale,&rdquo; began to warble
the following fragment of a robber melody:&mdash; 
<lb><lg><l>&ldquo;Oh! give me a chisel, a knife, or a file,</l>
<l>And the dubsmen shall find that I'll do it in style!</l>
<l align="r"><it>Tol&hyphen;de&hyphen;rol</it>!&rdquo;</l></lg></p>
<lb><p>&ldquo;Vot the devil are you about, noisy?&rdquo; inquired
Abraham.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Practising singing, Aaron,&rdquo; replied Jack.
&ldquo;Vot are you?&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="349">
<p>&ldquo;Practising patience,&rdquo; growled Abraham.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Not before it's needed,&rdquo; returned Jack,
aloud; adding in a whisper, &ldquo;get upon my
shoulders, Thames. Now you're up, take this
spike. Feel for the lock, and prize it open,&mdash; 
you don't need to be told <it>how</it>. When it's
done, I'll push you through. Take care of the
old clothesman, and leave the rest to me.</p>
<lb><lg><l>When the turnkey, next morning, stepp'd into his room,</l>
<l>The sight of the hole in the wall struck him dumb;</l>
<l>The sheriff's black bracelets lay strewn on the ground,</l>
<l>But the lad that had worn'em could nowhere be found.</l>
<l align="r"><it>Tol&hyphen;de&hyphen;rol</it>!&rdquo;</l></lg>
<lb><p>As Jack concluded his ditty, the door flew
open with a crash, and Thames sprang through
the aperture.</p>
<p><pp>This man&oelig;uvre was so suddenly executed
that it took Abraham completely by surprise.
He was standing at the moment close to the
hatch, with his ear at the keyhole, and received
a severe blow in the face. He staggered back a
few paces; and, before he could recover himself,
Thames tripped up his heels, and, placing
the point of the spike at his throat, threatened
to stab him if he attempted to stir, or cry out.
Nor had Jack been idle all this time. Clearing
the recess the instant after his companion, he</pp>
<pb n="350">
<pp>flew to the door of the inner room, and, locking
it, took out the key. The policy of this step
was immediately apparent. Alarmed by the
noise of the scuffle, Quilt and Sharples rushed
to the assistance of their comrade. But they
were too late. The entrance was barred against
them; and they had the additional mortification
of hearing Sheppard's loud laughter at their
discomfiture.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;I told you the prison wasn't built that could
hold me,&rdquo; cried Jack.</p>
<p>&ldquo;You're not out yet, you young hound,&rdquo; rejoined
Quilt, striving ineffectually to burst open
the door.</p>
<p>&ldquo;But I soon shall be,&rdquo; returned Jack; 
&ldquo;take these,&rdquo; he added, flinging the handcuffs
against the wooden partition, &ldquo;and wear 'em
yourself.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Halloo, Nab!&rdquo; vociferated Quilt. &ldquo;What
the devil are you about? Will you allow
yourself to be beaten by a couple of kids?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Not if I can help it,&rdquo; returned Abraham,
making a desperate effort to regain his feet.
&ldquo;By my shalvation, boy,&rdquo; he added, fiercely,
&ldquo;if you don't take your hand off my peard, I'll
shtrangle you.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="351">
<p>&ldquo;Help me, Jack!&rdquo; shouted Thames, &ldquo;or I
shan't be able to keep the villain down.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Stick the spike into him, then,&rdquo; returned
Sheppard, coolly, &ldquo;while I unbar the outlet.&rdquo;</p>
<p>But Thames had no intention of following
his friend's advice. Contenting himself with
brandishing the weapon in the Jew's eyes, he
exerted all his force to prevent him from rising.</p>
<p>While this took place, while Quilt thundered
at the inner door, and Jack drew back the
bolts of the outer, a deep, manly voice was
heard chanting&mdash;as if in contempt of the general
uproar&mdash;the following strain:&mdash; 
<lb><lg><l>With pipe and punch upon the board,</l>
<l>&indent;And smiling nymphs around us;</l>
<l>No tavern could more mirth afford</l>
<l>&indent;Than old Saint Giles's roundhouse!</l>
<l align="r"><it>The roundhouse</it>! <it>the roundhouse</it>!</l>
<l align="r"><it>The jolly&mdash;jolly roundhouse</it>!</l></lg></p>
<lb><p>&ldquo;The jolly, jolly roundhouse!&rdquo; chorussed
Sheppard, as the last bar yielded to his efforts.
&ldquo;Hurrah! come along, Thames; we're free.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Not sho fasht&mdash;not sho fasht!&rdquo; cried
Abraham, struggling with Thames, and detaining
him; &ldquo;if you go, you musht take me along
vid you.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Save yourself, Jack!&rdquo; shouted Thames,</pp>
<pb n="352">
<pp>sinking beneath the superior weight and
strength of his opponent; &ldquo;leave me to my
fate!&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Never,&rdquo; replied Jack, hurrying towards
him. And, snatching the spike from Thames,
he struck the janizary a severe blow on the
head. &ldquo;I'll make sure work this time,&rdquo; he
added, about to repeat the blow.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Hold!&rdquo; interposed Thames, &ldquo;he can do no
more mischief. Let us be gone.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;As you please,&rdquo; returned Jack, leaping up; 
&ldquo;but I feel devilishly inclined to finish him.
However, it would only be robbing the hangman
of his dues.&rdquo;</p>
<p>With this, he was preparing to follow his
friend, when their egress was prevented by
the sudden appearance of Jonathan Wild and
Blueskin.</p></div4></div3>
<trailer>END OF THE FIRST VOLUME.</trailer>
