CHAPTER I.
<subhead>THE RETURN.</subhead> <attbytes>43Kb</attbytes><reflink>000027</reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z400030648</ID><A1>Ainsworth, William Harrison, 1805&ndash;1882</A1><T1>Jack Sheppard. A Romance.</T1><PBL>Richard Bentley</PBL><Y1>1839</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd4>
<p><pp><smallcap>Nearly</smallcap> nine years after the events last recorded,
and about the middle of May, 1724, a
young man of remarkably prepossessing appearance
took his way, one afternoon, along
Wych&hyphen;street; and, from the curiosity with
which he regarded the houses on the left of
the road, seemed to be in search of some particular
habitation. The age of this individual
could not be more than twenty&hyphen;one; his figure
was tall, robust, and gracefully proportioned; 
and his clear grey eye and open countenance
bespoke a frank, generous, and resolute nature.
His features were regular, and finely&hyphen;formed; 
his complexion bright and blooming,&mdash;a little
shaded, however, by travel and exposure to the
sun; and, with a praiseworthy contempt for</pp>
<pb n="108">
<pp>the universal and preposterous fashion then
prevailing, of substituting a peruke for the
natural covering of the head, he allowed his
own dark&hyphen;brown hair to fall over his shoulders
in ringlets as luxuriant as those that distinguished
the court gallant in Charles the Second's
days&mdash;a fashion, which we do not despair
of seeing revived in our own days. He
wore a French military undress of the period,
with high jack&hyphen;boots, and a laced hat; and,
though his attire indicated no particular rank,
he had completely the air of a person of distinction.
Such was the effect produced upon
the passengers by his good looks and manly
deportment, that few&mdash;especially of the gentler
and more susceptible sex&mdash;failed to turn round
and bestow a second glance upon the handsome
stranger. Unconscious of the interest
he excited, and entirely occupied by his own
thoughts&mdash;which, if his bosom could have
been examined, would have been found composed
of mingled hopes and fears&mdash;the young
man walked on till he came to an old house,
with great, projecting, bay windows on the
first floor, and situated as nearly as possible at
the back of St. Clement's church. Here he</pp>
<pb n="109">
<pp>halted; and, looking upwards, read, at the foot
of an immense sign&hyphen;board, displaying a gaudily&hyphen;painted
angel with expanded pinions and
an olive&hyphen;branch, not the name he expected to
find, but that of WILLIAM KNEEBONE,
WOOLLEN&hyphen;DRAPER.</pp></p>
<p><pp>Tears started to the young man's eyes on
beholding the change, and it was with difficulty
he could command himself sufficiently to make
the inquiries he desired to do respecting the
former owner of the house. As he entered the
shop, a tall portly personage advanced to meet
him, whom he at once recognised as the present
proprietor. Mr. Kneebone was attired in
the extremity of the mode. A full&hyphen;curled wig
descended half&hyphen;way down his back and shoulders; 
a neckcloth of &ldquo;right Mechlin&rdquo; was
twisted round his throat so tightly as almost
to deprive him of breath, and threaten him
with apoplexy; he had lace, also, at his wrists
and bosom; gold clocks to his hose, and red
heels to his shoes. A stiff, formally&hyphen;cut coat
of cinnamon&hyphen;coloured cloth, with rows of plate
buttons, each of the size of a crown piece, on
the sleeves, pockets, and skirts, reached the
middle of his legs; and his costume was completed</pp>
<pb n="110">
<pp>by the silver&hyphen;hilted sword at his side,
and the laced hat under his left arm.</pp></p>
<p>Bowing to the stranger, the woollen&hyphen;draper
very politely requested to know his business.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I'm almost afraid to state it,&rdquo; faltered the
other; &ldquo;but, may I ask whether Mr. Wood, the
carpenter, who formerly resided here, is still
living?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;If you feel any anxiety on his account, sir,
I'm happy to be able to relieve it,&rdquo; answered
Kneebone, readily. &ldquo;My good friend, Owen
Wood,&mdash;heaven preserve him!&mdash;<it>is</it> still living.
And, for a man who'll never see sixty again,
he's in excellent preservation, I assure you.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You delight me with the intelligence,&rdquo; 
said the stranger, entirely recovering his cheerfulness
of look. &ldquo;I began to fear, from his
having quitted the old place, that some misfortune
must have befallen him.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Quite the contrary,&rdquo; rejoined the woollen&hyphen;draper,
laughing good&hyphen;humouredly. &ldquo;Everything
has prospered with him in an extraordinary
manner. His business has thriven; 
legacies have unexpectedly dropped into his
lap; and, to crown all, he has made a large
fortune by a lucky speculation in South&hyphen;Sea</pp>
<pb n="111">
<pp>stock,&mdash;made it, too, where so many others have
lost fortunes, your humble servant amongst
the number&mdash;ha! ha! In a word, sir, Mr.
Wood is now in very affluent circumstances.
He stuck to the shop as long as it was necessary,
and longer, in my opinion: When he
left these premises, three years ago, I took
them from him; or rather&mdash;to deal frankly
with you,&mdash;he placed me in them rent&hyphen;free,
for, I'm not ashamed to confess it, I've had
losses, and heavy ones; and, if it hadn't been
for him, I don't know where I should have
been. Mr. Wood, sir,&rdquo; he added, with much
emotion, &ldquo;is one of the best of men, and
would be the happiest, were it not that&mdash;&rdquo; 
and he hesitated.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Well, sir?&rdquo; cried the other, eagerly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;His wife is still living,&rdquo; returned Kneebone,
drily.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I understand,&rdquo; replied the stranger, unable
to repress a smile. &ldquo;But, it strikes me,
I've heard that Mrs. Wood was once a favourite
of yours.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;So she was,&rdquo; replied the woollen&hyphen;draper,
helping himself to an enormous pinch of snuff
with the air of a man who does not dislike to</pp>
<pb n="112">
<pp>be rallied about his gallantry,&mdash;&ldquo;so she was.
But those days are over&mdash;quite over. Since
her husband has laid me under such a weight
of obligation, I couldn't, in honour, continue&mdash; 
hem!&rdquo; and he took another explanatory pinch.
&ldquo;Added to which, she is neither so young as
she was, nor is her temper by any means improved
&mdash;hem!&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Say no more on the subject, sir,&rdquo; observed
the stranger, gravely; &ldquo;but let us turn to a
more agreeable one&mdash;her daughter.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;That is a far more agreeable one, I must
confess,&rdquo; returned Kneebone, with a self&hyphen;sufficient
smirk.</p>
<p>The stranger looked at him as if strongly
disposed to chastise his impertinence.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Is she married?&rdquo; he asked, after a brief
pause.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Married!&mdash;no&mdash;no,&rdquo; replied the woollen&hyphen;draper.
Winifred Wood will never marry,
unless the grave can give up its dead. When
a mere child, she fixed her affections upon a
youth named Thames Darrell, whom her father
brought up, and who perished, it is supposed,
about nine years ago; and she has determined
to remain faithful to his memory.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="113">
<p>&ldquo;You astonish me,&rdquo; said the stranger, in a
voice full of emotion.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Why it <it>is</it> astonishing, certainly,&rdquo; remarked
Kneebone, &ldquo;to find any woman constant&mdash; 
especially to a girlish attachment; but such is
the case. She has had offers innumerable; 
for where wealth and beauty are combined, as
in her instance, suitors are seldom wanting.
But she was not to be tempted.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;She is a matchless creature!&rdquo; exclaimed
the young man.</p>
<p>&ldquo;So I think,&rdquo; replied Kneebone, again applying
to the snuff&hyphen;box, and by that means
escaping the angry glance levelled at him by
his companion.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I have one enquiry more to make of
you, sir,&rdquo; said the stranger, as soon as he had
conquered his displeasure, &ldquo;and I will then
trouble you no further. You spoke just now
of a youth whom Mr. Wood brought up. As
far as I recollect, there were two. What has
become of the other?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Why, surely you don't mean Jack Sheppard?&rdquo; 
cried the woollen&hyphen;draper in surprise.</p>
<p>&ldquo;That was the lad's name?&rdquo; returned the
stranger.</p>
<pb n="114">
<p><pp>&ldquo;I guessed from your dress and manner, sir,
that you must have been long absent from your
own country,&rdquo; said Kneebone; &ldquo;and now I'm
convinced of it, or you wouldn't have asked
that question. Jack Sheppard is the talk and
terror of the whole town. The ladies can't
sleep in their beds for him; and as to the men,
they daren't go to bed at all. He's the most
daring and expert housebreaker that ever used
a crow&hyphen;bar. He laughs at locks and bolts; and
the more carefully you guard your premises
from him, the more likely are you to insure an
attack. His exploits and escapes are in every
body's mouth. He has been lodged in every
roundhouse in the metropolis, and has broken
out of them all, and boasts that no prison can
hold him. We shall see. His skill has not
been tried. At present, he is under the protection
of Jonathan Wild.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Does that villain still maintain his power?&rdquo; 
asked the stranger sternly.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;He does,&rdquo; replied Kneebone, &ldquo;and, what
is more surprising, it seems to increase. Jonathan
completely baffles and derides the ends
of justice. It is useless to contend with him,
even with right on your side. Some years ago,</pp>
<pb n="115">
<pp>in 1715, just before the Rebellion, I was rash
enough to league myself with the Jacobite
party, and by Wild's machinations got clapped
into Newgate, whence I was glad to escape
with my head upon my shoulders. I charged
the thieftaker, as was the fact, with having
robbed me, by means of the lad Sheppard,
whom he instigated to the deed, of the very
pocket&hyphen;book he produced in evidence against
me; but it was of no avail&mdash;I couldn't obtain
a hearing. Mr. Wood fared still worse.
Bribed by a certain Sir Rowland Trenchard,
Jonathan kidnapped the carpenter's adopted
son, Thames Darrell, and placed him in the
hands of a Dutch Skipper, with orders to throw
him overboard when he got out to sea; and
though this was proved as clear as day, the
rascal managed matters so adroitly, and gave
such a different complexion to the whole affair,
that he came off with flying colours. One reason,
perhaps, of his success in this case might
be, that having arrested his associate in the
dark transaction, Sir Rowland Trenchard, on a
charge of high treason, he was favoured by
Walpole, who found his account in retaining
such an agent. Be this as it may, Jonathan</pp>
<pb n="116">
<pp>remained the victor; and shortly afterwards,&mdash; 
at the price of a third of his estate, it was
whispered,&mdash;he procured Trenchard's liberation
from confinement.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>At the mention of the latter occurrence, a
dark cloud gathered upon the stranger's brow.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Do you know anything further of Sir
Rowland?&rdquo; he asked.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Nothing more than this,&rdquo; answered Kneebone,
&mdash;&ldquo;that after the failure of his projects,
and the downfall of his party, he retired to his
seat, Ashton Hall, near Manchester, and has
remained there ever since, entirely secluded
from the world.&rdquo;</p>
<p>The stranger was for a moment lost in reflection.</p>
<p>&ldquo;And now, sir,&rdquo; he said, preparing to take
his departure, &ldquo;will you add to the obligation
already conferred by informing me where I
can meet with Mr. Wood?&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;With pleasure,&rdquo; replied the woollen&hyphen;draper.
He lives at Dollis Hill, a beautiful spot
near Willesden, about four or five miles from
town, where he has taken a farm. If you ride
out there,&mdash;and the place is well worth a visit,
for the magnificent view it commands of some</pp>
<pb n="117">
<pp>of the finest country in the neighbourhood of
London,&mdash;you are certain to meet with him.
I saw him yesterday, and he told me he shouldn't
stir from home for a week to come. He
called here on his way back, after he had
been to Bedlam to visit poor Mrs. Shepdard.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Jack's mother!&rdquo; exclaimed the young man.
&ldquo;Gracious heaven!&mdash;is she the inmate of a
mad&hyphen;house?&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;She is, sir,&rdquo; answered the woollen&hyphen;draper,
sadly, &ldquo;driven there by her son's misconduct.
Alas! that the punishment of his offences
should fall on her head. Poor soul! she
nearly died when she heard he had robbed
his master; and it might have been well if she
had done so, for she never afterwards recovered
her reason. She rambles continually about
Jack, and her husband, and that wretch Jonathan,
to whom, as far as can be gathered
from her wild ravings, she attributes all her
misery. I pity her from the bottom of my
heart. But, in the midst of all her affliction,
she has found a steady friend in Mr. Wood,
who looks after her comforts, and visits her</pp>
<pb n="118">
<pp>constantly. Indeed, I've heard him say that,
but for his wife, he would shelter her under
his own roof. That, sir, is what I call being
a Good Samaritan.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>The stranger said nothing, but hastily brushed
away a tear. Perceiving he was about to take
leave, Kneebone ventured to ask whom he
had had the honour of addressing.</p>
<p>Before the question could be answered, a
side&hyphen;door was opened, and a very handsome
woman of Amazonian proportions presented
herself, and marched familiarly up to Mr. Kneebone.
She was extremely showily dressed,
and her large hooped petticoat gave additional
effect to her lofty stature. As soon as she
noticed the stranger, she honoured him with
an extremely impudent stare, and scarcely endeavoured
to disguise the admiration with
which his good looks impressed her.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Don't you perceive, my dear Mrs. Maggot,
that I'm engaged,&rdquo; said Kneebone, a little
disconcerted.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Who've you got with you?&rdquo; demanded
the Amazon, boldly.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;The gentleman is a stranger to me, Poll,&rdquo;</pp>
<pb n="119">
<pp>replied the woollen&hyphen;draper, with increased embarrassment.
&ldquo;I don't know his name.&rdquo; And
he looked at the moment as if he had lost all
desire to know it.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Well, he's a pretty fellow at all events,&rdquo; 
observed Mrs. Maggot, eyeing him from head
to heel with evident satisfaction;&mdash;&ldquo;a devilish
pretty fellow!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Upon my word, Poll,&rdquo; said Kneebone, becoming
very red, &ldquo;you might have a little
more delicacy than to tell him so before my
face.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;What!&rdquo; exclaimed Mrs. Maggot, drawing
up her fine figure to its full height; &ldquo;because
I condescend to live with you, am I never to
look at another man,&mdash;especially at one so
much to my taste as this? Don't think it!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You had better retire, madam,&rdquo; said the
woolen&hyphen;draper, sharply, &ldquo;if you can't conduct
yourself with more propriety.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Order those who choose to obey you,&rdquo; 
rejoined the lady scornfully. &ldquo;Though you
lorded it over that fond fool, Mrs. Wood, you
shan't lord it over me, I can promise you.
That for you!&rdquo; And she snapped her fingers
in his face.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="120">
<p>&ldquo;Zounds!&rdquo; cried Kneebone, furiously. &ldquo;Go
to your own room, woman, directly, or I'll
make you!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Make me!&rdquo; echoed Mrs. Maggot, bursting
into a loud contemptuous laugh. &ldquo;Try!&rdquo;</p>
<p>Enraged at the assurance of his mistress,
the woollen&hyphen;draper endeavoured to carry his
threat into execution, but all his efforts to
remove her were unavailing. At length, after
he had given up the point from sheer exhaustion,
the Amazon seized him by the throat,
and pushed him backwards with such force
that he rolled over the counter.</p>
<p>&ldquo;There!&rdquo; she cried, laughing, &ldquo;that'll teach
you to lay hands upon me again. You should
remember, before you try your strength against
mine, that when I rescued you from the watch,
and you induced me to come and live with
you, I beat off four men, any of whom was a
match for you&mdash;ha! ha!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;My dear Poll!&rdquo; said Kneebone, picking
himself up, &ldquo;I intreat you to moderate yourself.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Intreat a fiddlestick!&rdquo; retorted Mrs. Maggot:
&ldquo;I'm tired of you, and will go back to
my old lover, Jack Sheppard. He's worth a</pp>
<pb n="121">
<pp>dozen of you. Or, if this good&hyphen;looking young
fellow will only say the word, I'll go with
him.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;You may go, and welcome, madam!&rdquo; rejoined
Kneebone, spitefully. &ldquo;But, I should
think, after the specimen you've just given of
your amiable disposition, no person would be
likely to saddle himself with such an incumbrance.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;What say you, sir?&rdquo; said the Amazon,
with an engaging leer at the stranger. &ldquo;<it>You</it>
will find me tractable enough; and, with <it>me</it>
by your side, you need fear neither constable
nor watchman. I've delivered Jack Sheppard
from many an assault. I can wield a quarterstaff
as well as a prize&hyphen;fighter, and have beaten
Figg himself at the broadsword. Will you
take me?&rdquo;</p>
<p>However tempting Mrs. Maggot's offer may
appear, the young man thought fit to decline
it, and, after a few words of well&hyphen;merited
compliment on her extraordinary prowess, and
renewed thanks to Mr. Kneebone, he took his
departure.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Good bye!&rdquo; cried Mrs. Maggot, kissing
her hand to him. &ldquo;I'll find you out. And</pp>
<pb n="122">
<pp>now,&rdquo; she added, glancing contemptuously at
the woolen&hyphen;draper, &ldquo;I'll go to Jack Sheppard.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;You shall first go to Bridewell, you jade!&rdquo; 
rejoined Kneebone. &ldquo;Here, Tom,&rdquo; he added,
calling to a shop&hyphen;boy, &ldquo;run and fetch a constable.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;He had better bring half&hyphen;a&hyphen;dozen,&rdquo; said
the Amazon, taking up a cloth&hyphen;yard wand, and
quietly seating herself; &ldquo;one won't do.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>On leaving Mr. Kneebone's house, the
young man hastened to a hotel in the neighbourhood
of Covent Garden, where, having
procured a horse, he shaped his course towards
the west end of the town. Urging his
steed along Oxford Road,&mdash;as that great approach
to the metropolis was then termed,
&mdash;he soon passed Marylebone Lane, beyond
which, with the exception of a few scattered
houses, the country was completely open on
the right, and laid out in pleasant fields and
gardens; nor did he draw in the rein until he
arrived at Tyburn&hyphen;gate, where, before he
turned off upon the Edgeware Road, he halted
for a moment, to glance at the place of execution.
This &ldquo;fatal retreat for the unfortunate</pp>
<pb n="123">
<pp>brave&rdquo; was marked by a low wooden railing,
within which stood the triple tree. Opposite
the gallows was an open gallery, or scaffolding,
like the stand at a race&hyphen;course, which, on state
occasions, was crowded with spectators. Without
the inclosure were reared several lofty gibbets,
with their ghastly burthens. Altogether,
it was a hideous and revolting sight. Influenced,
probably, by what he had heard from
Mr. Kneebone, respecting the lawless career
of Jack Sheppard, and struck with the probable
fate that awaited him, the young man,
as he contemplated this scene, fell into a
gloomy reverie. While he was thus musing,
two horsemen rode past him; and, proceeding
to a little distance, stopped likewise. One of
them was a stout square&hyphen;built man, with a
singularly swarthy complexion, and harsh forbidding
features. He was well mounted, as
was his companion; and had pistols in his
holsters, and a hanger at his girdle. The
other individual, who was a little in advance,
was concealed from the stranger's view. Presently,
however, a sudden movement occurred,
and disclosed his features, which were those
of a young man of nearly his own age. The</pp>
<pb n="124">
<pp>dress of this person was excessively showy,
and consisted of a scarlet riding&hyphen;habit, lined
and faced with blue, and bedizened with broad
gold lace, a green silk&hyphen;knit waistcoat, embroidered
with silver, and decorated with a deep
fringe, together with a hat tricked out in the
same gaudy style. His figure was slight, but
well&hyphen;built; and, in stature he did not exceed
five feet four. His complexion was pale; and
there was something sinister in the expression
of his large black eyes. His head was small
and bullet&hyphen;shaped, and he did not wear a wig,
but had his sleek black hair cut off closely
round his temples. A mutual recognition
took place at the same instant between the
stranger and this individual. Both started.
The latter seemed inclined to advance and address
the former; but suddenly changing his
mind, he shouted to his companion in tones
familiar to the stranger's ear; and, striking
spurs into his steed, dashed off at full speed
along the Edgeware Road. Impelled by a
feeling, into which we shall not pause to inquire,
the stranger started after them; but
they were better mounted, and soon distanced
him. Remarking that they struck off at a</pp>
<pb n="125">
<pp>turning on the left, he took the same road,
and soon found himself on Paddington&hyphen;Green.
A row of magnificent, and even then venerable,
elms threw their broad arms over this pleasant
spot. From a man, who was standing beneath
the shade of one of these noble trees, information
was obtained that the horsemen had
ridden along the Harrow Road. With a faint
view of overtaking them, the pursuer urged
his steed to a quicker pace. Arrived at Westbourne
&hyphen;Green&mdash;then nothing more than a
common covered with gorse and furzebushes,
and boasting only a couple of cottages and an
alehouse&mdash;he perceived through the hedges
the objects of his search slowly ascending the
gentle hill that rises from Kensall&hyphen;Green.</pp></p>
<p><pp>By the time he had reached the summit of
this hill, he had lost all trace of them; and
the ardour of the chase having in some measure
subsided, he began to reproach himself
for his folly, in having wandered&mdash;as he conceived
&mdash;so far out of his course. Before retracing
his steps, however, he allowed his gaze
to range over the vast and beautiful prospect
spread out beneath him, which is now hidden
from the traveller's view by the high walls of</pp>
<pb n="126">
<pp>the General Cemetery, and can, consequently,
only be commanded from the interior of that
attractive place of burial,&mdash;and which, before
it was intersected by canals and railroads, and
portioned out into hippodromes, was exquisite
indeed. After feasting his eye upon this
superb panorama, he was about to return,
when he ascertained from a farmer that his
nearest road to Willesden would be down a
lane a little further on, to the right. Following
this direction, he opened a gate, and struck
into one of the most beautiful green lanes
imaginable; which, after various windings,
conducted him into a more frequented road,
and eventually brought him to the place he
sought. Glancing at the finger&hyphen;post over the
cage, which has been described as situated at
the outskirts of the village, and seeing no direction
to Dollis Hill, he made fresh inquiries
as to where it lay, from an elderly man, who
was standing with another countryman near
the little prison.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Whose house do you want, master?&rdquo; said
the man, touching his hat.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Mr. Wood's,&rdquo; was the reply.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;There is Dollis Hill,&rdquo; said the man, pointing</pp>
<pb n="127">
<pp>to a well&hyphen;wooded eminence about a mile
distant, &ldquo;and there,&rdquo; he added, indicating
the roof of a house just visible above a grove
of trees &ldquo;is Mr. Wood's. If you ride past
the church, and mount the hill, you'll come
to Neasdon, and then you'll not have above
half a mile to go.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>The young man thanked his informant, and
was about to follow his instructions, when the
other called after him&mdash;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I say, master, did you ever hear tell of
Mr. Wood's famous prentice?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;What apprentice?&rdquo; asked the stranger, in
surprise.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Why, Jack Sheppard, the notorious
house&hyphen;breaker,&mdash;him as has robbed half Lunnun, to
be sure. You must know, sir, when he was
a lad, the day after he broke into his master's
house in Wych Street, he picked a gentleman's
pocket in our church, during sarvice time,&mdash; 
that he did, the heathen. The gentleman
catched him i' th' fact, and we shut him up
for safety i' that pris'n. But,&rdquo; said the fellow,
with a laugh, &ldquo;he soon contrived to make his
way out on it, though. Ever since he's become
so famous, the folks about here ha' christened</pp>
<pb n="128">
<pp>it Jack Sheppard's cage. His mother used
to live i' this village, just down yonder; but
when her son took to bad ways, she went distracted,
&mdash;and now she 's i' Bedlam, I've
heerd.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;I tell e'e what, John Dump,&rdquo; said the
other fellow, who had hitherto preserved
silence, &ldquo;I don't know whether you talkin'
o' Jack Sheppard has put him into my head
or not; but I once had him pointed out to me,
and if that <it>were</it> him as I seed then, he's just
now ridden past us, and put up at the Six
Bells.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;The deuce he has!&rdquo; cried Dump. &ldquo;If
you were sure o' that we might seize him, and
get the reward for his apprehension.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;That'ud be no such easy matter,&rdquo; replied
the countryman. &ldquo;Jack's a desperate fellow,
and is always well armed; besides, he has a
comrade with him. But I'll tell e'e what we
<it>might</it> do&wblank;&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>The young man heard no more. Taking
the direction pointed out, he rode off. As he
passed the Six Bells, he noticed the steeds of
the two horsemen at the door; and glancing
into the house, perceived the younger of the</pp>
<pb n="129">
<pp>two in the passage. The latter no sooner
beheld him than he dashed hastily into an
adjoining room. After debating with himself
whether he should further seek an interview,
which, though now in his power, was so sedulously
shunned by the other party, he decided
in the negative; and contenting himself with
writing upon a slip of paper the hasty words,&mdash; 
&ldquo;You are known by the villagers,&mdash;be upon
your guard,&rdquo;&mdash;he gave it to the ostler, with
instructions to deliver it instantly to the owner
of the horse he pointed out, and pursued his
course.</pp></p>
<p><pp>Passing the old rectory, and still older
church, with its reverend screen of trees, and
slowly ascending a hill side, from whence he
obtained enchanting peeps of the spire and
college of Harrow, he reached the cluster of
well&hyphen;built houses which constitute the village
of Neasdon. From this spot a road, more
resembling the drive through a park than a
public thoroughfare, led him gradually to the
brow of Dollis Hill. It was a serene and
charming evening, and twilight was gently
stealing over the face of the country. Bordered
by fine timber, the road occasionally</pp>
<pb n="130">
<pp>offered glimpses of a lovely valley, until a
wider opening gave a full view of a delightful
and varied prospect. On the left lay the
heights of Hampstead, studded villas, while
farther off a hazy cloud marked the position
of the metropolis. The stranger concluded he
could not be far from his destination, and a
turn in the road showed him the house.</pp></p>
<p><pp>Beneath two tall elms, whose boughs completely
overshadowed the roof, stood Mr.
Wood's dwelling,&mdash;a plain, substantial, commodious
farmhouse. On a bench at the foot
of the trees, with a pipe in his mouth, and a
tankard by his side, sat the worthy carpenter,
looking the picture of good&hyphen;heartedness and
benevolence. The progress of time was marked
in Mr. Wood by increased corpulence and
decreased powers of vision,&mdash;by deeper
wrinkles and higher shoulders, by scantier
breath and a fuller habit. Still he looked
hale and hearty, and the country life he led
had imparted a ruddier glow to his cheek.
Around him were all the evidences of plenty.
A world of hay&hyphen;stacks, bean&hyphen;stacks, and straw&hyphen;ricks
flanked the granges adjoining his habitation; 
the yard was crowded with poultry,</pp>
<pb n="131">
<pp>pigeons were feeding at his feet, cattle were
being driven towards the stall, horses led to
the stable, a large mastiff was rattling his
chain, and stalking majestically in front of his
kennel, while a number of farming&hyphen;men were
passing and repassing about their various occupations.
At the back of the house, on a
bank, rose an old&hyphen;fashioned terrace&hyphen;garden,
full of apple&hyphen;trees and other fruit&hyphen;trees in
blossom, and lively with the delicious verdure
of early spring.</pp></p>
<p>Hearing the approach of the rider, Mr.
Wood turned to look at him. It was now
getting dusk, and he could only imperfectly
distinguish the features and figure of the
stranger.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I need not ask whether this is Mr.
Wood's,&rdquo; said the latter, &ldquo;since I find him
at his own gate.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You are right, sir,&rdquo; said the worthy carpenter,
rising. &ldquo;I am Owen Wood, at your
service.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You do not remember me, I dare say,&rdquo; 
observed the stranger.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;I can't say I do,&rdquo; replied Wood. &ldquo;Your
voice seems familiar to me&mdash;and&mdash;but I'm</pp>
<pb n="132">
<pp>getting a little deaf&mdash;and my eyes don't serve
me quite so well as they used to do, especially
by this light.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Never mind,&rdquo; returned the stranger, dismounting; 
&ldquo;you'll recollect me by and by,
I've no doubt. I bring you tidings of an old
friend.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Then you're heartily welcome, sir, whoever
you are. Pray, walk in. Here, Jem, take
the gentleman's horse to the stable&mdash;see him
dressed and fed directly. Now, sir, will you
please to follow me?&rdquo;</p>
<p>Mr. Wood then led the way up a rather
high and, according to modern notions, incommodious
flight of steps, and introduced
his guest to a neat parlour, the windows of
which were darkened by pots of flowers and
creepers. There was no light in the room; 
but, notwithstanding this, the young man
did not fail to detect the buxom figure of Mrs.
Wood, now more buxom and more gorgeously
arrayed than ever,&mdash;as well as a young and
beautiful female, in whom he was at no loss
to recognise the carpenter's daughter.</p>
<p><pp>Winifred Wood was now in her twentieth
year. Her features were still slightly marked</pp>
<pb n="133">
<pp>by the disorder alluded to in the description of
her as a child,&mdash;but that was the only drawback
to her beauty. Their expression was so amiable,
that it would have redeemed a countenance
a thousand times plainer than hers. Her
figure was perfect,&mdash;tall, graceful, rounded,&mdash; 
and, then, she had deep liquid blue eyes, that
rivalled the stars in lustre. On the stranger's
appearance, she was seated near the window
busily occupied with her needle.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;My wife and daughter, sir,&rdquo; said the carpenter,
introducing them to his guest.</p>
<p>Mrs. Wood, whose admiration for masculine
beauty was by no means abated, glanced at the
well&hyphen;proportioned figure of the young man, and
made him a very civil salutation. Winifred's
reception was kind, but more distant, and after
the slight ceremonial she resumed her occupation.</p>
<p>&ldquo;This gentleman brings us tidings of an old
friend, my dear,&rdquo; said the carpenter.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ay, indeed! And who may that be?&rdquo; inquired
his wife.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;One whom you may perhaps have forgotten,&rdquo; 
replied the stranger, &ldquo;but who can
never forget the kindness he experienced at</pp>
<pb n="134">
<pp>your hands, or at those of your excellent husband.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>At the sound of his voice every vestige of
colour fled from Winifred's cheeks, and the
work upon which she was engaged fell from her
hand.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I have a token to deliver to you,&rdquo; continued
the stranger, addressing her.</p>
<p>&ldquo;To me?&rdquo; gasped Winifred.</p>
<p>&ldquo;This locket,&rdquo; he said, taking a little ornament
attached to a black ribband from his breast,
and giving it her,&mdash;&ldquo;do you remember it?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I do&mdash;I do!&rdquo; cried Winifred.</p>
<p>&ldquo;What's all this?&rdquo; exclaimed Wood in
amazement.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Do you not know me, father?&rdquo; said the
young man, advancing towards him, and warmly
grasping his hand. &ldquo;Have nine years so
changed me, that there is no trace left of your
adopted son?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;God bless me!&rdquo; ejaculated the carpenter,
rubbing his eyes, &ldquo;can&mdash;can it be?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Surely,&rdquo; screamed Mrs. Wood, joining the
group, &ldquo;it isn't Thames Darrell come to life
again?&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;It is&mdash;it is!&rdquo; cried Winifred, rushing</pp>
<pb n="135">
<pp>towards him, and flinging her arms round his
neck,&mdash;&ldquo;it is my dear&mdash;dear brother!&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Well, this is what I never expected to see,&rdquo; 
said the carpenter, wiping his eyes; &ldquo;I hope
I'm not dreaming! Thames, my dear boy, as
soon as Winny has done with you, let me embrace you.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;My turn comes before yours, sir,&rdquo; interposed
his better half. &ldquo;Come to my arms,
Thames! Oh! dear! Oh! dear!&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>To repeat the questions and congratulations
which now ensued, or describe the extravagant
joy of the carpenter, who, after he had hugged
his adopted son to his breast with such warmth
as almost to squeeze the breath from his body,
capered around the room, threw his wig into
the empty fire&hyphen;grate, and committed various
other fantastic actions, in order to get rid of
his superfluous satisfaction&mdash;to describe the
scarcely less extravagant raptures of his spouse,
or the more subdued, but not less heartfelt delight
of Winifred, would be a needless task, as
it must occur to every one's imagination. Supper
was quickly served; the oldest bottle of
wine was brought from the cellar; the strongest
barrel of ale was tapped; but not one of the</pp>
<pb n="136">
<pp>party could eat or drink&mdash;their hearts were too
full.</pp></p>
<p>Thames sat with Winifred's hand clasped in
his own, and commenced a recital of his adventures,
which may be briefly told. Carried
out to sea by Van Galgebrok, and thrown overboard,
while struggling with the waves, he had
been picked up by a French fishing&hyphen;boat, and
carried to Ostend. After encountering various
hardships and privations for a long time, during
which he had no means of communicating with
England, he, at length, found his way to Paris,
where he was taken notice of by Cardinal
Dubois, who employed him as one of his
secretaries, and subsequently advanced to the
service of Philip of Orleans, from whom he
received a commission. On the death of his
royal patron, he resolved to return to his own
country; and, after various delays, which had
postponed it to the present time, he had succeeded
in accomplishing his object.</p>
<p>Winifred listened to his narration with the
profoundest attention; and, when it concluded,
her tearful eye and throbbing bosom told how
deeply her feelings had been interested.</p>
<p><pp>The discourse, then, turned to Darrell's old</pp>
<pb n="137">
<pp>playmate, Jack Sheppard; and Mr. Wood, in
deploring his wild career, adverted to the melancholy
condition to which it had reduced his
mother.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;For my part, it's only what I expected of
him,&rdquo; observed Mrs. Wood, and I'm sorry and
surprised he hasn't swung for his crimes before
this. The gallows has groaned for him for
years. As to his mother, I've no pity for her.
She deserves what has befallen her.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Dear mother, don't say so,&rdquo; returned
Winifred. &ldquo;One of the consequences of criminal
conduct, is the shame and disgrace which
&mdash;worse than any punishment the evil&hyphen;doer can
suffer&mdash;is brought by it upon the innocent relatives; 
and, if Jack had considered this, perhaps
he would not have acted as he has done,
and have entailed so much misery on his unhappy
parent.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I always detested Mrs. Sheppard,&rdquo; cried
the carpenter's wife bitterly; &ldquo;and, I repeat,
Bedlam's too good for her.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;My dear,&rdquo; observed Wood, &ldquo;you should
be more charitable&wblank;&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Charitable!&rdquo; repeated his wife, &ldquo;that's
your constant cry. Marry, come up! I've</pp>
<pb n="138">
<pp>been a great deal too charitable. Here's Winny
always urging you to go and visit Mrs. Sheppard
in the asylum, and take her this, and send
her that;&mdash;and I've never prevented you, though
such mistaken liberality's enough to provoke a
saint. And, then, forsooth, she must needs
prevent your hanging Jack Sheppard after the
robbery in Wych&hyphen;Street, when you might have
done so. Perhaps you'll call that charity: <it>I</it>
call it defeating the ends of justice. See what
a horrible rascal you've let loose upon the
world!&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;I'm sure, mother,&rdquo; rejoined Winifred, &ldquo;if
any one was likely to feel resentment, I was; 
for no one could be more frightened. But I
was sorry for poor Jack&mdash;as I am still, and
hoped he would mend.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Mend!&rdquo; echoed Mrs. Wood, contemptuously,
&ldquo;he'll never mend till he comes to
Tyburn.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;At least, I will hope so,&rdquo; returned Winifred.
&ldquo;But, as I was saying, I was most
dreadfully frightened on the night of the robbery.
Though so young at the time, I remember
every circumstance distinctly. I was sitting
up, lamenting your departure, dear Thames,</pp>
<pb n="139">
<pp>when, hearing an odd noise, I went to the
landing, and, by the light of a dark lantern, saw
Jack Sheppard stealing up stairs, followed by
two men with crape on their faces. I'm ashamed
to say that I was too much terrified to scream
out&mdash;but ran and hid myself.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Hold your tongue!&rdquo; cried Mrs. Wood. I
declare you throw me into an ague. Do you
think <it>I</it> forget it? Didn't they help themselves
to all the plate and the money&mdash;to several of
my best dresses, and, amongst others, to my
favourite kincob gown; and I've never been
able to get another like it! Marry, come up!
I'd hang 'em all, if I could. Were such a
thing to happen again, I'd never let Mr.
Wood rest till he brought the villains to justice.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I hope such a thing never <it>will</it> happen
again, my dear,&rdquo; observed Wood, mildly; &ldquo;but,
when it does, it will be time to consider what
course we ought to pursue.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Let them attempt it, if they dare!&rdquo; cried
Mrs. Wood, who had worked herself into a passion; 
&ldquo;and, I'll warrant 'em, the boldest robber
among 'em shall repent it, if he comes across
me.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="140">
<p>&ldquo;No doubt, my dear,&rdquo; acquiesced the carpenter,
&ldquo;no doubt.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Thames, who had been more than once on
the point of mentioning his accidental rencounter
with Jack Sheppard, not being altogether
without apprehension, from the fact of his
being in the neighbourhood,&mdash;now judged it
more prudent to say nothing on the subject,
from a fear of increasing Mrs. Wood's displeasure; 
and he was the more readily induced to
do this, as the conversation began to turn upon
his own affairs. Mr. Wood could give him no
further information respecting Sir Rowland
Trenchard than what he had obtained from
Kneebone; but begged him to defer the further
consideration of the line of conduct he
meant to pursue until the morrow, when he
hoped to have a plan to lay before him, of
which he would approve.</p>
<p>The night was now advancing, and the party
began to think of separating. As Mrs. Wood,
who had recovered her good humour, quitted
the room, she bestowed a hearty embrace on
Thames, and she told him, laughingly, that she
would &ldquo;defer all <it>she</it> had to propose to him
until to&hyphen;morrow.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="141">
<p>To&hyphen;morrow! She never beheld it.</p>
<p>After an affectionate parting with Winifred,
Thames was conducted by the carpenter to his
sleeping apartment&mdash;a comfortable cosy chamber; 
such a one, in short, as can only be met
with in the country, with its dimity&hyphen;curtained
bed, its sheets fragrant of lavender, its clean
white furniture, and an atmosphere breathing
of freshness. Left to himself, he took a survey
of the room, and his heart leaped as he
beheld over the chimney&hyphen;piece, a portrait of
himself. It was a copy of the pencil sketch
taken of him nine years ago by Winifred, and
awakened a thousand tender recollections.</p>
<p><pp>When about to retire to rest, the rencounter
with Jack Sheppard again recurred to him, and
he half blamed himself for not acquainting
Mr. Wood with the circumstances, and putting
him upon his guard against the possibility of
an attack. On weighing the matter over, he
grew so uneasy that he resolved to descend,
and inform him of his misgivings. But, when
he got to the door with this intention, he became
ashamed of his fears; and feeling convinced
that Jack&mdash;bad as he might be&mdash;was
not capable of such atrocious conduct as to</pp>
<pb n="142">
<pp>plunder his benefactor twice, he contented himself
with looking to the priming of his pistols,
and placing them near him, to be ready in case
of need, he threw himself on the bed, and
speedily fell asleep.</pp></p></div4>
<pb n="143">
<div4>
<comhd4><idref>Z400030649</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
CHAPTER II.
<subhead>THE BURGLARY AT DOLLIS HILL.</subhead> <attbytes>12Kb</attbytes><reflink>000027</reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z400030649</ID><A1>Ainsworth, William Harrison, 1805&ndash;1882</A1><T1>Jack Sheppard. A Romance.</T1><PBL>Richard Bentley</PBL><Y1>1839</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd4>
<p><smallcap>Thames Darrell's</smallcap> fears were not, however
groundless. Danger, in the form he
apprehended, was lurking outside: nor was he
destined to enjoy long repose. On receiving
the warning note from the ostler, Jack Sheppard
and his companion left Willesden, and
taking&mdash;as a blind&mdash;the direction of Harrow,
returned at night&hyphen;fall by a by&hyphen;lane to Neasdon,
and put up at a little public&hyphen;house called the
Spotted Dog. Here they remained till midnight
when, calling for their reckoning and their
steeds, they left the house.</p>
<p>It was a night well&hyphen;fitted to their enterprise,
calm, still, and profoundly dark. As they
passed beneath the thick trees that shade the
road to Dollis Hill, the gloom was almost impenetrable.
The robbers proceeded singly,
and kept on the grass skirting the road, so
that no noise was made by their horses' feet.</p>
<pb n="144">
<p>As they neared the house, Jack Sheppard,
who led the way, halted, and addressed his
companion in a low voice:&mdash;</p>
<lb><p>&ldquo;I don't half like this job, Blueskin,&rdquo; he
said; &ldquo;it always went against the grain. But,
since I've seen the friend and companion of
my childhood, Thames Darrell, I've no heart
for it. Shall we turn back?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;And disappoint Mr. Wild, captain?&rdquo; remonstrated
the other, in a deferential tone.
&ldquo;You know this is a pet project. It might be
dangerous to thwart him.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Pish!&rdquo; cried Jack: &ldquo;I don't value his
anger a straw. All our fraternity are afraid of
him; but <it>I</it> laugh at his threats. He daren't
quarrel with me: and if he does, let him look
to himself. I've my own reasons for disliking
this job.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Well, you know I always act under your
orders, captain,&rdquo; returned Blueskin; &ldquo;and if
you give the word to retreat, I shall obey, of
course: but I know what Edgeworth Bess will
say when we go home empty&hyphen;handed.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Why, what will she say?&rdquo; inquired Sheppard.</p>
<p>&ldquo;That we were afraid,&rdquo; replied the other; 
&ldquo;but never mind her.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="145">
<p>&ldquo;Ay; but I do mind her,&rdquo; cried Jack, upon
whom his comrade's observation had produced
the desired effect. &ldquo;We'll do it.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;That's right, captain,&rdquo; rejoined Blueskin.
&ldquo;You pledged yourself to Mr. Wild&wblank;&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I did,&rdquo; interrupted Jack; and I never yet
broke an engagement. Though a thief, Jack
Sheppard is a man of his word.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;To be sure he is,&rdquo; acquiesced Blueskin.
&ldquo;I should like to meet the man who would
dare to gainsay it.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;One word before we begin, Blueskin,&rdquo; 
said Jack, authoritatively; &ldquo;in case the family
should be alarmed&mdash;mind, no violence. There's
one person in the house whom I wouldn't
frighten for the world.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Wood's daughter, I suppose?&rdquo; observed
the other.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You've hit it,&rdquo; answered Sheppard.</p>
<p>&ldquo;What say you to carrying her off, captain?&rdquo; 
suggested Blueskin. &ldquo;If you've a
fancy for the girl, we might do it.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;No&mdash;no,&rdquo; laughed Jack. &ldquo;Bess wouldn't
bear a rival. But if you wish to do old Wood
a friendly turn, you may bring off his wife.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;I shouldn't mind ridding him of her,&rdquo; said</pp>
<pb n="146">
<pp>Blueskin, gruffly; &ldquo;and if she comes in my
way, may the devil seize me if I don't make
short work with her!&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;You forget,&rdquo; rejoined Jack, sternly, &ldquo;I've
just said I'll have no violence&mdash;mind that.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>With this, they dismounted; and fastening
their horses to a tree, proceeded towards the
house. It was still so dark, that nothing could
be distinguished except the heavy masses of
timber by which the premises were surrounded; 
but as they advanced, lights were visible in
some of the windows. Presently they came to
a wall, on the other side of which the dog began
to bark violently; but Blueskin tossed him
a piece of prepared meat, and uttering a low
growl, he became silent. They then clambered
over a hedge, and scaling another wall, got into
the garden at the back of the house. Treading
with noiseless step over the soft mould, they
soon reached the building. Arrived there, Jack
felt about for a particular window; and having
discovered the object of his search, and received
the necessary implements from his companion,
he instantly commenced operations. In
a few seconds, the shutter flew open,&mdash;then
the window,&mdash;and they were in the room.</pp>
<pb n="147">
<pp>Jack now carefully closed the shutters, while
Blueskin struck a light, with which he set fire
to a candle. The room they were in was a
sort of closet, with the door locked outside; 
but this was only a moment's obstacle to Jack,
who with a chisel forced back the bolt. The
operation was effected with so much rapidity
and so little noise, that even if any one had
been on the alert, he could scarcely have detected
it. They then took off their boots, and
crept stealthily up stairs, treading upon the
point of their toes so cautiously, that not a
board creaked beneath their weight. Pausing
at each door on the landing, Jack placed his
ear to the key&hyphen;hole, and listened intently.
Having ascertained by the breathing which
room Thames occupied, he speedily contrived
to fasten him in. He then tried the door of
Mr. Wood's bedchamber&mdash;it was locked, with
the key left in it. This occasioned a little delay; 
but Jack, whose skill as a workman in
the particular line he had chosen was unequalled,
and who laughed at difficulties, speedily
cut out a panel by means of a centre&hyphen;bit and
knife, took the key from the other side, and
unlocked the door. Covering his face with a</pp>
<pb n="148">
<pp>crape mask, and taking the candle from his
associate, Jack entered the room; and, pistol
in hand, stepped up to the bed, and approached
the light to the eyes of the sleepers. The loud
noise proceeding from the couch proved that
their slumbers were deep and real; and unconscious
of the danger in which she stood,
Mrs. Wood turned over to obtain a more comfortable
position. During this movement, Jack
grasped the barrel of his pistol, held in his
breath, and motioned to Blueskin, who bared a
long knife, to keep still. The momentary
alarm over, he threw a piece of wash leather
over a bureau, so as to deaden the sound, and
instantly broke it open with a small crow&hyphen;bar.
While he was filling his pockets with golden
coin from this store, Blueskin had pulled the
plate&hyphen;chest from under the bed, and having
forced it open, began filling a canvass bag with
its contents,&mdash;silver coffee&hyphen;pots, chocolate&hyphen;dishes,
waiters, trays, tankards, goblets, and
candlesticks. It might be supposed that these
articles, when thrust together into the bag,
would have jingled; but these skilful practitioners
managed matters so well that no noise
was made. After rifling the room of everything</pp>
<pb>
<edit>[Figure: <bytes>294Kb</bytes>]</edit><figure sys.id="N010116">
<pb n="149">
<pp>portable, including some of Mrs. Wood's
ornaments and wearing apparel, they prepared
to depart. Jack then intimated his intention
of visiting Winifred's chamber, in which several
articles of value were known to be kept; 
but as, notwithstanding his reckless character,
he still retained a feeling of respect for the object
of his boyish affections, he would not
suffer Blueskin to accompany him, so he commanded
him to keep watch over the sleepers&mdash; 
strictly enjoining him, however, to do them no
injury. Again having recourse to the centrebit,
&mdash;for Winifred's door was locked,&mdash;Jack
had nearly cut out a panel, when a sudden outcry
was raised in the carpenter's chamber.
The next moment, a struggle was heard, and
Blueskin appeared at the door, followed by
Mrs. Wood.</pp></p>
<p>Jack instantly extinguished the light, and
called to his comrade to come after him.</p>
<p>But Blueskin found it impossible to make
off,&mdash;at least with the spoil,&mdash;Mrs. Wood
having laid hold of the canvass&hyphen;bag.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Give back the things!&rdquo; cried the lady.
&ldquo;Help!&mdash;help, Mr. Wood!&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="150">
<p>&ldquo;Leave go! thundered Blueskin&mdash;&ldquo;leave
go&mdash;you'd better!&rdquo;&mdash;and he held the sack
as firmly as he could with one hand, while with
the other he searched for his knife.</p>
<p>&ldquo;No, I won't leave go!&rdquo; screamed Mrs.
Wood. &ldquo;Fire!&mdash;murder&mdash;thieves!&mdash;I've
got one of 'em!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Come along,&rdquo; cried Jack.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I can't,&rdquo; answered Blueskin. &ldquo;This shedevil
has got hold of the sack. Leave go, I
tell you!&rdquo; and he forced open the knife with
his teeth.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Help!&mdash;murder!&mdash;thieves!&rdquo; screamed
Mrs. Wood;&mdash;&ldquo;Owen&mdash;Owen!&mdash;Thames,
help!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Coming!&rdquo; cried Mr. Wood, leaping from
the bed. &ldquo;Where are you?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Here,&rdquo; replied Mrs. Wood. &ldquo;Help&mdash; 
I'll hold him!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Leave her,&rdquo; cried Jack, darting down
stairs, amid a furious ringing of bells,&mdash;&ldquo;the
house is alarmed,&mdash;follow me!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Curses light on you!&rdquo; cried Blueskin,
savagely; &ldquo;since you won't be advised, take
your fate.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="151">
<p>And seizing her by the hair, he pulled back
her head, and drew the knife with all his force
across her throat. There was a dreadful stifled
groan, and she fell heavily upon the landing.</p>
<p><pp>The screams of the unfortunate woman had
aroused Thames from his slumbers. Snatching
up his pistols, he rushed to the door, but
to his horror found it fastened. He heard the
struggle on the landing, the fall of the heavy
body, the groan,&mdash;and excited almost to
frenzy by his fears, he succeeded in forcing
open the door. By this time, several of the
terrified domestics appeared with lights. A
terrible spectacle was presented to the young
man's gaze:&mdash;the floor deluged with blood
&mdash;the mangled and lifeless body of Mrs.
Wood,&mdash;Winifred fainted in the arms of a
female attendant,&mdash;and Wood standing beside
them almost in a state of distraction. Thus, in
a few minutes, had this happy family been
plunged into the depths of misery. At this
juncture, a cry was raised by a servant from
below, that the robbers were flying through
the garden. Darting to a window looking in
that direction, Thames threw it up, and discharged</pp>
<pb n="152">
<pp>both his pistols, but without effect.
In another minute, the tramp of horses' feet
told that the perpetrators of the outrage had
effected their escape.</pp></p></div4>
<pb n="153">
<div4>
<comhd4><idref>Z400030650</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
CHAPTER III.
<subhead>JACK SHEPPARD'S QUARREL WITH JONATHAN WILD.</subhead> <attbytes>9Kb</attbytes><reflink>000027</reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z400030650</ID><A1>Ainsworth, William Harrison, 1805&ndash;1882</A1><T1>Jack Sheppard. A Romance.</T1><PBL>Richard Bentley</PBL><Y1>1839</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd4>
<p><smallcap>Scarcely</smallcap> an hour after the horrible occurrence
just related, as Jonathan Wild was seated
in the audience&hyphen;chamber of his residence at
the Old Bailey, occupied, like Peachum, (for
whose portrait he sat,) with his account&hyphen;books
and registers, he was interrupted by the sudden
entrance of Quilt Arnold, who announced
Jack Sheppard and Blueskin.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ah!&rdquo; cried Wild, laying down his pen
and looking up with a smile of satisfaction.
&ldquo;I was just thinking of you Jack. What news.
Have you done the trick at Dollis Hill?&mdash; 
brought off the swag&mdash;eh?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;No;&rdquo; answered Jack, flinging himself sullenly
into a chair, &ldquo;I've not.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Why how's this?&rdquo; exclaimed Jonathan.
&ldquo;Jack Sheppard failed! I'd not believe it, if
any one but himself told me so.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I've not failed,&rdquo; returned Jack, angrily; 
&ldquo;but we've done too much.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="154">
<p>&ldquo;I'm no reader of riddles,&rdquo; said Jonathan.
&ldquo;Speak plainly.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Let this speak for me,&rdquo; said Sheppard,
tossing a heavy bag of money towards him.
&ldquo;You can generally understand that language.
There's more than I undertook to bring. It
has been purchased by blood!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;What! have you cut old Wood's throat?&rdquo; 
asked Wild, with great unconcern, as he took
up the bag.</p>
<p>&ldquo;If I <it>had</it>, you'd not have seen me here,&rdquo; 
replied Jack, sullenly. &ldquo;The blood that has
been spilt is that of his wife.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;It was her own fault,&rdquo; observed Blueskin,
moodily. &ldquo;She wouldn't let me go. I did it
in self&hyphen;defence.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I care not why you did it,&rdquo; said Jack,
sternly. &ldquo;We work together no more.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Come, come, captain,&rdquo; remonstrated Blueskin.
&ldquo;I thought you'd have got rid of your
ill&hyphen;humour by this time. You know as well as
I do that it was accident.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Accident or not,&rdquo; rejoined Sheppard; 
&ldquo;you're no longer pal of mine.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;And so this is my reward for having made
you the tip&hyphen;top cracksman you are,&rdquo; muttered</pp>
<pb n="155">
<pp>Blueskin;&mdash;&ldquo;to be turned off at a moment's
notice, because I silenced a noisy woman. It's
too hard. Think better of it.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;My mind's made up,&rdquo; rejoined Jack,
coldly,&mdash;&ldquo;we part to&hyphen;night.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I'll not go,&rdquo; answered the other. &ldquo;I love
you like a son, and will follow you like a dog.
You'd not know what to do without me, and
shan't drive me off.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Well!&rdquo; remarked Jonathan, who had paid
little attention to the latter part of the conversation; 
&ldquo;this is an awkward business certainly; 
but we must do the best we can in it.
You must keep out of the way till it's blown
over. I can accommodate you below.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I don't require it,&rdquo; returned Sheppard.
&ldquo;I'm tired of the life I'm leading. I shall
quit it and go abroad.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I'll go with you,&rdquo; said Blueskin.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Before either of you go, you will ask my
permission,&rdquo; said Jonathan, coolly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;How!&rdquo; exclaimed Sheppard. &ldquo;Do you
mean to say you will interfere&mdash;&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;I mean to say this,&rdquo; interrupted Wild,
with contemptuous calmness, &ldquo;that I'll
neither allow you to leave England nor the</pp>
<pb n="156">
<pp>profession you've engaged in. I would'nt
allow you to be honest even if you could be so,
&mdash;which I doubt. You are my slave&mdash;and
such you shall continue.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Slave?&rdquo; echoed Jack.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Dare to disobey,&rdquo; continued Jonathan:
&ldquo;neglect my orders, and I will hang you.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Sheppard started to his feet.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Hear me,&rdquo; he cried, restraining himself
with difficulty. &ldquo;It is time you should know
whom you have to deal with. Henceforth, I
utterly throw off the yoke you have laid upon
me. I will neither stir hand nor foot for you
more. Attempt to molest me, and I split.
You are more in my power than I am in yours.
Jack Sheppard is a match for Jonathan Wild,
any day.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;That he is,&rdquo; added Blueskin, approvingly.</p>
<p>Jonathan smiled contemptuously.</p>
<p>&ldquo;One motive alone shall induce me to go on
with you,&rdquo; said Jack.</p>
<p>&ldquo;What's that?&rdquo; asked Wild.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The youth whom you delivered to Van&hyphen;Galgebrok,
&mdash;Thames Darrell, is returned.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Impossible!&rdquo; cried Jonathan. &ldquo;He was
thrown overboard, and perished at sea.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="157">
<p>&ldquo;He is alive,&rdquo; replied Jack, &ldquo;I have seen
him, and might have conversed with him if I
had chosen. Now, I know you can restore
him to his rights, if you choose. Do so; and
I am yours as heretofore.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Humph!&rdquo; exclaimed Jonathan.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Your answer!&rdquo; cried Sheppard. &ldquo;Yes,
or no?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I will make no terms with you,&rdquo; rejoined
Wild, sternly. &ldquo;You have defied me, and
shall feel my power. You have been useful to
me, or I would not have spared you thus long.
I swore to hang you two years ago, but I deferred
my purpose.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Deferred!&rdquo; echoed Sheppard.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Hear me out,&rdquo; said Jonathan. &ldquo;You
came hither under my protection, and you shall
depart freely,&mdash;nay, more, you shall have an
hour's grace. After that time, I shall place my
setters on your heels.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You cannot prevent my departure,&rdquo; replied
Jack, dauntlessly, &ldquo;and therefore your
offer is no favour. But I tell you in return,
I shall take no pains to hide myself. If you
want me, you know where to find me.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="158">
<p>&ldquo;An hour,&rdquo; said Jonathan, looking at his
watch,&mdash;&ldquo;remember!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;If you send for me to the Cross Shovels
in the Mint, where I'm going with Blueskin,
I will surrender myself without resistance,&rdquo; 
returned Jack.</p>
<p>&ldquo;You will spare the officers a labour then,&rdquo; 
rejoined Jonathan.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Can't I settle this business, captain,&rdquo; muttered
Blueskin, drawing a pistol.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Don't harm him,&rdquo; said Jack, carelessly:
&ldquo;he dares not do it.&rdquo;</p>
<p>So saying, he left the room.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Blueskin,&rdquo; said Jonathan, as that worthy
was about to follow, &ldquo;I advise you to remain
with me.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;No,&rdquo; answered the ruffian, moodily. &ldquo;If
you arrest him, you must arrest me also.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;As you will,&rdquo; said Jonathan, seating himself.</p>
<p><pp>Jack and his comrade went to the Mint,
where he was joined by Edgeworth Bess, with
whom he sat down most unconcernedly to
supper. His revelry, however, was put an
end to at the expiration of the time mentioned</pp>
<pb n="159">
<pp>by Jonathan, by the entrance of a posse of constables
with Quilt Arnold and Abraham Mendez
at their head. Jack, to the surprise of all
his companions, at once surrendered himself:
but Blueskin would have made a fierce resistance,
and attempted a rescue if he had not
been ordered by his leader to desist. He then
made off. Edgeworth Bess, who passed for
Sheppard's wife, was secured. They were hurried
before a magistrate, and charged by Jonathan
Wild with various robberies; but, as
Jack Sheppard stated that he had most important
disclosures to make, as well as charges
to bring forward against his accuser, he was
committed with his female companion to the
New Prison in Clerkenwell for further examination.</pp></p></div4>
<pb n="160">
<div4>
<comhd4><idref>Z400030651</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
CHAPTER IV.
<subhead>JACK SHEPPARD'S ESCAPE FROM THE NEW PRISON.</subhead> <attbytes>8Kb</attbytes><reflink>000027</reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z400030651</ID><A1>Ainsworth, William Harrison, 1805&ndash;1882</A1><T1>Jack Sheppard. A Romance.</T1><PBL>Richard Bentley</PBL><Y1>1839</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd4>
<p><pp><smallcap>In</smallcap> consequence of Jack Sheppard's desperate
character, it was judged expedient by the
keeper of the New Prison to load him with
fetters of unusual weight, and to place him in
a cell which, from its strength and security, was
called the Newgate Ward. The ward in which
he was confined, was about six yards in length,
and three in width, and in height, might be
about twelve feet. The windows which were
about nine feet from the floor, had no glass; 
but were secured by thick iron bars, and
an oaken beam. Along the floor ran an
iron bar to which Jack's chain was attached,
so that he could move along it from
one end of the chamber to the other. No
prisoner except Edgeworth Bess was placed in
the same cell with him. Jack was in excellent
spirits; and by his wit, drollery, and agreeable
demeanour, speedily became a great favourite</pp>
<pb n="161">
<pp>with the turnkey, who allowed him every indulgence
consistent with his situation. The
report of his detention caused an immense
sensation. Numberless charges were preferred
against him, amongst others, information was
lodged of the robbery at Dollis Hill, and
murder of Mrs. Wood, and a large reward
offered for the apprehension of Blueskin; and
as, in addition to this, Jack had threatened to
impeach Wild, his next examination was
looked forward to with the greatest interest.</pp></p>
<p><pp>The day before this examination was appointed
to take place&mdash;the third of the prisoner's
detention&mdash;an old man, respectably
dressed, requested permission to see him.
Jack's friends were allowed to visit him; but,
as he had openly avowed his intention of attempting
an escape, their proceedings were
narrowly watched. The old man was conducted
to Jack's cell by the turnkey, who
remained near him during the interview. He
appeared to be a stranger to the prisoner, and
the sole motive of his visit, curiosity. After
a brief conversation, which Sheppard sustained
with his accustomed liveliness, the old man
turned to Bess and addressed a few words of</pp>
<pb n="162">
<pp>common&hyphen;place gallantry to her. While this
was going on, Jack suddenly made a movement
which attracted the turnkey's attention; 
and during that interval the old man slipped
some articles wrapped in a handkerchief into
Bess's hands, who instantly secreted them in
her bosom. The turnkey looked round the
next moment, but the man&oelig;uvre escaped his
observation. After a little further discourse
the old man took his departure.</pp></p>
<p>Left alone with Edgeworth Bess, Jack burst
into a loud laugh of exultation.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Blueskin's a friend in need,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;His
disguise was capital; but I detected it in a
moment. Has he given you the tools?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;He has,&rdquo; replied Bess, producing the
handkerchief.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Bravo!&rdquo; cried Sheppard, examining its
contents, which proved to be a file, a chisel,
two or three gimblets, and a piercer.
&ldquo;Jonathan Wild shall find it's not easy to
detain me. As sure as he's now living, I'll
pay him a visit in the Old Bailey before morning.
And then I'll pay off old scores. It's
almost worth while being sent to prison to
have the pleasure of escaping. I shall now be</pp>
<pb n="163">
<pp>able to test my skill.&rdquo; And running on in this
way, he carefully concealed the tools.</pp></p>
<p>Whether the turnkey entertained any suspicions
of the old man, Jack could not tell,
but that night he was more than usually rigorous
in his search; and having carefully
examiend the prisoners and finding nothing
to excite his suspicions, he departed tolerably
satisfied.</p>
<p><pp>As soon as he was certain he should be
disturbed no more, Jack set to work, and with
the aid of the file in less than an hour had
freed himself from his fetters. With Bess's assistance
he then climbed up to the window,
which, as has just been stated, was secured
by iron bars of great thickness crossed by a
stout beam of oak. The very sight of these
impediments, would have appalled a less courageous
spirit than Sheppard's&mdash;but nothing
could daunt him. To work then he went, and
with wonderful industry filed off two of the
iron bars. Just as he completed this operation,
the file broke. The oaken beam, nine
inches in thickness, was now the sole but most
formidable obstacle to his flight. With his</pp>
<pb n="164">
<pp>gimblet he contrived to bore a number
of holes so close together that at last one
end of the bar, being completely pierced
through, yielded; and pursuing the same plan
with the other extremity, it fell out altogether.</pp></p>
<p><pp>This last operation was so fatiguing, that for
a short time he was obliged to pause to recover
the use of his fingers. He then descended; 
and having induced Bess to take off some
part of her clothing, he tore the gown and
petticoat into shreds and twisted them into a
sort of rope which he fastened to the lower
bars of the window. With some difficulty he
contrived to raise her to the window, and with
still greater difficulty to squeeze her through it
&mdash;her bulk being much greater than his own.
He then made a sort of running noose, passed
it over her body, and taking firmly hold of the
bars, prepared to guide her descent. But
Bess could scarcely summon resolution enough
to hazard the experiment; and it was only on
Jack's urgent intreaties, and even threats, that
she could be prevailed on to trust herself to
the frail tenure of the rope he had prepared.</pp>
<pb>
<edit>[Figure: <bytes>430Kb</bytes>]</edit><figure sys.id="N010117">
<pb n="165">
<pp>At length, however, she threw herself off; and
Jack carefully guiding the rope she landed in
safety.</pp></p>
<p>The next moment he was by her side.</p>
<p>But the great point was still unaccomplished.
They had escaped from the New Prison, it is
true; but the wall of Clerkenwell Bridewell, by
which that jail was formerly surrounded, and
which was more than twenty feet high, and
protected by formidable and bristling <it>chevaux
de frise</it>, remained to be scaled. Jack, however,
had an expedient for mastering this difficulty.
He ventured to the great gates, and by inserting
his gimblets into the wood at intervals, so
as to form points upon which he could rest his
foot, he contrived to ascend them; and when at
the top, having fastened a portion of his dress to
the spikes, he managed, not without considerable
risk, to draw up his female companion.
Once over the iron spikes, Bess exhibited no
reluctance to be let down on the other side of
the wall. Having seen his mistress safe down,
Jack instantly descended, leaving the best part
of his clothes, as a memorial of his flight, to the
jailor.</p>
<p>And thus he effected his escape from the
New Prison.</p></div4>
<pb n="166">
<div4>
<comhd4><idref>Z400030652</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
CHAPTER V.
<subhead>THE DISGUISE.</subhead> <attbytes>40Kb</attbytes><reflink>000027</reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z400030652</ID><A1>Ainsworth, William Harrison, 1805&ndash;1882</A1><T1>Jack Sheppard. A Romance.</T1><PBL>Richard Bentley</PBL><Y1>1839</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd4>
<p><pp><smallcap>In</smallcap> a hollow in the meadows behind the
prison whence Jack Sheppard had escaped,&mdash; 
for, at this time, the whole of the now thickly&hyphen;peopled
district north of Clerkenwell Bridewell
was open country, stretching out in fertile
fields in the direction of Islington&mdash;and about
a quarter of a mile off, stood a solitary hovel,
known as Black Mary's Hole. This spot,
which still retains its name, acquired the appellation
from an old crone who lived there, and
who, in addition to a very equivocal character
for honesty, enjoyed the reputation of being a
witch. Without enquiring into the correctness
of the latter part of the story, it may be sufficient
to state, that Black Mary was a person
in whom Jack Sheppard thought he could confide,
and, as Edgeworth Bess was incapable of
much further exertion, he determined to leave
her in the old woman's care till the following</pp>
<pb n="167">
<pp>night, while he shifted for himself and fulfilled
his design&mdash;for, however rash or hazardous a
project might be, if once conceived, Jack always
executed it,&mdash;of visiting Jonathan Wild at
his house in the Old Bailey.</pp></p>
<p><pp>It was precisely two o'clock on the morning
of Whitmonday, the 25th of May 1724, when
the remarkable escape before detailed was completed:
and, though it wanted full two hours
to daybreak, the glimmer of a waning moon
prevented it from being totally dark. Casting
a hasty glance, as he was about to turn an
angle of the wall, at the great gates and upper
windows of the prison, and perceiving no symptoms
of pursuit, Jack proceeded towards the
hovel at a very deliberate pace, carefully assisting
his female companion over every obstacle in the
road, and bearing her in his arms when, as was
more than once the case, she sank from fright
and exhaustion. In this way he crossed one
or two public gardens and a bowling&hyphen;green,
&mdash;the neighbourhood of Clerkenwell then
abounded in such places of amusement,&mdash; 
passed the noted Ducking Pond, where Black
Mary had been frequently immersed; and,</pp>
<pb n="168">
<pp>striking off to the left across the fields, arrived
in a few minutes at his destination.</pp></p>
<p>Descending the hollow, or rather excavation,
&mdash;for it was an old disused clay&hyphen;pit, at the
bottom of which the cottage was situated,&mdash;he
speedily succeeded in arousing the ancient sibyl,
and having committed Edgeworth Bess to her
care, with a promise of an abundant reward in
case she watched diligently over her safety,
and attended to her comforts till his return,&mdash; 
to all which Black Mary readily agreed,&mdash;he
departed with a heart lightened of half its load.</p>
<p><pp>Jack's first object was to seek out Blueskin,
whom he had no doubt he should find at the
New Mint, at Wapping, for the Old Mint no
longer afforded a secure retreat to the robber; 
and, with this view, he made the best of his
way along a bye&hyphen;lane leading towards Hockley&hyphen;in&hyphen;the&hyphen;Hole.
He had not proceeded far when
he was alarmed by the tramp of a horse, which
seemed to be rapidly approaching, and he had
scarcely time to leap the hedge and conceal
himself behind a tree, when a tall man, enveloped
in an ample cloak, with his hat pulled
over his brows, rode by at full speed. Another</pp>
<pb n="169">
<pp>horseman followed quickly at the heels of the
first; but just as he passed the spot where
Jack stood, his steed missed its footing, and
fell. Either ignorant of the accident, or heedless
of it, the foremost horseman pursued his
way without even turning his head.</pp></p>
<p>Conceiving the opportunity too favourable to
be lost, Jack sprang suddenly over the hedge,
and before the man, who was floundering on
the ground with one foot in the stirrup, could
extricate himself from his embarrassing position,
secured his pistols, which he drew from
the holsters, and held them to his head. The
fellow swore lustily, in a voice which Jack instantly
recognised as that of Quilt Arnold, and
vainly attempted to rise and draw his sword.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Dog!&rdquo; thundered Sheppard, putting the
muzzle of the pistol so close to the janizary's
car, that the touch of the cold iron made him
start, &ldquo;don't you know me?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Blood and thunder!&rdquo; exclaimed Quilt,
opening his eyes with astonishment. &ldquo;It can't
be Captain Sheppard!&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;It <it>is</it>,&rdquo; replied Jack; &ldquo;and you had better
have met the devil on your road than me. Do
you remember what I said when you took me</pp>
<pb n="170">
<pp>at the Mint four days ago? I told you my turn
would come. It <it>has</it> come,&mdash;and sooner than
you expected.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;So I find, captain,&rdquo; rejoined Quilt, submissively; 
&ldquo;but you're too noble&hyphen;hearted to
take advantage of my situation. Besides, I
acted for others, and not for myself.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I know it,&rdquo; replied Sheppard, &ldquo;and therefore
I spare your life.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I was sure you wouldn't injure me, captain,&rdquo; 
remarked Quilt, in a wheedling tone,
while he felt about for his sword; &ldquo;you're far
too brave to strike a fallen man.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ah! traitor!&rdquo; cried Jack, who had noticed
the movement; &ldquo;make such another attempt,
and it shall cost you your life.&rdquo; So saying, he
unbuckled the belt to which the janizary's
hanger was attached, and fastened it to his own
girdle.</p>
<p>&ldquo;And now,&rdquo; he continued, sternly, &ldquo;was it
your master who has just ridden by?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;No,&rdquo; answered Quilt, sullenly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Who, then?&rdquo; demanded Jack. &ldquo;Speak,
or I fire!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Well, if you <it>will</it> have it, it's Sir Rowland
Trenchard.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="171">
<p>&ldquo;Sir Rowland Trenchard!&rdquo; echoed Jack, in
amazement. &ldquo;What are you doing with
him?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;It's a long story, captain, and I've no
breath to tell it,&mdash;unless you choose to release
me,&rdquo; rejoined Quilt.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Get up, then,&rdquo; said Jack, freeing his foot
from the stirrup. &ldquo;Now&mdash;begin.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Quilt, however, seemed unwilling to speak.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I should be sorry to proceed to extremities,&rdquo; 
continued Sheppard, again raising the
pistol.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Well, since you force me to betray my
master's secrets,&rdquo; replied Quilt, sullenly, &ldquo;I've
ridden express to Manchester to deliver a message
to Sir Rowland.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Respecting Thames Darrell?&rdquo; observed
Jack.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Why, how the devil did you happen to
guess that?&rdquo; cried the janizary.</p>
<p>&ldquo;No matter,&rdquo; replied Sheppard. &ldquo;I'm
glad to find I'm right. You informed Sir
Rowland that Thames Darrell was returned?&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Exactly so;&rdquo; replied Quilt, &ldquo;and he instantly
decided upon returning to London with</pp>
<pb n="172">
<pp>me. We've ridden post all the way, and I'm
horribly tired, or you wouldn't have mastered
me so easily.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Perhaps not,&rdquo; replied Jack, to whom an
idea had suddenly occurred. &ldquo;Now, sir, I'll
trouble you for your coat. I've left mine on
the spikes of the New Prison, and must borrow
yours.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Why, surely you can't be in earnest, captain.
You wouldn't rob Mr. Wild's chief janizary?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I'd rob Mr. Wild himself if I met him,&rdquo; 
retorted Jack. &ldquo;Come, off with it, sirrah, or
I'll blow out your brains, in the first place,
and strip you afterwards.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Well, rather than you should commit so
great a crime, captain, here it is,&rdquo; replied Quilt,
handing him the garment in question. &ldquo;Anything
else?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Your waistcoat.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Zounds! captain, I shall get my death of
cold. I was in hopes you'd be content with
my hat and wig.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I shall require them as well,&rdquo; rejoined
Sheppard; &ldquo;and your boots.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="173">
<p>&ldquo;My boots! Fire and fury! They won't
fit you; they are too large. Besides, how am
I to ride home without them?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Don't distress yourself,&rdquo; returned Jack,
&ldquo;you shall walk. Now,&rdquo; he added, as his
commands were reluctantly obeyed, &ldquo;help me
on with them.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Quilt knelt down, as if he meant to comply; 
but, watching his opportunity, he made a
sudden grasp at Sheppard's leg, with the intention
of overthrowing him.</p>
<p>But Jack was too nimble for him. Striking
out his foot, he knocked half a dozen teeth
down the janizary's throat; and, seconding the
kick with a blow on the head from the buttend
of the pistol, stretched him, senseless and
bleeding on the ground.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Like master like man,&rdquo; observed Jack as
he rolled the inanimate body to the side of the
road. &ldquo;From Jonathan Wild's confidential
servant what could be expected but treachery?&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>With this, he proceeded to dress himself in
Quilt Arnold's clothes, pulled the wig over his
face and eyes so as completely to conceal his
features, slouched the hat over his brows, drew</pp>
<pb n="174">
<pp>the huge boots above his knees, and muffled
himself up in the best way he could. On
searching the coat, he found, amongst other
matters, a mask, a key, and a pocket&hyphen;book.
The latter appeared to contain several papers,
which Jack carefully put by, in the hope that
they might turn out of importance in a scheme
of vengeance which he meditated against the
thieftaker. He then mounted the jaded hack,
which had long since regained its legs, and was
quietly browsing the grass at the road&hyphen;side, and,
striking spurs into its side, rode off. He had
not proceeded far when he encountered Sir
Rowland, who, having missed his attendant,
had returned to look after him.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;What has delayed you?&rdquo; demanded the
knight, impatiently.</p>
<p>&ldquo;My horse has had a fall,&rdquo; replied Jack, assuming
to perfection&mdash;for he was a capital
mimic&mdash;the tones of Quilt Arnold. &ldquo;It was
some time before I could get him to move.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I fancied I heard voices,&rdquo; rejoined Sir
Rowland.</p>
<p>&ldquo;So did I,&rdquo; answered Jack; &ldquo;we had better
move on. This is a noted place for high&hyphen;waymen.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="175">
<p>&ldquo;I thought you told me that the rascal
who has so long been the terror of the town&mdash; 
Jack Sheppard&mdash;was in custody.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;So he is,&rdquo; returned Jack; &ldquo;but there's
no saying how long he may remain so. Besides,
there are greater rascals than Jack Sheppard
at liberty, Sir Rowland.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Sir Rowland made no reply, but angrily
quickened his pace. The pair then descended
Saffron&hyphen;hill, threaded Field&hyphen;lane, and, entering
Holborn, passed over the little bridge which
then crossed the muddy waters of Fleet&hyphen;ditch,
mounted Snow&hyphen;hill, and soon drew in the
bridle before Jonathan Wild's door. Aware of
Quilt Arnold's mode of proceeding, Jack instantly
dismounted, and, instead of knocking,
opened the door with the pass&hyphen;key. The
porter instantly made his appearance, and
Sheppard ordered him to take care of the
horses.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Well, what sort of journey have you had,
Quilt?&rdquo; asked the man as he hastened to assist
Sir Rowland to dismount.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Oh! we've lost no time, as you perceive,&rdquo; 
replied Jack. &ldquo;Is the governor within?&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="176">
<p>&ldquo;Yes; you'll find him in the audience&hyphen;chamber.
He has got Blueskin with him.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ah! indeed! what's he doing here?&rdquo; inquired
Jack.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Come to buy off Jack Sheppard, I suppose,&rdquo; 
replied the fellow. &ldquo;But it won't do.
Mr. Wild has made up his mind; and, when
that's the case, all the persuasion on earth
won't turn him. Jack will be tried to&hyphen;morrow; 
and, as sure as my name's Obadiah Lemon
he'll take up his quarters at the King's&hyphen;Head,&rdquo; 
pointing to Newgate, &ldquo;over the way.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Well, we shall see,&rdquo; replied Jack. &ldquo;Look
to the horses, Obadiah. This way, Sir Rowland.&rdquo;</p>
<p>As familiar as Quilt Arnold himself with
every part of Wild's mysterious abode, as well
as with the ways of its inmates, Jack, without
a moment's hesitation, took up a lamp which
was burning in the hall, and led his companion
up the great stone stairs. Arrived at the audience&hyphen;chamber,
he set down the light upon a
stand, threw open the door, and announced in
a loud voice, but with the perfect intonation of
the person he represented,&mdash;&ldquo;Sir Rowland
Trenchard.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="177">
<p>Jonathan, who was engaged in conversation
with Blueskin, instantly arose, and bowed with
cringing ceremoniousness to the knight. The
latter haughtily returned his salutation, and
flung himself, as if exhausted, into a chair.</p>
<p>&ldquo;You've arrived sooner than I expected,
Sir Rowland,&rdquo; observed the thieftaker. &ldquo;Lost
no time on the road&mdash;eh?&mdash;I didn't expect
you till to&hyphen;morrow at the earliest. Excuse me
an instant while I dismiss this person.&mdash;You've
your answer, Blueskin,&rdquo; he added, pushing
that individual, who seemed unwilling to depart,
towards the door; &ldquo;it's useless to urge
the matter further. Jack is registered in the
Black Book.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;One word before I go,&rdquo; urged Blueskin.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Not a syllable,&rdquo; replied Wild. &ldquo;If you
talk as long as an Old Bailey counsel, you'll
not alter my determination.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Won't my life do as well as his?&rdquo; supplicated
the other.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Humph!&rdquo; exclaimed Jonathan, doubtfully.
&ldquo;And you would surrender yourself&mdash; 
eh?&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;I'll surrender myself at once, if you'll engage
to bring him off; and you'll get the reward</pp>
<pb n="178">
<pp>from old Wood. It's two hundred
pounds. Recollect that.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Faithful fellow!&rdquo; murmured Jack. &ldquo;I forgive
him his disobedience.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Will you do it?&rdquo; persisted Blueskin.</p>
<p>&ldquo;No,&rdquo; replied Wild; &ldquo;and I've only listened
to your absurd proposal to see how far
your insane attachment to this lad would
carry you.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I <it>do</it> love him,&rdquo; cried Blueskin, &ldquo;and
that's the long and short of it. I've taught
him all he can do; and there isn't his fellow,
and never will be again. I've seen many a
clever cracksman, but never one like him. If
you hang Jack Sheppard, you'll cut off the
flower o' the purfession. But I'll not believe
it of you. It's all very well to read him a
lesson, and teach him obedience; but you've
gone far enough for that.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Not quite,&rdquo; rejoined the thieftaker, significantly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Well,&rdquo; growled Blueskin, &ldquo;you've had
my offer.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;And you my warning,&rdquo; retorted Wild.
&ldquo;Good night!&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Blueskin,&rdquo; whispered Jack, in his natural</pp>
<pb n="179">
<pp>tones, as the other passed him, &ldquo;wait without.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Powers o' mercy!&rdquo; cried Blueskin starting.</p>
<p>&ldquo;What's the matter?&rdquo; demanded Jonathan,
harshly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Nothin'&mdash;nothin',&rdquo; returned Blueskin; 
&ldquo;only I thought&mdash;&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You saw the hangman, no doubt,&rdquo; said
Jack. &ldquo;Take courage, man; it is only Quilt
Arnold. Come, make yourself scarce. Don't
you see Mr. Wild's busy.&rdquo; And then he added,
in an under tone, &ldquo;Conceal yourself outside,
and be within call.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Blueskin nodded, and left the room. Jack
affected to close the door, but left it slightly ajar.</p>
<p>&ldquo;What did you say to him?&rdquo; inquired Jonathan,
suspiciously.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I advised him not to trouble you farther
about Jack Sheppard,&rdquo; answered the supposed
janizary.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;He seems infatuated about the lad,&rdquo; observed
Wild. &ldquo;I shall be obliged to hang him
to keep him company. And now, Sir Rowland,&rdquo; 
he continued, turning to the knight, &ldquo;to our
own concerns. It's a long time since we met,
eight years and more. I hope you've enjoyed</pp>
<pb n="180">
<pp>your health. 'S life! you are wonderfully
altered. I should scarcely have known you.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>The knight was indeed greatly changed.
Though not much passed the middle term of
life, he seemed prematurely stricken with old
age. His frame was wasted, and slightly bent; 
his eyes were hollow, his complexion haggard,
and his beard, which had remained unshorn
during his hasty journey, was perfectly white.
His manner, however, was as stern and haughty
as ever, and his glances retained their accustomed
fire.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I did not come hither to consult you as to
the state of my health, sir,&rdquo; he observed, displeased
by Jonathan's allusion to the alteration
in his appearance.</p>
<p>&ldquo;True,&rdquo; replied Wild. &ldquo;You were no
doubt surprised by the unlooked&hyphen;for intelligence
I sent you of your nephew's return?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Was it <it>unlooked&hyphen;for</it> on your part?&rdquo; demanded
the knight, distrustfully.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;On my soul, yes,&rdquo; rejoined Jonathan. &ldquo;I
should as soon have expected the bones of
Tom Sheppard to reunite themselves and
walk out of that case, as Thames Darrell to
return. The skipper, Van Galgebrok, affirmed</pp>
<pb n="181">
<pp>to me,&mdash;nay, gave me the additional testimony
of two of his crew,&mdash;that he was thrown overboard.
But it appears he was picked up by
fishermen, and carried to France, where he has
remained ever since, and where it would have
been well for him if he had remained altogether.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Have you seen him?&rdquo; asked Trenchard.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I have,&rdquo; replied Wild; &ldquo;and nothing but
the evidence of my senses would have made me
believe he was living, after the positive assurance
I received to the contrary. He is at
present with Mr. Wood,&mdash;the person whom
you may remember adopted him,&mdash;at Dollis
Hill, near Willesden; and it's a singular but
fortunate circumstance, so far as we are concerned,
that Mrs. Wood chanced to be murdered
by Blueskin, the fellow who just left the
room, on the very night of his return, as it has
thrown the house into such confusion, and so
distracted them, that he has had no time as
yet for hostile movements.</p>
<p>&ldquo;And what course do you propose to pursue
in reference to him?&rdquo; asked Sir Rowland.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;My plan is a very simple one,&rdquo; rejoined</pp>
<pb n="182">
<pp>the thieftaker, smiling bitterly. &ldquo;I would
treat him as you treated his father, Sir Rowland.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Murder him!&rdquo; cried Trenchard, shuddering.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ay, murder him, if you like the term,&rdquo; 
returned Wild. &ldquo;I should call it putting him
out of the way. But, no matter how you
phrase it, the end is the same.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I cannot consent to it,&rdquo; replied Sir Rowland
firmly. &ldquo;Since the sea has spared him,
I will spare him. It is in vain to struggle
against the arm of fate. I will shed no more
blood.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;And perish upon the gibbet,&rdquo; rejoined
Jonathan, contemptuously.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Flight is still left me,&rdquo; replied Trenchard.
&ldquo;I can escape to France.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;And do you think I'll allow you to depart,&rdquo; 
cried Jonathan in a menacing tone, &ldquo;and compromise
<it>my</it> safety? No, no. We are linked
together in this matter, and must go through
with it. You cannot&mdash;shall not retreat.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Death and hell!&rdquo; cried Sir Rowland,
rising and drawing his sword; &ldquo;do you</pp>
<pb n="183">
<pp>think you can shackle my free will, villain?&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;In this particular instance I do, Sir Rowland,&rdquo; 
replied Jonathan, calmly, &ldquo;because
you are wholly in my power. But be patient,
I am your fast friend. Thames Darrell MUST
die. Our mutual safety requires it. Leave the
means to me.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;More blood! more blood!&rdquo; cried Trenchard,
passing his hand with agony across his
brow. &ldquo;Shall I never banish those horrible
phantoms from my couch&mdash;the father with his
bleeding breast and dripping hair!&mdash;the mother
with her wringing hands and looks of vengeance
and reproach!&mdash;And must another be
added to their number&mdash;their son! Horror!&mdash; 
let me be spared this new crime! And yet the
gibbet&ndash;my name tarnished&mdash;my escutcheon
blotted by the hangman!&mdash;No, I cannot
submit to that.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I should think not,&rdquo; observed Jonathan,
who had some practice in the knight's moods,
and knew how to humour him. &ldquo;It's a miserable
weakness to be afraid of bloodshed.</p>
<p><pp>The general who gives an order for wholesale
carnage never sleeps a wink the less</pp>
<pb n="184">
<pp>soundly for the midnight groans of his victims,
and we should deride him as a coward if he
did. And life is much the same, whether taken
in battle, on the couch, or by the road&hyphen;side. Besides
those whom I've slain with my own hands,
I've brought upwards of thirty persons to the
gallows. Most of their relics are in yonder cases; 
but I don't remember that any of them have
disturbed my rest. The mode of destruction
makes no difference. It's precisely the same
thing to me to bid my janizaries cut Thames
Darrell's throat, as to order Jack Sheppard's
execution.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>As Jonathan said this, Jack's hand involuntarily
sought a pistol.</p>
<p>&ldquo;But to the point,&rdquo; continued Wild, unconscious
of the peril in which the remark had
placed him,&mdash;&ldquo;to the point. On the terms
that procured your liberation from Newgate, I
will free you from this new danger.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Those terms were a third of my estate,&rdquo; 
observed Trenchard bitterly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;What of that?&rdquo; rejoined Jonathan. &ldquo;Any
price was better than your head. If Thames
Darrell escapes, you will lose both life and
property.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="185">
<p>&ldquo;True, true,&rdquo; replied the knight, with an
agonized look; &ldquo;there is no alternative.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;None whatever,&rdquo; rejoined Wild. &ldquo;Is it
a bargain?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Take half of my estate&mdash;take all&mdash;my life,
if you will&mdash;I am weary of it!&rdquo; cried Trenchard
passionately.</p>
<p>&ldquo;No,&rdquo; replied Jonathan, &ldquo;I'll not take you
at your word, as regards the latter proposition.
We shall both, I hope, live to enjoy
our shares&mdash;long after Thames Darrell is forgotten
&mdash;ha! ha! A third of your estate I
accept. And as these things should always be
treated as matters of business, I'll just draw
up a memorandum of our arrangement.&rdquo;</p>
<p>And, as he spoke, he took up a sheet of
paper, and hastily traced a few lines upon
it.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Sign this,&rdquo; he said, pushing the document
towards Sir Rowland.</p>
<p>The knight mechanically complied with his
request.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Enough!&rdquo; cried Jonathan, eagerly pocketing
the memorandum. &ldquo;And now, in return
for your liberality, I'll inform you of a secret</pp>
<pb n="186">
<pp>with which it is important you should be
acquainted.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;A secret!&rdquo; exclaimed Trenchard. &ldquo;Concerning
whom?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Mrs. Sheppard,&rdquo; replied Jonathan, mysteriously.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Mrs. Sheppard!&rdquo; echoed Jack, surprised
out of his caution.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ah!&rdquo; exclaimed Wild, looking angrily
towards his supposed attendant.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I beg pardon, sir,&rdquo; replied Jack, with the
accent and manner of the janizary; &ldquo;I was
betrayed into the exclamation by my surprise
that anything in which Sir Rowland Trenchard
was interested could have reference to so humble
a person as Mrs. Sheppard.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Be pleased, then, in future not to let your
surprise find vent in words,&rdquo; rejoined Jonathan,
sternly. &ldquo;My servants, like Eastern
mutes, must have eyes, and ears,&mdash;and <it>hands</it>,
if need be,&mdash;but no tongues. You understand
me, sirrah?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Perfectly,&rdquo; replied Jack. &ldquo;I'm dumb.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Your secret?&rdquo; demanded Trenchard, impatiently.</p>
<pb n="187">
<p>&ldquo;I need not remind you, Sir Rowland,&rdquo; replied
Wild, &ldquo;that you had two sisters&mdash;Aliva
and Constance.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Both are dead,&rdquo; observed the knight,
gloomily.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Not so;&rdquo; answered Wild. &ldquo;Constance
is yet living.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Constance alive! Impossible!&rdquo; ejaculated
Trenchard.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I've proofs to the contrary,&rdquo; replied Jonathan.</p>
<p>&ldquo;If this is the case, where is she?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;In Bedlam,&rdquo; replied the thieftaker, with a
Satanic grin.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Gracious heaven!&rdquo; exclaimed the knight,
upon whom a light seemed suddenly to break.
&ldquo;You mentioned Mrs. Sheppard. What has
she to do with Constance Trenchard?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Mrs. Sheppard <it>is</it> Constance Trenchard,&rdquo; 
replied Jonathan, maliciously.</p>
<p>Here Jack Sheppard was unable to repress
an exclamation of astonishment.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Again,&rdquo; cried Jonathan, sternly: &ldquo;beware!&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;What!&rdquo; vociferated Trenchard. &ldquo;My</pp>
<pb n="188">
<pp>sister the wife of one condemned felon! the
parent of another! It cannot be.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;It <it>is</it> so, nevertheless,&rdquo; replied Wild.
&ldquo;Stolen by a gipsy when scarcely five years
old, Constance Trenchard, after various vicissitudes,
was carried to London, where she
lived in great poverty, with the dregs of society.
It is useless to trace out her miserable
career; though I can easily do so if you require
it. To preserve herself, however, from destitution,
or what she considered worse, she wedded
a journeyman carpenter, named Sheppard.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Alas! that one so highly born should submit
to such a degradation?&rdquo; groaned the
knight.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;I see nothing surprising in it,&rdquo; rejoined
Jonathan. &ldquo;In the first place, she had no
knowledge of her birth; and, consequently, no
false pride to get rid of. In the second, she
was wretchedly poor, and assailed by temptations
of which you can form no idea. Distress
like hers might palliate far greater offences than
she ever committed. With the same inducements
we should all do the same thing. Poor</pp>
<pb n="189">
<pp>girl! she was beautiful once; so beautiful as to
make <it>me</it>, who care little for the allurements of
women, fancy myself enamoured of her.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>Jack Sheppard again sought his pistol, and
was only withheld from levelling it at the thieftaker's
head, by the hope that he might gather
some further information respecting his mother.
And he had good reason before long to congratulate
himself on his forbearance.</p>
<p>&ldquo;What proof have you of the truth of this
story?&rdquo; inquired Trenchard.</p>
<p>&ldquo;This,&rdquo; replied Jonathan, taking a paper
from a portfolio, and handing it to the knight,
&ldquo;this written evidence, signed by Martha
Cooper, the gipsy, by whom the girl was
stolen, and who was afterwards executed for a
similar crime. It is attested, you will observe,
by the Reverend Mr. Purney, the present ordinary
of Newgate.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I am acquainted with Mr. Purney's handwriting,&rdquo; 
said Jack, advancing, &ldquo;and can at
once decide whether this is a forgery or not.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Look at it, then,&rdquo; said Wild, giving him
the portfolio.</p>
<p>&ldquo;It's the ordinary's signature, undoubtedly,&rdquo; 
replied Jack.</p>
<pb n="190">
<p>And as he gave back the portfolio to Sir Rowland
he contrived, unobserved, to slip the precious
document into his sleeve, and from thence
into his pocket.</p>
<p>&ldquo;And, does any of our bright blood flow in
the veins of a ruffianly housebreaker?&rdquo; cried
Trenchard, with a look of bewilderment. &ldquo;I'll
not believe it.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Others may, if you won't,&rdquo; muttered
Jack, retiring. &ldquo;Thank heaven! I'm not
basely born.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Now, mark me,&rdquo; said Jonathan, &ldquo;and
you'll find I don't do things by halves. By
your father, Sir Montacute Trenchard's will,
you are aware,&mdash;and, therefore, I need not repeat
it, except for the special purpose I have in
view,&mdash;you are aware, I say, that, by this will,
in case your sister Aliva, died without issue,
or, on the death of such issue, the property
reverts to Constance and <it>her</it> issue.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I hear,&rdquo; said Sir Rowland, moodily.</p>
<p>&ldquo;And I,&rdquo; muttered Jack.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Thames Darrell once destroyed,&rdquo; pursued
Jonathan, &ldquo;Constance&mdash;or, rather, Mrs.
Sheppard&mdash;becomes entitled to the estates;</pp>
<pb n="191">
<pp>which eventually&mdash;provided he escaped the
gallows&mdash;would descend to her son.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Ha!&rdquo; exclaimed Jack, drawing in his
breath, and leaning forward with intense curiosity.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Well, sir?&rdquo; gasped Sir Rowland.</p>
<p>&ldquo;But this need give you no uneasiness,&rdquo; 
pursued Jonathan; &ldquo;Mrs. Sheppard, as I told
you, is in Bedlam, an incurable maniac; while
her son is in the New Prison, whence he will
only be removed to Newgate and Tyburn.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;So you think,&rdquo; muttered Jack, between
his ground teeth.</p>
<p>&ldquo;To make your mind perfectly easy on the
score of Mrs. Sheppard,&rdquo; continued Jonathan; 
&ldquo;after we've disposed of Thames Darrell, I'll
visit her in Bedlam; and, as I understand I
form one of her chief terrors, I'll give her
such a fright that I'll engage she shan't long
survive it.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Devil!&rdquo; muttered Jack, again grasping
his pistol. But, feeling secure of vengeance,
he determined to abide his time.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;And now, having got rid of the minor obstacles,&rdquo; 
said Jonathan, &ldquo;I'll submit a plan
for the removal of the main difficulty. Thames</pp>
<pb n="192">
<pp>Darrell, I've said, is at Mr. Wood's at Dollis&hyphen;hill,
wholly unsuspicious of any designs
against him, and, in fact, entirely ignorant of
your being acquainted with his return, or even
of his existence. In this state, it will be easy
to draw him into a snare. To&hyphen;morrow night&mdash; 
or rather to&hyphen;night, for we are fast verging on
another day&mdash;I propose to lure him out of the
house by a stratagem which I am sure will
prove infallible; and, then, what so easy as to
knock him on the head. To make sure work
of it, I'll superintend the job myself. Before
mid&hyphen;night, I'll answer for it, it shall be done.
My janizaries shall go with me. You hear
what I say, Quilt?&rdquo; he added, looking at
Jack.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;I do,&rdquo; replied Sheppard.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Abraham Mendez will like the task,&mdash;for
he has entertained a hatred to the memory of
Thames Darrell ever since he received the
wound in the head, when the two lads attempted
to break out of St. Giles's roundhouse.
I've despatched him to the New Prison. But
I expect him back every minute.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;The New Prison!&rdquo; exclaimed Sheppard.
&ldquo;What is he gone there for?&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="193">
<p>&ldquo;With a message to the turnkey to look
after his prisoner,&rdquo; replied Wild, with a cunning
smile. &ldquo;Jack Sheppard had a visiter, I
understand, yesterday, and may make an attempt
to escape. It's as well to be on the
safe side.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;It is,&rdquo; replied Jack.</p>
<p>At this moment, his quick ears detected the
sound of foot&hyphen;steps on the stairs. He drew
both his pistols, and prepared for a desperate
encounter.</p>
<p>&ldquo;There is another mystery I would have
solved,&rdquo; said Trenchard, addressing Wild; 
&ldquo;you have told me much, but not enough.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;What do you require further?&rdquo; asked Jonathan.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The name and rank of Thames Darrell's
father,&rdquo; said the knight.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Another time,&rdquo; replied the thieftaker, evasively.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I will have it now,&rdquo; rejoined Trenchard,
&ldquo;or our agreement is void.</p>
<p>&ldquo;You cannot help yourself, Sir Rowland,&rdquo; 
replied Jonathan, contemptuously.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Indeed!&rdquo; replied the knight, drawing his</pp>
<pb n="194">
<pp>sword, &ldquo;the secret, villain, or I will force it
from you.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>Before Wild could make any reply, the door
was thrown violently open, and Abraham
Mendez rushed into the room, with a face of
the utmost consternation.</p>
<p>&ldquo;He hash eshcaped!&rdquo; cried the Jew.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Who? Jack!&rdquo; exclaimed Jonathan.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Yesh,&rdquo; replied Abraham. &ldquo;I vent to de
New Prish'n, and on wishitin' his shell vid de
turnkey, vot should ve find but de shains on
de ground, de vinder broken, and Jack and
Agevorth Besh gone.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Damnation!&rdquo; cried Jonathan, stamping his
foot with uncontrollable rage. &ldquo;I'd rather
have given a thousand pounds than this had
happened. But he might have broken out of
prison, and yet not got over the wall of
Clerkenwell Bridewell. Did you search the
yard, fool?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ve did,&rdquo; replied Abraham; &ldquo;and found
his fine goat and ruffles torn to shtrips on de
shpikes near de creat cate. It vosh plain he
vent dat vay.&rdquo;</p>
<pb>
<edit>[Figure: <bytes>381Kb</bytes>]</edit><figure sys.id="N010118">
<pb n="195">
<p>Jonathan gave utterance to a torrent of imprecations.</p>
<p>While he thus vented his rage, the door again
opened, and Quilt Arnold rushed into the
room, bleeding, and half&hyphen;dressed.</p>
<p>&ldquo;'Sblood! what's this?&rdquo; cried Jonathan,
in the utmost surprise. &ldquo;Quilt Arnold, is
that you?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;It is, sir,&rdquo; sputtered the janizary. &ldquo;I've
been robbed, maltreated, and nearly murdered
by Jack Sheppard.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;By Jack Sheppard!&rdquo; exclaimed the thieftaker.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Yes; and I hope you'll take ample vengeance
upon him,&rdquo; said Quilt.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I will, when I catch him, rely on it,&rdquo; rejoined
Wild.</p>
<p>&ldquo;You needn't go far to do that,&rdquo; returned
Quilt; &lsquo;there he stands.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ay, here I am,&rdquo; said Jack, throwing off
his hat and wig, and marching towards the
group, amongst whom there was a general
movement of surprise at his audacity. &ldquo;Sir
Rowland, I salute you as your nephew.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Back, villain!&rdquo; said the knight, haughtily.</pp>
<pb n="196">
<pp>&ldquo;I disown you. The whole story of your relationship
is a fabrication.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Time will show,&rdquo; replied Jack with equal
haughtiness. &ldquo;But, however, it may turn
out, I disown <it>you.</it>&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Well, Jack,&rdquo; said Jonathan, who had
looked at him with surprise not unmixed with
admiration, &ldquo;you are a bold and clever fellow,
I must allow. Were I not Jonathan Wild, I'd
be Jack Sheppard. I'm almost sorry I've
sworn to hang you. But, it can't be helped.
I'm a slave to my word. Were I to let you
go, you'd say I feared you. Besides, you've
secrets which must not be disclosed. Nab and
Quilt to the door! Jack, you are my prisoner.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;And you flatter yourself you can detain
me?&rdquo; laughed Jack.</p>
<p>&ldquo;At least I'll try,&rdquo; replied Jonathan, sarcastically.
&ldquo;You must be a cleverer lad than
even <it>I</it> take you for, if you get out of this
place.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;What ho! Blueskin!&rdquo; shouted Jack.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Here I am, captain,&rdquo; cried a voice from
without. And the door was suddenly thrown</pp>
<pb n="197">
<pp>open, and the two janizaries felled to the
ground by the strong arm of the stalwart robber.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Your boast, you see, was a little premature,
Mr. Wild,&rdquo; said Sheppard. &ldquo;Adieu,
my worthy uncle. Fortunately, I've secured
the proof of my birth.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Confusion!&rdquo; thundered Wild. &ldquo;Close the
doors below! Loose the dogs! Curses! they
don't hear me! I'll ring the alarm&hyphen;bell.&rdquo; And
he raised his arm with the intention of executing
his purpose, when a ball from Jack's
pistol passed through the back of his hand,
shattering the limb. &ldquo;Aha! my lad!&rdquo; he
cried, without appearing to regard the pain of
the wound; &ldquo;now I'll show you no quarter.&rdquo; 
And, with the uninjured hand he drew a
pistol, which he fired, but without effect, at
Jack.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Fly, captain, fly!&rdquo; vociferated Blueskin; 
&ldquo;I shan't be able to keep these devils
down. Fly! They shall knock me on the
head&mdash;curse 'em!&mdash;before they shall touch
you.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="198">
<p>&ldquo;Come along!&rdquo; cried Jack, darting through
the door. &ldquo;The key's on the outside&mdash;quick!
quick!&rdquo;</p>
<p>Instantly alive to this chance, Blueskin
broke away. Two shots were fired at him by
Jonathan; one of which passed through his
hat, and the other through the fleshy part of
his arm; but he made good his retreat. The
door was closed&mdash;locked,&mdash;and the pair were
heard descending the stairs.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Hell's curses!&rdquo; roared Jonathan. &ldquo;They'll
escape. Not a moment is to be lost.&rdquo;</p>
<p>So saying, he took hold of a ring in the floor,
and disclosed a flight of steps, down which he
hurried, followed by the janizaries. This means
of communication instantly brought them to
the lobby. But Jack and his companion were
already gone.</p>
<p><pp>Jonathan threw open the street&hyphen;door. Upon
the pavement near the court lay the porter,
who had been prostrated by a blow from
the butt&hyphen;end of a pistol. The man, who
was just able to move, pointed towards
Giltspur&hyphen;street. Jonathan looked in that</pp>
<pb n="199">
<pp>direction, and beheld the fugitives riding off
in triumph.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;To&hyphen;night it is <it>their</it> turn,&rdquo; said Jonathan,
binding up his wounded fingers with a handkerchief.
&ldquo;To&hyphen;morrow it will be <it>mine.</it>&rdquo;</p></div4>
<pb n="200">
<div4>
<comhd4><idref>Z400030653</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
CHAPTER VI.
<subhead>WINIFRED RECEIVES TWO PROPOSALS.</subhead> <attbytes>13Kb</attbytes><reflink>000027</reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z400030653</ID><A1>Ainsworth, William Harrison, 1805&ndash;1882</A1><T1>Jack Sheppard. A Romance.</T1><PBL>Richard Bentley</PBL><Y1>1839</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd4>
<p><smallcap>The</smallcap> tragical affair at Dollis Hill, it need
scarcely be said, was a dreadful blow to the
family. Mr. Wood bore up with great fortitude
against the shock, attended the inquest,
delivered his evidence with composure, and
gave directions afterwards for the funeral,
which took place on the day but one following
&mdash;Sunday. As soon, however, as the last solemn
rites were over, and the remains of the
unfortunate woman committed to their final
resting&hyphen;place in Willesden churchyard, his firmness
completely deserted him, and he sank beneath
the weight of his affliction. It was fortunate
that by this time Winifred had so far
recovered, as to be able to afford her father the
best and only solace that, under the circumstances,
he could have received,&mdash;her personal
attentions.</p>
<pb n="201">
<p>The necessity which had previously existed
of leaving the ghastly evidence of the murderous
deed undisturbed,&mdash;the presence of the
mangled corpse,&mdash;the bustle of the inquest, at
which her attendance was required,&mdash;all these
circumstances produced a harrowing effect
upon the young girl's imagination. But when
all was over, a sorrowful calm succeeded, and,
if not free from grief, she was tranquil. As to
Thames, though deeply and painfully affected
by the horrible occurrence that had marked his
return to his old friends, he was yet able to
control his feelings, and devote himself to the
alleviation of the distress of the more immediate
sufferers by the calamity.</p>
<p><pp>It was Sunday evening&mdash;a soft delicious
evening, and, from the happy, <it>cheerful</it> look of
the house, none would have dreamed of the
dismal tragedy so lately acted within its walls.
The birds were singing blithely amid the trees,
&mdash;the lowing of the cows resounded from the
yard,&mdash;a delicious perfume from the garden
was wafted through the open window,&mdash;at a
distance, the church&hyphen;bells of Willesden were
heard tolling for evening service. All these</pp>
<pb n="202">
<pp>things spoke of peace;&mdash;but there are seasons
when the pleasantest external influences have a
depressing effect on the mind, by painfully recalling
past happiness. So, at least, thought
one of two persons who were seated together
in a small back&hyphen;parlour of the house at Dollis
Hill. She was a lovely girl, attired in deep
mourning, and having an expression of profound
sorrow on her charming features. Her
companion was a portly handsome man, also
dressed in a full suit of the deepest mourning,
with the finest of lace at his bosom and wrists,
and a sword in a black sheath by his side.
These persons were Mr. Kneebone and Winifred.</pp></p>
<p><pp>The funeral, it has just been said, took place
on that day. Amongst others who attended
the sad ceremony was Mr. Kneebone. Conceiving
himself called upon, as the intimate
friend of the deceased, to pay this last tribute
of respect to her memory, he appeared as one
of the chief mourners. Overcome by his affliction,
Mr. Wood had retired to his own room,
where he had just summoned Thames. Much
to her annoyance, therefore, Winifred was left</pp>
<pb n="203">
<pp>alone with the woollen&hyphen;draper, who following
up a maxim of his own, &ldquo;that nothing was
gained by too much bashfulness,&rdquo; determined
to profit by the opportunity. He had only
been prevented, indeed, by a fear of Mrs. Wood
from pressing his suit long ago. This obstacle
removed, he thought he might now make the
attempt. Happen what might, he could not
be in a worse position.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;We have had a sad loss, my dear Winifred,&rdquo; 
he began,&mdash;&ldquo;for I must use the privilege
of an old friend, and address you by that
familiar name,&mdash;we have had a sad loss in the
death of your lamented parent, whose memory
I shall for ever revere.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Winifred's eyes filled with tears. This was
not exactly what the woollen&hyphen;draper desired.
So he resolved to try another tack.</p>
<p>&ldquo;What a very remarkable thing it is,&rdquo; he
observed, applying to his snuff&hyphen;box, &ldquo;that
Thames Darrell, whom we all supposed dead,&rdquo; 
&mdash;Kneebone in his heart sincerely wished he
<it>had</it> been so,&mdash;&ldquo;should turn out to be alive
after all. Strange, I shouldn't know him when
he called on me.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="204">
<p>&ldquo;It <it>is</it> strange,&rdquo; replied Winifred, artlessly.
&ldquo;<it>I</it> knew him at once.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Of course,&rdquo; rejoined Kneebone, a little
maliciously, &ldquo;but that's easily accounted for.
May I be permitted, as a very old and very
dear friend of your lamented parent, whose
loss I shall ever deplore, to ask you one question?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Undoubtedly,&rdquo; replied Winifred.</p>
<p>&ldquo;And you will answer it frankly?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Certainly.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Now for it,&rdquo; thought the woollen&hyphen;draper.
&ldquo;I shall, at least, ascertain how the land lies.
&mdash;Well, then, my dear,&rdquo; he added aloud, &ldquo;do
you still entertain the strong attachment you
did to Captain Darrell?&rdquo;</p>
<p>Winifred's cheeks glowed with blushes, and
fixing her eyes, which flashed with resentment,
upon the questioner, she said,</p>
<p>&ldquo;I have promised to answer your question,
and I will do so. I love him as a brother.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;<it>Only</it> as a brother?&rdquo; persisted Kneebone.</p>
<p>If Winifred remained silent, her looks would
have disarmed a person of less assurance than
the woollen&hyphen;draper.</p>
<pb n="205">
<p>&ldquo;If you knew how much importance I attach
to your answer,&rdquo; he continued, passionately,
&ldquo;you would not refuse me one. Were Captain
Darrell to offer you his hand, would you accept
it?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Your impertinence deserves very different
treatment, sir,&rdquo; said Winifred; &ldquo;but, to put
an end to this annoyance, I will tell you&mdash;I
would not.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;And why not?&rdquo; asked Kneebone, eagerly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I will not submit to be thus interrogated,&rdquo; 
said Winifred, angrily.</p>
<p>&ldquo;In the name of your lamented parent,
whose memory I shall for ever revere, I implore
you to answer me,&rdquo; urged Kneebone, &ldquo;why
&mdash;why would you not accept him?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Because our positions are different,&rdquo; replied
Winifred, who could not resist this appeal
to her feelings.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;You are a paragon of prudence and discretion,&rdquo; 
rejoined the woollen&hyphen;draper, drawing his
chair closer to hers. &ldquo;Disparity of rank is
ever productive of unhappiness in the married
state. When Captain Darrell's birth is ascertained,
I've no doubt he'll turn out a nobleman's</pp>
<pb n="206">
<pp>son. At least, I hope so for his sake as
well as my own,&rdquo; he added, mentally. &ldquo;He
has quite the air of one. And now, my angel,
that I am acquainted with your sentiments on
this subject, I shall readily fulfil a promise
which I made to your lamented parent, whose
loss I shall ever deplore.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;A promise to my mother?&rdquo; said Winifred,
unsuspiciously.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Yes, my angel, to <it>her</it>&mdash;rest her soul! She
extorted it from me, and bound me by a so
lemn oath to fulfil it.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Oh! name it.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You are a party concerned. Promise me
that you will not disobey the injunctions of her
whose memory we must both of us ever revere.
Promise me.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;If in my power&mdash;certainly. But, what is
it? What <it>did</it> you promise?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;To offer you my heart, my hand, my life,&rdquo; 
replied Kneebone, falling at her feet.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Sir!&rdquo; exclaimed Winifred, rising.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Inequality of rank can be no bar to <it>our</it>
union,&rdquo; continued Kneebone. &ldquo;Heaven be
praised, <it>I</it> am not the son of a nobleman.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="207">
<p>In spite of her displeasure, Winifred could
not help smiling at the absurdity of this address.
Taking this for encouragement, her
suitor proceeded still more extravagantly.
Seizing her hand, he covered it with kisses.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Adorable girl!&rdquo; he cried, in the most impassioned
tone, and with the most impassioned
look he could command. &ldquo;Adorable girl, I
have long loved you to desperation. Your
lamented mother, whose loss I shall ever deplore,
perceived my passion, and encouraged it.
Would she were alive to back my suit!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;This is beyond all endurance,&rdquo; said Winifred,
striving to withdraw her hand. &ldquo;Leave
me, sir; I insist.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Never!&rdquo; rejoined Kneebone, with increased
ardour,&mdash;&ldquo;never, till I receive from your
own lips the answer which is to make me the
happiest or the most miserable of mankind.
Hear me, adorable girl! You know not the
extent of my devotion. No mercenary consideration
influences me. Love&mdash;admiration for
your matchless beauty alone sways me. Let
your father&mdash;if he chooses, leave all his wealth
to his adopted son. I care not. Possessed of</pp>
<pb n="208">
<pp><it>you</it>, I shall have a treasure such as kings could
not boast.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Pray cease this nonsense,&rdquo; said Winifred,
&ldquo;and quit the room, or I will call for assistance.&rdquo;</p>
<p>At this juncture, the door opened, and
Thames entered the room. As the woollen&hyphen;draper's
back was towards him, he did not perceive
him, but continued his passionate addresses.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Call as you please, beloved girl,&rdquo; he cried,
&ldquo;I will not stir till I am answered. You say
that you only love Captain Darrell as a brother
&wblank;&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Mr. Kneebone!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;That you would not accept him were he
to offer&wblank;&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Be silent, sir.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;He then,&rdquo; continued the woollen&hyphen;draper,
&ldquo;is no longer considered&wblank;&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;How, sir?&rdquo; cried Thames, advancing,
&ldquo;what is the meaning of your reference to my
name? Have you dared to insult this lady?
If so&wblank;&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Insult her!&rdquo; replied Kneebone, rising,</pp>
<pb n="209">
<pp>and endeavouring to hide his embarrassment
under a look of defiance. &ldquo;Far from it, sir. I
have made her an honourable proposal of marriage,
in compliance with the request of her
lamented parent, whose memory&wblank;&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Dare to utter that falsehood in my hearing
again, scoundrel,&rdquo; interrupted Thames fiercely,
&ldquo;and I will put it out of your power to repeat
the offence. Leave the room! leave the house,
sir! and enter it again at your peril.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I shall do neither, sir,&rdquo; replied Kneebone,
&ldquo;unless I am requested by this lady to withdraw,
&mdash;in which case I shall comply with her
request. And you have to thank her presence,
hot&hyphen;headed boy, that I do not chastise your
insolence as it deserves.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Go, Mr. Kneebone,&mdash;pray go!&rdquo; implored
Winifred. &ldquo;Thames, I entreat&wblank;&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Your wishes are my laws, beloved girl,&rdquo; 
replied Kneebone, bowing profoundly. &ldquo;Captain
Darrell,&rdquo; he added, sternly, &ldquo;you shall
hear from me.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;When you please, sir,&rdquo; said Thames,
coldly.</pp>
<pb n="210">
<pp>And the woollen&hyphen;draper departed.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;What is all this, dear Winny?&rdquo; inquired
Thames, as soon as they were alone.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Nothing&mdash;nothing,&rdquo; she answered, bursting
into tears. &ldquo;Don't ask me about it now.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Winny,&rdquo; said Thames, tenderly, &ldquo;something
which that self&hyphen;sufficient fool has said
has so far done me a service in enabling me to
speak upon a subject which I have long had
upon my lips, but have not had courage to
utter.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Thames!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You seem to doubt my love,&rdquo; he continued,
&mdash;&ldquo;you seem to think that change of
circumstances may produce some change in my
affections. Hear me then, now, before I take
one step to establish my origin, or secure my
rights. Whatever those rights may be, whoever
I am, my heart is yours. Do you accept
it?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Dear Thames!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Forgive this ill&hyphen;timed avowal of my love.
But, answer me. Am I mistaken? Is your
heart mine?&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="211">
<p>&ldquo;It is&mdash;it is; and has ever been,&rdquo; replied
Winifred, falling upon his neck.</p>
<p>Lovers' confidences should be respected.
We close the chapter.</p></div4>
<pb n="212">
<div4>
<comhd4><idref>Z400030654</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
CHAPTER VII.
<subhead>JACK SHEPPARD WARNS THAMES DARRELL.</subhead> <attbytes>18Kb</attbytes><reflink>000027</reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z400030654</ID><A1>Ainsworth, William Harrison, 1805&ndash;1882</A1><T1>Jack Sheppard. A Romance.</T1><PBL>Richard Bentley</PBL><Y1>1839</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd4>
<p><pp><smallcap>On</smallcap> the following night&mdash;namely Monday,&mdash; 
the family assembled together, for the first
time since the fatal event, in the chamber to
which Thames had been introduced on his arrival
at Dollis Hill. As this had been Mrs.
Wood's favourite sitting&hyphen;room, and her image
was so intimately associated with it, neither the
carpenter nor his daughter could muster courage
to enter it before. Determined, however, to
conquer the feeling as soon as possible, Wood
had given orders to have the evening meal served
there; but, notwithstanding all his good resolutions
upon his first entrance, he had much
ado to maintain his self&hyphen;command. His wife's
portrait had been removed from the walls, and
the place it had occupied was only to be known
by the cord by which it had been suspended.</pp>
<pb n="213">
<pp>The very blank, however, affected him more
deeply than if it had been left. Then a handkerchief
was thrown over the cage, to prevent
the bird from singing; it was <it>her</it> favourite canary.
The flowers upon the mantel&hyphen;shelf were
withered and drooping&mdash;<it>she</it> had gathered them.
All these circumstances,&mdash;slight in themselves,
but powerful in their effect,&mdash;touched the heart
of the widowed carpenter, and added to his depression.</pp></p>
<p><pp>Supper was over. It had been discussed in
silence. The cloth was removed, and Wood,
drawing the table as near the window as possible
&mdash;for it was getting dusk&mdash;put on his spectacles,
and opened that sacred volume from
which the best consolation in affliction is derived,
and left the lovers&mdash;for such they may
now be fairly termed&mdash;to their own conversation.
Having already expressed our determination
not to betray any confidences of this
sort, which, however interesting to the parties
concerned, could not possibly be so to others,
we shall omit also the &ldquo;love passages,&rdquo; and
proceeding to such topics as may have general
interest, take up the discourse at the point</pp>
<pb n="214">
<pp>when Thames Darrell expressed his determination
of starting for Manchester, as soon as Jack
Sheppard's examination had taken place.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;I am surprised we have received no summons
for attendance to&hyphen;day,&rdquo; he remarked; 
&ldquo;perhaps the other robber may be secured.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Or Jack have escaped,&rdquo; remarked Winny.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I don't think that's likely. But, this sad
affair disposed of, I will not rest till I have
avenged my murdered parents.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;&lsquo;<it>The avenger of blood himself shall slay
the murderer</it>,&rsquo;&rdquo; said Wood, who was culling
for himself certain texts from the scriptures.</p>
<p>&ldquo;It is the voice of inspiration,&rdquo; said
Thames; &ldquo;and I receive it as a solemn command.
The villain has enjoyed his security
too long.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;&lsquo;<it>Bloody and deceitful men shall not live
half their days</it>,&rsquo;&rdquo; said Wood, reading aloud
another passage.</p>
<p>&ldquo;And yet, <it>he</it> has been spared thus long; 
perhaps with a wise purpose,&rdquo; rejoined
Thames. &ldquo;But, though the storm has
spared him, <it>I</it> will not.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;&lsquo;<it>No doubt</it>,&rsquo;&rdquo; said Wood, who had again</pp>
<pb n="215">
<pp>turned over the leaves of the sacred volume,&mdash; 
&ldquo;&lsquo;<it>no doubt this man is a murderer, whom,
though he escaped the seas, yet vengeance suffereth
not to live</it>,&rsquo;&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;No feelings of consanguinity shall stay my
vengeance,&rdquo; said Thames, sternly. &ldquo;I will
have no satisfaction but his life.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;&lsquo;<it>Thou shalt take no satisfaction for the
life of a murderer which is guilty of death,
but he shall surely be put to death</it>,&rdquo; said Wood,
referring to another text.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Do not steel your heart against him, dear
Thames,&rdquo; interposed Winifred.</p>
<p>&ldquo;&lsquo;<it>And thine eye shall not pity</it>,&rsquo;&rdquo; said her
father, in a tone of rebuke, &ldquo;&lsquo;<it>but, life shall
be for life, eye for eye, tooth for tooth, hand
for hand, foot for foot.</it>&rsquo;&rdquo;</p>
<p>As these words were delivered by the carpenter
with stern emphasis, a female servant
entered the room, and stated that a gentleman
was at the door, who wished to speak with
Captain Darrell on business of urgent importance.</p>
<p>&ldquo;With me?&rdquo; said Thames. &ldquo;Who is
it?&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="216">
<p>&ldquo;He didn't give his name, sir,&rdquo; replied the
maid; &ldquo;but he's a young gentleman.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Don't go near him, dear Thames,&rdquo; said
Winifred; &ldquo;he may have some ill intention.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Pshaw!&rdquo; cried Thames. &ldquo;What! refuse
to see a person who desires to speak with me.
Say I will come to him.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Law! miss,&rdquo; observed the maid, &ldquo;there's
nothing mischievous in the person's appearance,
I'm sure. He 's as nice and civil&hyphen;spoken
a gentleman as need be; by the same
token,&rdquo; she added, in an under tone, &ldquo;that
he gave me a span new crown piece.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;&lsquo;<it>The thief cometh in the night, and the
troop of robbers spoileth without</it>,&rsquo;&rdquo; said Wood,
who had a text for every emergency.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Lor' ha' mussy, sir!&mdash;how you <it>do</it> talk,&rdquo; 
said the woman; &ldquo;this is no robber, I 'm
sure. I should have known at a glance if it
was. He 's more like a lord than&wblank;&rdquo;</p>
<p>As she spoke, steps were heard approaching; 
the door was thrown open, and a young man
marched boldly into the room.</p>
<p><pp>The intruder was handsomely, even richly,</pp>
<pb n="217">
<pp>attired in a scarlet riding&hyphen;suit, embroidered
with gold; a broad belt, to which a hanger
was attached, crossed his shoulders; his boots
rose above his knee, and he carried a laced hat
in his hand. Advancing to the middle of the
chamber, he halted, drew himself up, and fixed
his dark, expressive eyes, on Thames Darrell.
His appearance excited the greatest astonishment
and consternation amid the group. Winifred
screamed. Thames sprang to his feet,
and half drew his sword, while Wood, removing
his spectacles to assure himself that his
eyes did not deceive him, exclaimed in a tone
and with a look that betrayed the extremity
of surprise&mdash;&ldquo;Jack Sheppard!&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Jack Sheppard!&rdquo; echoed the maid. &ldquo;Is
this Jack Sheppard? Oh, la! I'm undone!
We shall all have our throats cut! Oh! oh!&rdquo; 
And she rushed, screaming, into the passage
where she fell down in a fit.</p>
<p><pp>The occasion of all this confusion and dismay,
meanwhile, remained perfectly motionless; 
his figure erect, and with somewhat of
dignity in his demeanour. He kept his keen</pp>
<pb n="218">
<pp>eyes steadily fixed on Thames, as if awaiting
to be addressed.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Your audacity passes belief,&rdquo; cried the
latter, as soon as his surprise would allow him
utterance. &ldquo;If you have contrived to break
out of your confinement, villain, this is the last
place where you ought to show yourself.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;And, therefore, the first I would visit,&rdquo; 
replied Jack, boldly. &ldquo;But, pardon my intrusion.
I was <it>resolved</it> to see you. And, fearing
you might not come to me, I forced my
way hither, even with certainty of discomposing
your friends.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Well, villain!&rdquo; replied Thames, &ldquo;I know
not the motive of your visit. But, if you have
come to surrender yourself to justice, it is well.
You cannot depart hence.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Cannot?&rdquo; echoed Jack, a slight smile
crossing his features. &ldquo;But, let that pass.
My motive in coming hither is to serve you,
and save your life. If you choose to requite
me by detaining me, you are at liberty to do
so. I shall make no defence. That I am not
ignorant of the reward offered for my capture
this will show,&rdquo; he added, taking a large placard</pp>
<pb n="219">
<pp>headed &lsquo;<it>Murder</it>&rsquo; from his pocket, and
throwing it on the floor. &ldquo;My demeanour ought
to convince you that I came with no hostile intention.
And, to show you that I have no intention
of flying, I will myself close and lock the
door. There is the key. Are you now satisfied?&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;No,&rdquo; interposed Wood, furiously, &ldquo;I
shall never be satisfied till I see you hanged on
the highest gibbet at Tyburn.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;A time may come when you will be gratified,
Mr. Wood,&rdquo; replied Jack, calmly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;May come!&mdash;it <it>will</it> come!&mdash;it <it>shall</it>
come!&rdquo; cried the carpenter, shaking his hand
menacingly at him. &ldquo;I have some difficulty
in preventing myself from becoming your
executioner. Oh! that I should have nursed
such a viper!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Hear me, sir,&rdquo; said Jack.</p>
<p>&ldquo;No, I won't hear you, murderer,&rdquo; rejoined
Wood.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I am no murderer,&rdquo; replied Sheppard. &ldquo;I
had no thought of injuring your wife, and would
have died rather than commit so foul a crime.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Think not to delude me, audacious
wretch,&rdquo; cried the carpenter. &ldquo;Even if you</pp>
<pb n="220">
<pp>are not a principal, you are an accessary. If
you had not brought your companion here, it
would not have happened. But you shall
swing, rascal,&mdash;you shall swing.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;My conscience acquits me of all share in
the offence,&rdquo; replied Jack, humbly. &ldquo;But
the past is irremediable, and I did not come
hither to exculpate myself. I came to save
<it>your</it> life,&rdquo; he added, turning to Thames.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I was not aware it was in danger,&rdquo; rejoined
Darrell.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Then you ought to be thankful to me for
the warning. You <it>are</it> in danger.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;From some of your associates?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;From your uncle, from <it>my</it> uncle,&mdash;Sir
Rowland Trenchard.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;What means this idle boasting, villain?&rdquo; 
said Thames. &ldquo;<it>Your</it> uncle, Sir Rowland?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;It is no idle boasting,&rdquo; replied the other.
&ldquo;You are cousin to the housebreaker, Jack
Sheppard.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;If it were so, he would have great reason
to be proud of the relationship, truly,&rdquo; observed
Wood, shrugging his shoulders.</p>
<p>&ldquo;It is easy to make an assertion like this,&rdquo; 
said Thames, contemptuously.</p>
<pb n="221">
<p>&ldquo;And equally easy to prove it,&rdquo; replied
Jack, giving him the paper he had abstracted
from Wild. &ldquo;Read that.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Thames hastily cast his eyes over it, and
transferred it, with a look of incredulity, to
Wood.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Gracious heavens! this is more wonderful
than all the rest,&rdquo; cried the carpenter, rubbing
his eyes. &ldquo;Thames, this is no forgery.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You believe it, father?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;From the bottom of my heart. I always
thought Mrs. Sheppard superior to her station.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;So did I,&rdquo; said Winifred. &ldquo;Let me look
at the paper.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Poor soul!&mdash;poor soul!&rdquo; groaned Wood,
brushing the tears from his vision. &ldquo;Well,
I'm glad she's spared this. Oh! Jack, Jack,
you've much to answer for!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I have, indeed,&rdquo; replied Sheppard, in a
tone of contrition.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;If this document is correct,&rdquo; continued
Wood, &ldquo;and I am persuaded it is so,&mdash;you
are as unfortunate as wicked. See what your
misconduct has deprived you of&mdash;see what</pp>
<pb n="222">
<pp>you might have been. This is retribution.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;I feel it,&rdquo; replied Jack, in a tone of agony,
&ldquo;and I feel it more on my poor mother's account
than my own.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;She has suffered enough for you,&rdquo; said
Wood.</p>
<p>&ldquo;She has, she has,&rdquo; said Jack, in a broken
voice.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Weep on, reprobate,&rdquo; cried the carpenter,
a little softened. &ldquo;Those tears will do you
good.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Do not distress him, dear father,&rdquo; said
Winifred; &ldquo;he suffers deeply. Oh, Jack!
repent, while it is yet time, of your evil conduct.
I will pray for you.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I cannot repent.&mdash;I cannot pray,&rdquo; replied
Jack, recovering his hardened demeanour.
&ldquo;I should never have been what I am, but
for you.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;How so?&rdquo; inquired Winifred.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;I loved you,&rdquo; replied Jack,&mdash;&ldquo;don't start
&mdash;it is over now&mdash;I loved you, I say, as a boy,
<it>hopelessly</it>, and it made me desperate. And now
I find, when it is too late, that I <it>might</it> have</pp>
<pb n="223">
<pp>deserved you&mdash;that I am as well born as
Thames Darrell. But I mustn't think of these
things, or I shall grow mad. I have said
your life is in danger, Thames. Do not slight
my warning. Sir Rowland Trenchard is aware of
your return to England. I saw him last night at
Jonathan Wild's, after my escape from the New
Prison. He had just arrived from Manchester,
whence he had been summoned by that
treacherous thief taker. I overheard them
planning your assassination. It is to take place
to&hyphen;night.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Oh heavens!&rdquo; screamed Winifred, while
her father lifted up his hands in silent horror.</p>
<p>&ldquo;And when I further tell you,&rdquo; continued
Jack, &ldquo;that, after yourself and my mother, <it>I</it>
am the next heir to the estates of my grandfather,
Sir Montacute Trenchard, you will perhaps
own that my caution is sufficiently disinterested.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Could I credit your wild story, I might do
so,&rdquo; returned Thames, with a look of perplexity.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Here are Jonathan Wild's written instructions
to Quilt Arnold,&rdquo; rejoined Sheppard, producing
the pocket&hyphen;book he had found in the</pp>
<pb n="224">
<pp>janizary's clothes. &ldquo;This letter will vouch for
me that a communication has taken place between
your enemies.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>Thames glanced at the despatch, and, after
a moment's reflection, inquired, &ldquo;In what
way is the attempt upon my life to be made?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;That I couldn't ascertain,&rdquo; replied Jack; 
&ldquo;but I advise you to be upon your guard.
For aught I know, they may be in the neighbourhood
at this moment.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Here!&rdquo; ejaculated Wood, with a look of
alarm. &ldquo;Oh lord! I hope not.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;This I do know,&rdquo; continued Jack,&mdash;&ldquo;Jonathan
Wild superintends the attack.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Jonathan Wild!&rdquo; repeated the carpenter,
trembling. &ldquo;Then it's all over with us. Oh
dear!&mdash;how sorry I am I ever left Wych&hyphen;street.
We may be all murdered in this unprotected
place, and nobody be the wiser.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;There's some one in the garden at this
moment,&rdquo; cried Jack; &ldquo;I saw a face at the
window.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Where&mdash;where?&rdquo; cried Thames.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Don't stir,&rdquo; replied Jack. &ldquo;I will at
once convince you of the truth of my assertions,</pp>
<pb n="225">
<pp>and ascertain whether the enemy really is at
hand.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>So saying, he advanced towards the window,
threw open the sash, and called out in the voice
of Thames Darrell,</p>
<p>&ldquo;Who's there?&rdquo;</p>
<p>He was answered by a shot from a pistol.
The ball passed over his head, and lodged in
the ceiling.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I was right,&rdquo; replied Jack, returning as
coolly as if nothing had happened. &ldquo;It is Jonathan.
Your uncle&mdash;<it>our</it> uncle is with him.
I saw them both.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;May I trust you?&rdquo; cried Thames, eagerly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;You may,&rdquo; replied Jack; &ldquo;I'll fight for
you to the last gasp.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Follow me, then,&rdquo; cried Thames, drawing
his sword, and springing through the window.</p>
<p>&ldquo;To the world's end,&rdquo; answered Jack, darting
after him.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Thames!&mdash;Thames!&rdquo; cried Winifred,
rushing to the window. &ldquo;He will be murdered!
&mdash;Help!&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="226">
<p>&ldquo;My child!&mdash;my love!&rdquo; cried Wood,
dragging her forcibly back.</p>
<p>Two shots were fired, and presently the
clashing of swords was heard below.</p>
<p>After some time, the scuffle grew more and
more distant, until nothing could be heard.</p>
<p>Wood, meanwhile, had summoned his men&hyphen;servants,
and having armed them with such
weapons as could be found, they proceeded to
the garden, where the first object they encountered
was Thames Darrell, extended on
the ground, and weltering in his blood. Of
Jack Sheppard or the assailants they could not
discover a single trace.</p>
<p>As the body was borne to the house in the
arms of the farming&hyphen;men, Mr. Wood fancied
he heard the exulting laugh of Jonathan Wild.</p></div4>
<pb n="227">
<div4>
<comhd4><idref>Z400030655</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
CHAPTER VIII.
<subhead>OLD BEDLAM.</subhead> <attbytes>25Kb</attbytes><reflink>000027</reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z400030655</ID><A1>Ainsworth, William Harrison, 1805&ndash;1882</A1><T1>Jack Sheppard. A Romance.</T1><PBL>Richard Bentley</PBL><Y1>1839</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd4>
<p><pp><smallcap>When</smallcap> Thames Darrell and Jack Sheppard
sprang through the window, they were instantly
assailed by Wild, Trenchard, and their attendants.
Jack attacked Jonathan with such
fury, that he drove him into a shrubbery, and
might perhaps have come off the victor, if his
foot had not slipped as he made a desperate
lunge. In this state it would have been all
over with him, as, being stunned by the fall,
it was some moments before he could recover
himself, if another party had not unexpectedly
come to his rescue. This was Blueskin, who
burst through the trees, and sword in hand assaulted
the thieftaker. As soon as Jack gained
his legs, he perceived Blueskin lying, as he
thought, dead in the plantation, with a severe
cut across his temples, and while he was stooping
to assist him, he heard groans at a little</pp>
<pb n="228">
<pp>distance. Hastening in the direction of the
sound, he discovered Thames Darrell, stretched
upon the ground.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Are you hurt, Thames?&rdquo; asked Jack,
anxiously.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Not dangerously, I hope,&rdquo; returned
Thames; &ldquo;but fly&mdash;save yourself.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Where are the assassins?&rdquo; cried Sheppard.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Gone,&rdquo; replied the wounded man. &ldquo;They
imagine their work is done. But I may yet
live to thwart them.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I will carry you to the house, or fetch Mr.
Wood,&rdquo; urged Jack.</p>
<p>&ldquo;No, no,&rdquo; rejoined Thames; &ldquo;fly&mdash;or I
will not answer for your safety. If you desire
to please me, you will go.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;And leave you thus?&rdquo; rejoined Jack. &ldquo;I
cannot do it.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Go, I insist,&rdquo; cried Thames, &ldquo;or take the
consequences upon yourself. I cannot protect
you.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>Thus urged, Jack reluctantly departed.
Hastening to the spot where he had tied his
horse to a tree, he vaulted into the saddle, and</pp>
<pb n="229">
<pp>rode off across the fields,&mdash;for he was fearful of
encountering the hostile party,&mdash;till he reached
the Edgeware Road. Arrived at Paddington,
he struck across Marylebone Fields,&mdash;for as yet
the New Road was undreamed of,&mdash;and never
moderated his speed until he reached the city.
His destination was the New Mint. At this
place of refuge, situated in the heart of Wapping,
near the river&hyphen;side, he arrived in less than
an hour, in a complete state of exhaustion.</pp></p>
<p><pp>In consequence of the infamous abuse of its
liberties, an act for the entire suppression of
the Old Mint was passed in the ninth year of
the reign of George the First, not many months
before the date of the present epoch of this history; 
and as, after the destruction of Whitefriars,
which took place in the reign of Charles
the Second, owing to the protection afforded
by its inmates to the Levellers and Fifth&hyphen;monarchy&hyphen;men,
when the inhabitants of Alsatia
crossed the water, and settled themselves in the
borough of Southwark,&mdash;so now, driven out of
their fastnesses, they again migrated, and recrossing
the Thames, settled in Wapping, in a
miserable quarter between Artichoke Lane and</pp>
<pb n="230">
<pp>Nightingale Lane, which they termed the New
Mint. Ousted from his old retreat, the Cross
Shovels, Baptist Kettleby opened another tavern,
conducted upon the same plan as the
former, which he denominated the Seven Cities
of Refuge. His subjects, however, were no
longer entirely under his control; and, though
he managed to enforce some little attention to
his commands, it was evident his authority
was waning fast. Aware that they would not
be allowed to remain long unmolested, the
New Minters conducted themselves so outrageously,
and with such extraordinary insolence,
that measures were at this time being taken for
their effectual suppression.</pp></p>
<p>To the Seven Cities of Refuge Jack proceeded.
Having disposed of his steed and
swallowed a glass of brandy, without taking any
other refreshment, he threw himself on a couch,
where he sank at once into a heavy slumber.
When he awoke it was late in the day, and he
was surprised to find Blueskin seated by his
bed&hyphen;side, watching over him with a drawn
sword on his knee, a pistol in each hand, and
a blood&hyphen;stained cloth bound across his brow.</p>
<pb n="231">
<p>&ldquo;Don't disturb yourself,&rdquo; said his follower,
motioning him to keep still; &ldquo;it's all right.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;What time is it?&rdquo; inquired Jack.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Past noon,&rdquo; replied Blueskin. &ldquo;I didn't
awake you, because you seemed tired.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;How did you escape?&rdquo; asked Sheppard,
who, as he shook off his slumber, began to recall
the events of the previous night.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Oh, easily enough,&rdquo; rejoined the other.
&ldquo;I suppose I must have been senseless for
some time; for, on coming to myself, I found
this gash in my head, and the ground covered
with blood. However, no one had discovered
me, so I contrived to drag myself to my horse.
I thought if you were living, and not captured,
I should find you here,&mdash;and I was right. I
kept watch over you, for fear of a surprise on
the part of Jonathan. But what's to be
done?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;The first thing I do,&rdquo; replied Jack, &ldquo;will
be to visit my poor mother in Bedlam.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You'd better take care of your mother's
son instead,&rdquo; rejoined Blueskin. &ldquo;It's runnin'
a great risk.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Risk, or no risk, I shall go,&rdquo; replied Jack.</pp>
<pb n="232">
<pp>&ldquo;Jonathan has threatened to do her some mischief.
I am resolved to see her, without delay,
and ascertain if it's possible to remove her.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;It's a hopeless job,&rdquo; grumbled Blueskin,
&ldquo;and harm will come of it. What are you to
do with a mad mother at a time when you
need all your wits to take care of yourself?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Don't concern yourself further about me,&rdquo; 
returned Jack. &ldquo;Once for all, I shall go.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Won't you take me?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;No; you must await my return here.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Then I must wait a long time,&rdquo; grumbled
Blueskin. &ldquo;You'll never return.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;We shall see,&rdquo; replied Jack. &ldquo;But, if I
should <it>not</it> return, take this purse to Edgeworth
Bess. You'll find her at Black Mary's Hole.&rdquo;</p>
<p>And, having partaken of a hasty breakfast,
he set out. Taking his way along East Smithfield,
mounting Little Tower&hyphen;hill, and threading
the Minories and Hounsditch, he arrived without
accident or molestation, at Moorfields.</p>
<p><pp>Old Bethlehem, or Bedlam,&mdash;every trace of
which has been swept away, and the hospital
for lunatics removed to Saint George's Field,&mdash; 
was a vast and magnificent structure. Erected</pp>
<pb n="233">
<pp>in Moorfields in 1675, upon the model of the
Tuileries, it is said that Louis the Fourteenth
was so incensed at the insult offered to his
palace, that he had a counterpart of St. James's
built for offices of the meanest description.
The size and grandeur of the edifice, indeed,
drew down the ridicule of several of the wits of
the age: by one of whom&mdash;the facetious Tom
Brown&mdash;it was said, &ldquo;Bedlam is a pleasant
place, and abounds with amusements;&mdash;the
first of which is the building, so stately a fabric
for persons wholly insensible of the beauty and
use of it: the outside being a perfect mockery
of the inside, and admitting of two amusing
queries,&mdash;Whether the persons that ordered the
building of it, or those that inhabit it, were the
maddest? and, whether the name and thing be
not as disagreeable as harp and harrow.&rdquo; By
another&mdash;the no less facetious Ned Ward&mdash;it
was termed, &ldquo;A costly college for a crackbrained
society, raised in a mad age, when the
chief of the city were in a great danger of losing
their senses, and so contrived it the more noble
for their own reception; or they would never
have flung away so much money to so foolish a</pp>
<pb n="234">
<pp>purpose.&rdquo; The cost of the building exceeded
seventeen thousand pounds. However the
taste of the architecture may be questioned,
which was the formal French style of the
period, the general effect was imposing. Including
the wings, it presented a frontage of
five hundred and forty feet. Each wing had a
small cupola; and, in the centre of the pile
rose a larger dome, surmounted by a gilded ball
and vane. The asylum was approached by a
broad gravel walk, leading through a garden
edged on either side by a stone balustrade, and
shaded by tufted trees. A wide terrace then
led to large iron gates, over which were placed
the two celebrated figures of Raving and Melancholy
Madness, executed by the elder Cibber,
and commemorated by Pope in the Dunciad, in
the well&hyphen;known lines:&mdash; 
<lb><lg><l>&ldquo;Close to those walls where Folly holds her throne,</l>
<l>And laughs to think Monroe would take her down,</l>
<l>Where, o'er the gates, by his famed father's hand,</l>
<l><it>Great Cibber's brazen, brainless brothers stand.</it>&rdquo;</l></lg></pp></p>
<lb><p><pp>Internally, it was divided by two long galleries,
one over the other. These galleries
were separated in the middle by iron grates.</pp>
<pb n="235">
<pp>The wards on the right were occupied by male
patients, on the left by the females. In the centre
of the upper gallery was a spacious saloon,
appropriated to the governors of the asylum.
But, the besetting evil of the place, and that
which drew down the severest censures of the
writers above&hyphen;mentioned, was that this spot,
&mdash;which of all others should have been most
free from such intrusion&mdash;was made a public
exhibition. There all the loose characters
thronged, assignations were openly made, and
the spectators diverted themselves with the
vagaries of its miserable inhabitants.</pp></p>
<p><pp>Entering the outer gate, and traversing the
broad gravel walk before&hyphen;mentioned, Jack
ascended the steps, and was admitted, on
feeing the porter, by another iron gate, into
the hospital. Here he was almost stunned by
the deafening clamour resounding on all sides.
Some of the lunatics were rattling their
chains; some shrieking; some singing; some
beating with frantic violence against the doors.
Altogether, it was the most dreadful noise he
had ever heard. Amidst it all, however, there</pp>
<pb n="236">
<pp>were several light&hyphen;hearted and laughing groups
walking from cell to cell, to whom all this
misery appeared matter of amusement. The
doors of several of the wards were thrown
open for these parties, and as Jack passed, he
could not help glancing at the wretched inmates.
Here was a poor half&hyphen;naked creature,
with a straw crown on his head, and a wooden
sceptre in his hand, seated on the ground with
all the dignity of a monarch on his throne.
There was a mad musician, seemingly rapt in
admiration of the notes he was extracting from
a child's violin. Here was a terrific figure
gnashing his teeth, and howling like a wild
beast;&mdash;there a lover, with hands clasped together,
and eyes turned passionately upward.
In this cell was a huntsman, who had fractured
his skull while hunting, and was perpetually
hallooing after the hounds;&mdash;in that,
the most melancholy of all, the grinning
gibbering lunatic, the realization of &ldquo;moody
madness, laughing wild.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p><pp>Hastening from this heart&hyphen;rending spectacle,
Jack soon reached the grating that divided the</pp>
<pb n="237">
<pp>men's compartment from that appropriated to
the women. Inquiring for Mrs. Sheppard, a
matron offered to conduct him to her cell.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;You'll find her quiet enough to&hyphen;day, sir,&rdquo; 
observed the woman, as they walked along; 
&ldquo;but she has been very outrageous latterly.
Her nurse says she may live some time; but
she seems to me to be sinking fast.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Heaven help her!&rdquo; sighed Jack. &ldquo;I hope
not.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Her release would be a mercy,&rdquo; pursued
the matron. &ldquo;Oh! sir, if you'd seen her as
I've seen her, you'd not wish her a continuance
of misery.&rdquo;</p>
<p>As Jack made no reply, the woman proceeded,</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;They say her son's taken at last, and is to
be hanged. I'm glad of it, I'm sure; for it's
all owing to him his poor mother's here.
See what crime does, sir. Those who act
wickedly bring misery on all connected with
them. And so gentle as the poor creature is,
when she's not in her wild fits&mdash;it would melt
a heart of stone to see her. She will cry for
days and nights together. If Jack Sheppard</pp>
<pb n="238">
<pp>could behold his mother in this state, he'd
have a lesson he'd never forget&mdash;ay, and a
severer one than even the hangman could
read him. Hardened as he may be, that would
touch him. But he has never been near her&mdash; 
never.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>Rambling in this way, the matron at
length came to a halt, and taking out a key,
pointed to a door and said, &ldquo;This is Mrs.
Sheppard's ward, sir.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Leave us together, my good woman,&rdquo; said
Jack, putting a guinea into her hand.</p>
<p>&ldquo;As long as you please, sir,&rdquo; answered the
matron, dropping a curtsey. &ldquo;There, sir,&rdquo; 
she added, unlocking the door, &ldquo;you can go
in. Don't be frightened of her. She's not
mischievous&mdash;and besides she's chained, and
can't reach you.&rdquo;</p>
<p>So saying, she retired, and Jack entered the
cell.</p>
<p><pp>Prepared as he was for a dreadful shock,
and with his nerves strung to endure it, Jack
absolutely recoiled before the appalling object
that met his gaze. Cowering in a corner upon
a heap of straw sat his unfortunate mother,</pp>
<pb n="239">
<pp>the complete wreck of what she had been. Her
eyes glistened in the darkness&mdash;for light was
only admitted through a small grated window
&mdash;like flames, and, as she fixed them on him,
their glances seemed to penetrate his very
soul. A piece of old blanket was fastened
across her shoulders, and she had no other
clothing except a petticoat. Her arms and
feet were uncovered, and of almost skeleton
thinness. Her features were meagre, and
ghastly white, and had the fixed and horrible
stamp of insanity. Her head had been shaved,
and around it was swathed a piece of rag, in
which a few straws were stuck. Her thin
fingers were armed with nails as long as the
talons of a bird. A chain, riveted to an iron
belt encircling her waist, bound her to the
wall. The cell in which she was confined was
about six feet long and four wide; the walls
were scored all over with fantastic designs,
snatches of poetry, short sentences and names,
&mdash;the work of its former occupants, and of its
present inmate.</pp></p>
<p><pp>When Jack entered the cell, she was talking
to herself in the muttering unconnected</pp>
<pb n="240">
<pp>way peculiar to her distracted condition; but,
after her eye had rested on him some time, the
fixed expression of her features relaxed, and a
smile crossed them. This smile was more harrowing
even than her former rigid look.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;You are an angel,&rdquo; she cried, with a look
beaming with delight.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Rather a devil,&rdquo; groaned her son, &ldquo;to
have done this.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You are an angel, I say,&rdquo; continued the
poor maniac; &ldquo;and my Jack would have been
like you, if he had lived. But he died when he
was a child&mdash;long ago&mdash;long ago&mdash;long ago.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Would he had done so!&rdquo; cried Jack.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Old Van told me if he grew up he would
be hanged. He showed me a black mark under
his ear, where the noose would be tied. And
so I'll tell you what I did&mdash;&rdquo;</p>
<p>And she burst into a laugh that froze Jack's
blood in his veins.</p>
<p>&ldquo;What did you do?&rdquo; he asked, in a broken
voice.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;I strangled him&mdash;ha! ha! ha!&mdash;strangled
him while he was at my breast&mdash;ha! ha!&rdquo;&mdash; 
And then with a sudden and fearful change of</pp>
<pb n="241">
<pp>look, she added, &ldquo;That's what has driven
me mad. I killed my child to save him from
the gallows&mdash;oh! oh! One man hanged in a
family is enough. If I'd not gone mad, they
would have hanged me.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Poor soul!&rdquo; ejaculated her son.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I'll tell you a dream I had last night,&rdquo; 
continued the unfortunate being. &ldquo;I was at
Tyburn. There was a gallows erected, and a
great mob round it&mdash;thousands of people, and
all with white faces like corpses. In the midst
of them there was a cart with a man in it&mdash; 
and that man was Jack&mdash;my son Jack&mdash;they
were going to hang him. And opposite to
him, with a book in his hand,&mdash;but it could'nt
be a prayer&hyphen;book,&mdash;sat Jonathan Wild, in a
parson's cassock and band. I knew him in
spite of his dress. And when they came to
the gallows, Jack leaped out of the cart, and
the hangman tied up Jonathan instead&mdash;ha!
ha! How the mob shouted and huzzaed&mdash;and
I shouted too&mdash;ha! ha! ha!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Mother!&rdquo; cried Jack, unable to endure
this agonizing scene longer. &ldquo;Don't you know
me, mother?&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="242">
<p>&ldquo;Ah!&rdquo; shrieked Mrs. Sheppard. &ldquo;What's
that?&mdash;Jack's voice!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;It is,&rdquo; replied her son.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The ceiling is breaking! the floor is opening!
he is coming to me!&rdquo; cried the unhappy
woman.</p>
<p>&ldquo;He stands before you,&rdquo; rejoined her son.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Where?&rdquo; she cried. &ldquo;I can't see him.
Where is he?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Here,&rdquo; answered Jack.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Are you his ghost, then?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;No&mdash;no,&rdquo; answered Jack. &ldquo;I am your
most unhappy son.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Let me touch you, then; let me feel if
you are really flesh and blood,&rdquo; cried the poor
maniac, creeping towards him on all fours.</p>
<p>Jack did not advance to meet her. He could
not move; but stood like one stupified, with
his hands clasped together, and eyes almost
starting out of their sockets, fixed upon his
unfortunate parent.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Come to me!&rdquo; cried the poor maniac, who
had crawled as far as the chain would permit
her,&mdash;&ldquo;come to me!&rdquo; she cried, extending her
thin arm towards him.</p>
<pb>
<edit>[Figure: <bytes>388Kb</bytes>]</edit><figure sys.id="N010119">
<pb n="243">
<p>Jack fell on his knees beside her.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Who are you?&rdquo; inquired Mrs. Sheppard,
passing her hands over his face, and gazing
at him with a look that made him shudder.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Your son,&rdquo; replied Jack,&mdash;&ldquo;your miserable,
repentant son.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;It is false,&rdquo; cried Mrs. Sheppard. &ldquo;You
are not. Jack was not half your age when he
died. They buried him in Willesden churchyard
after the robbery.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Oh, God!&rdquo; cried Jack, &ldquo;she does not
know me. Mother&mdash;dear mother!&rdquo; he added,
clasping her in his arms. &ldquo;Look at me
again.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Off!&rdquo; she exclaimed, breaking from his
embrace with a scream. &ldquo;Don't touch me.
I'll be quiet. I'll not speak of Jack or Jonathan.
I won't dig their graves with my nails. Don't
strip me quite. Leave me my blanket! I'm
very cold at night. Or, if you must take off my
clothes, don't dash cold water on my head.
It throbs cruelly.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Horror!&rdquo; cried Jack.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Don't scourge me,&rdquo; she cried, trying to
hide herself in the farthest corner of the cell.</pp>
<pb n="244">
<pp>&ldquo;The lash cuts to the bone. I can't bear it.
Spare me, and I'll be quiet&mdash;quiet&mdash;quiet!&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Mother!&rdquo; said Jack, advancing towards
her.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Off!&rdquo; she cried with a prolonged and
piercing shriek. And she buried herself beneath
the straw, which she tossed above her
head with the wildest gestures.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I shall kill her if I stay longer,&rdquo; muttered
her son, completely terrified.</p>
<p>While he was considering what would be
best to do, the poor maniac, over whose bewildered
brain another change had come,
raised her head from under the straw, and,
peeping round the room, asked in a low voice,
&ldquo;If they were gone?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Who?&rdquo; inquired Jack.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The nurses,&rdquo; she answered.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Do they treat you ill?&rdquo; asked her son.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Hush!&rdquo; she said, putting her lean fingers
to her lips. &ldquo;Hush!&mdash;come hither, and I'll
tell you.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Jack approached her.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Sit beside me,&rdquo; continued Mrs. Sheppard.</pp>
<pb n="245">
<pp>&ldquo;And, now I'll tell you what they do. Stop!
we must shut the door, or they'll catch us.
See!&rdquo; she added, tearing the rag from her
head,&mdash;&ldquo;I had beautiful black hair once. But
they cut it all off.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;I shall go mad myself if I listen to her
longer,&rdquo; said Jack, attempting to rise. &ldquo;I
must go.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Don't stir, or they'll chain you to the wall,&rdquo; 
said his mother detaining him. &ldquo;Now, tell me
why they brought you here?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I came to see you, dear mother!&rdquo; answered
Jack.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Mother!&rdquo; she echoed,&mdash;&ldquo;mother! why do
you call me by that name?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Because you are my mother.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;What!&rdquo; she exclaimed, staring eagerly
in his face. &ldquo;Are you my son? Are you
Jack?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I am,&rdquo; replied Jack. &ldquo;Heaven be praised
she knows me at last.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Oh, Jack!&rdquo; cried his mother, falling upon
his neck, and covering him with kisses.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Mother&mdash;dear mother!&rdquo; said Jack, bursting
into tears.</p>
<pb n="246">
<p>&ldquo;You will never leave me,&rdquo; sobbed the poor
woman, straining him to her breast.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Never&mdash;never!&rdquo;</p>
<p>The words were scarcely pronounced, when
the door was violently thrown open, and two
men appeared at it. They were Jonathan Wild
and Quilt Arnold.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ah!&rdquo; exclaimed Jack, starting to his
feet.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Just in time,&rdquo; said the thieftaker. &ldquo;You
are my prisoner, Jack.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;You shall take my life first,&rdquo; rejoined Sheppard.</p>
<p>And, as he was about to put himself into a
posture of defence, his mother clasped him in
her arms.</p>
<p>&ldquo;They shall not harm you, my love!&rdquo; she
exclaimed.</p>
<p>The movement was fatal to her son. Taking
advantage of his embarrassed position, Jonathan
and his assistant rushed upon him, and
disarmed him.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Thank you, Mrs. Sheppard,&rdquo; cried the
thieftaker, as he slipped a pair of handcuffs over
Jack's wrists, &ldquo;for the help you have given us</pp>
<pb n="247">
<pp>in capturing your son. Without you, we might
have had some trouble.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>Aware, apparently in some degree, of the
mistake she had committed, the poor maniac
sprang towards him with frantic violence, and
planted her long nails in his cheek.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Keep off, you accursed jade!&rdquo; roared
Jonathan,&mdash;&ldquo;Keep off, I say, or&mdash;&rdquo; And he
struck her a violent blow with his clenched
hand.</p>
<p>The miserable woman staggered, uttered a
deep groan, and fell senseless on the straw.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Devil!&rdquo; cried Jack; &ldquo;that blow shall cost
you your life.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;It'll not need to be repeated, at all events,&rdquo; 
rejoined Jonathan, looking with a smile of
malignant satisfaction at the body. &ldquo;And, now,
&mdash;to Newgate.</p></div4>
<pb n="248">
<div4>
