CHAPTER IX.
<subhead>OLD NEWGATE.</subhead> <attbytes>18Kb</attbytes><reflink>000027</reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z400030656</ID><A1>Ainsworth, William Harrison, 1805&ndash;1882</A1><T1>Jack Sheppard. A Romance.</T1><PBL>Richard Bentley</PBL><Y1>1839</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd4>
<p><pp><smallcap>At</smallcap> the beginning of the twelfth century,&mdash; 
whether in the reign of Henry the First, or
Stephen is uncertain,&mdash;a fifth gate was added to
the four principal entrances of the city of London; 
then, it is almost needless to say, surrounded
by ramparts, moats, and other defences.
This gate, called <it>Newgate</it>, &ldquo;as being latelier
builded than the rest,&rdquo; continued, for upwards
of three hundred years, to be used as a place
of imprisonment for felons and trespassers; at
the end of which time, having grown old, ruinous,
and &ldquo;horribly loathsome,&rdquo; it was rebuilt
and enlarged by the executors of the renowned
Sir Richard Whittington, <it>the</it> Lord Mayor of
London: whence it afterwards obtained amongst
a certain class of students, whose examinations
were conducted with some strictness at the
Old Bailey, and their highest degrees taken at</pp>
<pb n="249">
<pp>Hyde&hyphen;park&hyphen;corner, the appellation of Whittington's
College, or, more briefly, the Whit. It
may here be mentioned that this gate, destined
to bequeath its name&mdash;a name, which has since
acquired a terrible significance,&mdash;to every successive
structure erected upon its site, was
granted, in 1400, by charter by Henry the
Sixth to the citizens of London, in return for
their royal services, and thenceforth became the
common gaol to that city and the country of
Middlesex. Nothing material occurred to Newgate,
until the memorable year 1666, when it
was utterly destroyed by the Great Fire. It is
with the building raised after this direful calamity
that our history has to deal.</pp></p>
<p><pp>Though by no means so extensive or commodious
as the modern prison, Old Newgate was
a large and strongly&hyphen;built pile. The body of
the edifice stood on the south side of Newgate
Street, and projected at the western extremity
far into the area opposite Saint Sepulchre's
Church. One small wing lay at the north of
the gate, where Giltspur Street Computer now
stands; and the Press Yard, which was detached
from the main building, was situated at the</pp>
<pb n="250">
<pp>back of Ph&oelig;nix Court. The south or principal
front, looking <it>down</it> the Old Bailey, and not
<it>upon it</it>, as is the case of the present structure,
with its massive walls of roughened free&hyphen;stone,
&mdash;in some places darkened by the smoke, in
others blanched, by exposure to the weather,&mdash; 
its heavy projecting cornice, its unglazed
doubly&hyphen;grated windows, its gloomy porch decorated
with fetters, and defended by an enormous
iron door, had a stern and striking effect. Over
the Lodge, upon a dial was inscribed the appropriate
motto, &ldquo;<it>Venio sicut fur.</it>&rdquo; The Gate,
which crossed Newgate Street, had a wide arch
for carriages, and a postern, on the north side,
for foot&hyphen;passengers. Its architecture was richly
ornamental, and resembled the style of a triumphal
entrance to a capital, rather than a dungeon,
having battlements and hexagonal towers,
and being adorned on the western side with a
triple range of pilasters of the Tuscan order,
amid the intercolumniations of which were
niches embellished with statues. The chief of
these was a figure of Liberty, with a cat at her
feet, in allusion to the supposed origin of the
fortunes of its former founder, Sir Richard Wittington.</pp>
<pb n="251">
<pp>On the right of the postern against
the wall was affixed a small grating, sustaining
the debtor's box; and any pleasure which the
passer&hyphen;by might derive from contemplating the
splendid structure above described was damped
at beholding the pale faces and squalid figures
of the captives across the bars of its strongly&hyphen;grated
windows. Some years after the date of
this history, an immense ventilator was placed
at the top of the Gate, with the view of purifying
the prison, which, owing to its insufficient
space and constantly&hyphen;crowded state, was never
free from that dreadful and contagious disorder,
now happily unknown, the gaol&hyphen;fever. So
frightful, indeed, were the ravages of this malady,
to which debtors and felons were alike exposed,
that its miserable victims were frequently
carried out by cart&hyphen;loads, and thrown into a
pit in the burial&hyphen;ground of Christ&hyphen;church, without
ceremony.</pp></p>
<p><pp>Old Newgate was divided into three separate
prisons,&mdash;the Master's Side, the Common Side,
and the Press Yard. The first of these, situated
at the south of the building, with the exception
of one ward over the gateway, was allotted</pp>
<pb n="252">
<pp>to the better class of debtors, whose funds enabled
them to defray their chamber&hyphen;rent, fees,
and garnish. The second, comprising the bulk
of the gaol, and by many degrees worse in point
of accommodation, having several dismal and
noisome wards under ground, was common
both to debtors and malefactors,&mdash;an association
little favourable to the morals or comforts
of the former, who, if they were brought there
with any notions of honesty, seldom left with
untainted principles. The last,&mdash;in all respects
the best and airiest of the three, standing, as has
been before observed, in Ph&oelig;nix Court, at the
rear of the main fabric,&mdash;was reserved for state&hyphen; 
offenders, and such persons as chose to submit
to the extortionate demands of the keeper: from
twenty to five hundred pounds premium, according
to the rank and means of the applicant,
in addition to a high weekly rent, being required
for accommodation in this quarter. Some excuse
for this rapacity may perhaps be found in
the fact, that five thousand pounds was paid for
the purchase of the Press Yard by Mr. Pitt,
the then governor of Newgate. This gentleman,
tried for high treason, in 1716, on suspicion of</pp>
<pb n="253">
<pp>aiding Mr. Forster, the rebel general's escape
but acquitted, reaped a golden harvest during
the occupation of his premises by the Preston
rebels, when a larger sum was obtained for a
single chamber than (in the words of a sufferer
on the occasion) &ldquo;would have paid the rent of
the best house in Saint James's Square or Piccadilly
for several years.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p><pp>Nor was this all. Other, and more serious
impositions, inasmuch as they affected a poorer
class of persons, were practised by the underlings
of the gaol. On his first entrance, a
prisoner, if unable or unwilling to comply with
the exactions of the turnkeys, was thrust into
the Condemned Hold with the worst description
of criminals, and terrified by threats into
submission. By the old regulations, the free
use of strong liquors not being interdicted, a
tap&hyphen;house was kept in the Lodge, and also in a
cellar on the Common Side,&mdash;under the superintendence
of Mrs. Spurling, formerly, it may
be remembered, the hostess of the Dark House
at Queenhithe,&mdash;whence wine, ale, and brandy
of inferior quality were dispensed, in false</pp>
<pb n="254">
<pp>measures, and at high prices, throughout the
prison, which in noise and debauchery rivalled,
if it did not surpass, the lowest tavern.</pp></p>
<p><pp>The chief scene of these disgusting orgies,&mdash; 
the cellar, just referred to,&mdash;was a large low&hyphen;roofed
vault, about four feet below the level of
the street, perfectly dark, unless when illumined
by a roaring fire, and candles stuck in pyramidal
lumps of clay, with a range of butts and
barrels at one end, and benches and tables at
the other, where the prisoners, debtors and
malefactors, male and female, assembled as
long as their money lasted, and consumed the
time in drinking, smoking, and gaming with
cards and dice. Above was a spacious hall,
connected with it by a flight of stone steps, at
the further end of which stood an immense
grated door, called in the slang of the place
&ldquo;The Jigger,&rdquo; through the bars of which the
felons in the upper wards were allowed to converse
with their friends, or if they wished to
enter the room, or join the revellers below, they
were at liberty to do so, on payment of a small
fine. Thus, the same system of plunder was</pp>
<pb n="255">
<pp>every where carried on. The gaolers robbed
the prisoners: the prisoners robbed one
another.</pp></p>
<p><pp>Two large wards were situated in the Gate; 
one of which, the Stone Ward, appropriated to
the master debtors, looked towards Holborn; 
the other called the Stone Hall, from a huge
stone standing in the middle of it, upon which
the irons of criminals under sentence of death
were knocked off previously to their being
taken to the place of execution, faced Newgate&hyphen;street.
Here the prisoners took exercise; and
a quaint, but striking picture has been left of
their appearance when so engaged, by the
author of the English Rogue. &ldquo;At my first
being acquainted with the place,&rdquo; says this
writer, in the &lsquo;Miseries of a Prison,&rsquo; &ldquo;the prisoners,
methought, walking up and down the
Stone Hall, looked like so many wrecks upon
the sea. Here the ribs of a thousand pounds
beating against the Needles&mdash;those dangerous
rocks, credulity; here floated, to and fro, silks,
stuffs, camlets, and velvet, without giving place
to each other, according to their dignity; here
rolled so many pipes of canary, whose bungholes</pp>
<pb n="256">
<pp>lying open, were so damaged that the
merchant may go hoop for his money.&rdquo; A less
picturesque, but more truthful, and, therefore,
more melancholy description of the same scene,
is furnished by the shrewd and satirical Ned
Ward, who informs us, in the &ldquo;Delectable History
of Whittington's College,&rdquo; that &ldquo;When
the prisoners are disposed to recreate themselves
with walking, they go up into a spacious
room, called the Stone Hall; where, when you
see them taking a turn together, it would
puzzle one to know which is the gentleman,
which the mechanic, and which the beggar, for
they are all suited in the same garb of squalid
poverty, making a spectacle of more pity than
executions; only to be out at the elbows is in
fashion here, and a great indecorum not to be
threadbare.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p><pp>In an angle of the Stone Hall was the Iron
Hold, a chamber containing a vast assortment
of fetters and handcuffs of all weights and
sizes. Four prisoners, termed &ldquo;The Partners,&rdquo; 
had charge of this hold. Their duty was to
see who came in, or went out; to lock up, and
open the different wards; to fetter such prisoners</pp>
<pb n="257">
<pp>as were ordered to be placed in irons; 
to distribute the allowances of provision; and
to maintain some show of decorum; for which
latter purpose they were allowed to carry whips
and truncheons. When any violent outrage
was committed,&mdash;and such matters were of
daily, sometimes hourly, occurrence,&mdash;a bell
the rope of which descended into the hall,
assistance. A narrow passage at the north of
the Stone Hall led to the Bluebeard's room of
this enchanted castle, a place shunned even by
the reckless crew who were compelled to pass
it. It was a sort of cooking&hyphen;room, with an
immense fire&hyphen;place flanked by a couple of cauldrons,
and was called Jack Ketch's Kitchen,
because the quarters of persons executed for
treason were there boiled by the hangman in
oil, pitch, and tar, before they were affixed on
the city gates, or on London Bridge. Above
this revolting spot was the female debtor's
ward; below it a gloomy cell, called Tangier; 
and noisome dungeon, situated underground,
and unvisited by a single ray of daylight. Built</pp>
<pb n="258">
<pp>and paved with stone, without beds, or any
other sort of protection from the cold, this
dreadful hole, accounted the most dark and
dismal in the prison, was made the receptacle
of such miserable wretches as could not pay
the customary fees. Adjoining it was the
Lower Ward,&mdash;&ldquo;Though, in what degree of
latitude it was situated,&rdquo; observes Ned Ward,
&ldquo;I cannot positively demonstrate, unless it lay
ninety degrees beyond the North Pole; for,
instead of being dark there but half a year, it
is dark all the year round.&rdquo; It was only a
shade better than the Stone Hold. Here were
imprisoned the fines; and, &ldquo;perhaps,&rdquo; adds
the before&hyphen;cited authority, &ldquo;if he behaved himself,
an outlawed person might creep in among
them.&rdquo; Ascending the gate once more on the
way back, we find over the Stone Hall another
large room, called Debtors' Hall, facing Newgate&hyphen;street,
with &ldquo;very good air and light,&rdquo; A
little too much of the former, perhaps; as the
windows being unglazed, the prisoners were
subjected to sever annoyance from the weather
and easterly winds.</pp></p>
<p><pp>Of the women felon's rooms nothing has yet</pp>
<pb n="259">
<pp>been said. There were two. One called
Waterman's Hall, a horrible place adjoining
the postern under the gate, whence, through a
small barred aperture, they solicited alms from
the passengers: the other, a large chamber,
denominated My Lady's Hold, was situated in
the highest part of the gaol, at the northern
extremity. Neither of these wards had beds,
and the unfortunate inmates were obliged to
take their rest on the oaken floor. The condition
of the rooms was indescribably filthy and
disgusting; nor were the habits of the occupants
much more cleanly. In other respects,
they were equally indecorous and offensive.
&ldquo;It is with no small concern,&rdquo; writes an anonymous
historian of Newgate, &ldquo;that I am
obliged to observe that the women in every
ward of this prison are exceedingly worse than
the worst of the men, not only in respect to
their mode of living, but more especially as to
their conversation, which, to their great shame,
is as profane and wicked as hell itself can possibly
be.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p><pp>There were two Condemned Holds,&mdash;one for</pp>
<pb n="260">
<pp>each sex. That for the men lay near the
Lodge, with which it was connected by a dark
passage. It was a large room, about twenty
feet long and fifteen broad, and had an arched
stone roof. In fact, it had been anciently the
right hand postern under the gate leading towards
the city. The floor was planked with
oak, and covered with iron staples, hooks, and
ring&hyphen;bolts, with heavy chains attached to them.
There was only one small grated window in this
hold, which admitted but little light.</pp></p>
<p>Over the gateway towards Snow Hill were
two strong wards, called the Castle and the
Red Room. They will claim particular attention
hereafter.</p>
<p><pp>Many other wards,&mdash;especially on the Master
Debtor's side,&mdash;have been necessarily
omitted in the foregoing hasty enumeration.
But there were two places of punishment which
merit some notice from their peculiarity. The
first of these, the Press Room, a dark close
chamber, near Waterman's Hall obtained its
name from an immense wooden machine kept
in it, with which such prisoners as refused to</pp>
<pb n="261">
<pp>plead to their indictments were pressed to
death&mdash;a species of inquisitorial torture not
discontinued until so lately as the early part of
the reign of George the Third, when it was
abolished by an express statute. Into the
second, denominated the Bilbowes,&mdash;also a dismal
place,&mdash;refractory prisoners were thrust,
and placed in a kind of stocks, whence the
name.</pp></p>
<p>The Chapel was situated in the south&hyphen;east
angle of the gaol; the ordinary at the time of
this history being the Reverend Thomas Purney; 
the deputy chaplain, Mr. Wagstaff.</p>
<p><pp>Much has been advanced by modern writers
respecting the demoralising effect of prison
society; and it has been asserted, that a youth
once confined in Newgate, is certain to come
out a confirmed thief. However this may be
now, it was unquestionably true of old Newgate.
It was the grand nursery of vice,&mdash;&ldquo;a
famous university,&rdquo; observes Ned Ward, in the
London Spy, &ldquo;where, if a man has a mind to
educate a hopeful child in the daring science of
padding; the light&hyphen;fingered subtlety of shoplifting;</pp>
<pb n="262">
<pp>the excellent use of jack and crow; for
the silently drawing bolts, and forcing barricades; 
with the knack of sweetening; or the
most ingenious dexterity of picking pockets; 
let him but enter in this college on the
Common Side, and confine him close to his
study but for three months; and if he does not
come out qualified to take any degree of villainy,
he must be the most honest dunce that
ever had the advantage of such eminent
tutors.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>To bring down this imperfect sketch of
Newgate to the present time, it may be mentioned
that, being found inadequate to the
purpose required, the old gaol was pulled down
in 1770. Just at the completion of the new
gaol, in 1780, it was assailed by the mob during
the Gordon riots, fired, and greatly damaged.
The devastations, however, were speedily made
good; and, in two years more, it was finished.</p>
<p><pp>It is a cheering reflection, that in the present
prison, with its clean, well&hyphen;whitewashed, and
well&hyphen;ventilated wards, its airy courts, its infirmary,
its improved regulations, and its humane</pp>
<pb n="263">
<pp>and intelligent officers, many of the miseries of
the old gaol are removed. The these beneficial
changes society is mainly indebted to the
unremitting exertions of the philanthropic
<smallcap>Howard.</smallcap></pp></p></div4>
<pb n="264">
<div4>
<comhd4><idref>Z400030657</idref><collection>1 2</collection>
CHAPTER X.
<subhead>HOW JACK SHEPPARD GOT OUT OF THE CONDEMNED
HOLD</subhead> <attbytes>34Kb</attbytes><reflink>000027</reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z400030657</ID><A1>Ainsworth, William Harrison, 1805&ndash;1882</A1><T1>Jack Sheppard. A Romance.</T1><PBL>Richard Bentley</PBL><Y1>1839</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd4>
<p><pp><smallcap>Monday</smallcap>, the 31st of August 1724,&mdash;a day
long afterwards remembered by the officers
of Newgate,&mdash;was distinguished by an unusual
influx of visitors to the Lodge. On that morning
the dead warrant had arrived from Windsor,
ordering Sheppard for execution, (since
his capture by Jonathan Wild in Bedlam, as
related in a former chapter, Jack had been
tried, convicted, and sentenced to death,)
together with three malefactors, on the
following Friday. Up to this moment, hopes
had been entertained of a respite, strong representations
in his favour having been made
in the highest quarter; but now that his fate
seemed sealed, the curiosity of the sight&hyphen;seeing
public to behold him was redoubled. The
prison gates were besieged like the entrance of
a booth at a fair; and the Condemned Hold,</pp>
<pb n="265">
<pp>where he was confined, and to which visitors
were admitted at the moderate rate of a guinea
a&hyphen;head, had quite the appearance of a showroom.
As the day wore on, the crowds diminished,
&mdash;many who would not submit to the
turnkey's demands were sent away ungratified,
&mdash;and at five o'clock, only two strangers, Mr.
Shotbolt, the head turnkey of Clerkenwell
Prison, and Mr. Griffin, who held the same
office in Westminster Gatehouse, were left in
the Lodge. Jack, who had formerly been in
the custody of both these gentlemen, gave them
a very cordial welcome; apologized for the
sorry room he was compelled to receive them
in; and when they took leave, insisted on
treating them to a double bowl of punch, which
they were now discussing with the upper
gaoler, Mr. Ireton, and his two satellites, Austin
and Langley. At a little distance from the
party, sat a tall, sinister&hyphen;looking personage,
with harsh inflexible features, a gaunt but muscular
frame, and large bony hands. He was
sipping a glass of cold gin and water, and
smoking a short black pipe. His name was</pp>
<pb n="266">
<pp>Marvel, and his avocation, which was as repulsive
as his looks, was that of public executioner.
By his side sat a remarkably stout dame, to
whom he paid as much attention as it was in his
iron nature to pay. She had a nut&hyphen;brown
skin, a swarthy upper lip, a merry black eye, a
prominent bust, and a tun&hyphen;like circumference of
waist. A widow for the fourth time, Mrs. Spurling,
(for she it was,) either by her attractions
of purse or person, had succeeded in moving the
stony heart of Mr. Marvel, who, as he had
helped to deprive her of her former husbands,
thought himself in duty bound to offer to supply
their place. But the lady was not so easily
won; and though she did not absolutely reject
him, gave him very slight hopes. Mr. Marvel,
therefore, remained on his probation. Behind
Mrs. Spurling stood her negro attendant,
Caliban; a hideous, misshapen, malicious
monster, with broad hunched shoulders, a flat
nose, and ears like those of a wild beast, a
head too large for his body, and a body
too long for his legs. This horrible piece of
deformity, who acted as drawer and cellarman,</pp>
<pb n="267">
<pp>and was a constant butt to the small wits
of the gaol, was nicknamed the Black Dog of
Newgate.</pp></p>
<p><pp>In the general survey of the prison, taken in
the preceding chapter, but little was said of the
Lodge. It may be well, therefore, before proceeding
farther, to describe it more minutely.
It was approached from the street by a flight
of broad stone steps, leading to a ponderous
door, plated with iron, and secured on the
inner side by huge bolts, and a lock, with
wards of a prodigious size. A little within
stood a second door, or rather wicket, lower
than the first, but of equal strength, and surmounted
by a row of sharp spikes. As no
apprehension was entertained of an escape by
this outlet,&mdash;nothing of the kind having been
attempted by the boldest felon ever incarcerated
in Newgate,&mdash;both doors were generally
left open during the day&hyphen;time. At six o'clock,
the wicket was shut; and at nine, the gaol
was altogether locked up. Not far from the
entrance, on the left, was a sort of screen, or
partition&hyphen;wall, reaching from the floor to the
ceiling, formed of thick oaken planks riveted</pp>
<pb n="268">
<pp>together by iron bolts, and studded with broadheaded
nails. In this screen which masked the
entrance of a dark passage communicating with
the Condemned Hold, about five feet from the
ground, was a hatch, protected by long spikes
set six inches apart, and each of the thickness
of an elephant's tusk. The spikes almost
touched the upper part of the hatch: scarcely
space enough for the passage of a hand being
left between their points and the beam. Here,
as has already been observed, condemned malefactors
were allowed to converse with such of
their guests as had not interest or money
enough to procure admission to them in the
hold. Beyond the hatch, an angle, formed by
a projection in the wall of some three or four
feet, served to hide a door conducting to the
interior of the prison. At the farther end of
the Lodge, the floor was raised to the height of
a couple of steps; whence the whole place,
with the exception of the remotest corner of
the angle before&hyphen;mentioned, could be commanded
at a single glance. On this elevation a
table was now placed, around which sat the
turnkeys and their guests, regaling themselves
on the fragrant beverage provided by the prisoner.</pp>
<pb n="269">
<pp>A brief description will suffice for
them. They were all stout ill&hyphen;favoured men,
attired in the regular gaol&hyphen;livery of scratch
wig and snuff&hyphen;coloured suit; and had all a
strong family likeness to each other. The only
difference between the officers of Newgate and
their brethren was, that they had enormous
bunches of keys at their girdles, while the
latter had left their keys at home.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Well, I've seen many a gallant fellow in
my time, Mr. Ireton,&rdquo; observed the chief turnkey
of Westminster Gatehouse, as he helped
himself to his third glass of punch; &ldquo;but I
never saw one like Jack Sheppard.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Nor I,&rdquo; returned Ireton, following his example:
&ldquo;and I've had some experience too.
Ever since he came here, three months ago,
he has been the life and soul of the place; and
now the dead warrant has arrived, instead of
being cast down, as most men would be, and
as all others <it>are</it>, he's gayer than ever. Well,
<it>I</it> shall be sorry to lose him, Mr. Griffin.
We've made a pretty penny by him&mdash;sixty
guineas this blessed day.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;No more!&rdquo; cried Griffin, incredulously;</pp>
<pb n="270">
<pp>I should have thought you must have made
double that sum at least.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Not a farthing more, I assure you,&rdquo; rejoined
Ireton, pettishly; &ldquo;we're all on the
square here. I took the money myself, and
<it>ought</it> to know.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Oh! certainly,&rdquo; answered Griffin; &ldquo;certainly.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I offered Jack five guineas as his share,&rdquo; 
continued Ireton; &ldquo;but he wouldn't take it
himself, and gave it to the poor debtors and
felons, who are now drinking it out in the
cellar on the Common Side.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Jack's a noble fellow,&rdquo; exclaimed the
head&hyphen;gaoler of Clerkenwell Prison, raising his
glass; &ldquo;and, though he played me a scurvy
trick, I'll drink to his speedy deliverance.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;At Tyburn, eh, Mr. Shotbolt?&rdquo; rejoined
the executioner. &ldquo;I'll pledge you in that
toast with all my heart.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Well, for my part,&rdquo; observed Mrs. Spurling,
&ldquo;I hope he may never see Tyburn.
And, if I'd my own way with the Secretary of
State, he never <it>should</it>. It's a thousand pities
to hang so pretty a fellow. There haven't</pp>
<pb n="271">
<pp>been so many ladies in the Lodge since the
days of Claude Du Val, the gentleman highwayman; 
and they all declare it'll break their
hearts if he's scragged.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Bah!&rdquo; ejaculated Marvel, gruffly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;You think our sex has no feeling, I suppose,
sir,&rdquo; cried Mrs. Spurling, indignantly; 
&ldquo;but I can tell you we have. And, what's
more, I tell you, if Captain Sheppard <it>is</it> hanged,
you need never hope to call <it>me</it> Mrs. Marvel.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;'Zounds!&rdquo; cried the executioner, in astonishment.
&ldquo;Do you know what you are talking
about, Mrs. Spurling? Why, if Captain
Sheppard should get off, it 'ud be fifty guineas
out of my way. There's the grand laced coat
he wore at his trial, which I intend for my
wedding&hyphen;dress.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Don't mention such a thing, sir,&rdquo; interrupted
the tapstress. &ldquo;I could'nt bear to see
you in it. You're speaking of the trial brings
the whole scene to my mind. Ah! I shall
never forget the figure Jack cut on that occasion.
What a buzz of admiration ran round
the court as he appeared! And, how handsome
and composed he looked! Everybody</pp>
<pb n="272">
<pp>wondered that such a stripling could commit
such desperate robberies. His firmness never
deserted him till his old master, Mr. Wood,
was examined. Then he <it>did</it> give way a bit.
And when Mr. Wood's daughter,&mdash;to whom,
I've heard tell, he was attached years ago,&mdash; 
was brought up, his courage forsook him altogether,
and he trembled, and could scarcely
stand. Poor young lady! <it>She</it> trembled too,
and was unable to give her evidence. When
sentence was passed there wasn't a dry eye in
the court.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Yes, there was one,&rdquo; observed Ireton.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I guess who you mean,&rdquo; rejoined Shotbolt.
&ldquo;Mr. Wild's.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Right,&rdquo; answered Ireton. &ldquo;It's strange
the antipathy he bears to Sheppard. I was
standing near Jack at that awful moment, and
beheld the look Wild fixed on him. It was
like the grin of a fiend, and made my flesh
creep on my bones. When the prisoner was removed
from the dock, we met Jonathan as we
passed through the yard. He stopped us, and,
addressing Jack in a taunting tone, said,
&lsquo;Well, I've been as good as my word!&rsquo;&mdash;</pp>
<pb n="273">
<pp>&lsquo;True,&rsquo; replied Sheppard; &lsquo;and I'll be as
good as mine!&rsquo; And so they parted.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;And I hope he will, if it's anything to
Jonathan's disadvantage,&rdquo; muttered Mrs. Spurling,
half aside.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I'm surprised Mr. Wild hasn't been to inquire
after him to&hyphen;day,&rdquo; observed Langley; 
&ldquo;it's the first time he's missed doing so since
the trial.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;He's gone to Enfield after Blueskin, who
has so long eluded his vigilance,&rdquo; rejoined
Austin. &ldquo;Quilt Arnold called this morning to
say so. Certain information, it seems, has
been received from a female, that Blueskin
would be at a flash&hyphen;ken near the Chase at five
o'clock to day, and they're all set out in the
expectation of nabbing him.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Mr. Wild had a narrow escape lately, in
that affair of Captain Darrell,&rdquo; observed Shotbolt.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I don't exactly know the rights of that
affair,&rdquo; rejoined Griffin, with some curiosity.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Nor any one else, I suspect,&rdquo; answered
Ireton, winking significantly. &ldquo;It's a mysterious
transaction altogether. But, as much</pp>
<pb n="274">
<pp>as is known is this: Captain Darrell, who
resides with Mr. Wood at Dollis Hill,
was assaulted and half&hyphen;killed by a party
of ruffians, headed, he swore, by Mr. Wild,
and his uncle, Sir Rowland Trenchard. Mr.
Wild, however, proved, on the evidence of
his own servants, that he was at the Old Bailey
at the time; and Sir Rowland proved that <it>he</it>
was in Manchester. So the charge was dismissed.
Another charge was then brought against them
by the captain, who accused them of kidnapping
him when a boy, and placing him in the
hands of a Dutch skipper, named Van Galgebrok,
with instructions to throw him overboard,
which was done, though he afterwards
escaped. But this accusation, for want of sufficient
evidence, met with the same fate as the
first, and Jonathan came off victorious. It
was thought, however, if the skipper <it>could</it>
have been found, that the result of the case
would have been materially different. This
was rather too much to expect; for we all
know, if Mr. Wild wishes to keep a man out of
the way, he'll speedily find the means to do so.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Ay, ay,&rdquo; cried the gaolers, laughing.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;<it>I</it> could have given awkward evidence in</pp>
<pb n="275">
<pp>that case, if I'd been so inclined,&rdquo; said Mrs.
Spurling, &ldquo;ay and found Van Galgebrok too.
But I never betray an old customer.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Mr. Wild is a great man,&rdquo; said the hangman,
replenishing his pipe, &ldquo;and we owe him
much, and ought to support him. Were any
thing to happen to him, Newgate wouldn't be
what it is, nor Tyburn either.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Mr. Wild has given you some employment,
Mr. Marvel,&rdquo; remarked Shotbolt.</p>
<p>&ldquo;A little, sir,&rdquo; replied the executioner, with
a grim smile. &ldquo;Out of the twelve hundred
subjects I've tucked up, I may safely place
half to his account. If ever he requires my
services, he shall find I'm not ungrateful.
And though I say it that shouldn't say it, no
man can tie a better knot. Mr. Wild, gentlemen,
and the nubbin'&hyphen;cheat.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Fill your glasses, gentlemen,&rdquo; observed
Ireton, &ldquo;and I'll tell you a droll thing Jack said
this morning. Amongst others who came to see
him, was a Mr. Kneebone, a woollen&hyphen;draper in
Wych Street, with whose pockets, it appears,
Jack, when a lad, made a little too free. As
this gentleman was going away, he said to Jack</pp>
<pb n="276">
<pp>in a jesting manner, &lsquo;that he should be glad
to see him to&hyphen;night at supper.&rsquo; Upon which
the other answered, &lsquo;that he accepted his invitation
with pleasure, and would make a point
of waiting upon him.&rsquo; Ha! ha! ha!&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;<it>Did</it> he say so?&rdquo; cried Shotbolt. &ldquo;Then I
advise you to look sharply after him, Mr. Ireton; 
for may I be hanged myself if I don't
believe he'll be as good as his word.&rdquo;</p>
<p>At this juncture, two women, very smartly
attired in silk hoods and cloaks, appeared at
the door of the Lodge.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ah! who have we here?&rdquo; exclaimed Griffin.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Only Jack's two wives&mdash;Edgeworth Bess
and Poll Maggot,&rdquo; replied Austin, laughing.</p>
<p>&ldquo;They can't go into the Condemned Hold,&rdquo; 
said Ireton, consequentially; &ldquo;it's against Mr.
Wild's orders. They must see the prisoner at
the hatch.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Very well, sir,&rdquo; replied Austin, rising and
walking towards them. &ldquo;Well, my pretty
dears,&rdquo; he added,&mdash;&ldquo;come to see your husband,
eh? You must make the most of your time.
You won't have him long. You've heard the
news, I suppose?&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="277">
<p>&ldquo;That the dead warrant's arrived,&rdquo; returned
Edgeworth Bess, bursting into a flood of tears; 
&ldquo;oh, yes! we've heard it.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;How does Jack bear it?&rdquo; inquired Mrs.
Maggot.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Like a hero,&rdquo; answered Austin.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I knew he would,&rdquo; replied the Amazon.
&ldquo;Come, Bess,&mdash;no whimpering. Don't unman
him. Are we to see him here?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Yes, my love.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Well, then, lose no time in bringing him
to us,&rdquo; said Mrs. Maggot. There's a guinea
to drink our health,&rdquo; she added, slipping a
piece of money into his hand.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Here, Caliban,&rdquo; shouted the under&hyphen;turnkey,
&ldquo;unlock Captain Sheppard's padlock, and tell
him his wives are in the Lodge waiting to see
him.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Iss, Massa Austin,&rdquo; replied the black. And
taking the keys, he departed on the errand.</p>
<p><pp>As soon as he was gone, the two women
divested themselves of their hoods and cloaks,
and threw them, as if inadvertently, into the
farthest part of the angle in the wall. Their
beautifully proportioned figures and rather overdisplayed</pp>
<pb n="278">
<pp>shoulders attracted the notice of
Austin, who inquired of the chief turnkey
&ldquo;whether he should stand by them during the
interview?&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Oh! never mind them,&rdquo; said Mrs. Spurling,
who had been hastily compounding another
bowl of punch. &ldquo;Sit down, and enjoy yourself.
I'll keep a look out that nothing happens.&rdquo;</p>
<p>By this time Caliban had returned, and Jack
appeared at the hatch. He was wrapped in a
loose dressing&hyphen;gown of light material, and stood
near the corner where the women's dresses
had just been thrown down, quite out of sight
of all the party, except Mrs. Spurling, who sat
on the right of the table.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Have you got Jonathan out of the way?&rdquo; 
he asked, in an eager whisper.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Yes, yes,&rdquo; replied Edgeworth Bess. &ldquo;Patience
Kite has lured him to Enfield on a false
scent after Blueskin. You need fear no interruption
from him, or any of his myrmidons.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;That's well!&rdquo; cried Jack. &ldquo;Now stand
before me, Poll. I've got the watch&hyphen;spring
saw in my sleeve. Pretend to weep both of</pp>
<pb n="279">
<pp>you as loudly as you can. This spike is more
than half cut through. I was at work at it
yesterday and the day before. Keep up the
clamour for five minutes, and I'll finish it.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>Thus urged, the damsels began to raise their
voices in loud lamentation.</p>
<p>&ldquo;What the devil are you howling about?&rdquo; 
cried Langley. &ldquo;Do you think we are to be
disturbed in this way? Make less noise,
hussies, or I'll turn you out of the Lodge.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;For shame, Mr. Langley,&rdquo; rejoined Mrs.
Spurling: &ldquo;I blush for you, sir! To call
yourself a man, and interfere with the natural
course of affection! Have you no feeling
for the situation of those poor disconsolate
creatures, about to be bereaved of all they hold
dear? Is it nothing to part with a husband to
the gallows? I've lost four in the same way,
and know what it is.&rdquo; Here she began to
blubber loudly for sympathy.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Comfort yourself, my charmer,&rdquo; said Mr.
Marvel, in a tone intended to be consolatory.
&ldquo;I'll be their substitute.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;<it>You</it>!&rdquo; cried the tapstress, with a look of
horror: &ldquo;Never!&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="280">
<p>&ldquo;Confusion!&rdquo; muttered Jack, suddenly
pausing in his task, &ldquo;the saw has broken just
as I am through the spike.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Can't we break it off?&rdquo; replied Mrs.
Maggot.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I fear not,&rdquo; replied Jack, despondingly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Let's try, at all events,&rdquo; returned the
Amazon.</p>
<p>And grasping the thick iron rod, she pushed
with all her force against it, while Jack seconded
her efforts from within. After great
exertions on both parts, the spike yielded to
their combined strength, and snapped suddenly off.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Holloa&mdash;what's that?&rdquo; cried Austin, starting up.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Only my darbies,&rdquo; returned Jack, clinking
his chains.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Oh! that was all, was it?&rdquo; said the turnkey,
quietly re&hyphen;seating himself.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Now, give me the woollen cloth to tie
round my fetters,&rdquo; whispered Sheppard.
&ldquo;Quick.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Here it is,&rdquo; replied Edgeworth Bess.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Give me your hand, Poll, to help me</pp>
<pb>
<edit>[Figure: <bytes>407Kb</bytes>]</edit><figure sys.id="N010120">
<pb n="281">
<pp>through,&rdquo; cried Jack, as he accomplished the
operation. &ldquo;Keep a sharp look out, Bess.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Stop!&rdquo; interposed Edgeworth Bess; &ldquo;Mr
Langley is getting up, and coming this way.
We're lost.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Help me through at all hazards, Poll,&rdquo; 
cried Jack, straining towards the opening.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The danger's past,&rdquo; whispered Bess.
&ldquo;Mrs. Spurling has induced him to sit down
again. Ah! she looks this way, and puts her
finger to her lips. She comprehends what
we're about. We're all safe!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Don't lose a moment then,&rdquo; cried Jack,
forcing himself into the aperture, while the
Amazon, assisted by Bess, pulled him through
it.</p>
<p>&ldquo;There!&rdquo; cried Mrs. Maggot, as she placed
him without noise upon the ground; &ldquo;you're
safe so far.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Come, my disconsolate darlings,&rdquo; cried
Austin, &ldquo;it only wants five minutes to six. I
expect Mr. Wild here presently. Cut it as
short as you can.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Only two minutes more, sir,&rdquo; intreated
Edgeworth Bess, advancing towards him in</pp>
<pb n="282">
<pp>such a manner as to screen Jack, who crept
into the farthest part of the angle,&mdash;&ldquo;only two
minutes, and we've done.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Well, well, I'm not within a minute,&rdquo; 
rejoined the turnkey.</p>
<p>&ldquo;We shall never be able to get you out unseen,
Jack,&rdquo; whispered Poll Maggot. &ldquo;You
must make a bold push.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Impossible,&rdquo; replied Sheppard, in the
same tone. &ldquo;That would be certain destruction.
I can't run in these heavy fetters. No:
I must face it out. Tell Bess to slip out, and
I'll put on her cloak and hood.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Meanwhile, the party at the table continued
drinking and chatting as merrily as before.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I can't help thinking of Jack Sheppard's
speech to Mr. Kneebone,&rdquo; observed Shotbolt,
as he emptied his tenth tumbler; &ldquo;I'm sure
he's meditating an escape, and hopes to accomplish
it to&hyphen;night.&rdquo;</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Poh! poh!&rdquo; rejoined Ireton; it was mere
idle boasting. I examined the Condemned
Hold myself carefully this morning, and didn't
find a nail out of its place. Recollect, he's
chained to the ground by a great horse&hyphen;padlock,</pp>
<pb n="283">
<pp>and is never unloosed except when he
comes to that hatch. If he escapes at all, it
must be before our faces.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;It wouldn't surprise me if he did,&rdquo; remarked
Griffin. &ldquo;He's audacity enough for
anything. He got out in much the same way
from the Gatehouse,&mdash;stole the keys, and passed
through a room where I was sitting halfasleep
in a chair.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Caught you napping, eh?&rdquo; rejoined Ireton,
with a laugh. &ldquo;Well, he won't do that here.
I'll forgive him if he does.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;And so will I,&rdquo; said Austin. &ldquo;We're
too wide awake for that. Ain't we, partner?&rdquo; 
he added, appealing to Langley, whom punch
had made rather dozy.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I should think so,&rdquo; responded the lethargic
turnkey, with a yawn.</p>
<p>During this colloquy, Jack had contrived
unobserved to put on the hood and cloak, and
being about the size of the rightful owner, presented
a very tolerable resemblance to her.
This done, Edgeworth Bess, who watched her
opportunity, slipped out of the Lodge.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Halloa!&rdquo; exclaimed Austin, who had</pp>
<pb n="284">
<pp>caught a glimpse of her departing figure, &ldquo;one
of the women is gone!&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;No&mdash;no,&rdquo; hastily interposed Mrs. Spurling; 
they're both here. Don't you see they're
putting on their cloaks?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;That's false!&rdquo; rejoined Marvel, in a low
tone; &ldquo;I perceive what has taken place.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Oh! goodness!&rdquo; ejaculated the tapstress,
in alarm. &ldquo;You won't betray him.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Say the word, and I'm mum,&rdquo; returned
the executioner. &ldquo;Will you be mine?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;It's a very unfair advantage to take&mdash; 
very,&rdquo; replied Mrs. Spurling; &ldquo;however, I
consent.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Then I'll lend a helping hand. I shall
lose my fees and the laced coat. But it's better
to have the bride without the weddin'
dress, than the weddin' dress without the
bride.&rdquo;</p>
<p>At this moment, Saint Sepulchre's clock
struck six.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Close the wicket, Austin,&rdquo; vociferated
Ireton, in an authoritative tone.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Good bye!&rdquo; cried Jack, as if taking leave
of his mistresses, &ldquo;to&hyphen;morrow, at the same
time.</p>
<pb n="285">
<p>&ldquo;We'll be punctual,&rdquo; replied Mrs. Maggot.
&ldquo;Good bye, Jack! Keep up your spirits.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Now for it!&mdash;life or death!&rdquo; exclaimed
Jack, assuming the gait of a female, and stepping
towards the door.</p>
<p>As Austin rose to execute his principal's
commands, and usher the women to the gate,
Mrs. Spurling and Marvel rose too. The latter
walked carelessly towards the hatch, and
leaning his back against the place whence the
spike had been removed, so as completely to
hide it, continued smoking his pipe as coolly as
if nothing had happened.</p>
<p>Just as Jack gained the entrance, he heard a
man's footstep behind him, and aware that the
slightest indiscretion would betray him, he
halted, uncertain what to do.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Stop a minute, my dear,&rdquo; cried Austin.
&ldquo;You forget that you promised me a kiss the
last time you were here.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Won't one from me do as well?&rdquo; interposed
Mrs. Maggot.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Much better,&rdquo; said Mrs. Spurling, hastening
to the rescue. &ldquo;I want to speak to Edgeworth
Bess myself.&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="286">
<p>So saying, she planted herself between Jack
and the turnkey. It was a moment of breathless
interest to all engaged in the attempt.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Come&mdash;the kiss!&rdquo; cried Austin, endeavouring
to pass his arm familiarly round the
Amazon's waist.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Hands off!&rdquo; she exclaimed, &ldquo;or you'll
repent it.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Why, what'll you do?&rdquo; demanded the
turnkey.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Teach you to keep your distance!&rdquo; retorted
Mrs. Maggot, dealing him a buffet that sent
him reeling several yards backwards.</p>
<p>&ldquo;There! off with you!&rdquo; whispered Mrs.
Spurling, squeezing Jack's arm, and pushing
him towards the door, &ldquo;and, don't come here
again.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Before Austin could recover himself, Jack
and Mrs. Maggot had disappeared.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Bolt the wicket!&rdquo; shouted Ireton, who,
with the others, had been not a little entertained
by the gallant turnkey's discomfiture.</p>
<p><pp>This was done, and Austin returned with a
crest&hyphen;fallen look to the table. Upon which</pp>
<pb n="287">
<pp>Mrs. Spurling, and her now accepted suitor,
resumed their seats.</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;You'll be as good as your word, my
charmer,&rdquo; whispered the executioner.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Of course,&rdquo; responded the widow, heaving
a deep sigh. &ldquo;Oh! Jack! Jack!&mdash;you little
know what a price I've paid for you!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Well, I'm glad those women are gone,&rdquo; 
remarked Shotbolt. &ldquo;Coupling their presence
with Jack's speech, I couldn't help fearing
some mischief might ensue.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;That reminds me he's still at large,&rdquo; returned
Ireton. &ldquo;Here, Caliban, go and fasten
his padlock.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Iss, Massa Ireton,&rdquo; replied the black.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;Stop, Caliban,&rdquo; interposed Mrs. Spurling,
who wished to protract the discovery of the
escape as long as possible. &ldquo;Before you go,
bring me the bottle of pine&hyphen;apple rum I opened
yesterday. I should like Mr. Ireton and his
friends to taste it. It is in the lower cupboard.
Oh! you haven't got the key&mdash;then <it>I</it> must
have it, I suppose. How provoking!&rdquo; she
added, pretending to rummage her pockets;</pp>
<pb n="288">
<pp>&ldquo;one never <it>can</it> find a thing when one wants
it.&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Never mind it, my dear Mrs. Spurling,&rdquo; 
rejoined Ireton; &ldquo;we can taste the rum when
he returns. We shall have Mr. Wild here presently,
and I wouldn't for the world&mdash;Zounds!&rdquo; 
he exclaimed, as the figure of the thieftaker
appeared at the wicket, &ldquo;here he is. Off with
you, Caliban! Fly, you rascal!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Mr. Wild here!&rdquo; exclaimed Mrs. Spurling
in alarm. &ldquo;Oh gracious! he's lost.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Who's lost?&rdquo; demanded Ireton.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The key,&rdquo; replied the widow.</p>
<p>All the turnkeys rose to salute the thieftaker,
whose habitually&hyphen;sullen countenance looked
gloomier than usual. Ireton rushed forward to
open the wicket for him.</p>
<p>&ldquo;No Blueskin, I perceive, sir,&rdquo; he observed,
in a deferential tone, as Wild entered the
Lodge.</p>
<p><pp>&ldquo;No,&rdquo; replied Jonathan, moodily. I've
been deceived by false information. But the
wench who tricked me shall bitterly repent it.
I hope this is all. I begin to fear I might be</pp>
<pb n="289">
<pp>purposely got out of the way. Nothing has
gone wrong here?&rdquo;</pp></p>
<p>&ldquo;Nothing whatever,&rdquo; replied Ireton. &ldquo;Jack
is just gone back to the Condemned Hold.
His two wives have been here.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ha!&rdquo; exclaimed Jonathan, with a sudden
vehemence that electrified the chief turnkey; 
&ldquo;what's this! a spike gone! 'Sdeath! the
women, you say, have been here. He has
escaped.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Impossible, sir,&rdquo; replied Ireton, greatly
alarmed.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Impossible!&rdquo; echoed Wild, with a fearful
imprecation. &ldquo;No, sir, it's quite possible&mdash; 
more than possible. It's certain. I'll lay my
life he's gone. Come with me to the Condemned
Hold directly, and, if I find my fears
confirmed, I'll&mdash;&rdquo;</p>
<p>He was here interrupted by the sudden
entrance of the black, who rushed precipitately
into the room, letting fall the heavy bunch of
keys in his fright.</p>
<p>&ldquo;O Massa Ireton! Massa Wild!&rdquo; ejaculated
Caliban, &ldquo;Shack Sheppart gone!&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="290">
<p>&ldquo;Gone? you black devil!&mdash;Gone?&rdquo; cried
Ireton.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Iss, Massa. Caliban sarch ebery hole in
de place, but Shack no dere. Only him big
hoss padlock&mdash;noting else.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I knew it,&rdquo; rejoined Wild, with concentrated
rage; &ldquo;and he escaped you all in broad
day, before your faces. You may well say it's
impossible! His Majesty's goal of Newgate is
admirably guarded, I must say. Ireton, you
are in league with him.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Sir,&rdquo; said the chief turnkey, indignantly.</p>
<p>&ldquo;You <it>are</it>, sir,&rdquo; thundered Jonathan; &ldquo;and,
unless you find him, you shan't hold your
place a week. I don't threaten idly, as you
know. And you, Austin; and you Langley
I say the same thing to you.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;But, Mr. Wild,&rdquo; implored the turnkeys.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I've said it,&rdquo; rejoined Jonathan, peremptorily.
&ldquo;And you, Marvel, you must have
been a party&mdash;&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;I, sir!&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;If he's not found, I'll get a new hangman.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Zounds!&rdquo; cried marvel, &ldquo;I&mdash;&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="291">
<p>&ldquo;Hush!&rdquo; whispered the tapstress, &ldquo;or I
retract my promise.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Mrs. Spurling,&rdquo; said Jonathan, who overheard
the whisper, &ldquo;you owe your situation to
me. If you have aided Jack Sheppard's escape,
you shall owe your discharge to me also.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;As you please, sir,&rdquo; replied the tapstress,
coolly. &ldquo;And the next time Captain Darrell
wants a witness, I promise you he shan't look
for one in vain.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Ha! hussy, dare you threaten?&rdquo; cried
Wild; but, checking himself, he turned to
Ireton and asked, &ldquo;How long have the women
been gone?&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Scarcely five minutes,&rdquo; replied the latter.</p>
<p>&ldquo;One of you fly to the market,&rdquo; returned
Jonathan; &ldquo;another to the river; a third to
the New Mint. Disperse in every direction.
We'll have him yet. A hundred pounds to
the man who takes him.&rdquo;</p>
<p>So saying, he rushed out, followed by Ireton
and Langley.</p>
<p>&ldquo;A hundred pounds!&rdquo; exclaimed Shotbolt.
&ldquo;That's a glorious reward. Do you think
he'll pay it?&rdquo;</p>
<pb n="292">
<p>&ldquo;I'm sure of it,&rdquo; replied Austin.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Then I'll have it before to&hyphen;morrow morning,&rdquo; 
said the keeper of the New Prison, to
himself. &ldquo;If Jack Sheppard sups with Mr.
Kneebone, I'll make one of the party.&rdquo;</p></div4></div3>
<trailer>END OF SECOND VOLUME.</trailer></div2>
